[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This is a general introductory file. In the course, you will be presented with various overview chapters before the main lines/files.   In fact, six overview chapters will help the readers understand the direction before going through the lines. These overview chapters are as follows:  1. Early deviations overview that covers Colle System and early g3 lines.   2. QGD overview that covers all of the moves except for 4.g3 and 4.Nc3 after:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  d5  .  3. Semi-Tarrasch sidelines overview that covers all Semi-Tarrasch lines except for the 6.e4 mainline.   4 and 5. Two parts overview chapters on Main Semi Tarrasch with 6.e4. The first part deals with a basic introduction, followed by a series of endgames, followed by another overview chapter.   Finally, 6. An overview of the Catalan. }
1... Nf6 2. c4
{ 2.Nf3  d5  3.e3  The Colle system is easy to underestimate, and one can have the attitude of 'I will see it on the board,' and that's where the problem starts. Wouldn't it be nice to have a system which you see once and never forget? To have some simple logical solution that takes care of everything? Move order is the crux of everything here, and in the main file, it is explained clearly.   3.g3  Played by the World Champion in the marathon game 6 of the 2021 World Championship match.   Incidentally, I was commenting with Judit on chess24 for this entire game. As soon as Magnus opted for this move, I was sharing my thoughts in this line. Check out @@LinkStart@@https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=crhU-pg7Rvw@@LinkEnd@@ and skip to 34.00 to get the exact moment  3...c5  4.Bg2  cxd4  5.O-O  Waiting for Nc6 to get a reverse Grunfeld after Nxd4.  5...h6!  Stunning and surprising move that is indeed the best. Black does not commit Nc6 to make sure after Nxd4, he can play e5, and White won't have Nxc6.   Black also made sure not to play e6 so that he plays e5 at one go, saving a tempo. The move h6 tells the d5 pawn that I have got your back. The knight will protect the d5 pawn on f6, and the knight gets immunity from Bg5 thanks to h6 :@@EndBracket@@ More on this brilliant move is given in the main files.  3...c5  4.c3  The ideal way to reach the Colle.   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/5n2/2pp4/3P4/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.b3  cxd4  ruins White's strategy as developing the c1 bishop will become an issue. If it comes to b2, it is blocked with the pawn on d4, and if it develops on f4/g5, the c3 square remains weak.  Of course, there is more to it, which is given in the main files.  4...e6  Avoiding Nc6-dxc5 ideas.  5.Bd3  Nbd7!  Move orders in this position are essential. White plays for quick e4 ideas and sometimes dxc5-b4 with a reverse Semi-Slav plan, and Black takes care of both plans with a knight on d7.   Now, dxc5 will be answered with Nxc5, and White is not getting a quick e4 as Black intends to skip Bd6-O-O for a while, and we will start with b6-Bb7-Ne4 to counter White's plan of playing e4. Once Black has established superiority in the center, only then we shift focus to our kingside. In the main file, further details are given, and here I just wanted to highlight how important it is not to make an automatic move like Be7 or Bd6.  Playing any opening gets easier once you understand the ideas behind every move. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3
{ ➥  4.g3  dxc4  5.Bg2  c5  I started working on the Catalan intensely since the Anand-Topalov match in 2010. Team Anand prepared the Catalan, and we produced some incredible ideas that even modern engines approve of today.   One of the major blocks was the dxc4-c5 line during our preparation, which was also our Black side repertoire if Topalov opted for Catalan from the White side. After the match, Anand and his team kept faith in this system and continued producing many good games showing various unused ideas in their tournament games. What was the world championship match preparation like? Have a look inside the main file and witness how entertaining Catalan can be. Going through the files will enhance both your dynamic and strategic play.   In the Catalan overview chapter, you can find more about the direction of this system.   ➥  4.e3  Be7  Preparing slow systems like this can often be tedious and, more importantly, extremely difficult due to various move orders.   My priority was to fix that and make life easier from the move order point of view. How good will it be if you know that we take on c4 every time White moves the bishop without playing b3, and once he plays b3, our setup is fixed with O-O-c5-cxd4-b6, etc.? After playing b3, White can play Bd3-Bb2-O-O-Nc3/Nbd2 in every possible permutation and combination. This can make our opening preparation very confusing, right? Check out the overview file, and the main file of this chapter, and you will never be bothered about any move-order issues ever again.   ➥  4.cxd5  The QGD exchange might seem intimidating and vert theoretical, but it gets much easier when we sidestep the oceans of theory and find creative ideas.   White's big issue is that they have committed with Nf3, which prevents them from getting the ideal setup of Bd3-Ne2-O-O-  4...exd5  5.Nc3  c6  6.Bg5  h6  Sidestepping the impossible amount of theory in 6...Be7. The 6...h6 move relies entirely on fine move order tricks that one needs to understand.  7.Bh4  Bf5   @@StartBracket@@It is important to include h6-Bh4 before Bf5. That way, after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3pp1/2p2n1p/3p1b2/3P3B/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qb3  Black has  8...g5  9.Bg3  Qb6  , and the kingside structure remains unbroken.@@EndBracket@@  8.e3  Nbd7  A lovely move order finesse. Black is now ready to meet Qb3 with Qb6 as the knight on f6 is protected. We keep the d6 square available for the bishop. Black gets a lovely position, and going through the main files will give a clear concept on how to play the upcoming middlegame.   ➥  4.Bg5  This move can be a nightmare if Black is unaware of the possible transpositions. Black can easily end up in a proper Semi-Slav, Botvinnik, Anti-Moscow, Ragozin, Vienna, QGD. However, our file remains unique, and we sidestep everything :@@EndBracket@@  4...dxc4  5.e4   @@StartBracket@@ After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/6B1/2pP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  , we get to a Vienna, but White played a toothless Bg5 instead of the main e4. Black goes  5...a6  , and after  6.a4  Nc6  with Na5 ideas, we get a lovely position.@@EndBracket@@  5...c5   @@StartBracket@@ After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/6B1/2pPP3/5N2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  6.a4  c6  Black gets to the Botvinnik system a4 variation. 5...c5 keeps our repertoire unique, and it is very easy to underestimate this direction from the White side, which means chances of getting our opponent to unknown territory are higher. @@EndBracket@@  6.Nc3  The main move.   @@StartBracket@@ After  6.Bxc4  cxd4  7.O-O  Nc6  , only six games have been played. The position is fresh, and in the main files,  the ideas are crystal clear for Black, who is fine in every direction.@@EndBracket@@  6...cxd4  7.Qxd4  Qxd4  8.Nxd4  a6  This is the starting position of the main file. At first sight, it might feel White is better developed, but in reality, all White's pieces will be chased away. The bishop on g5 is going back after h6. The bishop on c4 will be hit back with b5, followed by Bb7 will take another tempo. The knight on d4 will be attacked soon, and the knight on c3 will constantly watch out for b4 ideas. Black is not fighting for equality. In fact, one slight error from White and Black will take over. Black is fighting on equal terms and looking for opportunities to take over. Check out the main file to see the effortlessness in Black's play. }
4... c5 5. cxd5
{ 5.e3  Nc6  This position often also occurs from the English opening from the following move order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  c5  2.c4  Nf6  3.Nc3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e3  e6  . There are different tries for White. The overview chapter of Semi Tarrasch Sidelines will give the readers a general idea of the direction, and in the main file, every move is analyzed with great detail, which will help the readers play a better middlegame. }
5... Nxd5
{ The Semi-Tarrasch is one of the most solid systems, but most often people underestimate the dynamism of this line. The main position of this line occurs after 6.e4 when a mass exchange takes place. }
6. e4
{ 6.e3  Nc6  This seemingly harmless line has its venom. I will give one example here.  7.Bc4  cxd4  8.exd4  Be7  9.O-O  O-O  10.Re1  The first thing one needs to do to understand this line will be finding the game between Botvinnik and Alekhine from Avro 1938.   In fact, I refused to show any move further before someone saw the game as I felt it would be pointless to explain the details if someone didn't understand the danger that lies in such an innocent-looking position. I have also included this game in the model game section to make sure the readers know how NOT to play from the Black side here.  10...Bf6  Playing these positions will become effortless once you go through the overview files and the correspondent chapters. }
6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O
{ The starting position of the mainline Semi-Tarrasch. How do we approach an opening so that ideas and concepts remain crystal clear in our minds?   Going through a bunch of moves is often overwhelming. For example, in this position, White has at least 7-8 different moves, all of which have different ideas. It is utterly confusing even with the engines on. I took a different approach here to clear the concept.   Even before we make another move, in the introduction file of the Mainline Semi-Tarrasch, you will see every possible endgame with a similar pawn structure discussed: Starting from king and pawn endgames to every likely endgame. This will immediately make one thing clear... any piece exchange favors Black.   What is the difference between all possible rook moves in the mainline? Why is White developing the bishop to all available squares from e2 to b5? The ideas behind every move are clearly explained, and once again, if you think the Semi-Tarrasch is a boring line, do check the files to get amused with the insanely complicated lines. This entire system is mixed with strategy and intense tactical battles.   Once again, going through this course will not only make you a better opening expert but a better player in general. This is why you will also face 230+ training positions. These positions are purposefully jumbled with strategic and tactical ideas to create a tournament-like ambiance when we don't know what the position demands. Going through these positions will make you more alert and eventually will come in handy as a revision.  I am looking forward to seeing all of you active in the discussion forum :@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: Early Deviations and the QGD"]
[Black "Early g3 lines: 3.Bg2 c5 4.Nf3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. g3 { 2.Nf3  d5  3.g3  is covered via a different move order. }
2... d5 3. Bg2 { 3.Nf3  c5  4.Bg2  transposes to the mainline. } 3... c5
{ Charging in the center immediately. Typically our moves for the sidelines remain the same Nf6-d5-c5. We saw this in Part 1 of this course. In every sideline, we counter with the standard Nf6-d5-c5 plan. }
4. Nf3
{ After  4.c3  Nc6  5.Nf3  , we get a position that we will see from the 3.c3 move order. After  4.c4  dxc4  5.Nf3  Black can play lazily with  5...e6  and get to our Catalan repertoire that is covered in a different file, or we can be brave and punish White's naive move order by going  5...Nc6  when we get a similar position, but the bishop on c8 remains active. The engine already prefers Black there. }
4... cxd4
{ The perfect moment to take on d4. If the knight was on c6 already, then this would be a Reversed Grünfeld. However, that would also mean when White takes Nxd4, and Black goes e5 White will have the important Grünfeld idea of taking Nxc6. Here that's not the case, which means we grab the center with e5 as soon as White takes Nxd4. }
5. O-O
{ The main move. White cunningly waits for Black to play Nc6 when they get a perfect Reversed Grünfeld with an extra tempo. }
5... h6
{ An excellent prophylactic move. Black does not commit with Nc6 to make sure that after Nxd4, we can play e5, and White won't have Nxc6. Black also made sure not to play e6 so that we play e5 in one go, saving a tempo. Realizing that eventually, we will get full control over the center, Black makes sure to consolidate the center. This is done by playing h6! Chess is beautiful, isn't it? The move h6 tells the d5 pawn that I have got your back. The d5 pawn will be protected by the knight on f6, and the knight gets immunity from Bg5 thanks to h6 :@@EndBracket@@ }
6. Bf4
{ It is not easy for White to find a useful move like Black. It looks natural to wait for Nc6 and not to take on d4. :@@EndBracket@@ }
6... e6
{ Black makes a normal developing move and indicates that we don't want to fight for e5 yet. }
7. Nxd4
{ It is hard to suggest anything else for White at this point. White will have to take the pawn to justify their play. }
7... g5
{ Unexpected resource! Another hidden role of the brilliant 5...h6 move :@@EndBracket@@ White now must make a tough choice of where to hide their bishop. }
8. Be5 { White manages to stop e5 but only temporarily. } 8... Nbd7
{ Forcing White to give up the bishop. } 9. Bxf6 Nxf6 10. c4
{ After all, White will have to justify why they gave up the bishop. Now White is trying to prove that Black is two moves away from castling, so it is time to open up the game.  10.Qd3  was played in some games but after  10...Bd7  11.c4  dxc4  12.Qxc4  , we will get to the same position starting from  10. c4 . }
10... dxc4
{ Black is happy to release the tension in the center and open up the game. After all, we have the bishop pair. }
11. Qa4+ Bd7 12. Qxc4 Qb6
{ It is obvious that White cannot create an attack on the center, and Black will play Bg7-O-O shortly.   @@StartBracket@@More importantly, White will also have to deal with Rc8 ideas that gain a tempo against White's queen. This position occurred in a few correspondence games, and Black never lost a single one and won one game. That also underlines the solidity of Black's position. }
