[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: Early Deviations and the QGD"]
[Black "QGD 4th Move alternatives: 4.Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5
{ We will see various options on the 4th move in this chapter. This will not include 4.e3/Bg5/g3/Nc3 as those are covered separately in other chapters. }
4. Bf4
{ White is ready to play e3 when his bishop won't be stuck anymore on c1. }
4... dxc4
{ As usual, we are happy to take on c4 when White is unable to play e4. } 5.
Qa4+
{ After  5.e3  b5  , White won't be able to strike with  6.a4  anymore since  6...Bb4+  will cause a lot of trouble. The bishop on f4 is stuck outside of the pawn chain, and is unable to protect d2.   Playing  5.Nc3  makes no sense either, since after  5...c6  , White's bishop belongs to g5 and not f4. White needs to stop Black from playing b5, but after  6.a4  Bb4  , the bishop on f4 is heavily misplaced, and White cannot deal with b5/Nd5 ideas. No wonder the engines give a significant advantage to Black. }
5... Nbd7
{ Once again, we see a similar pattern. There is no need to gain an immediate tempo with  5...Bd7  as White is forced to take on c4 in any case. Black is getting ready for an a6-b5-Bb7 plan. }
6. e3
{ After  6.Qxc4  c5  there is no good way to stop Black from playing b5. Note that once again White can't stop a6-b5 with a4 as the a1 rook hangs. }
6... Nd5
{ With a double threat of taking the bishop on f4 and an annoying check on b4. Black can already fight for advantage here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: Early Deviations and the QGD"]
[Black "QGD 4th Move alternatives: 4.Qc2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5
{ We will see various options on the 4th move in this chapter. This will not include 4.e3/Bg5/g3/Nc3 as those are covered separately in other chapters. }
4. Qc2
{ White protects the pawn with the queen, and this has an obvious disadvantage that Black exploits instantly. }
4... dxc4
{ Simplest solution. Black lures the queen to c4 so that further tempos will be gained by chasing the queen. }
5. Qxc4 a6
{ Encashing the misplacement of White's queen. Black wants to play b5-Bb7. } 6.
Bf4
{ After  6.a4  Nbd7  Black can play a quick c5 when White will have to take care of their exposed queen and uncastled king, or opt for a direct b5 going for the queen. Note that Black will be able to castle faster here when every tempo counts. }
6... Bd6
{ Simple and effective. We are ready to trade our good bishop, as it gives us another extra tempo for castling. Also, it is important that if White takes on d6, Black gets further control in the center. }
7. Bxd6
{ 7.Bg3  was played a few times, but Black had absolutely no problem after  7...b5  and Bb7 next. White just wasted way too many tempos with Bf4-Bg3 and Qc2-Qxc4 and will further lose another move with the queen while Black finishes development and castles quickly. }
7... cxd6 8. e3 b5
{ The bishop is coming to a lovely diagonal via b7, and the rook will get to an open file soon. White still needs to find a decent square for the queen. Black's minor pieces will be controlling the center nicely. In the future, we can look forward to e5 breaks. There is nothing to complain about in Black's position here. }
