[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: Early Deviations and the QGD"]
[Black "QGD: 4.cxd5 exd5 5.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. cxd5
{ The exchange variation of QGD only works when the knight is on g1 as White keeps the strong option of the Bd3-Ne2 set up to facilitate the f3-e4 breaks in the future. It is one of the main reasons why this version of the exchange variation is rarely seen at the top level. }
4... exd5 5. Nc3 { The most popular move in the position. } 5... c6
{ It is the ideal pawn formation. Black keeps the development of the bishop flexible for now. By playing c6, we stabilize the central d5 pawn.   This position can also come from a Semi-Slav @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  c6  @@EndBracket@@, where taking on d5 is not the main or critical move. }
6. Bg5
{ Once again, the most popular move in the position. Now that e4 square is under control, White is not worried about h6-g5-Ne4 ideas like in the 5.Bg5 line. }
6... h6
{ One can argue why not play  6...Bd6  , so we can transpose to 6.Qc2 line after White plays  7.Qc2  .   The problem here is White plays  7.e3  with the idea of Bd3, and Black is not on time to get  7...Bf5  as  8.Qb3  becomes very strong and it is unclear how to save the b7 pawn without structural compromises. The main move is Be7 in the position, but h6 is the modern treatment of this line. Black wants to develop his bishop to its ideal square on d6. }
7. Bxf6
{ Was played many times, but this gives Black the bishop pair for free. } 7...
Qxf6 8. e3
{ White's long-term plan is based on b4-b5 ideas after finishing development. Black should make sure this does not happen. }
8... Bd6 9. Bd3 O-O
{ Nothing to comment here. This is a very standard way of finishing the development on the kingside. }
10. O-O Bg4
{ The easiest solution. Black wants to take on f3 and break White's pawn structure, then with opposite-color bishop position White can forget about any opening advantage.  Playing e4 would give White an isolated pawn structure. That leaves them with the tempting b4-b5 plan. After  11.Rb1?!  Black plays  11...Nd7  12.b4  b5!  when White's queenside expansion comes to a dead-end, and Black gets a clear advantage with a5 coming next. }
11. h3
{ Wise decision. White doesn't mind getting into an opposite color bishop position. }
11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Nd7
{ The right decision. There is no need to bring White's g2 pawn to f3 with Qxf3, as then it will be easier for White to get the e4 break. }
13. Qxf6 Nxf6
{ Now playing f3 will weaken the pawn on e3. Playing Rab1 with the idea of b4 will be stopped by a5. In the game, ½-½ Shengelia, D @@StartBracket@@2582@@EndBracket@@-Ragger, M @@StartBracket@@2614@@EndBracket@@ Vienna 2010 White played  14.e4  and it got fizzled out to a draw after  14...dxe4  15.Nxe4  Nxe4  16.Bxe4  Rad8  . }
