[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: Early Deviations and the QGD"]
[Black "QGD: 4.Bg5 dxc4 5.Nc3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Bg5
{ This line is quite popular. It immediately avoids the Semi-Tarrasch line @@StartBracket@@as White has not committed to Nc3@@EndBracket@@ and keeps the option wide open of transposing into lines like the Ragozin, QGD, Semi-Slav, Vienna, Moscow, etc. None of these are part of our repertoire; so knowing how to deal with this particular move order is of utmost importance. If we don't pay attention here, then we might suddenly find ourselves in a foreign theoretical territory in a completely different line. }
4... dxc4
{ The most popular move was  4...Be7  , which would have got us to the mainline QGD. There are other moves too which could get us into various other systems that we are bypassing and keeping our repertoire unique and independent. }
5. Nc3
{ Currently we transposed into the Vienna system @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  d5  4.Nc3  dxc4  , but here White went with the lesser popular  5.Bg5  @@StartBracket@@instead of  5.e4  @@EndBracket@@.   Black has a plethora of options here; we could play:  ➫  5...Bb4  and get a Ragozin.  ➫  5...c6  and get a Botvinnik system.  ➫  5...Be7  and get a worse version of QGD.  So how do we play then? We keep our repertoire unique and independent by going  5...a6  here :@@EndBracket@@ }
5... a6
{ This has been played by Gelfand, Ding, Anand, etc. Black is forcing White to get into foreign territory.   The idea is straightforward - Black wants to play b5 and protect the c4 pawn. }
6. a4 { Stopping b5 and planning e4. } 6... Nc6
{ Now we save the pawn with Na5. } 7. e4 Na5
{ Once again, we address the real threat, which is to take the pawn on c4. White can never win a piece with the e5 trick. }
8. e5 h6
{ A similar idea to the Botvinnik system, but this time Black has a much better option to get a clearly better position. }
9. Bh4 g5 10. Nxg5 Nd5
{ This move is a blunder in the Botvinnik system, and White usually wins by taking on f7. Here the major difference is Black has the knight on a5 instead of b8, and White has committed to a4 giving Black Nb3 ideas. }
11. Nxf7
{ 11.Nf3  Be7  would be the lesser evil for White, and they can escape with an evaluation of -1, but definitely, that was not the point of White's play. We should only check this variation to understand the difference. }
11... Qxh4 12. Nxh8 Bb4
{ In the Botvinnik system, here White would have won with Rc1, but that is not an option here as Black can play Nb3 just in time, and most importantly, we get to castle long quickly by going Bd7 next.   White is dead lost at this point with the king still stuck in the center. }
