[White "Quickstarter: Early Deviations and the QGD"]
[Black "QGD: 4.Bg5 dxc4 5.Qa4+ #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Bg5
{ This line is quite popular. It immediately avoids the Semi-Tarrasch line @@StartBracket@@as White has not committed to Nc3@@EndBracket@@ and keeps the option wide open of transposing into lines like the Ragozin, QGD, Semi-Slav, Vienna, Moscow, etc. None of these are part of our repertoire; so knowing how to deal with this particular move order is of utmost importance. If we don't pay attention here, then we might suddenly find ourselves in a foreign theoretical territory in a completely different line. }
4... dxc4
{ The most popular move was  4...Be7  , which would have got us to the mainline QGD. There are other moves too which could get us into various other systems that we are bypassing and keeping our repertoire unique and independent. }
5. Qa4+ Nbd7
{ As usual for Qa4+, like in every other line, we don't attack the queen immediately with Bd7 but just develop our knight to d7. We want to get our a6-b5-Bb7 ideas in. }
6. Qxc4 c5 { Charging in the center and getting ready for the a6-b5 plans. } 7.
Nc3 a6
{ Threatening b5. White can't stop it by playing  9.a4  as Black can still play  9...b5  as the rook on a1 hangs. }
8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Ne4
{ After  9.e3  b5  Black still gets a better position, as White's queen will have to lose a few more tempos while Black calmly develops with Bb7. }
9... b5 10. Bxf6
{ 10.Qd3  Bb4  was also worse for White when their kingside army snores. }
10... gxf6
{ There is no need to be scared of the broken pawn structure. White is underdeveloped on the kingside, and the king remains weak. }
11. Qc3 Be7
{ This position occurred in ½-½ Dreev,A  @@StartBracket@@2677@@EndBracket@@ -Inarkiev,E @@StartBracket@@2663@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2019. Black was completely winning at this point. In fact, the engine gives around -2 here. Bb7-Rc8 everything comes with a tempo.   With some absolute miracle from a -5 position, White managed to escape with a draw. However, that is not relevant for our repertoire at this moment :@@EndBracket@@ }
