[White "Quickstarter: Early Deviations and the QGD"]
[Black "QGD: 4.Bg5 dxc4 5.e3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Bg5
{ This line is quite popular. It immediately avoids the Semi-Tarrasch line @@StartBracket@@as White has not committed to Nc3@@EndBracket@@ and keeps the option wide open of transposing into lines like the Ragozin, QGD, Semi-Slav, Vienna, Moscow, etc. None of these are part of our repertoire; so knowing how to deal with this particular move order is of utmost importance. If we don't pay attention here, then we might suddenly find ourselves in a foreign theoretical territory in a completely different line. }
4... dxc4
{ The most popular move was  4...Be7  , which would have got us to the mainline QGD. There are other moves too which could get us into various other systems that we are bypassing and keeping our repertoire unique and independent. }
5. e3
{ White wants to take on c4, but unlike the 5.e4 line here the pawn wont be hanging on e3. }
5... b5 { Black is not going to give up the c4 pawn that easily. } 6. a4 c6
{ The pawns remain protected. } 7. Nc3
{ White keeps going for the pawn. Any other move allows Black to save the pawn ultimately. }
7... a6
{ Black brings more protection to the pawn on b5 to keep the support for the c4 pawn intact. It was possible to play the simpler  7...Bb4  , but White could move order us with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/6B1/2pP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  a6  6.e3  b5  7.a4  when Black is obliged to play  7...c6  and we get the same position. }
8. axb5 cxb5
{ Now the only question is if White can take on b5 and grab the exchange. } 9.
Bxf6
{ White can take on b5 with or without including Bxf6. In either case, they get a horrible position. }
9... gxf6
{ Black needs the queen on d8 to maintain the protection of the b8-knight. This will allow us to play Bb7 when White takes on a8. }
10. Nxb5 axb5 11. Rxa8 Bb7
{ It is also possible to start with  11...Bb4  and then play Bb7. } 12. Ra1
Bb4+ { White's king is now in danger. } 13. Ke2
{ 13.Nd2  e5  further opens up the game, and the White king will remain exposed in the center. }
13... O-O
{ There is no chance to survive with the Bongcloud king and underdeveloped pieces. This time Hikaru was on the other side of Bongcloud and went on to win in the following game. 0-1 Mamedyarov,S @@StartBracket@@2817@@EndBracket@@-Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2746@@EndBracket@@ Kolkata 2018 }
