[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: The Semi-Tarrasch"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 Nc6
{ This position often also occurs in the English opening from the following move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  c5  2.c4  Nf6  3.Nc3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e3  e6  . }
6. a3
{ White remains non-commital in the center but prepares dxc5-Bxc5-b4 ideas. }
6... dxc4
{ Before White can implement their original idea of taking on c5 and playing b4, Black does the same. }
7. Bxc4 a6
{ One can argue that when White played dxc5 and a3, we were happy, and now we are playing dxc4-a6 with one tempo down @@StartBracket@@White got an extra a3@@EndBracket@@, yet we are happy. So, where is the logic in all of that? The explanation is straightforward. As Black, we don't mind getting easy equality and consider this to be a good outcome from the opening, while from White's perspective, that's not ideal. }
8. O-O
{ The most natural move. Any other bishop with the c4 bishop would be answered with b5 when White will eventually castle, and we will transpose.  8.dxc5  Qxd1  followed by Bc5 gives Black a comfortable position to play. }
8... b5 { Of course! Why else did we play a6 in the previous move! } 9. Ba2
{ The most popular move. White is trying their best to open up the game with d5 while Black's king remains in the center. }
9... Bb7
{ It is important to get ready for the d5 break, which is the only way for White to open up the center while keeping the queens alive. Black will now castle after playing Be7. }
10. Qe2
{ Developing fast and getting ready for Rd1-d5 ideas, and keeping dxc5 ideas open, when there are no queen trades anymore. }
10... cxd4 { Not giving a chance to play dxc5 or d5. } 11. Rd1
{ Otherwise, White just remains a pawn down. } 11... b4
{ This is the key move! Black strikes once again against the knight on c3. }
12. exd4
{ Sacrificing a piece temporarily.  12.Nxd4  bxc3  13.Nxc6  Qc7  forces White to go back with  14.Nd4  when Black gains another tempo by attacking the h2 pawn with  14...Bd6  and takes the lead in development as the bishop on c1 remains jobless. }
12... bxc3
{ Not fearing any ghosts! Black accepts the challenge of the piece sacrifice. }
13. d5 Nxd5
{ Time to give back the piece, but to make sure the safety of our king remains intact. }
14. Rxd5 Qc7
{ The pawn on e6 makes sure that nothing goes wrong with the king on e8. Black is ready to play Be7-O-O next. }
15. bxc3 Be7
{ Black is ready to castle while White ended up with a bad pawn structure. }
16. Rh5
{ White must play energetically and dynamically. From a strategic point of view, they got into a bad pawn structure. }
16... Rd8
{ There is no rush to castle yet. The Black king is safe on e8 for now. } 17.
Be3 g6
{ Black removes the rook from h5 and will play Ne5 next. This position was reached twice. Once Black drew in a correspondence game, and once David Howell defeated Amin Tabatabaei in the 2019 World Team, Astana. If we look at the bishops, we will notice that White's king comes into danger, and Black's king doesn't have any problems. }
