[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: The Semi-Tarrasch"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline 11.Bc4 Nd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7
{ Better than the b6 move order, as this avoids d5. After  11...b6  12.d5  White gets a clearly better position as Black can't take on d5 since Bxd5 traps the rook on a8. Black is now ready to play b6-Bb7 next. }
12. O-O { 12.d5  Nb6  would be a disaster for White. } 12... b6
{ Black wants to gain tempo with Bb7 attacking e4 followed by Rc8 attacking c4. }
13. Rfe1
{ It is the most popular move in the position. White is protecting the pawn even before it is under attack.  13.Bd3  Bb7  14.a4  and  13.a4  Bb7  14.Rfe1  and  13.a4  Bb7  14.Bd3  Nf6  15.Rfe1  all of the lines mentioned above transposes to  13. Rfe1 variation. }
13... Bb7 14. a4
{ White wants to play a5, and claim that after the exchange of one pawn Black will remain with a weak pawn on the queenside. That's one way of looking into the position. We will soon see what is the reality.  14.Rad1  is the main move in the position, which is covered in a separate chapter.  14.Bb3  Rc8  15.Rad1  also transposes to 14.Rad1 line.   The same applies to  14.Qf4  Rc8  15.Bb3  Qc7  16.Qh4  Rfe8  17.Rad1  . }
14... Nf6
{ Now that White showed their hand on the queenside, it makes sense to keep the rook on a8 for a while. Black attacks on e4 when White is unable to play d5. }
15. Bd3
{ When White wants to fight for d5 breaks, they keep the bishop on b3. And when they fight for a5 ideas, then they prefer to keep the bishop on d3, looking at the queenside. }
15... h6
{ Black waits for White to show their queenside plans. For now, they make a calm move to stop any kind of e5-Ng5 ideas in the future. }
16. a5
{ The most direct way. White continues with the plan of playing on the queenside. }
16... a6
{ It is also possible to play the more popular move  16...bxa5  but after  17.Rxa5  Qc7  White is not obliged to transpose with Qb4, and they can keep their queen less exposed on d2. I like the text move  16...a6  with the idea of b5, which in a way, forces White to take on b6. }
17. axb6
{ Otherwise, Black would be happy to get a protected passed pawn with b5. }
17... Qxb6 18. Rab1
{ The most logical move. The other rook is needed on  e1  to protect the pawn on e4.  18.Qa5  would make Black happier after  18...Qxa5  19.Rxa5  Rfc8  with the idea of invading with Rc3. }
18... Qc7
{ Black is happy to see White's rook on c1 when it can later be traded with Rc8 }
19. Rec1 { Attacking the queen but leaving the protection of the pawn on e4. }
19... Qe7 20. Qf4 Rfc8 { Black gets the ideal setup for exchanging the rooks. }
21. Rxc8+ Rxc8
{ As usual, Black is happy to play endgames. With Qc7-a5 coming next, Black had a lovely endgame in: 0-1 Rychagov,A @@StartBracket@@2545@@EndBracket@@-Xiong,J @@StartBracket@@2709@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2021 }
