[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: The Semi-Tarrasch"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline 11.Bc4 Nd7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7 12. O-O b6 13. Rfe1 Bb7 14.
Rad1
{ It is one of the ideal setups for White. With this piece formation, White is best prepared for the central break with d5. It is also difficult for Black to exchange any piece, and white wants to play the middlegame without trading a single piece. }
14... Rc8 15. Bb3 { The main move. The bishop on b3 facilitates the d5 break. }
15... h6
{ A lovely move order finesse. Black waits for White to show their plans.  If Black rushes with  15...Nf6  then after  16.d5  exd5  17.exd5  Re8  18.d6  gives White some pressure. Black is now claiming that White got everything they wanted, yet they can't strike. The move h6 is politely telling your opponent, 'I am not intimidated with your play. Please show me your plans'. Black also deliberately keeps the rook on f8, which protects the f7 pawn once the center blows up and/or White knight comes to e5 in the future. }
16. Re3 { White wants to play Qe2/Qe1 next and then aim for the d5 break. }
16... Nf6
{ White skipped playing h3, and Black takes full advantage of that by attacking the e4 pawn and keeping Ng4 ideas open. }
17. d5
{ Now it gets pretty forced. White clearly says that they are ready for the d5 break, but Black also claims so. Let's see who is right here. }
17... exd5 18. exd5 { 18.Qe1  Re8  transposes to 17.Qe1 line. } 18... Qd6
{ Of course, we are not going to allow White to play d6. Now there is only one question, is White getting Nf5-d6 or not. The evaluation of the position will be dependent on this factor. }
19. Nh4
{ The best way to get to f5. After  19.Nd4  Qd7  Black stops Nf5 ideas and also attacks the pawn on d5. With the knight on h4, White is ready to meet  19...Qd7  with  20.d6  . }
19... Rfe8
{ An extremely logical and vital move. Black could be lost without this move, but it is also the most natural move in the position. Black wants to trade pieces and take control of the e7 square so that Nf5-Ne7 doesn't become a threat. }
20. Nf5 { This forces Black to know some only moves. } 20... Qd7
{ This position reached four times in tournament games. Keymer, who is a specialist of this line got this position twice. Black attacks the knight on f5 and asks White to show their attacking plans. }
21. Rf3
{ White prepares Nxh6 ideas, and if Black doesn't have anything immediately, then they might as well resign here. }
21... Bxd5
{ A fantastic resource using the back rank trick. This move was seen twice in tournament practice. Once by Keymer in 2019, and once by Nepo in 2020. }
22. Bxd5
{ White is hoping for  22...Qxd5  23.Qxd5  Nxd5  24.Nd6  fork, but Black has an amazing trick here. }
22... Rc5
{ This was the hidden trick that is very easy to miss from a distance. Black exploits the back rank issue in White's position. }
23. Nxh6+
{ 23.Bxf7  Qxf7  gives Black a fine position since  24.Nd6  fork loses for White after  24...Rd5  , when once again Black exploits the back rank issue. }
23... Kf8
{ Not falling for any traps. Black completely ignores White's attack on the kingside and aims to take on d5 next. }
24. Qb4 a5
{ White cannot maintain the pin as  25.Qa3  runs into  25...Qxd5  when the e1 square is not controlled anymore and after  26.Rxd5  Re1  White gets mated. Black now picks up the bishop on d5 and gets a fine position. Eljanov, P @@StartBracket@@2663@@EndBracket@@ -Keymer, V @@StartBracket@@2506@@EndBracket@@ Douglas 2019 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: The Semi-Tarrasch"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline 11.Bc4 Nd7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7 12. O-O b6 13. Rfe1 Bb7 14.
Rad1
{ It is one of the ideal setups for White. With this piece formation, White is best prepared for the central break with d5. It is also difficult for Black to exchange any piece, and white wants to play the middlegame without trading a single piece. }
14... Rc8 15. Bb3 { The main move. The bishop on b3 facilitates the d5 break. }
15... h6
{ A lovely move order finesse. Black waits for White to show their plans.  If Black rushes with  15...Nf6  then after  16.d5  exd5  17.exd5  Re8  18.d6  gives White some pressure. Black is now claiming that White got everything they wanted, yet they can't strike. The move h6 is politely telling your opponent, 'I am not intimidated with your play. Please show me your plans'. Black also deliberately keeps the rook on f8, which protects the f7 pawn once the center blows up and/or White knight comes to e5 in the future. }
16. Re3 { White wants to play Qe2/Qe1 next and then aim for the d5 break. }
16... Nf6
{ White skipped playing h3, and Black takes full advantage of that by attacking the e4 pawn and keeping Ng4 ideas open. }
17. d5
{ Now it gets pretty forced. White clearly says that they are ready for the d5 break, but Black also claims so. Let's see who is right here. }
17... exd5 18. exd5 { 18.Qe1  Re8  transposes to 17.Qe1 line. } 18... Qd6
{ Of course, we are not going to allow White to play d6. Now there is only one question, is White getting Nf5-d6 or not. The evaluation of the position will be dependent on this factor. }
19. Nh4
{ The best way to get to f5. After  19.Nd4  Qd7  Black stops Nf5 ideas and also attacks the pawn on d5. With the knight on h4, White is ready to meet  19...Qd7  with  20.d6  . }
19... Rfe8
{ An extremely logical and vital move. Black could be lost without this move, but it is also the most natural move in the position. Black wants to trade pieces and take control of the e7 square so that Nf5-Ne7 doesn't become a threat. }
20. h3
{ My good friend GM Sam Shankland recommends this move in his 1.d4 LTR and ends with the following comment 'After one last preparatory move, White is ready for Nh4-f5 next. Black cannot maintain the blockade on the d-pawn and is under unpleasant pressure'.   I disagree with this evaluation, and if we go slightly further, we shall see that Black has no problem in the position. After all, we are getting into an endgame, as we saw in the introduction; usually, almost any kind of endgame is fine for Black. }
20... Rxe3
{ 21.Nf5  Qe5  22.Nxe3  Ne4  gives Black too much counter-attacking chances and a nice blockade on d6. }
21. Qxe3 { Renewing the threat of Nf5. } 21... Re8 22. Nf5
{ The only way to fight for an advantage. After  22.Qd3  Ne4  Black creates counterplay against White's pawn on f2 while White's bishop on b3 remains out of play. }
22... Rxe3 23. Nxd6 Re7
{ Black gets to an endgame, and as we have seen many times throughout this course, any endgames are usually fine for Black. The pawn on d5 is unsafe, with the Black king being close to it. }
24. f3 Rd7 25. Nxb7 Rxb7 26. d6 Rd7
{ Black threatens to take the pawn on d6 now. } 27. Ba4 Rd8
{ Black intends to play Kf8-Ne8 forcing White to play d7 and then go back to Nf6-Ke7, which will force White to give perpetual with Re1. One of my training partners and a good friend, IM Arghydip Das, got this position as Black in a correspondence game 2020. Cronje, H @@StartBracket@@2199@@EndBracket@@-Das,A  @@StartBracket@@2362@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2020. }
