[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: The Catalan"]
[Black "Early Qa4 lines: 4.Bg2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Qa4+
{ This is the most precise move order if White wants to get to the Qa4 lines. In this move order, White can stop Black from playing Bd7-Qc4-b5 which, would have been possible with the knight on f3. }
5... Nbd7
{ Life is easier when we don't have to remember different moves for different move orders. As per our repertoire, we will be playing Nbd7 every single time White gives a check on a4. }
6. Qxc4
{ This is once again a very subtle move order, and Black must be careful to understand the difference of delaying Nf3. We will see that in our next move. }
6... c5
{ It is crucial to avoid any move order trick by White. After the natural  7...a6  Fabiano used a very interesting idea of going  8.Be3  b5  9.Qc1  against Anand in the 2018 Olympiad. Later he developed the knight from h3 instead of f3 to keep the bishop on g2 open. By playing, 7...c5 Black avoids those ideas and practically forces White to develop the knight on f3 next. }
7. Nf3
{ The idea that Fabiano used for 6... a6 won't work here.   Since after  7.Be3  Black has the strong  7...Nd5  and after  8.Bxd5  Nb6  White is missing Bc6+, an option he had when Black played a6 instead of c5. }
7... a6
{ Now Black goes for the usual a6-b5 plan to attack the queen and develop the bishop on b7. It is important to note that playing  8.a4  doesn't stop Black from playing  8...b5  since the rook on a1 will be hanging after the exchange on b5. }
8. Qc2
{ Getting away from the c4 square by anticipating b5 and now White pretends to stop b5 by giving threats on a8 rook. A very rare move  8.Qd3  happened recently in 2021 FIDE Grand Prix. Black then took  8...cxd4  and after  9.Nxd4  Nc5  10.Qe3  we get to the position that is covered from 8.Qb3 move order. }
8... b5
{ This move is pretty much a slap on the face for White as we openly take on the challenge by ignoring the g2 bishop completely. Black prepares Bb7 without fearing Ne5 ideas. }
9. Ne5 { White tries to exploit the vulnarable rook on a8 immediately. } 9...
Nd5
{ This is a nice way to block the g2 bishop. The knight on d5 can be removed by playing e4 but then the pawn on e4 will block the bishop on g2. }
10. Bxd5
{ White now parts with the bishop and plays for better structure. If white plays any other move, Black would take on e5 and play Bb7 when White will have nothing to fight for the initiative. Playing  10.Nxd7  Bxd7  11.Bxd5  exd5  has occurred several times, getting to the same position that we will be seeing now from the 10.Bxd5 move order. }
10... exd5 11. Nxd7 Bxd7 12. dxc5
{ This was the main point of White's play. Give Black an isolated pawn, and get one extra pawn. However, the price White paid for this is quite high. They had to give up the Catalan bishop and compromised with the king's safety which won't feel comfortable on g1. }
12... Bc6
{ A lovely move that was played by Anand in 2018. It is amazing how many years one might have to wait to use their preparation. Black completely ignores the c5 pawn and plays for attack instead. We would now like to play d4 and open up the bishop on c6. }
13. O-O d4
{ Due to their own king, White might not be super happy about giving the light-squared bishop. Two over-the-board tournament games reached this position. First, it was played by Anand in 2018 Wijk against Anish, and in 2021 Levon played this in an online rapid tournament against Arjun Erigaisi. It has also occurred twice in Correspondence games in 2020-21, and Black never had any issues. }
14. Bf4
{ Finally, White focuses on developing the queenside pieces and also vacates the c1 square for the rook in case Black tries to take the pawn on c5. }
14... Qd5 { Threatening mate in one and forcing White to play f3. } 15. f3 d3
{ Right on time Black breaks White's pawn structure and will now capture on c5 with a tempo. In a 2021 correspondence game, Black played  15...O-O-O  and after  16.Nd2  d3  he had no problems. It is impossible to say which one is the best as both are equally good.   I chose  15...d3  as it is most direct and gives White limited options. }
16. exd3 { 16.Qxd3  Qxd3  17.exd3  Bxc5  transposes to the 16.exd3 line } 16...
Qxc5+
{ Once again, Black is spoiled for choice :@@EndBracket@@  At this point, it is purely a matter of taste. If Black wants to keep the position more complex, then we can also opt for  16...Bxc5  17.Kg2  O-O  18.Nc3  Qd7  offers another pawn sacrifice with  19.Nxb5  axb5  20.Qxc5  Rac8  and gets ample compensation for two pawns against White's vulnerable king. }
17. Qxc5 Bxc5+ { This position could also occur from 16.Qxd3 move order. } 18.
Kg2 Bd4
{ Black completely dominates the game with the bishop pair and plays against White's bad pawn structure and passive pieces. }
19. Nc3 Kd7
{ Black gets more than enough compensation for a pawn. We have got two fantastic bishops, an active king and we are ready to push the pawns on the queenside. In fact, White should rather be careful not to become worse. Thanks to the extra pawn the position remains equal. In the game, Anish vs Anand from Wijk 2018 White played 20.Rae1 and offered a draw which was a wise decision and was accepted. 1/2-1/2 Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2752@@EndBracket@@ -Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2767@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2018 }
