[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: The Catalan"]
[Black "Open Catalan 7.Ne5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Ne5
{ The second most popular move in the position. White opens up the bishop on g2 and tries to go for a direct assault. }
7... Bd7
{ Black coolly protects the knight on c6, and we are not afraid of giving up the bishop on d7. After all, we are a pawn up. If White wastes two tempos with Ne5-Nxd7 to take the bishop, which was not doing much on c8, why should Black object to that! }
8. Na3
{ Compared to the 7.Na3 lines here White forced Black's bishop on d7 before bringing the other knight to the game. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/2p5/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nbd2  cxd4  8.Nxc4  transposes to the mainline. }
8... cxd4
{ Our response, for now, remains the same. We take the pawn on d4 and are ready to give up the pawn on c4. }
9. Naxc4 Be7
{ So with this move order, White wants to trick us, which we are not going to fall for.  9...Bc5  the is mainline in terms of the number of games, and White usually responds with  10.Qb3  . The move that we are playing prepares nicely against White's main Qb3 idea. We will see that now in the mainline. }
10. Qb3
{ The main move. White attacks the pawn on b7 and doesn't allow castling.   10.e3  was played twice. The simplest solution could be to take  10...dxe3  11.Bxe3  and play  11...Nd5  when sooner or later White will have to take on d5 with the bishop to regain the pawn. Once the light-squared bishop is gone it is White who should be more careful. }
10... Qc7
{ This move would be a disaster with the bishop on c5, and it only works with the bishop on e7. We will soon see the point in the mainline. At first sight, it looks naive to allow Bf4, but that's precisely what we look forward to. }
11. Bf4
{ Definitely the most critical. For a long time, this entire line was dubious for Black due to this very direction. }
11... Nh5
{ There were almost no games during the world championship match between Anand and Topalov when we found this direction. We prepared Catalan from the White side and were also ready from the Black side if needed. Anand and his team kept playing this variation of dxc4-c5 successfully and continue to do so. }
12. Nxc6
{ Otherwise, White loses the bishop on f4 and breaks the structure for nothing. }
12... Nxf4 13. Nxe7 Nxg2
{ The first time we saw this position, the entire team was thrilled to discover this aesthetically beautiful position. It was never played at a GM level before back then.   At first glance, it looks ugly for Black since, after Kxe7 Black is going to have huge trouble. Upon a closer look, it gets clear that Black has no intention to take Kxe7, but he wants to play the super cool Qc5 next, giving the king complete immunity. Let's not forget that currently, Black enjoys an extra pawn, and we also got the g2 bishop while keeping our light-squared bishop alive. }
14. Qb4
{ Very tempting, but it's a blunder. White protects the knight and threatens Nd6+. This move was played 4 times, thrice by Grandmasters and once by a 2374 player. It shows how easy it is to fall for this. The move is tempting but loses on the spot. }
14... a5
{ Only move to win the game and also the only move to not to lose the game :@@EndBracket@@ There is no time, and Black must attack the queen immediately. }
15. Nd6+
{ Out of four games, thrice this move was played which is once again the most principled. White goes for mate! }
15... Kxe7
{ Black is least bothered about getting mated and gobbles up the knight. The same motif with  16.Nc8  doesn't work due to  16...Kd8  wins on the spot as Black takes the knight on c8 as well. }
16. Nf5+
{ A double-check was the only way to make sure Black doesn't take the queen. }
16... Kf6 17. Qe7+
{ 17.Qxd4  e5!  is important and then Black takes the knight on f5 and keeps the huge material advantage. }
17... Kg6
{ This is the key move. Based on this the entire line works. Otherwise, Black would be lost. Pay attention to our amazing defender on g2! The knight from g2 is doing an incredible job by stopping White from playing Nh4!! What a spectacular defensive piece :@@EndBracket@@ }
18. Nxd4
{ After  18.Nd6  Rhf8  White cannot stop Black from playing Qd8 which forces a queen trade and Black is totally winning at that point. }
18... Rhe8
{ Look at the poor queen on e7 which is struggling to find a square apart from going back all the way to a3. }
19. Qa3 { There was not a single square available apart from this one. } 19...
e5
{ With the king on g6, Black keeps attacking and chasing away White's pieces. }
20. Rac1
{ 20.Qd3  e4  was lost for White as Black would eventually save the extra piece with Bh3. }
20... Qb6 21. Nf3
{ It is interesting that despite the engine evaluation of about -7, both games that reached this position ended in a draw. The reasoning is clear as Black decided to opt for only a slight advantage position by trading the queen with  21...Qb4  . Black has a much stronger move here that wins the game. }
21... Bh3
{ Cold-bloodedly Black saves the piece and will play Qb4 next. f6 at some point will kill the knight on f3 which will lack any target. It is important to understand that saving the knight on g2 also completely restricts its counterpart as there is no Nh4 happening anymore. The evaluation of -7 confirms that Black is clearly winning which is not surprising at all. }
