[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: The Catalan"]
[Black "Open Catalan 7.Qa4 Bd7 8.Qc4 b5 9.Qc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4
b5
{ A nice move to attack the queen, and gain more space. White is unable to take  10.Qxb5  as after  10...Nxd4  White can't save the e2 pawn since  11.Qc4  runs into  11...Bb5  .   White needs to keep the d4-pawn protected. Thus, in this position, they have two alternatives,  10.Qc3  and  10.Qd3  . Right now we will focus only on  10.Qc3  . }
9. Qc3
{ Whether White keeps the queen on d3 or c3, Black will attack it further with c4 or b4. So it is White who decides which pawn push to be allowed. In this case, they chose the b-pawn. }
9... b4
{ Gaining further space and tempo by attacking the queen yet once again. } 10.
Qd3
{ Now we reach the same position as the 9.Qd3 line except, the pawn is on b4. This means Black does not have the c4 move. 9.Qc4 has never been played as Black would then go 9...Na5 and c4 would also come in the future with a tempo. }
10... Rc8
{ A standard move in this Qa4 line. Black gets away from the pin on the long diagonal. }
11. dxc5
{ Opens up the position at the first chance, but it is with some concession as Black would now develop his bishop with one tempo to c5. }
11... Bxc5
{ Obviously, we would like to recapture the pawn with a tempo, and now we are ready to castle. At this point, White tried four different logical moves, but none of them are scary. }
12. Be3
{ An interesting approach by White. They want to trade the dark-squared bishop, which was lacking a good square as we saw in the Bf4/Bg5 variation. White wants to get rid of it and finish developing his queenside pieces. This move was played by many strong players like Duda, Ding, Wang Hao, etc. }
12... Bxe3 13. Qxe3 Qb6
{ There are various ways to deal with this position, and I like this simple move which seems logical to me. Black offers queen trade, and he doesn't mind getting doubled pawns on the b-file as the b4 pawn restricts White's queenside, and the Black king is ideally placed on the center for the upcoming endgame.   13...O-O  is the main move which is also doable.   13...Ng4  was played by Levon in 2021, which is also interesting. However, in my opinion, 13...Qb6 is the easiest among all. }
14. Qxb6
{ If White doesn't take, then we will take on e3 when the pawn on e3 will become weak. White could waste another tempo by moving the queen. But in that case, Black would get a free tempo, and after castling, we would get a fine position. }
14... axb6
{ Now the king in the center is a blessing. Obviously, we are not going to castle and take full advantage of not having castled by playing Ke7. }
15. Nbd2
{ 15.a3  b3  doesn't help White when Black will eventually play Na5 aiming at c4 square with the knight and c2 square with the rook. }
15... Na5 { Simple prophylaxis against Nc4 ideas. } 16. Rfc1 Ke7
{ With Bb5 and Rhd8 coming next, it is White who will have to take care of his weak spots. Black indeed has double pawns but I don't see any way to target them. Engine evaluation of flat 0.00 confirms that Black has no issues here. This position was first time reached in the game: 1/2 @@StartBracket@@19@@EndBracket@@ -1/2 Bluebaum,M @@StartBracket@@2633@@EndBracket@@-Kryvoruchko,Y @@StartBracket@@2705@@EndBracket@@ Brest 2018. }
