1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qd3
{ White keeps the queen on d3 this time and avoids the b4 ideas that we saw in the  9.Qc3  lines. However, this move allows the other pawn push. }
9... c4
{ The advantage of having the pawn on b5. There are two major options White has at this point. They can either play Qc2 and aim for a quick e4 or play Qd1 and keep the d4 pawn protected and play for Ne5 ideas. Let's start with the Qd1 plans. }
10. Qd1
{ Keeping the pawn on d4 protected and aiming for quick Ne5 ideas or Re1-e4 ideas. }
10... Rc8 { Not allowing Ne5 } 11. Ne5
{ One of the most challenging options.  11.Bf4  runs into  11...Nd5  when White loses another tempo to remove the bishop.   Including  11.a4  b4  only helps Black, as it restricts the knight on b1. }
11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd5
{ The most strategic solution. Black sacrifices a pawn to eliminate White's Catalan bishop. In terms of the number of games,  12...Ng4  is more popular which is also fine, but I like this move more since it is easier to play. }
13. Bxd5
{ Nothing else makes sense at this point. This is the only way White can maintain the tension. Black would have played consolidated otherwise. After  13.Nc3  Nxc3  14.bxc3  Bc5  Black gets a clear advantage due to White's bad pawn structure and less piece activity compared to Black's harmonious development. }
13... exd5 14. Qxd5 Be7
{ There is absolutely no rush. Black wants to finish development first. White is hugely underdeveloped now. }
15. Rd1
{ The only time this position occurred was in a correspondence game that continued in this manner. White tries his best to prevent Black from castling. }
15... Bc6
{ Black looks forward to the endgame. Our compensation is long term and strategic so we don't mind getting into an endgame. }
16. Qxd8+ Rxd8 17. Rxd8+ Kxd8
{ Bc5-Kc7-Rd8-b4 on the way. White is hugely behind in development. } 18. Be3
{ Stopping Bc5 and also attacking a7. } 18... Kc7
{ The correspondence game continued with  18...a6  which is a waste of time. This move ignores White's threat of taking on a7 and invites them to grab the pawn. }
19. Nd2
{ After  19.Bxa7  Rd8  engine screams -2 for Black when White can't stop Black's rook from invading. }
19... Rd8
{ Black gets great compensation thanks to the double bishops and advanced pawns. At the right time, they will break with f6 and get the bishop to f6 to put pressure on the b2 pawn. If we look at all the pieces, including the king, we will see every single piece of Black is more active than White's. }
