[White "Quickstarter: The Catalan"]
[Black "dxc5 endgame: 9.Nfd2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5
{ One of the most popular choices in recent times. White wants to get an endgame without risk and play for two results. As we will see throughout this course, Black will never allow such a scenario. }
7... Qxd1
{ We should not allow White to take on d8 when black will have to make the uncomfortable choice of either breaking our castle or retreating the knight from c6. Hence we take the queen first. }
8. Rxd1 Bxc5
{ For now, Black has an extra pawn. In order for White to win the pawn back, they must make some concessions. }
9. Nfd2
{ This highly interesting move was first played at a GM level by Women World Champion Ju Wenjun in 2016. It soon became popular when Magnus used this move to beat Harikrishna in World Rapid 2017. White wants to take the pawn on c4 with the f3 knight so that the bishop on g2 remains open. }
9... Nd4
{ 9...Na5  is almost exclusively played, and this move is very rare.  Out of about 50 games, 46 times  9...Na5  was played while only  9...Nd4  was only played 4 times. I think it's just a matter of time before this move will get more popular.  It's much more dynamic and fun to play from the Black side. Black attacks e2 and also threatens to play Nc2, practically forcing White's next move. }
10. Nc3 Nd5
{ The big point. Once again targetting the pawn on e2 by attacking the knight on c3. This position reached only twice in tournaments so far. }
11. Nxd5 { White's best option. } 11... exd5 12. Bxd5
{ There is just no other option for White at this stage. } 12... O-O
{ Castling and getting ready to develop remaining pieces. Only two games reached this position, and White played  13.Kg2  and  13.Bxc4  in this position. Both moves are not critical and are toothless. }
13. Nxc4
{ This move is likely to get popular very soon. Although this was never played, and it might have gone unnoticed if I didn't give this variation @@StartBracket@@since it is not the machine's top choice@@EndBracket@@. But to me, it is the most critical line, and we must be ready for this. }
13... Rd8
{ I think this is the most principled response. It was possible to play  13...Nxe2  and take the bishop on c1 Most likely, Black will hold, but as I said in the introduction, I would never want a position with only two possible results in our opponent's favor. }
14. e4 Bg4 { White is about to lose an exchange but that is part of the plan. }
15. b4 Bxd1 16. bxc5
{ The engine thinks this position is equal, but at a first glance, I did not like it for Black. Then after going deeper I realized that Black has sufficient counter and White is unable to maintain the bind. Also, it is important that we are an exchange up, and all three results are possible. }
16... Ba4 { All we need is to trade a few pieces. } 17. Nd6
{ White tries their best to maintain the bind. } 17... Rd7
{ Black is ready to play Bc6/b6 and break free. Let's not forget that Black is having a material advantage. }
18. Bb2
{ This was necessary as White cannot take on b7 with either piece as Black would play Rb8, and later Nc2 might trap the a1 rook. }
18... Nc6
{ The engine says this is an equal position as Black has various plans to break White's domination in the center. Plans like Nd8-Bc6 and b6 are something that White will have to watch out for. }
19. e5
{ Naturally, this looked critical and scary to me. If I am playing Black, this will be the only move that I could be worried about. White wants to play e6 next. }
19... Nb4 20. Bc4
{ After  20.Bxb7  Rb8  21.Be4  Rc7  White loses their pawns, and Black's rooks occupy the open file giving them an advantage. }
20... b5
{ That's our get out of jail free card! Black is targetting the pawn on c5 and opening up files for the rooks. }
21. Nxb5
{ If the bishop moves, then after Rc7 White will lose a pawn. After  21.cxb6  axb6  White loses the grip in the center while Black manages to open up the files for their rooks. }
21... Bxb5 22. Bxb5 Rd5
{ Finally, the center dissolves, and Black's rooks get on the open files. Due to the pair of bishops, White still has compensation which will be enough to make a draw but nothing beyond that. }
