[White "Quickstarter: The Catalan"]
[Black "dxc5 endgame: 9.Nbd2 - 11.Bb2 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8.
Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 c3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Bb2
{ This is another critical line. The move  11.c4  does not have any independent value as  11...Bd7  12.Nb3  transposes to the mainline that is covered extensively in a different chapter.   12.Bb2  Be7  transposes to the line that we will be seeing now. }
11... Bd7
{ Natural and suits our repertoire. Black is finishing development, keeping in mind that White has some strategic weaknesses. }
12. c4
{ This is a tricky move order, and it's easy to get confused. White is playing like the main variation of this system, but without including Nb3-Be7. This keeps a tactical threat of Bxf6-Ne4 ideas open when Black loses a piece due to the double attack on f6 and d7. At this point, if White played  12.Nb3  then it would transpose into the mainline after  12...Be7  that is covered in another file. }
12... Be7
{ Fits into our repertoire. It's hard to find something more critical than  13.Nb3  that transposes to the mainline, which is covered in a different chapter.   Starting with  12...Rfc8  would be a blunder due to the above-mentioned threat of  13.Bxf6  gxf6  14.Ne4  which wins a piece.   12...Rfd8  13.Nb3  Be7  also gets us to the mainline, but the problem is in the mainline we are playing Rfc8 instead of Rfd8. So for our repertoire, we must start with 12...Be7. The idea is obvious we are getting away from the Bxf6-Ne4 trick and keeping the option open on where to keep our rooks. }
13. e4
{ 13.Nb3  Rfc8  and @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1bbppp/2n1pn2/8/2P5/5NP1/PB1NPPBP/R2R2K1 w - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13.c5  Rfc8  14.Nb3  are the main critical moves here, and both are covered under the mainline, starting with 11.Nb3. Only a few times this position was reached, and every time White played the critical 13.Nb3. }
13... Rfd8
{ Once again, let's remind ourselves that we have a strategic advantage, and White has a dynamic advantage. Our job is to stop White's threats, and then the broken pawn structure will speak for itself. }
14. e5 Ne8
{ It may look a bit passive at the first sight, but White has done nothing special to fix the weaknesses. Black is ready to bring the rook to c8 and start playing on the queenside. The knight on e8 is doing an excellent job of controlling the d6 square where the d2 knight is heading for.   After  15.Ne4  both the cool b6 with Rc8-Na5 ideas or the dynamic Nb4-Rc8 plans look fine for Black. }
