[White "Quickstarter: The Catalan"]
[Black "dxc5 endgame: 9.Nbd2 - 11.Ne1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8.
Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 c3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Ne1
{ The second most popular move after  11.Nb3  . White wants to get the knight to  d3  with a tempo. }
11... Rd8
{ Makes perfect sense to take over the d-file when White clearly doesn't want to fight for that.  11...Bd7  12.Rb1  is annoying because Black is unable to play  12...b6  as  13.Nb3  wins material. }
12. Nd3 Be7 13. Rb1
{ The main move in this position. White stops Black from playing Bd7.  13.Nb3  is covered in a different file.  13.Bb2  Bd7  we have already seen from 11.Bb2 move order. }
13... Nd5
{ Black exploits the fact that White did not bother to stop this move. The knight comes to the center, immediately attacking White's weak pawn on c3. }
14. Bb2 { 14.c4  Nc3  loses material due to the fork. } 14... Bd7
{ Keeping the knight on d5 to meet c4 with Ndb4. Black now develops peacefully with the standard Bd7-Rac8. It would be difficult for White to progress on the queenside as they would never like to part with the Catalan bishop by taking on d5, and they will be reluctant to allow Ndb4 after c4, which will allow some trades. }
15. Ba1
{ Playing c4 directly allows Ndb4, White now gets ready to play c4 next. }
15... b6 16. c4 Nf6
{ Black's job was to delay White's queenside play, job well done! White can't seize anything on the queenside, and Black is one move away from finishing development. As usual, White is lacking target while Black's pawn structure remains better. The fact that White has a tiny bit more space than Black compensates the worse pawn structure, and the position remains balanced. }
17. Nb3 { Threatening Ne5. } 17... Be8
{ It was also possible to play  17...Rac8  to get away from the pin. } 18. c5
Nd5
{ The knight gets back to d5, shutting the bishop on g2. White can get rid of his weak c5 pawn, but taking on b6 would make the a2 pawn a clear target. Though the position remains equal, I think Black keeps more practical chances to gain a slight edge here. Rodshtein,M  @@StartBracket@@2687@@EndBracket@@-Najer,E @@StartBracket@@2677@@EndBracket@@ Czech Republic 2017 }
