[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: The Catalan"]
[Black "dxc5 endgame 9.Nbd2 -11.Nb3 Be7 12.c4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8.
Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 c3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Nb3 Be7 12. c4
{ This is the second most popular move after  12.Nfd4  . White keeps their plans flexible. They can now develop the bishop on e3/f4/b2 or play a4-a5 or go for c5. Primarily, for now, they stopped Black from getting Nd5 ideas. }
12... Bd7
{ Black also has various plans at their disposal. Depending on how White develops Black will decide on their plans. Black's plans are as follows: Rac8-Rfd8-Be8 ideas, Rfc8-Be8-Nd8 ideas, playing b6 and restricting the knight on b3, playing e5, and taking the d4 square from White's knights.  Let us understand the position clearly. White's pieces have more free space, but Black has a better pawn structure. So, White's nature of advantage is dynamic while Black's advantage is static. That means if Black can finish the development and White doesn't take any action, then Black might even take over. }
13. Bb2
{ By far the most popular move. White stops e5 and gets ready to play c5 after Rac8. The seeming threat of Bxf6 and taking on d7 is not a threat as we will see in the next move. }
13... Rfc8
{ This move is very rare. More than 200 games reached this position, and this move was played only about 10 times so far.   However, it is gaining rapid popularity, and in the World Rapid and Blitz, every time this position was reached, Black opted for this move. Now that White committed to Bb2 and stopped the e5 plan, Black gets the forces to the queenside and goes for Be8 plans.   This is not a blunder. Black invites White to take on f6 and take on d7.   After  13...Rac8  White plays  14.c5  and gets a better version of a4 lines when they didn't have to play a4-a5 to stop Black from playing b6.   The traditional mainline is to play  13...Rfd8  when the line goes with  14.Nfd4  Rac8  15.Nb5  and White get a double bishop advantage by playing Nd6. Those positions are also playable, but I like this rare concrete approach, and I feel soon this will become the mainline instead of the traditional Rfd8. }
14. c5
{ This move is probably the most challenging. White tries to gain more space and eventually plans to get the knight to d6.   It didn't make sense to play  14.Nfd4  when Black was perfectly ready to meet it with  14...Nxd4  15.Bxd4  Bc6  and exchange the light-squared bishop. }
14... Be8
{ Moving away from Bxf6-Rxd7 ideas just in case and ready to charge with a5-a4 next. This position reached only twice in tournament games, and in both games, White opted for  15.Nfd2  . }
15. Nfd2
{ Consistent with the previous move. White aims to get the knight to d6.   After  15.Ne5  or  15.Nfd4  Black would gladly trade the knights and then exchange the light-squared bishop with  Bc6  , leaving White with weak kingside pawns. }
15... b6
{ Just on time. The evaluation of this variation is important for our 13...Rfc8 line. }
16. cxb6
{ Once again, the most critical line. White will get Nc4 with a tempo. After  16.Rac1  Nd5  Black is already slightly better since the pawn on a2 becomes a clear target, and White will not be able to take cxb6-axb6 for this reason. }
16... axb6
{ White must do something immediately. Otherwise, Black will play b5 and stop White from playing Nc4. }
17. Nc4
{ White makes sure either they pick up the pawn or get the knight to d6. }
17... Rab8 18. Nd6
{ White will get one of the bishops, and Black can decide which one to keep. }
18... Bxd6
{ The nature of the position is changing. White will get the static advantage of the bishop pair with no weaknesses. In return, Black gets the dynamic advantage by activating their rooks. So now time and speed are critical for Black. }
19. Rxd6 Na5
{ By threatening Rc2/Nc4, Black practically forces White to take on a5. It is also possible to play  19...Nd5  and after  20.Bxd5  exd5  21.Rxd5  f6  I don't think Black is ever going to lose the position, but there is no need for us to get there. There is a much better option. }
20. Nxa5 bxa5
{ Thanks to the active rooks, Black gets enough compensation for the bishop pair. }
21. Be5
{ White activates the bishop and plans to play Ra6 next. After  21.Rd2  Nd5  Black gets full compensation for White's bishop pair due to the active pieces. }
21... Rb4
{ Planning Ne4 ideas and keeping Ra4 options open. The pawn on a2 is an easier target than the pawn on a5. }
22. Rad1
{ 22.Ra6  a4  doesn't scare Black when the a4 pawn gets complete immunity. White now threatens Rd8, which would be fatal if Black doesn't take action. }
22... h6
{ Simple and effective. Black removes Rd8 threats by creating space for the king. }
23. Bf3 { White creates a space for the king and threatens Rd8 again. } 23...
Rb5
{ In the game Predke-Tari from FIDE Grand Swiss 2021, Black played the natural Kh7, which also holds. I think this move is more precise. Black now doesn't allow White to get Rd8 ideas. }
24. Ba1
{ Keeping an eye on the long diagonal, stopping Rb2, and once again planning Rd8. If White moves away from this diagonal then they are no longer threatening Rd8 as the knight on f6 is no longer under attack. }
24... Nd5 { No more Rd8 ideas! The knight blocks the connection. } 25. Kg2 Nb4
{ Black threatens to take on a2 and also gives a strategic threat. To play Nc2 and eliminate the dark square bishop in case of a3 or R1d2. Black fights on equal terms and conditions now, and the position remains equal. }
