e3
{ To make sure the knight can move once it is attacked. Srinath's Chessable course for White ends here with the following comment:   'At the outset White's advantage doesn't look great as the Knight on  c6  doesn't look stable. Indeed, it is only a small advantage. However, it is still an advantage.  17...Bb7  18.Nb4  Rfd8  19.a4  is a natural continuation after which White would likely continue with a5. The Knights and the light square Bishops are likely to be traded, leaving a position where White has these five connected pawns vs Black, whose e6 pawn and the a7 pawn will be on the weaker side. This gives White a slight edge and that typical two-results position. If White doesn't want to exchange too much and keep the position more alive, then Nd3 is also an option'.  However, we shall see Black has nothing to worry about in the upcoming position and can look forward to having a nice game. }
