[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Early Deviations: Overview"]
[Black "1) Early g3 lines: Overview #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. g3
{ 2.Nf3  d5  3.g3  is covered from a different move order and given below. }
2... d5 3. Bg2 { 3.Nf3  c5  4.Bg2  transposes to the mainline. } 3... c5
{ Typically our moves for the sidelines remain the same Nf6-d5-c5. We saw this in Part One of this course. In every sideline, we counter with the standard Nf6-d5-c5 plan. }
4. Nf3 cxd4
{ The perfect moment to take on d4. If the knight was on c6 already, then this would be reversed Grünfeld. That would also mean that when White takes Nxd4, and Black goes e5, White will have the important Grünfeld idea of taking Nxc6. Here that's not the case, which means we grab the center with e5 as soon as White takes Nxd4. }
5. O-O
{ The main move. White cunningly waits for Black to play Nc6 when he gets a perfect reverse Grünfeld with an extra tempo. }
5... h6
{ An excellent prophylactic move. Black does not commit with Nc6 to make sure after Nxd4, they can play e5, and White won't have Nxc6. Black also made sure not to play e6 so that they play e5 in one go, saving a tempo. Realizing that they will get full control over the center, black makes sure that the center is consolidated. This is done by playing h6! Chess is beautiful, isn't it? The move h6 tells the d5 pawn that I have got your back. The d5 pawn will be protected by the knight on f6, and the knight gets immunity from Bg5 thanks to h6 :@@EndBracket@@ }
6. Nxd4 e5
{ Just what we wanted. The white knight must retreat as Black has delayed Nc6, and there are no Bg5 ideas in the future. More on this variation is available in the corresponding chapter. }
