[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ The proper way to get to the Colle system. White refrains from playing c4 and develops his minor pieces first. There are usually two setups White opts for:  1.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3/O-O/c3/Nbd2 and fight for e4.   2.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3/O-O/b3/Bb2/Nbd2 and fight for e4. }
3... c5 { We stick to our fixed move order of Nf6-d5-c5 and grab the center. }
4. c4 cxd4 { Black wants to play against White's isolated pawn in the future. }
5. exd4
{ This position can come from Caro Kann @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.c4  Nf6  . Here more than 40000 games are played with  5.Nc3  and about only 1000 games played with  5.Nf3  , which is our current position. It shows White tries to avoid this position in Caro Kann. The main disadvantage of having Nf3 instead of Nc3 is that White is not putting enough pressure on the d5 pawn quickly. Thus, Black is not obliged to play e6. He has an ample choice here to get a comfortable position. }
5... g6
{ Among various other options, I like this simplistic approach of getting the bishop out from g7, from where it puts pressure on the d4 pawn. This entire line is covered with the usual crystal clear explanations in the main file. Black's position is easy to play with no weakness on the board. }
