[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Early Deviations: Overview"]
[Black "5) Colle System: Overview #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ The proper way to get to the Colle system. White refrains from playing c4 and develops his minor pieces first. There are usually two setups White opts for:  1.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3/O-O/c3/Nbd2 and fight for e4.   2.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3/O-O/b3/Bb2/Nbd2 and fight for e4. }
3... c5 { We stick to our fixed move order of Nf6-d5-c5 and grab the center. }
4. dxc5
{ In Chessable Masters 2021, Le Quang played this move 4 times. Thrice against Levon @@StartBracket@@ Game 1, Game 2, Game 3 @@EndBracket@@ and once against Wesley. }
4... e6 5. b4 a5
{ Black charges at the b4 pawn to put pressure on the c5 pawn. } 6. c3 axb4 7.
cxb4 b6 { The pawns are now collapsing. } 8. Bb5+
{ It is high time to make this trade. After  8.a4  bxc5  9.b5  c4!  White's light-squared bishop gets stuck. }
8... Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7
{ White cannot save the pawns, but they can create passed pawns on the queenside. }
10. a4 bxc5
{ Black gets a tremendous center, but in return, White gets strong connected passers on the queenside. }
11. b5 Bd6
{ There are some games with the dynamic g5 move, but I like this approach more where Black doesn't reveal their hand too early. After  11...g5  White is not obliged to castle quickly. By playing  11...Bd6  Black wants to play for e5, and only once White castles do we go for the attack with g5.  Note that Black's king is perfectly safe on e8 due to their massive control of the center. The position gets dynamic, but Black has nothing to worry about.  The upcoming middle game is analyzed with crystal clear explanations in the main file. }
