[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Early Deviations: Overview"]
[Black "6) Colle System: Overview #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ The proper way to get to the Colle system. White refrains from playing c4 and develops his minor pieces first. There are usually two setups White opts for:  1.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3/O-O/c3/Nbd2 and fight for e4.   2.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3/O-O/b3/Bb2/Nbd2 and fight for e4. }
3... c5 { We stick to our fixed move order of Nf6-d5-c5 and grab the center. }
4. c3
{ This move is prophylaxis against  4...Nc6  . White is ready to take  5.dxc5  and protect the c5 pawn with b4. }
4... e6
{ Usually, we are always playing Nc6 before e6, but this time White was ready to take on c5. }
5. Bd3 { 5.Nbd2  Nbd7  6.Bd3  transposes to 5.Bd3 lines. } 5... Nbd7
{ White typically fights for e4 and dxc5-b4 plans. The knight is ideally placed on d7 to meet both of them. We are ready to take with Nxc5 after dxc5 and prepare for White's e4 plans, as we plan to play b6-Bb7, taking control of the e4 square. }
6. Nbd2
{ 6.O-O  b6  7.Nbd2  will reach the same position covered from 6.Nbd2 move order. }
6... b6
{ It is important to deal with e4 plans before castling. Black gets their bishop out quickly. The move orders are of utmost importance in such openings.  Once Black has a clear concept about the initial move orders, they won't face any trouble or get into some odd transpositions.   Often we make automatic hand moves without understanding the intricacies, and that's usually the inception of getting an uncomfortable middlegame. }
7. O-O
{ Black was ready to meet  7.e4  with  7...cxd4  . There are some more details to know in this direction, but those are not difficult and are clearly explained in the main file. }
7... Bb7
{ Black takes control over the e4 square, making it difficult for White to develop the dark-squared bishop. After  8.Qe2  or  8.Re1  Black stops White from playing e4 by going  8...Ne4  . Only then do we concentrate on castling short by playing Bd6 next. Of course, in the main file, you get a larger picture with much more detailed explanations. }
