2... d5 3. Nf3
{ This could also come from the 2.Nf3-3.g2 move order. Incidentally, this is the move that was played in the Magnus - Nepo 2021 World Championship match, on game 6, when coincidentally I was commenting live with Judit. You can a have look, at that here for reference: @@LinkStart@@https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=crhU-pg7Rvw&t=8175s@@LinkEnd@@ }
3... c5
{ We fight for the center as fast as possible. This is the reason why 3.g3 is considered not the best way to get a Catalan setup. In game 6 of the World Championship match, Nepo decided to stick to his setup by playing  3...e6  . }
4. dxc5 { 4.Bg2  is covered via the 3.Bg2 move order. } 4... e6
{ We get a reversed Queens Gambit Accepted, where White got an extra g3. This is not particularly threatening as Black gets a strong center in return. }
5. c4
{ This is an inaccurate way of getting a Catalan. We will see why it is wrong and the move order subtleties soon. }
5... Bxc5 6. cxd5 { 6.Bg2  transposes to the 5.Bg2 line. } 6... Qb6
{ That's the point! Black takes advantage of the inaccuracy and forces White to play e3 by attacking the pawn on f2. }
7. e3 O-O
{ Playing energetically. With Rd8-Nxd5 coming and White being underdeveloped, Black gets a lovely position. }
