1. d4 Nf6 2. g3 { 2.Nf3  d5  3.g3  is covered via a different move order. }
2... d5 3. Nf3
{ This could also come from the 2.Nf3-3.g2 move order. Incidentally, this is the move that was played in the Magnus - Nepo 2021 World Championship match, on game 6, when coincidentally I was commenting live with Judit. You can a have look, at that here for reference: @@LinkStart@@https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=crhU-pg7Rvw&t=8175s@@LinkEnd@@ }
3... c5
{ We fight for the center as fast as possible. This is the reason why 3.g3 is considered not the best way to get a Catalan setup. In game 6 of the World Championship match, Nepo decided to stick to his setup by playing  3...e6  . }
4. c3
{ White is playing reverse Slav with a tempo up. This might not give Black an advantage, but we are definitely doing fine with any logical and normal move. }
4... Nc6 5. Bg2
{ 5.dxc5  would be a mistake as after  5...a5  , we get a reverse Slav where White has an extra g3 move. It turns out this extra move is in favor of Black as White won't get the usual Bf4 idea, as the pawn on g3 will block its retreat in the future. For this reason, the computer immediately gives an advantage to Black after  5.dxc5  . }
5... cxd4
{ The simplest solution. We want to get the light-squared bishop out before playing e6. Playing Bf5 right away isn't attractive due to dxc5 ideas. Hence, we first clarify the center. }
6. cxd4 Bf5
{ Getting ready to play e6 next. Black is not scared of Nh4 ideas as Be4 is available. }
7. Nc3 { 7.O-O  e6  8.Nc3  would transpose to the mainline. } 7... e6 8. Nh4
{ After  9.O-O  h6  , Black saves the bishop, which is amazingly placed on a long diagonal that cannot be challenged easily. Its counterpart on c1 won't have that kind of future, thanks to the pawn on g3.  Many games were played in this position, and Black had a fantastic result which is not surprising. White needs to solve the issue of the bishops @@StartBracket@@both are not playing@@EndBracket@@, and it doesn't seem trivial. The engine already prefers Black. }
8... Bg4
{ We won't give up the bishop before making some damage to the enemy camp. } 9.
h3 Bh5 10. g4 Bg6
{ After provoking h3-g4, Black is now ready to give up the bishop. The kingside gets opened up after Nxg6-hxg6, the f4 square remains weak. White has a double bishop but, they can't open up the game with e4 as that would make the d4 pawn weak. Black is doing fine, and the position remains dynamically balanced. }
