[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1: Early g3 lines"]
[Black "Early g3 lines: 3.Bg2 c5 4.Nf3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. g3 { 2.Nf3  d5  3.g3  is covered via a different move order. }
2... d5 3. Bg2 { 3.Nf3  c5  4.Bg2  transposes to the mainline. } 3... c5
{ Charging in the center immediately. Typically our moves for the sidelines remain the same Nf6-d5-c5. We saw this in Part 1 of this course. In every sideline, we counter with the standard Nf6-d5-c5 plan. }
4. Nf3
{ After  4.c3  Nc6  5.Nf3  , we get a position that we will see from the 3.c3 move order. After  4.c4  dxc4  5.Nf3  Black can play lazily with  5...e6  and get to our Catalan repertoire that is covered in a different file, or we can be brave and punish White's naive move order by going  5...Nc6  when we get a similar position, but the bishop on c8 remains active. The engine already prefers Black there. }
4... cxd4
{ The perfect moment to take on d4. If the knight was on c6 already, then this would be a Reversed Grünfeld. However, that would also mean when White takes Nxd4, and Black goes e5 White will have the important Grünfeld idea of taking Nxc6. Here that's not the case, which means we grab the center with e5 as soon as White takes Nxd4. }
5. O-O
{ The main move. White cunningly waits for Black to play Nc6 when they get a perfect Reversed Grünfeld with an extra tempo. }
5... h6
{ An excellent prophylactic move. Black does not commit with Nc6 to make sure that after Nxd4, we can play e5, and White won't have Nxc6. Black also made sure not to play e6 so that we play e5 in one go, saving a tempo. Realizing that eventually, we will get full control over the center, Black makes sure to consolidate the center. This is done by playing h6! Chess is beautiful, isn't it? The move h6 tells the d5 pawn that I have got your back. The d5 pawn will be protected by the knight on f6, and the knight gets immunity from Bg5 thanks to h6 :@@EndBracket@@ }
6. b3
{ White plays another waiting move. They are patiently waiting for Black to play Nc6 before taking on d4. However, that is not going to happen. }
6... e6 7. Bb2
{ Still, the cat and mouse game goes on. White waits for Nc6 while Black refrains from playing it. }
7... Bc5 8. Nxd4
{ Finally White gives up. It is clear that Black has more useful waiting moves than White. Taking on d4 with  8.Bxd4  doesn't help. Since after  8...Bxd4  Black will either get e5 or Nc6 with a tempo, based on how White recaptures. Once White has committed to b3, it doesn't make sense to trade the dark-squared bishop and weaken the c3-square. }
8... e5 9. Nf3
{ This way, White manages to force Black to play e4 and open up the dark-squared bishop and get an outpost on d4. }
9... e4 { No other choice. We need to save the pawn. } 10. Nd4
{ White has two big assets at this point. The knight on d4 and the bishop on b2, but they didn't come for free. They had to compromise with the center that is under Black's control, and also the bishop on g2 stares at the rocks of e4-d5 for now. Black's moves are rather easy, and we have more space. }
10... O-O { Black gets ready to protect the center with Nc6-Re8. } 11. c4
{ Charging at the center and trying to open the g2 bishop. Here Black has two moves that are equally good and tough to choose which one to opt for. }
11... Re8
{ I like this move more, as it gives more protection to the pawn on e4. There was nothing wrong with  11...Nc6  , when we could have the following variation,  12.cxd5  Qxd5  13.Nxc6  Qxc6  and with Bf5 coming next, the position remains balanced. }
12. cxd5
{ Neither  12.Nc3  dxc4  , nor  12.Na3  Nc6  was looking promising for White when the knight on d4 gets unstable, and the bishop on g2 remains shut. }
12... Nxd5
{ We see the point of Re8. Black was getting ready to take on d5 with the knight by giving protection to the e4 pawn. }
13. e3
{ After  13.Nc3  Nxc3  14.Bxc3  Bg4!  Black starts to put pressure on the e2 pawn. To avoid this, White starts with e3. }
13... Nd7 { Getting ready to bring more force towards the center. } 14. Nc3
Nxc3 15. Bxc3 Bf8
{ Black is ready to occupy the c5 square with the knight and aim at d3. The e4 pawn remains solid. Two Correspondence games in 2021 reached this position, and Black had no problems in holding them. It shows the solidity of his position.   White can get the e4 pawn if they want by playing  16.Qc2  Nc5  17.b4  Nd3  18.Bxe4  . However, after the trade on e4, White's king becomes too weak as the g2 bishop is gone. Black's bishop on c8 has no match, and although engines are giving equal, I would prefer Black. No wonder that in the correspondence games, no one dared to take that pawn. }
