[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 2: Colle System"]
[Black "Colle System 2.e3 d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. e3
{ This move order gives Black many options, and almost everything is fine for Black. Therefore this move order has never been popular at the top level. }
2... d5
{ It is easier when we play a similar setup in most lines. In Part One of this course, we have also seen Black sticking to Nf6-d5-c5 move order in all of the sidelines. }
3. Bd3
{ White gets the bishop out first, controlling Bf5. I agree with my friend GM Sam Shankland who rightly pointed out that  3.f4  is the worst way to play the Stonewall as it allows Black to play  3...Bf5  and White get into a worse position instantly.  3.Nf3  is covered via the 2.Nf3 move order. }
3... c5 4. c3
{ After  4.dxc5  e6  Black gets the pawn on c5, as  5.b4  a5  6.a3  runs into  6...axb4  7.axb4  b6  . It doesn't make sense to lock the c1 bishop and give the center to Black then fight for equality. I don't see this coming ever from any strong player. }
4... Nc6 { Threatening to play e5 next. } 5. f4
{ White goes for a Stonewall setup, but the most significant disadvantage is the Black bishop on c8 is not stuck as Black did not play e6 yet. }
5... Bg4
{ Immediately exploiting the move order finesse. Black gets the bishop out before playing e6. }
6. Nf3 e6
{ In his Semi-Slav course, Sam Shankland ended here saying, 'Again, White has a lousy Stonewall since Black's bishop is outside the pawn chain, and it will soon retreat to f5'. I have nothing to add to this apart from the computer evaluation of -1 in favor of Black :@@EndBracket@@ }
*

