[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 2: Colle System"]
[Black "Colle System 2.Nf3 d5 3.e3 c5 4.Bb5+ "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ The proper way to reach the Colle system. White refrains from playing c4 and develops the minor pieces first. There are usually two setups White opts for:  1.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3-O-O-c3-Nbd2 and fight for e4.   2.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3-O-O-b3-Bb2-Nbd2 and fight for e4.   Of course, there are various move orders to get there with many transpositions possible.  3.c3  has been played several times, but it doesn't have any independent value and gets transposed to different lines. For example,  3.c3  c5  4.Bf4  gets us to the London system covered in Part One of this course.  4.Bg5  transposes to Trompowski, also covered in Part One of this course.  4.e3  transposes to 3.e3 lines.  4.dxc5  e6  5.b4  a5  once again transposes to a line that is covered from 3.e3 move order. }
3... c5 { We stick to our fixed move order of Nf6-d5-c5 and grab the center. }
4. Bb5+
{ This move is a rare guest at the master level. I don't understand the purpose of this move at all. First, White blocks the dark-squared bishop with e3 then exchanges the good light-squared bishop. Usually, I would never analyze such moves, but I will give a sample line just for the sake of completeness. }
4... Bd7 { Of course, we don't mind exchanging White's good bishop. } 5. Bxd7+
{ It baffles me that twice, this position was reached by players above 2500! }
5... Nbxd7 6. O-O
{ Probably the only trick White has in this position; to get a quick c4 and play for rapid development. }
6... Rc8
{ Anticipating c4, Black brings his rook to c8. Now, c4 would lose a pawn after dxc4. Black is ready to play e6-Be7-O-O and White is stuck with his bad bishop on c1. Black already got some advantage due to White's poor strategic play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 2: Colle System"]
[Black "Colle System 2.Nf3 d5 3.e3 c5 4.Bd3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ The proper way to reach the Colle system. White refrains from playing c4 and develops the minor pieces first. There are usually two setups White opts for:  1.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3-O-O-c3-Nbd2 and fight for e4.   2.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3-O-O-b3-Bb2-Nbd2 and fight for e4.   Of course, there are various move orders to get there with many transpositions possible.  3.c3  has been played several times, but it doesn't have any independent value and gets transposed to different lines. For example,  3.c3  c5  4.Bf4  gets us to the London system covered in Part One of this course.  4.Bg5  transposes to Trompowski, also covered in Part One of this course.  4.e3  transposes to 3.e3 lines.  4.dxc5  e6  5.b4  a5  once again transposes to a line that is covered from 3.e3 move order. }
3... c5 { We stick to our fixed move order of Nf6-d5-c5 and grab the center. }
4. Bd3 Nc6
{ Black plays in the simple manner of controlling the center and keeping the bishop on c8 open. }
5. O-O
{ 5.c3  transposes to a line that is covered via the 2.e3 move order. After  5.b3  cxd4!  6.exd4  Bg4  White faces some issues to support the pawn on d4 due to  7.Bb2  Qa5  . }
5... Bg4
{ With the bishop on d3, the pin on the knight becomes especially annoying. Black is preparing to play e6 and get the other bishop out. }
6. c3 e6
{ Black has better center control, and White's bishop on c1 is not getting out easily. Black already has an advantage. }
