[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 2: Colle System"]
[Black "Colle System 2.Nf3 d5 3.e3 c5 4.Be2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ The proper way to reach the Colle system. White refrains from playing c4 and develops the minor pieces first. There are usually two setups White opts for:  1.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3-O-O-c3-Nbd2 and fight for e4.   2.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3-O-O-b3-Bb2-Nbd2 and fight for e4.   Of course, there are various move orders to get there with many transpositions possible.  3.c3  has been played several times, but it doesn't have any independent value and gets transposed to different lines. For example,  3.c3  c5  4.Bf4  gets us to the London system covered in Part One of this course.  4.Bg5  transposes to Trompowski, also covered in Part One of this course.  4.e3  transposes to 3.e3 lines.  4.dxc5  e6  5.b4  a5  once again transposes to a line that is covered from 3.e3 move order. }
3... c5 { We stick to our fixed move order of Nf6-d5-c5 and grab the center. }
4. Be2
{ Ideas are similar to  4.Bd3  , but White is better prepared for Bg4 plans this time. }
4... Nc6 5. O-O Bf5
{ This time f5 square is available for the bishop, and Black encashes that. }
6. dxc5
{ 6.a3  e5  7.dxc5  Bxc5  has been discussed from 6.dxc5 move order.   After  6.c4  dxc4  7.Bxc4  e6  Black is ready for Be7-O-O, and the bishop is out on f5 while its counterpart remains shut on c1. }
6... e6 7. Nd4
{ The only move that could look scary. White threatens to take on f5. after  7.a3  Bxc5  8.b4  Be7  Black is ready to castle and keeps a strong center with zero weaknesses in the position. }
7... Bxc5
{ Black is ready to break the pawn structure and give up the bishop. This looks illogical, but the key factor is that the bishop on c1 is having trouble getting out. }
8. Nxf5 exf5
{ White is never getting e4 in this game ever now. The only route for the c1 bishop remains via b2. }
9. b3
{ It is not the best move in the position but a human response. The best option according to the engine is  9.Qd3  Qd7  10.c4  when Black plays  10...Ne5  and has no problem as we can either play d4 next and play against e2 bishop or take twice on c4 and collect the light-squared bishop. }
9... O-O 10. Bb2 d4
{ Breaking the center at the right moment when White is behind the development. }
11. exd4 Nxd4
{ Black dominates the center while White's queenside pieces are not coming out.  12.Bd3  looks natural, but after  12...Qd6  , it gets insanely challenging to withstand the pressure in the open files with Rad8 coming and kingside attacking plans with Ng4-g3-Qh6. Black stands clearly better now. }
