3... c5 { We stick to our fixed move order of Nf6-d5-c5 and grab the center. }
4. Nbd2 { White prepares to take on c5 and support the pawn with his knight. }
4... cxd4
{ Perfect timing. The knight on d2 now becomes misplaced as it blocks the bishop on c1. }
5. exd4 Qc7
{ A fine waiting move. White was waiting for Black to play  5...Nc6  and opt for  6.Bb5  a6  7.Bxc6  bxc6  8.c4  . By starting with Qc7, Black improves his position and waits for White to commit with his light square bishop or play c3. There are hardly any other useful moves left. }
6. Bd3 Nc6
{ Black finishes the queenside development first before playing e6. } 7. c3
{ 7.O-O  Bg4  8.c3  transposes to 7.c3 lines. } 7... Bg4
{ Black is now ready to play e6. } 8. O-O
{ Trying to counter pin with  8.Qa4  with the idea that playing Ne5 does not work as Black responds with  8...Nd7  9.O-O  e6  when White has the usual trouble with the dark-squared bishop development. }
8... e6 9. Re1 { Getting ready for Nf1 after Bd6. } 9... Bd6 10. Nf1 O-O
{ It is equally possible to play  10...O-O-O  and get a dynamic position. } 11.
Bg5 { The only decent square available for the bishop. } 11... Bh5
{ Black is ready to change White's good bishop with Bg6 whenever we feel like it. Bxf6-gxf6 only worsens White's position when Black gets total control in the center and White has no kingside attacking plans. }
