[Black "Colle System 2.Nf3 d5 3.e3 c5 4.dxc5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ The proper way to reach the Colle system. White refrains from playing c4 and develops the minor pieces first. There are usually two setups White opts for:  1.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3-O-O-c3-Nbd2 and fight for e4.   2.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3-O-O-b3-Bb2-Nbd2 and fight for e4.   Of course, there are various move orders to get there with many transpositions possible.  3.c3  has been played several times, but it doesn't have any independent value and gets transposed to different lines. For example,  3.c3  c5  4.Bf4  gets us to the London system covered in Part One of this course.  4.Bg5  transposes to Trompowski, also covered in Part One of this course.  4.e3  transposes to 3.e3 lines.  4.dxc5  e6  5.b4  a5  once again transposes to a line that is covered from 3.e3 move order. }
3... c5 { We stick to our fixed move order of Nf6-d5-c5 and grab the center. }
4. dxc5
{ In Chessable Masters 2021, Le Quang played this move 4 times. Thrice against Levon and once against Wesley. }
4... e6 { Of course, we want to take the pawn back immediately. } 5. b4
{ White is not giving up the pawn easily. } 5... a5
{ Black charges the b4 pawn to put pressure on the c5 pawn. } 6. c3 axb4 7.
cxb4 b6 { The pawns are now collapsing. } 8. Bb5+
{ It is high time to make this trade. After  8.a4  bxc5  9.b5  c4!  White's light-squared bishop got stuck, and Black got an edge in the game So, W @@StartBracket@@2815@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2832@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2017 }
8... Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7
{ White cannot save the pawns, but they can create passed pawns on the queenside. }
10. a4 bxc5
{ Black gets a tremendous center, but in return, White gets strong connected passed pawns on the queenside. }
11. b5 Bd6
{ There are some games with the dynamic g5 move, but I like this approach more where Black doesn't show their hands too early. After  11...g5  White is not obliged to castle quickly. By playing  11...Bd6  Black wants to play for e5, and only once White castles would they go for the attack with g5. Note that Black's king is perfectly safe on e8 due to their massive control in the center. }
12. Bb2 { 12.O-O  Qc7  13.Bb2  transposes to 12.Bb2. } 12... Qc7
{ Black keeps waiting for White to castle. It is hard for White to wait for a long time as Black also wants to grab more space in the center with e5-e4. }
13. O-O g5 { Now is the time to go for a kingside attack. } 14. g3
{ After  14.Nxg5  Bxh2  15.Kh1  Be5  White's king won't feel super safe on the kingside with the open g-file. }
14... g4 15. Nh4 Be5
{ The knight on h4 is out of play, Black has a fantastic center, and the king remains safe on e7. White's queenside pawns are not moving. Engines rightly claim Black has a good initiative here. }
