1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ The proper way to reach the Colle system. White refrains from playing c4 and develops the minor pieces first. There are usually two setups White opts for:  1.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3-O-O-c3-Nbd2 and fight for e4.   2.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3-O-O-b3-Bb2-Nbd2 and fight for e4.   Of course, there are various move orders to get there with many transpositions possible.  3.c3  has been played several times, but it doesn't have any independent value and gets transposed to different lines. For example,  3.c3  c5  4.Bf4  gets us to the London system covered in Part One of this course.  4.Bg5  transposes to Trompowski, also covered in Part One of this course.  4.e3  transposes to 3.e3 lines.  4.dxc5  e6  5.b4  a5  once again transposes to a line that is covered from 3.e3 move order. }
3... c5 { We stick to our fixed move order of Nf6-d5-c5 and grab the center. }
4. c4 cxd4 { Black wants to play against White's isolated pawn in the future. }
5. exd4
{ This position can come from Caro Kann @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.c4  Nf6  . Here more than 40000 games are played with  5.Nc3  and about only 1000 games played with  5.Nf3  , which is our current position. It shows White tries to avoid this position in Caro Kann. The main disadvantage of having Nf3 instead of Nc3 is that White is not putting enough pressure on the d5 pawn quickly. Thus, Black is not obliged to play e6. We have plenty of choices here to get a comfortable position. }
5... g6
{ Among various other options, I like this simplistic approach of getting the bishop out from g7, from where it puts pressure on the d4 pawn. }
6. Nc3 { 6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.Nc3  Bg7  transposes to 6.Nc3 line. } 6... Bg7 7. Bg5
{ White wants to take the d5 pawn by taking on f6 next. } 7... O-O
{ A fantastic move, completely ignoring White's threat. } 8. Bxf6
{ Otherwise his previous move had no point. } 8... exf6
{ It is important to play for White's king on e1. Black opens up the e-file, and also, the pawn on f6 controls the knight on f3. }
9. Nxd5
{ After  9.cxd5  Nd7  Black will eventually get back the pawn and White will remain with an isolated pawn. }
9... Nc6 { Developing harmoniously and putting pressure on the d4 pawn. } 10.
Be2 f5 { Black keeps increasing the pressure on the d4 pawn. } 11. O-O Be6
{ Finally, White must give the pawn back and will remain in a passive position. }
