[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ The proper way to reach the Colle system. White refrains from playing c4 and develops the minor pieces first. There are usually two setups White opts for:  1.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3-O-O-c3-Nbd2 and fight for e4.   2.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3-O-O-b3-Bb2-Nbd2 and fight for e4.   Of course, there are various move orders to get there with many transpositions possible.  3.c3  has been played several times, but it doesn't have any independent value and gets transposed to different lines. For example,  3.c3  c5  4.Bf4  gets us to the London system covered in Part One of this course.  4.Bg5  transposes to Trompowski, also covered in Part One of this course.  4.e3  transposes to 3.e3 lines.  4.dxc5  e6  5.b4  a5  once again transposes to a line that is covered from 3.e3 move order. }
3... c5 { We stick to our fixed move order of Nf6-d5-c5 and grab the center. }
4. c4 cxd4 { Black wants to play against White's isolated pawn in the future. }
5. exd4
{ This position can come from Caro Kann @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.c4  Nf6  . Here more than 40000 games are played with  5.Nc3  and about only 1000 games played with  5.Nf3  , which is our current position. It shows White tries to avoid this position in Caro Kann. The main disadvantage of having Nf3 instead of Nc3 is that White is not putting enough pressure on the d5 pawn quickly. Thus, Black is not obliged to play e6. We have plenty of choices here to get a comfortable position. }
5... g6
{ Among various other options, I like this simplistic approach of getting the bishop out from g7, from where it puts pressure on the d4 pawn. }
6. Nc3 { 6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.Nc3  Bg7  transposes to 6.Nc3 line. } 6... Bg7 7. Be2
{ White wants to finish castling quickly. } 7... O-O
{ Black's play remains simple and straightforward. } 8. O-O Nc6
{ It was also possible to play  8...dxc4  and play against White's isolated pawn. White's play has been so naive that Black can play almost anything and get a fine position. Black has two strong plans now:   1. Take on c4 and play Na5-Be6 next.   2. Play Bg4 and put pressure on the d4 pawn. }
9. Be3
{ White compromises their bishop's ideal position but over-protects the weak d4-pawn. }
9... dxc4
{ After  9...Bg4  10.c5  Ne4  this time, White is ready as the bishop is already on e3. However, the bishop on e3 Black has another trick available with dxc4-Ng4 ideas. }
10. d5 { After  10.Bxc4  Ng4  White loses the bishop on e3. } 10... Na5
{ Black saves the pawn on c4. White must do something immediately not to remain a pawn down for nothing. }
11. b4 { Going for the knight on a5. } 11... cxb3 12. axb3
{ Threatening to trap the knight on a5 with b4. } 12... Nxd5
{ There are many other moves to get a fine position, but this one is the most forcing.  12...Bf5  or  12...Bg4  also gives Black a dynamically balanced position. }
13. Nxd5 { Now the play becomes very forcing for both sides. } 13... Bxa1 14.
Qxa1 Qxd5
{ White is heavily materially down, and if we don't find anything immediate, we will be lost. }
15. Bh6 { Threatening mate in one. } 15... f6 { Only move, but a logical one. }
16. Rd1
{ Only move to keep the game balanced.  16.Bxf8  Kxf8  doesn't bother Black as we remain two pawns up. }
16... Qc5 { The most active square available. } 17. b4
{ Once again, White must find this only move to make a draw. After  17.Bxf8  Kxf8  18.Rd8  Kg7  19.Nd4  Black goes  19...Qc7  when White is obliged to play  20.Ne6  Bxe6  21.Rxa8  and Black take  21...Nxb3  when only Black can be better. }
17... Qxb4 18. Qa2+ Nb3
{ Shutting the diagonal to make sure the queen remains out of play. } 19. Bxf8
Kxf8
{ White is now three pawns down, but they have a precise way to make a draw. }
20. Rd8+ Kg7 21. Bd1
{ Attacking the knight on b3, which cannot move due to Qg8 check. White did not find this only move in the game 0-1 Inkiov, V @@StartBracket@@2455@@EndBracket@@-Gharamian, T @@StartBracket@@2581@@EndBracket@@ France 2009, and lost after  21.Re8  Be6  22.Rxa8  Nd4  when Black had a huge material advantage. }
21... Qb6 { Chasing the rook out from d8. } 22. Re8
{ White cant leave the back rank, and this is the only square available. }
22... Kf7 { The rook comes under attack once again. } 23. Rh8
{ Once again the only square available. } 23... Kg7
{ White must play Re8 again, and the position repeats. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 2: Colle System"]
[Black "Colle System 2.Nf3 d5 3.e3 c5 4.b3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ The proper way to reach the Colle system. White refrains from playing c4 and develops the minor pieces first. There are usually two setups White opts for:  1.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3-O-O-c3-Nbd2 and fight for e4.   2.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3-O-O-b3-Bb2-Nbd2 and fight for e4.   Of course, there are various move orders to get there with many transpositions possible.  3.c3  has been played several times, but it doesn't have any independent value and gets transposed to different lines. For example,  3.c3  c5  4.Bf4  gets us to the London system covered in Part One of this course.  4.Bg5  transposes to Trompowski, also covered in Part One of this course.  4.e3  transposes to 3.e3 lines.  4.dxc5  e6  5.b4  a5  once again transposes to a line that is covered from 3.e3 move order. }
3... c5 { We stick to our fixed move order of Nf6-d5-c5 and grab the center. }
4. b3 { Trying to get the bishop out from b2. } 4... cxd4
{ Nice timing. White's bishop will now look stupid on b2, with their own pawn blocking on d4. If the bishop develops on the other diagonal in f4/g5, the c3 square becomes a target. }
5. exd4 Nc6
{ Black intends to bring the light-squared bishop out and play e6. } 6. Bd3
{ After  6.Bb2  Bf5  Black has solved the bishop issues, but White will struggle a long time with their dark-squared bishop. }
6... Bg4 7. Bb2
{ The bishop on b2 is worse, but White also faces some direct issues now. }
7... Qa5+
{ It is very difficult for White to block this check as he can't play  8.c3  due to  8...Nxd4  . After  8.Bc3  Qc7  , the bishop on c3, remains vulnerable. }
8. Nbd2 Nb4
{ Black's play seems very direct, and if they don't get the bishop on d3 soon, the pieces will have to come back. }
9. Be2 { Otherwise White loses the bishop on d3. } 9... Bxf3
{ A very easy move to miss. It has never occurred in tournament practice yet. This highly anti-positional move wins immediately for Black tactically. }
10. Bxf3
{ There was no other good way to take the bishop. White is strategically clearly better now, but the next move spoils the fun for White. }
10... Qc7
{ There is no way to save the pawn on c2 for White. They can't move the c-pawn due to the Nd3 fork while Rc1 runs into Nxa2. Black wins a pawn and gets a winning position. }
*

