1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ The proper way to reach the Colle system. White refrains from playing c4 and develops the minor pieces first. There are usually two setups White opts for:  1.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3-O-O-c3-Nbd2 and fight for e4.   2.@@EndBracket@@ Bd3-O-O-b3-Bb2-Nbd2 and fight for e4.   Of course, there are various move orders to get there with many transpositions possible.  3.c3  has been played several times, but it doesn't have any independent value and gets transposed to different lines. For example,  3.c3  c5  4.Bf4  gets us to the London system covered in Part One of this course.  4.Bg5  transposes to Trompowski, also covered in Part One of this course.  4.e3  transposes to 3.e3 lines.  4.dxc5  e6  5.b4  a5  once again transposes to a line that is covered from 3.e3 move order. }
3... c5 { We stick to our fixed move order of Nf6-d5-c5 and grab the center. }
4. c3
{ This move is prophylaxis against  4...Nc6  when White is ready to take  5.dxc5  and protect the c5 pawn with b4. }
4... e6
{ Usually, we are always playing Nc6 before e6, but this time White was ready to take on c5. }
5. Bd3 { 5.Nbd2  Nbd7  6.Bd3  transposes to 5.Bd3 line. } 5... Nbd7
{ White typically fights for e4 and dxc5-b4 plans. The knight is ideally placed on d7 to meet both of them. Black is ready to take Nxc5 after dxc5 and counter e4 plans, and then we plan to play b6-Bb7, taking control of the e4 square. }
6. Nbd2
{ 6.O-O  b6  7.Nbd2  will reach the same position covered from 6.Nbd2 move order. }
6... b6
{ It is important to deal with e4 plans before castling. Black gets the bishop out quickly. }
7. O-O { 7.Qe2  Bb7  8.O-O  transposes to 7.O-O line. } 7... Bb7
{ Black takes control over the e4 square, which makes it difficult for White to develop the dark-squared bishop. }
8. Qe2
{ After  8.Re1  Ne4  White is not getting the  e4  break in the near future, and the bishop on c1 remains passive. }
8... Ne4 { Simplest. Don't allow White to play e4. } 9. c4
{ The only other way White can hope to break the center. } 9... Bd6
{ The e6 pawn nicely protects the pawn on d5. Black can ignore White's play in the center and finally focus on castling. }
10. cxd5 exd5 11. b3 O-O
{ Black keeps good control in the center, and all of our pieces are harmoniously developed. White's opening strategy has failed miserably, and it is easier to play from the Black side. }
