[Black "4) Queen's Gambit Declined: Overview "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5
{ The Queens Gambit Declined is especially effective when White has committed his knight to f3. This way, White never gets the dangerous Bd3-Ne2 setup.   The major moves in this position are:  -  4.Nc3  when we opt for Semi-Tarrasch with  4...c5  .   -  4.g3  getting into a Catalan System.   These two lines are covered in various chapters with separate overviews. Right now, we will focus on all other moves apart from  4.Nc3  and  4.g3  . }
4. cxd5
{ This is the best example where the knight on f3 is misplaced. White's best setup in Exchange QGD is to get Bd3-Ne2-O-O-f3 ideas. With already committed Nf3, White is missing this formation. }
4... exd5 5. Nc3 { The most popular move in the position. } 5... c6
{ It is the ideal pawn formation. This position can also come from Semi-Slav @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  c6  @@EndBracket@@, where taking on d5 is not the main or critical move. }
6. Bg5
{ Once again, the most popular move in the position. White gets the bishop out before playing e3. }
6... h6
{ The most popular move is Be7 in the position, but h6 is the modern treatment of this line, and we sidestep a colossal amount of theory this way. Black wants to develop the bishop to its ideal square on d6. }
7. Bh4 Bf5
{ The move order is very important here. Playing Bf5 is a dream for Black as the bishop gets to its perfect square. However, every time Black plays Bf5, they must be prepared to deal with Qb3 ideas. }
8. Qb3 g5
{ Getting rid of Bxf6 ideas before getting Qb6. This is why including h6 was important. }
9. Bg3
{ After  9.Qxb7??  gxh4  10.Qxa8  Qb6  White's queen remains trapped on a8. }
9... Qb6
{ Black solved the queenside issues without making a single compromise. White will never get b4-b5 ideas now, and they also lack breaks in the center. Black is already slightly better. }
