[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Queen's Gambit Declined: Overview"]
[Black "9) Queen's Gambit Declined: Overview "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5
{ The Queens Gambit Declined is especially effective when White has committed his knight to f3. This way, White never gets the dangerous Bd3-Ne2 setup.   The major moves in this position are:  -  4.Nc3  when we opt for Semi-Tarrasch with  4...c5  .   -  4.g3  getting into a Catalan System.   These two lines are covered in various chapters with separate overviews. Right now, we will focus on all other moves apart from  4.Nc3  and  4.g3  . }
4. e3
{ White is ready for  4...c5  with  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.e4  when Black is missing Nxc3 compared to 4.Nc3 lines. }
4... Be7
{ Black keeps c5 ideas in the back pocket and first goes for a quick short castle. }
5. b3
{ Preparing such lines can be tricky as one can feel overwhelmed and drowned in the immense number of the various move orders.  It can be very frustrating to deal with the different permutations and combinations.   My first job was to weed out all of these move order issues and create a file that is easy to understand. White will eventually make the moves Bd3-O-O-Bb2, which can happen in every permutation and combination.  Essentially the choice is to put the b1 knight on c3 or d2. To avoid any further confusion, I kept all of the lines under the 6. Bd3-O-O-Bb2 move order only. After this, I gave the option of Nbd2/Nc3. No matter what move order White chooses, our setup remains the same with O-O-c5-cxd4-b6. This renders the preparation part much easier. }
5... O-O 6. Bd3
{ The move order issues are taken care of, so you can relax and ignore the oceans of different move orders like Nc3/Nbd2/Bd3/Bb2 in every position. }
6... c5
{ Black's response remains the same irrespective of White's Bb2/Bd3/Nc3/Nbd2 move order. This way, it is also very easy to prepare and understand the ideas. We strike at the center no matter what. }
7. cxd5
{ This rare move has been faced by Levon and Radek. Unfortunately, in both cases, Black missed a nice trick here. }
7... cxd4 8. dxe6 dxe3
{ What a lovely position to get after 8 moves :@@EndBracket@@ It turns out Black is already better in this direction. More on this in the main file :@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Queen's Gambit Declined: Overview"]
[Black "10) Queen's Gambit Declined: Overview "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5
{ The Queens Gambit Declined is especially effective when White has committed his knight to f3. This way, White never gets the dangerous Bd3-Ne2 setup.   The major moves in this position are:  -  4.Nc3  when we opt for Semi-Tarrasch with  4...c5  .   -  4.g3  getting into a Catalan System.   These two lines are covered in various chapters with separate overviews. Right now, we will focus on all other moves apart from  4.Nc3  and  4.g3  . }
4. e3
{ White is ready for  4...c5  with  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.e4  when Black is missing Nxc3 compared to 4.Nc3 lines. }
4... Be7
{ Black keeps c5 ideas in the back pocket and first goes for a quick short castle. }
5. b3
{ Preparing such lines can be tricky as one can feel overwhelmed and drowned in the immense number of the various move orders.  It can be very frustrating to deal with the different permutations and combinations.   My first job was to weed out all of these move order issues and create a file that is easy to understand. White will eventually make the moves Bd3-O-O-Bb2, which can happen in every permutation and combination.  Essentially the choice is to put the b1 knight on c3 or d2. To avoid any further confusion, I kept all of the lines under the 6. Bd3-O-O-Bb2 move order only. After this, I gave the option of Nbd2/Nc3. No matter what move order White chooses, our setup remains the same with O-O-c5-cxd4-b6. This renders the preparation part much easier. }
5... O-O 6. Bd3
{ The move order issues are taken care of, so you can relax and ignore the oceans of different move orders like Nc3/Nbd2/Bd3/Bb2 in every position. }
6... c5
{ Black's response remains the same irrespective of White's Bb2/Bd3/Nc3/Nbd2 move order. This way, it is also very easy to prepare and understand the ideas. We strike at the center no matter what. }
7. O-O cxd4 8. exd4 b6 9. Bb2 Bb7
{ Finally, we reached the position which could have occurred in many different ways. White can now keep their knight on c3 or d2. The bishop on b7 is stronger than the bishop on b2 as Black can open up the bishop by taking on c4 while White doesn't have that privilege.   Just like playing Nc3 or Nbd2 doesn't change anything in terms of the evaluation of the position, the same applies for Black also, and we can choose either way of developing the knight. I would like to have one way of developing to avoid confusion.  I like the knight on c6, directly putting pressure on the d4 pawn. So, irrespectively of how White plays, I would like to put my knight on c6. Also, to provide a general picture of the position: Even with White to play engines think this position is 0.00.   More details and middlegame plans are given in the main file. }
