[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Queen's Gambit Declined: Overview"]
[Black "11) Queen's Gambit Declined: Overview "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5
{ The Queens Gambit Declined is especially effective when White has committed his knight to f3. This way, White never gets the dangerous Bd3-Ne2 setup.   The major moves in this position are:  -  4.Nc3  when we opt for Semi-Tarrasch with  4...c5  .   -  4.g3  getting into a Catalan System.   These two lines are covered in various chapters with separate overviews. Right now, we will focus on all other moves apart from  4.Nc3  and  4.g3  . }
4. Bg5
{ A super tricky line where Black can transpose into various lines like the Ragozin, QGD, Semi-Slav, Vienna, Moscow, etc. None of these are part of our repertoire, and we keep our repertoire unique so that we don't need to learn another extensive line.   4.Nbd2  and  4.b3  are harmless, as Black get to open up the center with  4...c5  . Further details are given in the main file. }
4... dxc4 5. Nc3
{ Currently we transposed into the Vienna system @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  d5  4.Nc3  dxc4  , but here White went with the lesser popular  5.Bg5  @@StartBracket@@instead of  5.e4  @@EndBracket@@.   Black has a plethora of options here; we could play:  ➫  5...Bb4  and get a Ragozin.  ➫  5...c6  and get a Botvinnik system.  ➫  5...Be7  and get a worse version of QGD.  So how do we play then? We keep our repertoire unique and independent by going  5...a6  here :@@EndBracket@@ }
5... a6
{ This has been played by Gelfand, Ding, Anand, etc. Black is forcing White to get into foreign territory.   The idea is straightforward - Black wants to play b5 and protect the c4 pawn. }
6. a4
{ Stopping b5 and planning e4.   After  6.e4  b5  , the position resembles the Botvinnik system, but it is not the same. There is a huge difference that works in Black's favor. Instead of c6, Black played a6, which means the bishop on b7 will be open. This changes everything. }
6... Nc6
{ Now we save the pawn with Na5 and get an excellent position avoiding a colossal amount of theory.   These positions are analyzed in detail in the main file. White should be careful so they don't end up with a worse position. }
