[Black "13) Queen's Gambit Declined: Overview "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5
{ The Queens Gambit Declined is especially effective when White has committed his knight to f3. This way, White never gets the dangerous Bd3-Ne2 setup.   The major moves in this position are:  -  4.Nc3  when we opt for Semi-Tarrasch with  4...c5  .   -  4.g3  getting into a Catalan System.   These two lines are covered in various chapters with separate overviews. Right now, we will focus on all other moves apart from  4.Nc3  and  4.g3  . }
4. Bg5
{ A super tricky line where Black can transpose into various lines like the Ragozin, QGD, Semi-Slav, Vienna, Moscow, etc. None of these are part of our repertoire, and we keep our repertoire unique so that we don't need to learn another extensive line.   4.Nbd2  and  4.b3  are harmless, as Black get to open up the center with  4...c5  . Further details are given in the main file. }
4... dxc4 5. e4
{ We will discuss two main moves,  5.e4  and  5.Nc3  . All other moves are considered in the main file extensively. }
5... c5
{ I like this move the most as it keeps our repertoire once again unique and independent. }
6. Nc3
{ White protects the e4 pawn getting ready to meet  6...cxd4  with  7.Qxd4  , when the e4 pawn won't be hanging. }
6... cxd4 7. Qxd4
{ This was the main point of playing 6.Nc3. White tries to take the lead in development. }
7... Qxd4 8. Nxd4 a6 { Stopping Nb5 ideas. } 9. Bxc4
{ I love this trend where the game is going because it is easy to relax from the White side, assuming they are better. In reality, White should be careful as their pieces will soon have to run away.  This is the starting position of the main file. It will give you a clear picture of how to play these positions logically and effortlessly. }
9... h6
{ An important improvement over the Dubov-Radjabov game that was played in 2021 Opera Euro Rapid. Radjabov played  9...Nbd7  , which allowed White to consolidate with  10.f3  . It is very important to start chasing White's pieces immediately.    At first glance, it feels that White should be better because they are way ahead in development. They have developed four minor pieces and are just one move away from castling, while Black has developed only one minor piece and is two moves away from castling. Also, White has better center control.   However, when we think deeper, things change drastically. The main issue is White's pieces; although nicely developed, they lack targets and can be attacked by the black army. The bishop on g5 is chased away with h6 and lacks a good retreating square. The bishop on c4 will also be chased away by b5 and again will have difficulty finding a good square. The e4 pawn comes under attack immediately with the help of b5-Bb7 and b4 ideas. The knight on d4 can also be targetted with Bc5.   So, although at present Black is underdeveloped on paper, we will soon start gaining many tempos. }
