1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5
{ We will see various options on the 4th move in this chapter. This will not include 4.e3/Bg5/g3/Nc3 as those are covered separately in other chapters. }
4. a3
{ This move prepares c5. Given a chance, White might play c5 as they are ready to protect the pawn with b4. }
4... dxc4
{ Black takes advantage of the non-developing move 4.a3 and changes the pattern of the game by opening up the position. }
5. Qa4+ { Trying to take back the pawn immediately. } 5... Nbd7
{ We don't want to take a tempo with  5...Bd7  as White will take the pawn on c4 anyways. We need the bishop on the a8-h1 diagonal, and there is a nicer way to get there. }
6. Qxc4 c5
{ Soon a6-b5 will happen, and the black bishop will land on b7. Note that playing a4 to stop b5 not only loses a tempo but also doesn't stop Black from playing b5 as the a1 rook hangs at the end. }
