[White "Chapter 3: QGD (4th move alternatives)"]
[Black "4th Move alternatives: 4.a3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5
{ We will see various options on the 4th move in this chapter. This will not include 4.e3/Bg5/g3/Nc3 as those are covered separately in other chapters. }
4. a3
{ This move prepares c5. Given a chance, White might play c5 as they are ready to protect the pawn with b4. }
4... dxc4
{ Black takes advantage of the non-developing move 4.a3 and changes the pattern of the game by opening up the position. }
5. e3
{ It is important to understand that we are taking on c4 when White can't play e4. White now tries to get back the pawn by playing e3, which opens up the light-squared bishop but shuts down the other one. }
5... b5
{ There are many ways to play this position. For example, there is nothing wrong with playing  5...c5  here when we get to a Queen's Gambit Accepted line; when White has played the  a3  move, which is nothing special, and Black gets easy play.    However, I like the text move more. It makes perfect sense to protect the pawn now, and in order to break the pawn chain, White must play a4 and lose a tempo instantly. }
6. a4
{ After  6.b3  c5  , the center gets fizzled out, and White gets nothing out of the opening. }
6... c6 { Holding on to our pawn chain. } 7. axb5 cxb5 8. b3
{ This way White managed to keep the center intact. } 8... a5
{ Gaining more space on the queenside. } 9. bxc4 bxc4 10. Bxc4 Nbd7
{ At this point, the move order doesn't really matter. We could also play  10...Bb7  , or  10...Bb4  and get a comfortable position. }
11. Ba3
{ After  11.O-O  Bb4  12.Ba3  Bb7  Black will get the a5 pawn to b4 after the trade of bishops. This will further restrict the knight on b1. }
11... Bxa3 12. Nxa3 O-O 13. O-O Bb7
{ White has a better center, but they can't use those pawns. Black meanwhile controls the key e4-d5 square, got a better bishop that is looking on the kingside, got an outside passed pawn, and the rooks are ready to grab the open file soon. This position appeared in a correspondence game in 2020, and Black had no problems whatsoever. }
