1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5
{ We will see various options on the 4th move in this chapter. This will not include 4.e3/Bg5/g3/Nc3 as those are covered separately in other chapters. }
4. b3
{ White brings more protection to the c4 pawn to get better control over the center. }
4... dxc4
{ At first sight, this move feels illogical since it gives away the center. However, it has a straightforward plan of striking at the center immediately, with c5 coming next. }
5. bxc4 c5 6. e3
{ The only way to make sure White doesn't end up with an isolated c4 pawn. }
6... cxd4 7. exd4
{ Once again, the only way to avoid getting a weak isolated pawn on c4. White now claims that they are fine with the hanging pawns, arguing that it gives enough control over the center. }
7... e5
{ A fantastic idea that has never been played yet. Black strikes at the place where White has maximum control. }
8. dxe5 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Ng4
{ Even without the queens, the white king remains exposed. The pawn on f2 hangs for now, and the knight on g4 also keeps a target on the e5 pawn. }
10. Ke1 Nc6 { Putting another target on e5. } 11. Bf4 Bb4+ 12. Nbd2 O-O
{ White has too many weaknesses to take care of. The king is not only weak on e1 but also can never castle as it has moved already. With Re8 coming next and Bc3 in the air, White is bound to lose the e5 pawn, and the exposed king will seal their fate. Black is clearly winning at this point. }
