1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5
{ We will see various options on the 4th move in this chapter. This will not include 4.e3/Bg5/g3/Nc3 as those are covered separately in other chapters. }
4. Qc2
{ White protects the pawn with the queen, and this has an obvious disadvantage that Black exploits instantly. }
4... dxc4
{ Simplest solution. Black lures the queen to c4 so that further tempos will be gained by chasing the queen. }
5. e3
{ It is possible to play this move, but then one might ask, 'what was the point of playing 4.Qc2?'. It turns out  5.e4  with a similar idea wouldn't work due to  5...b5  6.a4  c6  7.axb5  cxb5  8.b3  Bb7  and Black gains a tempo by attacking the pawn on e4, and  9.Nbd2  runs into  9...Bb4  . Engines give -2 at this stage. }
5... c5
{ Black has a straightforward plan: Open up the c-file quickly and get the rook to c8 to harass the queen on c2. }
6. Bxc4
{ After  6.dxc5  Bxc5  White has got one extra move @@StartBracket@@Qc2@@EndBracket@@ which is in a way useless since Black will soon create a setup Nbd7-b6-Bb7-Rc8, and the queen will have to move again. Black gets a good position. }
6... cxd4 { Going as per the plan of opening up the c-file. } 7. Nxd4
{ After  7.exd4  Nc6  White will have an isolated pawn that will come under attack immediately, with no compensation visible in return. }
7... Bd7
{ We don't need to rush with castling here, as no attack is coming. It is important to get the rook to c-file quickly and gain further tempos. }
8. O-O Nc6
{ Giving a positional threat of taking on d4 and forcing White to get an isolated pawn. Black also has the original plan of getting the rook to c8 and putting pressure on the c-file.   Eventually, Black will castle after playing Be7 while White can't take advantage of that. White will probably get equality with correct play, but clearly, they have to solve some issues to get there. Black had no problem in the game: 1/2-1/2 Riazantsev,A @@StartBracket@@2634@@EndBracket@@-Vidit,S @@StartBracket@@2727@@EndBracket@@ Warsaw POL 2021 }
