1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. cxd5
{ The exchange variation of QGD only works when the knight is on g1 as White keeps the strong option of the Bd3-Ne2 set up to facilitate the f3-e4 breaks in the future. It is one of the main reasons why this version of the exchange variation is rarely seen at the top level. }
4... exd5 5. g3
{ I am really surprised to see there are about 250 games in this position. In the Catalan, Black's biggest problem is how to develop the c8 bishop. Here White plays the Catalan after including cxd5 and opening up the bishop on c8. No wonder it has never been played by a GM. }
5... Bd6 6. Bg2 O-O
{ Black continues to play most naturally and develops harmoniously. } 7. O-O c6
{ The engine already gives a substantial advantage to Black, which is not surprising when we look at the bishops. Both White's bishops are bad, while both Black bishops got free play. }
