1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. cxd5
{ The exchange variation of QGD only works when the knight is on g1 as White keeps the strong option of the Bd3-Ne2 set up to facilitate the f3-e4 breaks in the future. It is one of the main reasons why this version of the exchange variation is rarely seen at the top level. }
4... exd5 5. Bg5
{ The second most popular move in the position. However, this particular move order of getting the bishop out is inaccurate. White should have guarded the e4 square first before getting the bishop to g5.   5.Bf4  has also been played several times, but it does not have any independent value as we will transpose after  5...c6  6.Nc3  or  6.e3  Bf5  7.Nc3  which is covered from 5.Nc3 move order. }
5... h6
{ It was also possible to play  5...c6  and after both  6.Qc2  and  6.Nc3  Black could have transposed in lines covered from 5.Qc2 and 5.Nc3. However, there is no need to let White get away with an inaccurate move order. It is time to punish them. }
6. Bh4 { 6.Bxf6  Qxf6  7.Nc3  c6  is covered from 5.Nc3 move order. } 6... g5
{ Going for the bishop straight away. } 7. Bg3 Ne4
{ White is paying the price of not playing Nc3. Black is now threatening to play h5 and go for the bishop on g3. }
8. Nfd2
{ White desperately tries to get rid of the knight on e4. They want to take on e4 and also make sure the knight on f3 is not hanging. That is the reason for playing Nfd2 and not Nbd2. }
8... Nxg3 { It is time to collect the bishop and then open up the game. } 9.
hxg3 c5
{ Opening up the game is a good thing to do while having a pair of bishops. }
10. dxc5 Bg7
{ The game opened up, and White has no match for the bishop on g7. Black remains better. }
