[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: QGD (4.cxd5)"]
[Black "4.cxd5 exd5 5.Qc2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. cxd5
{ The exchange variation of QGD only works when the knight is on g1 as White keeps the strong option of the Bd3-Ne2 set up to facilitate the f3-e4 breaks in the future. It is one of the main reasons why this version of the exchange variation is rarely seen at the top level. }
4... exd5 5. Qc2
{ White plays against the bishop on c8 and takes away its ideal f5 square. }
5... c6
{ It is the typical pawn formation that Black takes in this system. Keeping total control in the center. For now, Black remains non-committal with the bishop moves. }
6. Bg5 { 6.Nc3  is covered via the 5.Nc3 move order. } 6... Bd6
{ It was also possible to play  6...h6  7.Bh4  g5  8.Bg3  Ne4  . However, with the queen on c2 already, White has the option to play  9.Nc3  and after  9...Bf5  10.Nxe4  Bxe4  , the position remains dynamically balanced. }
7. e3 { 7.Nc3  is the most natural move, and it transposes to the 5.Nc3 line. }
7... Qa5+ { Getting ready to play Ne4 next. } 8. Nc3 Ne4
{ White must give up the bishop on g5 to take care of the Bb4 threat. Once the bishop on g5 is gone, Black will get a fine position due to the active double bishops. }
