[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: QGD (4.cxd5)"]
[Black "4.cxd5 exd5 5.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. cxd5
{ The exchange variation of QGD only works when the knight is on g1 as White keeps the strong option of the Bd3-Ne2 set up to facilitate the f3-e4 breaks in the future. It is one of the main reasons why this version of the exchange variation is rarely seen at the top level. }
4... exd5 5. Nc3 { The most popular move in the position. } 5... c6
{ It is the ideal pawn formation. Black keeps the development of the bishop flexible for now. By playing c6, we stabilize the central d5 pawn.   This position can also come from a Semi-Slav @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  c6  @@EndBracket@@, where taking on d5 is not the main or critical move. }
6. Bf4
{ Jobava played this move a few times, but only in rapid and blitz. Magnus also tried this move in speed chess against Wesley. In Classical chess, this move is not so popular. It allows Black to solve the light-squared bishop issue instantly. }
6... Bf5
{ It was also possible to play  6...Bd6  and after  7.Bxd6  Qxd6  8.e3  Bf5  Black gets a fine position. However, I like this solution more, which keeps more dynamism in the position. }
7. e3 Nbd7 { Black got the bishop out, and now intends to play Qb6 next. } 8.
h3
{ White wants to go for the f5 bishop by playing g4. White also can get away from any sort of Nh5 ideas by emptying a square for the bishop on h2. }
8... Qb6
{ Gaining a tempo before addressing the f5 bishop issue. Qxb2 is a serious threat that stops White from playing g4. }
9. Qc1 h6
{ Black also creates a space for his bishop on h7, getting away from g4 ideas. }
10. Be2
{ There is no way to get rid of and counter the bishop on f5, so White will have to compromise with their own bishop's development and keep it on e2 instead of the ideal square d3. }
10... Be7
{ Likewise, Black also can't get to its ideal square on d6. It is funny that on paper White's good bishop is the light-squared bishop, and Black's good bishop is the dark-squared bishop, but in reality, it's the other way round. }
11. O-O O-O
{ Black managed to develop without any issues, and the queen is better placed than White's queen. Usually, White plays for a minority attack with b4-b5 ideas, but Black is way too active, and once we play a5, it would be difficult for White to generate any play on the queenside.   The resulting position is good for Black and we can look forward to a nice middlegame. Black's bishop on e7 is not as useless as White's bishop on e2 since the black bishop stops White's main idea of b4-b5. }
