[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. cxd5
{ The exchange variation of QGD only works when the knight is on g1 as White keeps the strong option of the Bd3-Ne2 set up to facilitate the f3-e4 breaks in the future. It is one of the main reasons why this version of the exchange variation is rarely seen at the top level. }
4... exd5 5. Nc3 { The most popular move in the position. } 5... c6
{ It is the ideal pawn formation. Black keeps the development of the bishop flexible for now. By playing c6, we stabilize the central d5 pawn.   This position can also come from a Semi-Slav @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  c6  @@EndBracket@@, where taking on d5 is not the main or critical move. }
6. Bf4
{ Jobava played this move a few times, but only in rapid and blitz. Magnus also tried this move in speed chess against Wesley. In Classical chess, this move is not so popular. It allows Black to solve the light-squared bishop issue instantly. }
6... Bf5
{ It was also possible to play  6...Bd6  and after  7.Bxd6  Qxd6  8.e3  Bf5  Black gets a fine position. However, I like this solution more, which keeps more dynamism in the position. }
7. e3 Nbd7 { Black got the bishop out, and now intends to play Qb6 next. } 8.
Bd3
{ The bishop on f5 is so ideally placed that unless White actively tries to get rid of it, their own light-squared bishop will remain poor.   This is a sensible decision to trade the light-squared bishop as White also got their other bishop out on f4. After  8.Nh4  Bg4  9.Qc2  Black picks up the f4 bishop with  9...Nh5  . }
8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Be7
{ White did manage to get rid of the bishop on f5, but they had to part with the strategically good bishop. In a normal QGD exchange variation, White tries to get the bishop to d3 before Black gets Bf5. }
10. O-O
{ Going for the long castle is too risky as Black's pawn storm comes much faster with b5-a5-b4-c5 etc.   10.h3  O-O  11.O-O  is covered via the 10.O-O  move order. }
10... O-O
{ White cannot break in the center with e4, which will give him an isolated pawn for nothing. So the only play remains on the queenside with the idea to play b4-b5. This is the only thing that could bother Black, and we should be ready for that. For now, b4 is not playable as the bishop on e7 controls it. }
11. h3
{ Getting away from any Nh5 ideas by vacating a square for the bishop on h2. }
11... Re8 12. Rab1 { Now it is time to stop White from playing b4. } 12... a5
13. Qc2
{ 13.a3  a4  would stop White from playing b4-b5 permanently, so White first stops Black from playing a4. }
13... Nb6
{ Black is not going to let White play a3-b4 so easily. Once again, a3 is met by a4. }
14. b3 { The fight for the a4 square continues. } 14... Bb4
{ White can forget about any play in the center or queenside now. Black managed to stop White's play on the queenside even before it started. }
