[White "Chapter 4: QGD (4.cxd5)"]
[Black "4.cxd5 exd5 5.Nc3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. cxd5
{ The exchange variation of QGD only works when the knight is on g1 as White keeps the strong option of the Bd3-Ne2 set up to facilitate the f3-e4 breaks in the future. It is one of the main reasons why this version of the exchange variation is rarely seen at the top level. }
4... exd5 5. Nc3 { The most popular move in the position. } 5... c6
{ It is the ideal pawn formation. Black keeps the development of the bishop flexible for now. By playing c6, we stabilize the central d5 pawn.   This position can also come from a Semi-Slav @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  c6  @@EndBracket@@, where taking on d5 is not the main or critical move. }
6. Qc2
{ White plays against the bishop on c8 and takes away its best square on f5.   6.e3  has been played about 450 times, but never by a GM. I totally understand that as there is no justification as to why White should first open up Black's c8 bishop with cxd5 and then close his own bishop on c1 with e3. Black can continue normally with  6...Bd6  7.Bd3  O-O  8.O-O  Re8  , and already the computer gives an advantage to Black which is obvious when we look at the bishops.  6.g3  will be similar to 5.g3 lines. }
6... Bd6
{ This is the modern way of dealing with this line. Black ignores any Bg5 ideas and keeps the bishop on its ideal d6-square. }
7. Bg5
{ White gives a silent threat of  7...--  8.Bxf6  Qxf6  9.Nxd5  when the bishop on c8 hangs. }
7... O-O
{ The variation mentioned above won't work anymore as the bishop on c8 is protected by the rook on f8.   I am super surprised to see that in more than 90 games, Black played  7...h6  , which immediately loses after  8.Bxf6  Qxf6  9.Nxd5  as the c8 bishop hangs; I am even more surprised to see that out of those 90+ games, in about 60 games, White automatically played @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3pp1/2pb1n1p/3p4/3P3B/2N2N2/PPQ1PPPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bh4  . This is what happens when one memorizes moves without understanding the reasoning behind them :@@EndBracket@@ }
8. e3
{ White's main issue is that his knight is misplaced on f3. They need a Bd3-Ne2-f3-e4 set up to create some pressure. With the knight on f3, no such things are happening. }
8... h6 9. Bh4 Be6 { Getting ready to play Nbd7 next. } 10. Bd3 Nbd7 11. O-O
{ Hard to suggest anything else. Castling long would be playing with fire as Black's attack will come much faster with Rc8-b5-b4-c5 etc. }
11... Re8
{ Black needs to make sure White does not get b4-b5 breaks. Playing e4 is not tempting for White as they will end up with an isolated pawn structure. Move order is not that important here. Apart from the text move, it is also possible to start with  11...Qc7  and after  12.Bg3  Bxg3  13.hxg3  a5  14.a3  Qd6  15.Rab1  Rfe8  we get to the mainline that we will see through the 11...Rfe8 move order. }
12. Rab1 { White is coming for their trademark plan of b4-b5. } 12... a5
{ We have seen this theme multiple times already. Never allow White to play b4-b5. }
13. a3 Qb8 { Black gets away from the pin and invites White to play b4. } 14.
b4 { Trying to get b5 and put pressure on the c6 pawn. } 14... axb4
{ That's the reason why playing a5 is important. Now the rook on a8 will open up. }
15. axb4 b5
{ Putting an end to the b5 plans. Imagine the same with pawns on a2-a7. Then White could play a4-a5-a6, Black's rook won't get the open file, and there will be no access to Nb6-Nc4 ideas. }
16. Ne2 { Going for the pawn on c6. } 16... Ra3
{ Black stops the Qxc6 threat by attacking the bishop on d3. He is now ready to play Qa8 and support the pawn on c6.   After  17.Bg3  Bxg3  18.hxg3  Qd6  once again, the pawn on b4 becomes a target, and Black is ready to take control of the a-file with Rea8 next. }
