6. Bg5
{ Once again, the most popular move in the position. Now that e4 square is under control, White is not worried about h6-g5-Ne4 ideas like in the 5.Bg5 line. }
6... h6
{ One can argue why not play  6...Bd6  , so we can transpose to 6.Qc2 line after White plays  7.Qc2  .   The problem here is White plays  7.e3  with the idea of Bd3, and Black is not on time to get  7...Bf5  as  8.Qb3  becomes very strong and it is unclear how to save the b7 pawn without structural compromises. The main move is Be7 in the position, but h6 is the modern treatment of this line. Black wants to develop his bishop to its ideal square on d6. }
7. Bh4 Bf5
{ The move order is very important here. Playing Bf5 is a dream for Black as the bishop gets to its perfect square. However, every time Black plays Bf5, we must know how to deal with Qb3 ideas. }
8. Qb3
{ White claims that Black can't play Qb6 as that will shatter the pawn structure on the kingside permanently after White takes on f6. }
8... g5 { Getting rid of Bxf6 ideas before going Qb6. } 9. Bg3
