{ The exchange variation of QGD only works when the knight is on g1 as White keeps the strong option of the Bd3-Ne2 set up to facilitate the f3-e4 breaks in the future. It is one of the main reasons why this version of the exchange variation is rarely seen at the top level. }
4... exd5 5. Nc3 { The most popular move in the position. } 5... c6
{ It is the ideal pawn formation. Black keeps the development of the bishop flexible for now. By playing c6, we stabilize the central d5 pawn.   This position can also come from a Semi-Slav @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  c6  @@EndBracket@@, where taking on d5 is not the main or critical move. }
6. Bg5
{ Once again, the most popular move in the position. Now that e4 square is under control, White is not worried about h6-g5-Ne4 ideas like in the 5.Bg5 line. }
6... h6
{ One can argue why not play  6...Bd6  , so we can transpose to 6.Qc2 line after White plays  7.Qc2  .   The problem here is White plays  7.e3  with the idea of Bd3, and Black is not on time to get  7...Bf5  as  8.Qb3  becomes very strong and it is unclear how to save the b7 pawn without structural compromises. The main move is Be7 in the position, but h6 is the modern treatment of this line. Black wants to develop his bishop to its ideal square on d6. }
7. Bh4 Bf5
{ The move order is very important here. Playing Bf5 is a dream for Black as the bishop gets to its perfect square. However, every time Black plays Bf5, we must know how to deal with Qb3 ideas. }
8. e3 { White now threatens to play Qb3. } 8... Nbd7
{ A vital move order finesse. Black gets ready to meet Qb3 with Qb6 by protecting the knight on f6 so that White doesn't get to break the pawn structure on the kingside. Why didn't Black play Be7 in this case? Because the Black bishop is ideally placed on d6. Hence Nbd7. }
9. Bd3
{ 9.Qb3  Qb6  doesn't lead anywhere while there is no other way to get rid of the strong bishop on  f5  . Therefore White doesn't have a lot of options to continue. }
9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Bd6
{ The bishop gets to its ideal square. Ding Liren played  10...Be7  in Online Olympiad 2020, but a few moves later he ended up playing Bd6. }
11. O-O O-O 12. e4
{ The only way to argue about the Bd6 move over Be7. After  12.Rab1  Qe7  White will never be able to play b4 nor e4. }
12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 Be7
{ White ended up with an isolated pawn, and Black has zero weakness in the position. There is nothing to worry about in Black's position. }
