[White "Chapter 5: QGD (4.e3)"]
[Black "4. e3 Be7 5.Bd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. e3
{ This way, White temporarily stops Black from playing c5. Although Black can still play  5...c5  after  6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.e4  , they will be slightly worse as Nxc3 is not available anymore. }
4... Be7
{ Black keeps the c5 idea in hand and first goes for a quick short castle. } 5.
Bd3 dxc4
{ As soon as White plays Bd3 without playing b3 Black can take on c4, gaining one tempo. }
6. Bxc4
{ Black now gets a Queen's Gambit Accepted with one extra tempo. This makes a huge difference in the position. }
6... O-O 7. O-O a6 { With the idea of playing b5-Bb7-c5. } 8. Qe2
{ Playing for a quick e4.  8.a4  c5  9.Nc3  is covered via the 5.Nc3 move order. }
8... b5 9. Bd3 Nbd7
{ Black is getting ready to play c5 quickly. In the case of dxc5, we would like to recapture with the knight. }
10. Rd1
{ After the natural  10.e4  c5  the engines already give a significant advantage to Black.  This makes sense as Black will soon take on d4 and play Nc5 when the pressure on the d-file and White's army snoring queenside will only create trouble for White. }
10... Bb7
{ Sooner or later, Black will play c5 and free themselves completely. White's queenside pieces are still underdeveloped, and the bishop on c1 will have a hard time getting out. Black gets an excellent dynamic position and can look forward to a nice middlegame. }
