[White "Chapter 5: QGD (4.e3)"]
[Black "4. e3 Be7 5.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. e3
{ This way, White temporarily stops Black from playing c5. Although Black can still play  5...c5  after  6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.e4  , they will be slightly worse as Nxc3 is not available anymore. }
4... Be7
{ Black keeps the c5 idea in hand and first goes for a quick short castle. } 5.
Nc3 O-O
{ Black waits for White to show their hands. If White moves the light-squared bishop, Black gains a tempo by taking on c4, Otherwise Black will charge with c5 next. }
6. cxd5
{ This move has been played a few times in online chess. It makes little sense to restrict the bishop on c1 and then open up the bishop on c8. There is no strong logic to support White's play here. }
6... exd5
{ Just by looking at the bishops it is obvious who should be more careful here. }
7. Bd3 Re8
{ Keeping control of the e4 square and we are ready to improve the e7-bishop next. The white bishop on c1 is suffering big time. }
8. h3 { White indicates that they might opt for a kingside attack! } 8... Bd6
{ Black takes control of the center. } 9. Qc2
{ After  9.Nb5  Bf8  White's knight will be chased away with c6. } 9... c6
{ Cori had this position twice with White against Radek and Firouza. In both games, he got into big trouble. White's king is unsafe on the queenside, and Black gets to attack much faster. }
10. b3 Qe7 11. Bb2 Nbd7 { Black is now ready to play Ne4. } 12. O-O
{ After playing b3, castling long will be suicidal since Black will be able to break with a5-a4 easily. }
12... Ne4
{ The bishop on b2 is dead, and Black was clearly better in the game Cori,J 2652-Wojtaszek,R @@StartBracket@@2719@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020 }
*

