1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. e3
{ This way, White temporarily stops Black from playing c5. Although Black can still play  5...c5  after  6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.e4  , they will be slightly worse as Nxc3 is not available anymore. }
4... Be7
{ Black keeps the c5 idea in hand and first goes for a quick short castle. } 5.
Nc3 O-O
{ Black waits for White to show their hands. If White moves the light-squared bishop, Black gains a tempo by taking on c4, Otherwise Black will charge with c5 next. }
6. Qc2
{ White stays non-committal with the light-squared bishop. They would like to take on c4 with one tempo. Obviously Black is not going to give them that privilege so easily. }
6... c5
{ One day the c-file will be open, the black rook will come to c8, and White will regret playing Qc2 :@@EndBracket@@ }
7. dxc5
{ 7.cxd5  cxd4  opens up the c-file faster, and the queen on c2 starts to feel uncomfortable. }
7... Bxc5 8. a3 { White threatens to play b4. } 8... dxc4
{ The right time to take on c4. We don't mind allowing White to take on c4 with one tempo. Thanks to the open c-file, Black will play Rc8 and gain tempos by attacking the bishop on c4 and the queen on c2. }
9. Bxc4 Nbd7 { Preparing a6-b5-Bb7-Rc8. } 10. O-O a6 11. b4
{ 11.a4  b6  doesn't change anything apart from White getting another headache with the weak b4 square. }
11... Be7 12. Bb2 b5
{ Black manages to win back the tempo that we didn't win earlier, when we allowed White to take on c4 in one move instead of two. }
13. Bd3 Bb7
{ The rook will come to c8, and White will have to move the queen from c2.   The position remains symmetrical and evenly balanced.  This position has been reached a few times, and Black never had any issues. Also in a 2021 Correspondence chess game, White tried this position, but Black had zero trouble throughout the game. }
