{ Black keeps the c5 idea in hand and first goes for a quick short castle. } 5.
Nc3 O-O
{ Black waits for White to show their hands. If White moves the light-squared bishop, Black gains a tempo by taking on c4, Otherwise Black will charge with c5 next. }
6. Qc2
{ White stays non-committal with the light-squared bishop. They would like to take on c4 with one tempo. Obviously Black is not going to give them that privilege so easily. }
6... c5
{ One day the c-file will be open, the black rook will come to c8, and White will regret playing Qc2 :@@EndBracket@@ }
7. dxc5
{ 7.cxd5  cxd4  opens up the c-file faster, and the queen on c2 starts to feel uncomfortable. }
7... Bxc5 8. cxd5
{ Giving Black an isolated pawn at least justifies White's previous moves. }
8... exd5
{ Black got an isolated pawn, but in return, White's bishop on c1 remains stuck, his king on e1 is not ideal, and the queen on c2 will soon come under X-ray once Black gets the rook to c8. It looks like Black made a good deal. }
9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O Be6 { Getting ready to bring the rook to the c-file. } 11.
Rd1
{ White tries to put pressure on the d5-pawn. After  11.b3  Rc8  12.Bb2  Qe7  13.Rad1  Rfd8  Black eventually gets the d4 break with ample counterplay. }
11... Qe7 { Developing and unpinning our queen from the d-file. } 12. a3 Rac8
13. b4
{ Black has a sweet choice of forcing a draw right away or continuing to play a dynamic middle game. }
13... Nxb4
{ Just for the sake of completeness, I would like to show this pretty variation. It was also possible to play  13...Bd6  with a dynamically balanced position. }
14. axb4 Bxb4 { The pinned knight on c3 comes under attack. } 15. Bb2
{ 15.Rd3  Ne4  16.Bb2  transposes back to our 15.Bb2 variation. } 15... Ne4 16.
Rd3
{ There are too many ways to take the knight on c3 and get an equal position. I will show one of them. }
16... b5
{ Threatening to take and play b4. White must find the only move that does not lose on the spot. }
17. Nd4 Bd6
{ Black could also take on c3 and play b4, but this move is prettier. Black threatens both b4 and Bxh2 at the same time. }
18. Qd1 Bxh2+
{ After  19.Kxh2  Qh4  20.Kg1  Qxf2  the game ends with a perpetual. } *

