1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. e3
{ This way, White temporarily stops Black from playing c5. Although Black can still play  5...c5  after  6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.e4  , they will be slightly worse as Nxc3 is not available anymore. }
4... Be7
{ Black keeps the c5 idea in hand and first goes for a quick short castle. } 5.
Nc3 O-O
{ Black waits for White to show their hands. If White moves the light-squared bishop, Black gains a tempo by taking on c4, Otherwise Black will charge with c5 next. }
6. Bd3
{ The most popular move in the position.  6.Be2  dxc4  7.Bxc4  transposes back to our 6.Bd3 line. }
6... dxc4
{ Immediately gaining a tempo. White must waste another move with his bishop to take on c4. }
7. Bxc4 a6
{ Black now gets a Queen's Gambit Accepted position with an extra tempo, and White's knight on c3 is often not ideally placed. }
8. O-O b5 9. Bd3 Bb7
{ More than 300 games reached this position and the engines already love Black's position. Look at the bishop on c1 if you have some doubt about the evaluation. }
10. Qe2 { White prepares e4. } 10... Nbd7
{ Preparing c5 to strike in the center. } 11. e4
{ After  11.Rd1  c5  12.dxc5  Bxc5  White could not solve the dark-squared bishop issue as  13.e4  runs into  13...Ng4  . Black was better in the game 0-1 Danielian, E @@StartBracket@@2467@@EndBracket@@-Lysyj, I @@StartBracket@@2655@@EndBracket@@ Yerevan 2014. }
11... c5 12. e5 Nd5
{ The pressure on the d4-pawn escalates. Black now has a lovely outpost on d5. }
13. Ne4
{ This position was reached in the game 1-0 Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@-Sjugirov,S @@StartBracket@@2663@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020 }
13... cxd4 { This cold-blooded move would have given Black a clear advantage. }
14. Neg5
{ Naturally, Black was worried about such a direct attack. It is understandable to panic when you are under such an attack, especially in blitz. }
14... h6 15. Qe4 { It looks like Black is now lost. } 15... N5f6
{ A great move! Only move that doesn't lose on the spot and the only move that gives almost a winning advantage to Black. }
16. Qh4
{ 16.Qxb7  Nc5  is the point. White queen gets trapped after  17.Qc6  Rc8  :@@EndBracket@@ }
16... Ne8 { Black threatens to take on f3 and take on g5 with the bishop. } 17.
Qh3 { Only move to stay in the game. Now, Bxf3 can be answered with Nxf3. }
17... Nxe5
{ Black eliminates White's last central pawn.   Please don't forget that we can't capture the knight on g5 with  17...hxg5  since will get mated with  18.Qh7  . }
18. Nxe5 Bxg5
{ Black is now two pawns up. Luckily White has a trick to win an exchange that does not lose the game immediately. }
19. Bxg5 Qxg5 20. Nd7
{ Thanks to this move, White can temporarily delay resignation. } 20... Nd6 21.
Nxf8 Rxf8
{ Black has two pawns for the exchange, and what pawns! Soon e6-e5-e4 will be coming. The bishop on b7 is a monster. Engines already give -1.45 for Black. }
