1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. e3
{ This way, White temporarily stops Black from playing c5. Although Black can still play  5...c5  after  6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.e4  , they will be slightly worse as Nxc3 is not available anymore. }
4... Be7
{ Black keeps the c5 idea in hand and first goes for a quick short castle. } 5.
b3
{ White will eventually make the moves Bd3-O-O-Bb2, and it can happen in a lot of permutations and combinations, which will definitely involve a lot of transpositions.   Essentially the main difference is the choice for White whether to put the b1 knight on c3 or d2. In order to avoid confusion, I kept all the lines under the 6.Bd3-O-O-Bb2 move order and only at this point gave the option of Nbd2/Nc3.   White could also start with  5.Nbd2  O-O  6.b3  , and after  6...c5  , we will eventually reach a position that is covered via 5.b3-Bd3-O-O-Bb2 move order. }
5... O-O
{ White can choose any move order, but we will get to a similar setup irrespective of which move order White opts for. }
6. Bd3
{ White wants to finish castling first before developing the queenside pieces. The move order doesn't matter here as such, and White practically chooses any move order, and it won't disturb Black's play.   No matter what, we play c5 next! }
6... c5
{ Black's response remains the same irrespective of White's Bb2/Bd3/Nc3/Nbd2 move order. This way it is also very easy to prepare and understand the ideas. We strike at the center no matter what. }
7. cxd5
{ This rare move has been faced by Levon and Radek. Unfortunately, in both cases, Black missed a nice trick here. }
7... cxd4 8. dxe6
{ Practically forced as  8.Nxd4  e5  gives Black total central control, and taking on d4 with the pawn will leave White with an isolated pawn and zero compensation in return. }
8... dxe3
{ What a lovely position! White's two main issues are his king is in the center, and the rook on a1 is vulnerable due to the open diagonal. }
9. exf7+ Kh8
{ Avoiding Rxf7 as in the future White could have Bc4 pinning ideas. } 10. O-O
{ After  10.Bxe3  Bb4  White can't block the check as the bishop on d3 hangs.  11.Bd2  Qxd3  12.Bxb4  Qe4  wins the bishop on b4. }
10... exf2+
{ I have never seen any position like this before, just after 10 moves :@@EndBracket@@ }
11. Kh1 Nc6
{ Nb4 is a serious threat. White can play  12.Nc3  , but after  12...Be6  the threat of Nb4 continues. The bishop on d3 and the rook on a1 both are prone to attack which makes White's position worse. Engine evaluation of -0.60 in Black's favor seems fair. }
