1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. e3
{ This way, White temporarily stops Black from playing c5. Although Black can still play  5...c5  after  6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.e4  , they will be slightly worse as Nxc3 is not available anymore. }
4... Be7
{ Black keeps the c5 idea in hand and first goes for a quick short castle. } 5.
b3
{ White will eventually make the moves Bd3-O-O-Bb2, and it can happen in a lot of permutations and combinations, which will definitely involve a lot of transpositions.   Essentially the main difference is the choice for White whether to put the b1 knight on c3 or d2. In order to avoid confusion, I kept all the lines under the 6.Bd3-O-O-Bb2 move order and only at this point gave the option of Nbd2/Nc3.   White could also start with  5.Nbd2  O-O  6.b3  , and after  6...c5  , we will eventually reach a position that is covered via 5.b3-Bd3-O-O-Bb2 move order. }
5... O-O
{ White can choose any move order, but we will get to a similar setup irrespective of which move order White opts for. }
6. Bd3
{ White wants to finish castling first before developing the queenside pieces. The move order doesn't matter here as such, and White practically chooses any move order, and it won't disturb Black's play.   No matter what, we play c5 next! }
6... c5
{ Black's response remains the same irrespective of White's Bb2/Bd3/Nc3/Nbd2 move order. This way it is also very easy to prepare and understand the ideas. We strike at the center no matter what. }
7. O-O
{ Once again, White could choose a different move order with  7.Bb2  cxd4  8.exd4  b6  9.O-O  , and we get transposed back to our 7.O-O line. }
7... cxd4 8. exd4 b6 { Black gets the bishop out from b7. } 9. Bb2 Bb7
{ Finally, we reached the position which could have occurred in many different ways. White can now keep the knight on c3 or d2. The bishop on b7 is stronger than the bishop on b2 as Black can anytime open up the bishop by taking on c4 while White doesn't have that privilege. }
10. Nbd2
{ Just like playing Nc3 or Nbd2 doesn't change anything in terms of evaluating the position, the same applies for Black also, and we can choose either way of developing the knight.   I would like to have one way of developing, to avoid confusion. I like the knight on c6, directly putting pressure on the d4 pawn. So irrespectively of how White plays, I would like to put my knight on c6. Also, to give a generic picture of the position: Even with White to play, engines think this position is 0.00. }
10... Nc6 11. Rc1
{ Once again, the move order doesn't matter much since there are no fast plans here. Both sides will finish development. I would like to show one important plan from the Black side that is most efficient. }
11... Rc8
{ We could also start with  11...Re8  and go for our plan, but there is no rush. Black has all the time in the world. }
12. Re1 Re8
{ Now we see the idea. Black wants to bring more forces against the d4 pawn, and we intend to play Bf8-g6-Bg7 next. It is good to have this plan in mind, and the move order won't matter much. }
13. a3
{ After  13.Qe2  Bf8  14.h3  g6  15.Qe3  Bg7  Black got a lovely position in the game ½-½ Sargissian, G @@StartBracket@@2672@@EndBracket@@-Anand, V @@StartBracket@@2782@@EndBracket@@ Riadh 2017. }
13... Bf8 { Black continues with the plan of getting the bishop to g7. } 14. c5
{ An important moment. Black should not let White grab more space on the queenside with b4. }
14... a5
{ b4 is stopped, and Black threatens to take on c5 and play Nd7 to put pressure on the c5 pawn. Black was pressing in the game ½-½ Nisipeanu,L @@StartBracket@@2674@@EndBracket@@-Kramnik,V @@StartBracket@@2812@@EndBracket@@ Dortmund 2016. }
