10. Nc3
{ A few high-level games reached this position. Computer screams 0.00, but we should know where to put our pieces in order to get harmonious development. }
10... Nc6 { Keeping an eye on the d4 pawn. } 11. Qe2
{ I am surprised to see many Grandmasters play this move as White which immediately gives Black a clear advantage. }
11... Nb4
{ In the game Svidler - Carlsen from online rapid 2020 Black missed this opportunity which gives immediate advantage. }
12. Bb1 { Naturally White would not like to give up the bishop. } 12... dxc4
{ The d4 pawn comes under attack now. } 13. bxc4 Bxf3 14. gxf3
{ Unfortunately forced.  14.Qxf3  loses a pawn after  14...Qxd4  . } 14... Bd6
{ Going for mate with Nh5-Qh4 ideas. } 15. Ne4 Bf4
{ Black threatens to take on e4 and play Qh4. With a horrible pawn structure and a weak king, it gets difficult for White to play this position. }
