[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 6: QGD (4.Bg5)"]
[Black "4.Bg5 dxc4 5.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Bg5
{ This line is quite popular. It immediately avoids the Semi-Tarrasch line @@StartBracket@@as White has not committed to Nc3@@EndBracket@@ and keeps the option wide open of transposing into lines like the Ragozin, QGD, Semi-Slav, Vienna, Moscow, etc. None of these are part of our repertoire; so knowing how to deal with this particular move order is of utmost importance. If we don't pay attention here, then we might suddenly find ourselves in a foreign theoretical territory in a completely different line. }
4... dxc4
{ The most popular move was  4...Be7  , which would have got us to the mainline QGD. There are other moves too which could get us into various other systems that we are bypassing and keeping our repertoire unique and independent. }
5. Nc3
{ Currently we transposed into the Vienna system @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  d5  4.Nc3  dxc4  , but here White went with the lesser popular  5.Bg5  @@StartBracket@@instead of  5.e4  @@EndBracket@@.   Black has a plethora of options here; we could play:  ➫  5...Bb4  and get a Ragozin.  ➫  5...c6  and get a Botvinnik system.  ➫  5...Be7  and get a worse version of QGD.  So how do we play then? We keep our repertoire unique and independent by going  5...a6  here :@@EndBracket@@ }
5... a6
{ This has been played by Gelfand, Ding, Anand, etc. Black is forcing White to get into foreign territory.   The idea is straightforward - Black wants to play b5 and protect the c4 pawn. }
6. e4
{ Going for the pawn on c4.  6.e3  b5  7.a4  c6  transposes to the 5.e3 move order. }
6... b5
{ This position resembles the Botvinnik system, but it is not the same. There is a huge difference that works in Black's favor. Instead of c6, Black played a6, which means the bishop on b7 will have free reign on the diagonal, this changes everything. }
7. e5
{ How else we can we justify White's play? They will remain one pawn down for nothing otherwise. After  7.a4  Bb7  the pawn on e4 will be hanging if White goes for the pawn on b5. }
7... h6 { A typical way of saving the knight is by attacking the bishop. } 8.
Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5
{ 9.Bg3  Nd5  happened at GM level in an online blitz where Black was a pawn up and clearly winning. }
9... hxg5 10. Bxg5 Nbd7
{ This is a fantastic version of the Botvinnik system. Instead of c6, we got a6, and now there is no need to worry about how to open up the b7 bishop. It remains open as it is :@@EndBracket@@ }
11. Be2
{ 11.exf6  Bb7  happened several times with great results for Black, which is not surprising. The bishop on b7 is a monster, eyeing the g2-pawn, and White's king remains unsafe on every side of the board. It is important to note that if White goes  12.d5  black has the strong counter  12...Nc5  and remains better. }
11... Bb7 12. Bf3
{ Trying to take advantage of the open diagonal. White wants to exchange Black's dangerous bishop as early as possible.   It was wiser to play  12.exf6  and accept a slightly worse position at this stage. Black could then choose between the strategic  12...Bh6  or the direct  12...b4  . In either case, Black's position remains preferable. }
12... Nxe5
{ That's the point! White is unable to exchange the bishop without getting into a direct attack. }
13. dxe5
{ After  13.Bxb7  Nd3+  White's king will remain in the center and will have to endure a tremendous attack. Black is also doing fine materially speaking, so we are just getting a free attack after all. }
13... Qxd1+ 14. Rxd1 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Nd7
{ With a horrible structure and a Black knight coming to d3, White has very little chance to save the game. }
*

