{ The most popular move was  4...Be7  , which would have got us to the mainline QGD. There are other moves too which could get us into various other systems that we are bypassing and keeping our repertoire unique and independent. }
5. Nc3
{ Currently we transposed into the Vienna system @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  d5  4.Nc3  dxc4  , but here White went with the lesser popular  5.Bg5  @@StartBracket@@instead of  5.e4  @@EndBracket@@.   Black has a plethora of options here; we could play:  ➫  5...Bb4  and get a Ragozin.  ➫  5...c6  and get a Botvinnik system.  ➫  5...Be7  and get a worse version of QGD.  So how do we play then? We keep our repertoire unique and independent by going  5...a6  here :@@EndBracket@@ }
5... a6
{ This has been played by Gelfand, Ding, Anand, etc. Black is forcing White to get into foreign territory.   The idea is straightforward - Black wants to play b5 and protect the c4 pawn. }
6. a4 { Stopping b5 and planning e4. } 6... Nc6
{ Now we save the pawn with Na5. } 7. e4 Na5
{ Once again, we address the real threat, which is to take the pawn on c4. White can never win a piece with the e5 trick. }
8. Qc2
{ With the idea of playing Rd1 and aiming for a quick d5. Such ideas exist in the Anti-Moscow, and I remember that we worked a lot in this direction during the Bonn match.  Anand later won a lovely game against Shirov using the same preparation. A huge difference here is that the black knight is on a5 instead of b8. }
8... Be7 { Getting away from the pin with a natural developing move. } 9. Rd1
{ White continues with the plan. If it was White to play then they would have won the game with d5 right away. }
9... c6
{ Black stops d5, and is ready to play b5 which will cement the pawn on c4. I like this move more than 9...h6 which was played in the game 1/2-1/2 Mamedyarov,S  @@StartBracket@@2817@@EndBracket@@ - Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2773@@EndBracket@@ Kolkata 2018. }
10. e5
{ Since d5 is stopped it is hard to imagine what else White could play. Engines already give a big advantage to Black. }
10... Nd5 11. Ne4 { The knight is now coming to d6. } 11... f6
{ This is the breaking move that Black should be aware of. White's center gets blasted now. }
12. exf6 gxf6 13. Bh6 { White plays against Black's king. } 13... b5
{ Bb4-Qe7-Nb3-Rg8 are some of the automatic moves that Black can make. White's king remains in danger.  Black can also consider keeping the king on d7 where it is super safe. The engine gives -2 for Black. }
