[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 6: QGD (4.Bg5)"]
[Black "4.Bg5 dxc4 5.Qa4+ #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Bg5
{ This line is quite popular. It immediately avoids the Semi-Tarrasch line @@StartBracket@@as White has not committed to Nc3@@EndBracket@@ and keeps the option wide open of transposing into lines like the Ragozin, QGD, Semi-Slav, Vienna, Moscow, etc. None of these are part of our repertoire; so knowing how to deal with this particular move order is of utmost importance. If we don't pay attention here, then we might suddenly find ourselves in a foreign theoretical territory in a completely different line. }
4... dxc4
{ The most popular move was  4...Be7  , which would have got us to the mainline QGD. There are other moves too which could get us into various other systems that we are bypassing and keeping our repertoire unique and independent. }
5. Qa4+ Nbd7
{ As usual for Qa4+, like in every other line, we don't attack the queen immediately with Bd7 but just develop our knight to d7. We want to get our a6-b5-Bb7 ideas in. }
6. e4 Be7 7. Nc3
{ After  7.Nbd2  O-O  8.Bxc4  Black can either take the c4 bishop with Nb6-Nc4 or keep gaining tempos with h6 and a6-b5. Note that White can't capture Nxb5 as Black has the intermediate move Nb6, which wins the piece. I personally like this a6-b5 idea more. }
7... h6
{ An important improvement over the Mamedyarov - Ding, L Shamkir 2019 game where Black opted for  7...O-O  . }
8. Be3
{ The main point of this move was that White could not play  8.Bh4  due to  8...Nxe4  9.Bxe7  Nxc3  , Black gets a material advantage.   White could try  8.Bxf6  , but after  8...Bxf6  , Black's bishop pair would compensate for White's center. And Black would still opt for the a6-b5 plan, which is annoying for White. }
8... a6 { Preparing a future b5. } 9. Bxc4
{ This time White is ready for  9...b5  as after  10.Bxb5  Black is unable to play Nb6 due to the pin. }
9... O-O
{ Now the threat of b5 is real as Black is ready to follow it up with Nb6. }
10. Qc2 b5 11. Bd3 c5
{ White got chased away, and their center is now under attack. Threats like Bb7/Ng4 and cxd4 in the future with Rc8-Nc5 look scary. The engines prefers Black already. }
