{ The most popular move was  4...Be7  , which would have got us to the mainline QGD. There are other moves too which could get us into various other systems that we are bypassing and keeping our repertoire unique and independent. }
5. Qa4+ Nbd7
{ As usual for Qa4+, like in every other line, we don't attack the queen immediately with Bd7 but just develop our knight to d7. We want to get our a6-b5-Bb7 ideas in. }
6. e3
{ A standard move. White keeps the center stable while planning to take on c4 next.  Once Radjabov played  6.Bxf6  against Kramnik, but after  6...Qxf6  7.e3  c6  8.Qxc4  e5  Black keeps the double bishop advantage and opens up the position where he gets a better position. }
6... Be7 7. Bxc4 O-O { Black keeps ideas of a6-b5/c5 open and castles first. }
8. Be2 { White escapes from any kind of fork against the queen and bishop. }
8... h6 9. Bh4 a6
{ Once again, a similar plan of getting a6-b5-Bb7 ideas in and striking the center with c5. White should be careful so they don't end up in a worse position at this point. }
