{ I like this move the most as it keeps our repertoire once again unique and independent.  However, there is absolutely nothing wrong with  5...b5  when White will be obliged to play  6.a4  , and after  6...c6  we transpose into a proper Botvinnik system where instead of playing the critical mainline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p1p2ppp/4pn2/1p4B1/2pPP3/5N2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.e5  White has committed into the less critical sideline  6.a4  . I encourage the readers to take a look at that line also as it is a sideline of the Botvinnik system that would not take much time to prepare and can be prepared as a backup.     I personally prefer the text move  5...c5  , which is rare and very easy to underestimate. It also gets us to a fresh kind of position.  Black could also play  5...Bb4  but then the game would transpose into a proper Ragozin after  6.Nc3  which is not part of our repertoire. }
6. Bxc4
{ White recaptures the pawn and is one move away from castling. Black must act fast before White consolidates and claims an advantage. }
6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Qa5+ { Forces White to play Bd2. } 8. Bd2 Qc5
{ White has too many things in the center, and all of them are under attack now :@@EndBracket@@ }
9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Nbxd7
{ Black will either get the pawn or a huge initiative after  11.Nb3  Qc4  with  12.--  Ne5  coming next. }
