{ This line is quite popular. It immediately avoids the Semi-Tarrasch line @@StartBracket@@as White has not committed to Nc3@@EndBracket@@ and keeps the option wide open of transposing into lines like the Ragozin, QGD, Semi-Slav, Vienna, Moscow, etc. None of these are part of our repertoire; so knowing how to deal with this particular move order is of utmost importance. If we don't pay attention here, then we might suddenly find ourselves in a foreign theoretical territory in a completely different line. }
4... dxc4
{ The most popular move was  4...Be7  , which would have got us to the mainline QGD. There are other moves too which could get us into various other systems that we are bypassing and keeping our repertoire unique and independent. }
5. e4
{ The most direct way. There was no time to play slowly with  5.a4  as after  5...c5  White won't have time to get back the pawn without giving heavy concessions.   Attacking the pawn with  5.Nbd2  or  5.Qc2  would not suffice as Black will play  5...b5  6.a4  c6  in both cases and remain one pawn up. }
5... c5
{ I like this move the most as it keeps our repertoire once again unique and independent.  However, there is absolutely nothing wrong with  5...b5  when White will be obliged to play  6.a4  , and after  6...c6  we transpose into a proper Botvinnik system where instead of playing the critical mainline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p1p2ppp/4pn2/1p4B1/2pPP3/5N2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.e5  White has committed into the less critical sideline  6.a4  . I encourage the readers to take a look at that line also as it is a sideline of the Botvinnik system that would not take much time to prepare and can be prepared as a backup.     I personally prefer the text move  5...c5  , which is rare and very easy to underestimate. It also gets us to a fresh kind of position.  Black could also play  5...Bb4  but then the game would transpose into a proper Ragozin after  6.Nc3  which is not part of our repertoire. }
6. Nc3
{ White protects the  e4  pawn and is now ready for  6...cxd4  7.Qxd4  , where the e4 pawn won't be hanging. }
6... cxd4 7. Qxd4
{ This was the main point of playing 6.Nc3. However,  7.Nxd4  is also equally popular. }
7... Qxd4 8. Nxd4 a6 { Stopping Nb5 ideas. } 9. Bxc4
{ At first glance, it feels that White should be better because they are way ahead in development. They have developed four minor pieces and are just one move away from castling, while Black has developed only one minor piece and is two moves away from castling. Also, White has better center control.   However, when we think deeper, things change drastically. The main issue is White's pieces. Although nicely developed, they lack targets and can be attacked by Black's army:  ⟿ The bishop on g5 will be chased away with h6, where it will lack a decent retreating square.   ⟿ The bishop on c4 will also be chased away by b5 and again will have difficulty finding a good square.   ⟿ The e4 pawn comes under attack immediately with the help of b5-Bb7 and b4 ideas.   ⟿ The knight on d4 can also be targetted with Bc5.   So, although at present Black is underdeveloped on the paper, we would soon start gaining many tempos. Let us have a look at how the game can proceed. }
9... h6
{ An important improvement over the Dubov - Radjabov game that was played in 2021 Opera Euro Rapid. Radjabov played  9...Nbd7  , which allowed White to consolidate with  10.f3  . It is very important to start chasing White's pieces immediately. }
10. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Now Black gets the bishop pair, and the rooks will soon occupy the g and c files. }
11. O-O-O Bd7
{ Nc6-Rc8 is on the way, and there is no match for the f8 bishop. Black gets a long-lasting advantage here. }
*

