[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Semi-Tarrasch: Sidelines Overview"]
[Black "1) Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5
{ Black strikes in the center. The first game that reached this position goes back to 1834! In the late 19th century, 2nd world champion Lasker played this line twice. However, taking Nxd5 after cxd5 was first popularised by Schlechter and later played by Alekhine heavily. }
5. e3
{ The only other serious challenging move apart from  5.cxd5  . Although  5.Bg5  has also been tried several times, Black gets a good position after  5...cxd4  6.Nxd4  e5  taking complete control of the center.   White can try  5.Bf4  but after  5...cxd4  6.Nxd4  Nbd7  , the idea of e5, is difficult to deal with. }
5... Nc6
{ This position often also occurs from an English opening from the following move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  c5  2.c4  Nf6  3.Nc3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e3  e6  . }
6. a3
{ The main move in the position. After  6.cxd5  Nxd5  , we get to a position covered via the 5.cxd5 move order. }
6... dxc4
{ With the idea of getting into a Queens Gambit Accepted setup where White had already played moves like Nc3/a3, which are not the ideal way to deal with the QGA. In the 1886 World Championship match, this move was first seen between Zukertort vs. Steinitz. However, Black took on d4 on the next move, which is not our idea. }
7. Bxc4 a6
{ From Maroczy in 1899 to Ding in 2021, the strong players believed in this simple approach. Black is ready to play b5-Bb7 while White still faces trouble to get the c1 bishop out. }
8. O-O b5 9. Ba2
{ The bishop stays on the a2-g8 diagonal to help with the d5 break. } 9... Bb7
10. Qe2 { Bringing the rook out to get the d5 break. } 10... cxd4 11. Rd1
{ White plays against Black's king, but they doesn't have enough pieces ready for an attack. }
11... b4
{ This lovely move solves all of the issues for Black.  White has various ways of continuing the game, but nothing is scary anymore when the Black knight gets a nice spot on b4. More on this in the main file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Semi-Tarrasch: Sidelines Overview"]
[Black "2) Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5
{ Black strikes in the center. The first game that reached this position goes back to 1834! In the late 19th century, 2nd world champion Lasker played this line twice. However, taking Nxd5 after cxd5 was first popularised by Schlechter and later played by Alekhine heavily. }
5. cxd5
{ The main option. Earlier, White tried to play less ambitiously without taking on d5, which still remains popular among all levels. }
5... Nxd5
{ This is the proper Semi-Tarrasch. Unlike the regular Tarrasch, in the Semi-Tarrasch Defense, Black does not accept an isolated pawn. This move has been played frequently by Kramnik, Ding, and Magnus, among many other top GMs who frequently employ this variation. The solidity of this line is beyond any doubt, but often people do not realize how sharp and dynamic it can get. No wonder many young players like Abdusattarov, Keymer, etc. picked up this line and played it regularly. }
6. g3
{ This move has been played several times, and there are multiple ways to deal with it. I liked the straightforward approach that Black is playing in case 6.e4. }
6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 b6
{ The bishop on b7 nullifies the bishop on g2. Black gets control over the e4 square and brings his knight to f6 from d7 to gain further control in the center. In this direction, it is easier to play for Black, and in the main file, more details are given. }
*

