10. Re1
{ One of the old traditional ways for White to play this position.   I started my main file with the following words that I would like to copy-paste here:  The major move in this position. White waits for Black to reveal their plan and makes a standard developing move. The first step to learning what NOT to do will be crucial here. So let me ask all of the readers to see the famous game Botvinnik - Alekhine from Avro 1938.   Before making the next move, please take a look at the game, you can also find the game in  Kasparov's book 'My great Predecessors volume 2' @@StartBracket@@Game 36, which you can find here @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/my-great-predecessors-part-2/course/25417/@@EndBracket@@LinkEnd@@@@. You can also check the Model Games chapter of this course where I have included this game to make sure no one misses it :@@EndBracket@@ Without knowing the details of this game, it would be difficult to understand and develop a sense of danger in this seemingly harmless and peaceful position. }
10... Bf6
{ This is a nice way to play against the pawn on d4. Black threatens Nb6 to take the pawn on d4. }
11. Ne4 b6
{ Now, and only now, Black plays b6 when White cannot take on d5. These lines look pretty harmless, but it can get tricky if either side takes it casually. }
