1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. dxc5
{ Taking on c5 without waiting for Black to develop the dark-squared bishop only helps Black as we now take on c5 with a gain of a tempo. }
5... Bxc5 6. cxd5
{ 6.e3  Nc6  is covered from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pp4/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.e3  move order in a different chapter.   6.Bg5  was played a few times, but after  6...Qb6  White can resign as there is no way to defend the double attack on b2 and f2. }
6... exd5
{ Given a chance, Black might play d4. We are ahead in development, and White is not on time to consolidate the position and exploit the isolated pawn. }
7. e3
{ A sad necessity to stop Black from playing d4. Now White's dark-squared bishop's position is compromised. }
7... Nc6
{ Black is getting ready to play d4, which will liquidate the position completely. }
8. Bb5
{ This move has been played more than 200 times. White is ready to give up the light-squared bishop and claim that Black will get a worse pawn structure in the end. }
8... O-O 9. O-O a6
{ Clearly saying that the entire concept of giving the bishop is wrong, and Black insists that White captures on c6. }
10. Bxc6 { Otherwise, there is no justification for 8. Bb5. } 10... bxc6 11. b3
{ The only way to develop the bishop. White wants to get control over the c5 square with Bb2-Na4-Rc1 and stop Black from playing c5. }
11... Bd6
{ Anticipating White's plan, Black is getting ready to play c5 before White takes control over that square. }
12. Bb2 Bb7
{ The bishop will be dead if Black doesn't get to play c5, but there is no way for White to stop that. }
13. Rc1 c5
{ Right on time, Black got to play c5 and activated the bishop. Better control in the center with a pair of bishops gives us an advantage. The pawn on c5 will be well protected with Rc8-Qe7. }
