{ White gets the dark-squared bishop out to play e3 next. } 5... cxd4
{ Right on time when White is obliged to take on d4 with a piece. } 6. Nxd4
Nbd7
{ Taking advantage of the bishop's placement on f4. Black wants to fork with e5 next. }
7. Qa4 { Stopping e5 with the help of the pin. } 7... Bc5
{ Developing with a tempo and getting ready to castle. } 8. Nb3 O-O
{ Black is not worried about giving up the bishop for the knight. Development is the key here and White's king remains in the center. }
9. Nxc5 { 9.cxd5  is covered via the 8.cxd5 move order. } 9... Nxc5 10. Qa3 b6
{ Black continues to develop at rapid speed. Bb7 is coming next. White is still three moves away from castling. }
11. cxd5
{ After  11.Rd1  Bb7  12.e3  Qe7  it was difficult for white to stop the e5 threat. In Nisipeanu - Fridman,  2014 White got into trouble after  13.Bg3  Rfd8  when it was difficult to castle as Black kept threatening to take on c4 and g2. }
11... Nxd5 12. Nxd5
{ White still hopes to get an advantage with the pair of bishops, but they are way too behind in the development. }
12... exd5
{ A spectacular strategic decision, showing flexible thinking. Dynamism is more important at this stage as White is way behind in castling. To develop the light-squared bishop, White will eventually have to play e4, and Black is getting ready to play d4 as an antidote for that. }
13. e3 d4 { Going for the king by opening up the position. } 14. Rd1 Bb7
{ Once again, development is the key factor. Black doesn't mind giving up a pawn to expedite the development. }
15. Bc4
{ Wise decision. Taking on  d4  would bring White's position to grave danger. After  15.Rxd4  Qf6  , it would be impossible to meet threats like Ne6, Rad8-Rfe8 as White cannot develop the light-squared bishop due to the unprotected pawn on g2. The engine gives a clear advantage for Black. If in doubt, just ask the king on e1 about it :@@EndBracket@@ }
15... Qf6 { No rush to take on g2 and open the file for White. } 16. O-O Rfd8
{ 16...dxe3  17.Bxe3  Bxg2  ends with a perpetual. The move played in the game keeps the show going. }
17. f3 h5
{ Black's position remains active and that compensates for White's bishop pair. In one correspondence game, Black had no problem and, the game eventually ended in a draw. }
