1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bg5
{ White is putting direct pressure on the d5 pawn, but for now, they ignore the development on the kingside. }
5... cxd4
{ The standard way of challenging the center. Black will now gain a tempo with Nc6 or e5, depending on how White recaptures d4. }
6. Nxd4
{ After  6.Bxf6  gxf6  we will transpose irrespective of how White takes on d4. }
6... e5 { The typical response, when White takes on d4 with the knight. } 7.
Nf3
{ 7.Nc2  d4  8.Nd5  Nbd7  gives Black a strong center and a good position. }
7... d4 { Black's pawns keep marching forward in the center. } 8. Nd5
{ After  8.Bxf6  gxf6!  9.Nd5  Be6  White will have difficulty maintaining the knight in the center without making any compromise. }
8... Be7
{ The point of keeping the bishop on g5 can be seen after  8...Be6  9.e4  when Black is unable to take  9...dxe3  due to  10.Nxf6  gxf6  11.Qxd8  Kxd8  12.Bxf6  and White wins. }
9. Nxe7 { White takes the bishop and hopes to get a bishop pair advantage. }
9... Qxe7 10. e3 Bg4
{ The threats of e4 and Bxf3-Qxf3-Qb4 put White in a difficult situation. } *

