1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bg5
{ White is putting direct pressure on the d5 pawn, but for now, they ignore the development on the kingside. }
5... cxd4
{ The standard way of challenging the center. Black will now gain a tempo with Nc6 or e5, depending on how White recaptures d4. }
6. Nxd4
{ After  6.Bxf6  gxf6  we will transpose irrespective of how White takes on d4. }
6... e5 { The typical response, when White takes on d4 with the knight. } 7.
Bxf6 { Forcing Black to take on f6 with the pawn. } 7... gxf6
{ Black doesn't care about the broken pawn structure. The game is open, and we have a pair of bishops. }
8. Nc2
{ 8.Nf3  has been discussed from 7.Nf3 move order. After  8.Nb3  Black has a sweet choice of taking the pawn on c4 or playing for the initiative with  8...d4  . }
8... d4 { Gaining another tempo and more control in the center. } 9. Nd5 Be6
{ Harassing the knight immediately. } 10. e4
{ Trying not to give up the nice spot so easily. It was better for White to bail out with  10.e3  Bxd5  11.cxd5  Qxd5  12.exd4  Nc6  when with few more precise moves they would attain equality. }
10... Nd7
{ White has only one asset on d5, which can be eliminated at any time. On the other hand, Black has a pair of bishops, a strong passed pawn in the center, and breaks like f5 in the future, etc. }
11. Bd3 { The bishop doesn't look very bright here, but where else to go? }
11... Nc5 12. O-O Bg7
{ The undermining threats of f5 and b5 make the knight on d5 vulnerable. The engine gives a clear edge to Black, which is understandable as White lacks a plan and cannot stop the b5/f5 breaks. The so-called good knight on d5 has now become a burden. }
