[White "Chapter 8: Semi-Tarrasch (5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Alternatives)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines  5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg5
{ Gets a tempo, but in return, also gives a tempo after Black's next move. }
6... f6
{ It is also possible to play  6...Qa5  and follow the game Zubov - Naiditsch,  2019 where Black had easy equality. However, I like this option more since it is more forcing and easy to play from the Black side. }
7. Bd2 { There was no other good square available. } 7... cxd4
{ Black now takes control of the center. } 8. Nxd4 Nxc3 9. Bxc3 e5
{ The pawn formation of f6-e5 not only takes good control of the center but also kills the bishop on c3. }
10. Nb5 { White's only way to create some counterplay. } 10... Be6
{ Black has a strategic advantage since White's bishop on c3 is misplaced, and Black's bishop on e6 is ideally placed, which stops its counterpart from coming to c4 in the future. }
11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Rd1+
{ After  12.O-O-O  Nd7  , White's king won't feel safe on the queenside in the long run. }
12... Nd7 { Black now intends to kick the b5 knight out. } 13. e3
{ Finishing development and also stopping Black from playing a6. } 13... Bc5
{ Not falling for White's trap! After  13...a6  14.Ba5  b6  15.Bxb6  Ke7  16.Nc7  Nxb6  17.Nxa8  Nxa8  , the pawn on a6 falls due to  18.Bxa6  . }
14. Nd6 Kc7
{ The knight comes under attack. The engine's top choice here is to repeat the position with Nb5. Clearly Black has no problem in any kind of endgame at this point. }
