13. Rfc1
{ If White wants to control the 'c' file, then definitely it makes more sense to bring the rook from f1 and keep the a1 rook for the a4-a5 push. }
13... Nd7
{ The knight is ready to jump to f6 anytime to have more control on the e4 square. }
14. a4
{ White waited for Black to move his knight from b8 before playing a4. Black doesn't have a5-Na6 ideas available anymore. }
14... Rc8 { Trading pieces is the basic principle of this line. } 15. a5
{ White hopes to create a weakness for Black, but in reality, Black gets a passed pawn. }
15... Rxc1+
{ There are simply too many ways to play. Engines' top choice is to ignore White's idea and play h6. I am giving this variation to show how easy it is to play from the Black side. }
16. Qxc1 bxa5 17. Qc3 Qb6
{ Black gives up the pawn on a5 and brings his rook to protect his a7 pawn. }
18. Qxa5 Ra8
{ White's central pawns are not marching. Black got the rook behind their own passed pawn. The endgame looks nice for Black. }
