[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 8: Semi-Tarrasch (5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Alternatives)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines  5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.g3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. g3
{ This move is the only serious alternative apart from  6.e3  and  6.e4  . After opening up the center, White wants to get the bishop to g2 and claim the bishop on c8 will have a difficult time.  6.e3  Nc6  is covered from 5.e3 move order. }
6... Nxc3
{ Aiming for a simple endgame with a queenside pawn majority. The move  6...cxd4  gets to an equal endgame after  7.Nxd5  Qxd5  8.Qxd4  Qb5  9.e4  Qb4  10.Bd2  Nc6!  when a mass trade happens, and Black gets a perfectly acceptable endgame.   I like the move  6...Nc3  more simply because our play remains identical to the  6.e4  mainline. There is no other reasoning for choosing  6...Nxc3  over  6...cxd4  . If you are interested in adding  6...cxd4  , I suggest following the game Postny - Keymer,  2021, which is pretty straightforward. }
7. bxc3 cxd4 8. cxd4
{ After  8.Qxd4  Nc6  White ends up with a weak pawn on c3. } 8... Bb4+
{ This is important. Since White has a better center and Black has a queenside majority, it is beneficial for Black to exchange pieces. }
9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 b6
{ The move order is super important. Black should get the bishop to b7, and this is only possible if we start with this move order. After  10...O-O  11.Bg2  it would be impossible to play b6. }
11. Bg2 Bb7 12. O-O
{ Almost exclusively played. After  6...Nxc3  , we reach this position in most games. I want to point out a cheap trick that has not been tried yet. White can try  12.Qd3  and Black must be careful not to lose the game instantly with the careless  12...O-O  13.Ng5  when White wins material.   The simple  12...Nc6  13.O-O  O-O  is fine when White's Qd3 move is nothing but a waste of tempo.   White can also start with  12.a4  , but this doesn't change anything, and after  12...a5  13.O-O  O-O  , we get to the mainline covered from 12.O-O move order. }
12... O-O
{ The bishop on b7 nullifies its counterpart. Black is always happy to trade more pieces. White's main issue is that they are unable to get e4 easily. Let us first see if they can try to get e4 somehow. }
13. a4 { White wants to play a5 and create some pressure on the queenside. }
13... a5
{ I like this move when the Black's knight is still on b8. Black will now head for Na6-Nb4. This entire line lost its popularity after Kramnik played  13...Nc6  and showed a deep preparation against Svidler in Sochi 2016 and won a beautiful game. However, by improving on move 16 and precise play, White could get into a drawn rook pawn endgame with one extra pawn. I like the text move more as we don't even need to get to such a position just on principle :@@EndBracket@@ }
14. Rfc1
{ A rook on the b-file makes no sense as Black is ready with immediate Na6-Nb4. After  14.Ne5  Bxg2  15.Kxg2  f6  White knight lacks a good square due to Qd5/Qd4 ideas and must go back to f3. }
14... Na6 { Very straightforward plan of getting the knight to b4. } 15. Ne5
{ White tried  15.Qf4  Nb4  16.Qc7  in one game, but this makes no sense as Black is happy to trade some more pieces. Black played  16...Bd5  and was soon better due to White's weak pawn on a4 in the game Jankovic - Nabaty, 2014. }
15... Bxg2 16. Kxg2
{ With the rook on c1, playing  16...f6  doesn't make sense as White can play  17.Nc6  , and the knight is not hanging after  17...Qd5+  . }
16... Nb4 { Taking control of the c6 square. } 17. e4 Rc8
{ Welcoming a trade and planning to kick the knight out with f6 next. The pawn on a4 remains an easier target than the pawn on b6. If White keeps his knight on c4, it won't be stable as Black can triple on the c-file. In a correspondence game in 2020, Black had no problem, and eventually, the game ended in a draw. }
