[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9: Semi-Tarrasch(5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Others)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3 Nc6 7. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ Usually we should not get our queen out on d5 but without the knight on c3 it is not easy to kick the queen out while it keeps more pressure on the d4 pawn. }
8. dxc5 { If White moves the bishop from f1, Black takes on d4. } 8... Qxd1+ 9.
Kxd1 Bxc5
{ More than 20 games played in this position. I don't understand where is the fun of playing this setup as White! The king is more exposed in a symmetrical position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9: Semi-Tarrasch(5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Others)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.e4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3 Nc6 7. e4
{ I am surprised to see that even this move has been played a few times. Compared to the 5.e4 line, here White is trying to claim that the extra Nc6 is not ideal for Black. Seriously?? }
7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 cxd4 9. cxd4 Bb4+
{ In the mainline, we reach the same position with the knight on b8. } 10. Bd2
O-O
{ One of the ten ways to deal with this line. Clearly, Black benefits with an extra move compared to the mainline. }
