[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9: Semi-Tarrasch(5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Others)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Be2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3 Nc6 7. Be2
{ Too naive and toothless. White's bishop is definitely more meaningful on c4 or d3. Here it is a bit aimless. }
7... cxd4 8. exd4 Be7
{ Black's play is pretty straightforward. We saddled White with an isolated pawn and now we want to finish our development peacefully. }
9. O-O O-O
{ I don't see a single reason why the bishop is better on e2 than any other square. The engine wants to play Bb5/Bd3/ Bc4 in this position, and with that note, I would like to end it here :@@EndBracket@@ It is difficult to point out what compensation White has got for the isolated pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9: Semi-Tarrasch(5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Others)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bb5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3 Nc6 7. Bb5
{ This move has been played several times. White pins the knight, and in some cases, they are willing to take on c6 to damage Black's pawn structure. }
7... cxd4 8. exd4 Bd6
{ 8...Be7  is also perfectly playable, and after  9.O-O  O-O  , we get a position that usually comes from the Caro-Kann. However, Black can exploit the move order and place the bishop on a slightly better square on d6. The main point is, it keeps the e7 square free for the c6 knight. }
9. O-O O-O { Funnily engines are advising to play Bd3. } 10. Re1 Bd7
{ White's bishop is not doing much on  b5  , and they got an isolated pawn without having any compensation against it. Of course, White can bail out with  11.Nxd5  exd5  and claim equality, but that doesn't bother Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9: Semi-Tarrasch(5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Others)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bb5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3 Nc6 7. Bb5
{ This move has been played several times. White pins the knight, and in some cases, they are willing to take on c6 to damage Black's pawn structure. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4
{ The main point of the 7.Bb5 move. White builds pressure on c6 with the help of the pin. }
8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 a6
{ I like this move more instead of the popular Bd7. Out of 38 games that reached this position as of today, in every single game Black played  9...Bd7  . By playing  9...a6  Black questions White's entire strategy of keeping the bishop on b5. }
10. Be2
{ The computer's first choice of playing Be2 immediately underlines that Black's last move was a success. White was unable to take on c6 with either piece.  10.Nxc6  Qxd1  11.Kxd1  axb5  gives Black the bishop pair advantage while White ends up with an exposed king on d1 and a pathetic bishop on c1.   After  11.Bxc6  bxc6  12.Nxc6  Qxd1  13.Kxd1  Bb7  White eventually loses the pawn on g2 and ends up again with a dead bishop on c1. In either case, Black remains clearly better. }
10... Bd7 11. O-O Qc7
{ Black has nothing to complain about in this position as White got a weak pawn structure on the queenside, and Black is ready to castle next after playing Be7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 10: Semi-Tarrasch (5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bc4)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3 Nc6 7. Bc4
{ One of the most common moves in this position. White builds pressure on the knight on d5. }
7... cxd4
{ Black plays thematically. White will now have to deal with the isolated pawn. Black now gets a strategic advantage while White fights for a dynamic advantage. }
8. exd4 Be7
{ Keeping it simple and logical. Black wants to finish castling first. There are many games with  8...Bb4  but White sacrifices a pawn after  9.O-O  , and the position gets unnecessarily wild. }
9. O-O O-O
{ This is the main position. Black has various plans at their disposal, and it is of utmost importance that we understand the details here.   This is a perfect moment to take a break and clarify the position. Strategically speaking, Black is better due to the weak pawn on d4. However, White's pieces got more free space, and Black must deal with the less-than-perfect c8 bishop. If Black can consolidate the position, they will have a strategic advantage.   White naturally will try to stop and create some havoc on the board, but as we shall see, Black will manage to survive.   There are some move order details and plans that we should know:   ➥ Black can often play Bf6 to restrict the queen on d1, but this move makes less sense if White has already played Qe2 and is ready to answer Bf6 with Rd1.   ➥ Black can opt for a b6-Bb7 plan but must be careful to do so only after taking on c3 first. Otherwise, White takes Nxd5-exd5, and in a symmetrical structure, Black gets a weakness on c6.   ➥ There are also plans with a6-b5, which would ideally work with White's queen on e2 as that discourages White from opening up the e-file by exchanging on d5.   Before I confuse you any further, let us now look at some variations to get more clarity :@@EndBracket@@ }
10. Bb3
{ A pointless move. We now reach a position which can come from Sicilian Alapin with White to play, and even there, Black is doing fine :@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  Nf6  3.e5  Nd5  4.Nf3  d6  5.d4  cxd4  6.Bc4  Nb6  7.Bb3  dxe5  8.Nxe5  e6  9.cxd4  Nc6  10.Nf3  Be7  11.O-O  O-O  12.Nc3  Nd5  . }
10... Bf6
{ Putting more pressure on the d4 pawn and planning to play Nde7-Nf5 next. }
11. Ne4 { 11.Re1  is covered from 10.Re1 move order. } 11... b6
{ Black doesn't mind trading a few pieces as White has the isolated pawn, and trading would only help Black. }
12. Nxf6+
{ 12.Bxd5  exd5  13.Nxf6  Qxf6  gets to a completely equal position and is likely to end in a draw soon. }
12... Nxf6 { Not allowing Bg5 with a tempo. } 13. Bg5 Ne7
{ In Part One of this course, we saw a similar motif in the Karpov-Nimzo variation. Black welcomes White to take on f6 when we take back with the g-pawn, and after the bishop comes to b7 and the rook comes to g8, White will regret taking on f6. By playing Ne7, Black completely stopped White from playing d5, and with Bb7 coming next, we get a good position. }
