[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 10: Semi-Tarrasch (5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bc4)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bc4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3 Nc6 7. Bc4
{ One of the most common moves in this position. White builds pressure on the knight on d5. }
7... cxd4
{ Black plays thematically. White will now have to deal with the isolated pawn. Black now gets a strategic advantage while White fights for a dynamic advantage. }
8. exd4 Be7
{ Keeping it simple and logical. Black wants to finish castling first. There are many games with  8...Bb4  but White sacrifices a pawn after  9.O-O  , and the position gets unnecessarily wild. }
9. O-O O-O
{ This is the main position. Black has various plans at their disposal, and it is of utmost importance that we understand the details here.   This is a perfect moment to take a break and clarify the position. Strategically speaking, Black is better due to the weak pawn on d4. However, White's pieces got more free space, and Black must deal with the less-than-perfect c8 bishop. If Black can consolidate the position, they will have a strategic advantage.   White naturally will try to stop and create some havoc on the board, but as we shall see, Black will manage to survive.   There are some move order details and plans that we should know:   ➥ Black can often play Bf6 to restrict the queen on d1, but this move makes less sense if White has already played Qe2 and is ready to answer Bf6 with Rd1.   ➥ Black can opt for a b6-Bb7 plan but must be careful to do so only after taking on c3 first. Otherwise, White takes Nxd5-exd5, and in a symmetrical structure, Black gets a weakness on c6.   ➥ There are also plans with a6-b5, which would ideally work with White's queen on e2 as that discourages White from opening up the e-file by exchanging on d5.   Before I confuse you any further, let us now look at some variations to get more clarity :@@EndBracket@@ }
10. Qe2
{ Levon's latest try. He played it against MVL in 2021. I knew this very interesting pawn sacrifice for a long time, and the first time it got popular was after the Adams - Salem, Sharjah GP 2017 game. It was strange that MVL went straight into it and got a worse position. Interestingly, more than 30 games in this position with White to play came from Sicilian! @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bc4  e6  4.Qe2  Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  6.d4  d5  7.exd5  Nxd5  8.O-O  cxd4  9.cxd4  Be7  10.Nc3  O-O  . }
10... a6
{ This direction is much better against the Qe2 lines. Usually, for a6-b5 ideas, White takes on d5, but with the queen on e2, White won't feel comfortable opening up the e-file.  10...Bf6  that we are playing against  10.Re1  is not ideal here, as White is ready to play  11.Rd1  in this case.   Finally, the main idea behind this move is to offer a pawn sacrifice after  10...Nb6  11.Bd3  Nxd4  12.Nxd4  Qxd4  13.Rd1  , White gets tremendous compensation, it is easier to play from White. Adams won a nice game against Salem,  and Levon also got an excellent position against MVL. }
11. Rd1
{ 11.Bb3  b5  12.Nxd5  exd5  doesn't look attractive for White with the queen on e2 as Black soon gets another tempo with Re8. The position remains fine for Black.   11.a4  b6  gives Black a lovely square on b4 for the knight. }
11... b5
{ GM David Paravyan played this position twice @@StartBracket@@#1, #2 @@EndBracket@@ in 2020, and in both games, he had no trouble getting a comfortable position. }
12. Bd3 Nf6
{ Getting away from White's threats of taking on d5. White now remains with an isolated pawn, and Black would like to continue the usual way of developing with Bb7 next. }
13. Bg5 { Threatening to win a piece after Bxf6-Qe4. } 13... Bb7
{ Black is right on time to develop the pieces normally, and stop White's threat. }
14. Rac1 Nb4 { Taking complete control over the d5 square. } 15. Bb1 Rc8
{ White has no attack or initiative to claim. Black got complete control over the d5 square. Black had no problem in the game 1/2-1/2 Rakhmanov,A @@StartBracket@@2646@@EndBracket@@ -Paravyan,D @@StartBracket@@2653@@EndBracket@@ Khanty-Mansiysk 2020 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 10: Semi-Tarrasch (5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bc4)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bc4 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3 Nc6 7. Bc4
{ One of the most common moves in this position. White builds pressure on the knight on d5. }
7... cxd4
{ Black plays thematically. White will now have to deal with the isolated pawn. Black now gets a strategic advantage while White fights for a dynamic advantage. }
8. exd4 Be7
{ Keeping it simple and logical. Black wants to finish castling first. There are many games with  8...Bb4  but White sacrifices a pawn after  9.O-O  , and the position gets unnecessarily wild. }
9. O-O O-O
{ This is the main position. Black has various plans at their disposal, and it is of utmost importance that we understand the details here.   This is a perfect moment to take a break and clarify the position. Strategically speaking, Black is better due to the weak pawn on d4. However, White's pieces got more free space, and Black must deal with the less-than-perfect c8 bishop. If Black can consolidate the position, they will have a strategic advantage.   White naturally will try to stop and create some havoc on the board, but as we shall see, Black will manage to survive.   There are some move order details and plans that we should know:   ➥ Black can often play Bf6 to restrict the queen on d1, but this move makes less sense if White has already played Qe2 and is ready to answer Bf6 with Rd1.   ➥ Black can opt for a b6-Bb7 plan but must be careful to do so only after taking on c3 first. Otherwise, White takes Nxd5-exd5, and in a symmetrical structure, Black gets a weakness on c6.   ➥ There are also plans with a6-b5, which would ideally work with White's queen on e2 as that discourages White from opening up the e-file by exchanging on d5.   Before I confuse you any further, let us now look at some variations to get more clarity :@@EndBracket@@ }
10. Qe2
{ Levon's latest try. He played it against MVL in 2021. I knew this very interesting pawn sacrifice for a long time, and the first time it got popular was after the Adams - Salem, Sharjah GP 2017 game. It was strange that MVL went straight into it and got a worse position. Interestingly, more than 30 games in this position with White to play came from Sicilian! @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bc4  e6  4.Qe2  Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  6.d4  d5  7.exd5  Nxd5  8.O-O  cxd4  9.cxd4  Be7  10.Nc3  O-O  . }
10... a6
{ This direction is much better against the Qe2 lines. Usually, for a6-b5 ideas, White takes on d5, but with the queen on e2, White won't feel comfortable opening up the e-file.  10...Bf6  that we are playing against  10.Re1  is not ideal here, as White is ready to play  11.Rd1  in this case.   Finally, the main idea behind this move is to offer a pawn sacrifice after  10...Nb6  11.Bd3  Nxd4  12.Nxd4  Qxd4  13.Rd1  , White gets tremendous compensation, it is easier to play from White. Adams won a nice game against Salem,  and Levon also got an excellent position against MVL. }
11. Rd1
{ 11.Bb3  b5  12.Nxd5  exd5  doesn't look attractive for White with the queen on e2 as Black soon gets another tempo with Re8. The position remains fine for Black.   11.a4  b6  gives Black a lovely square on b4 for the knight. }
11... b5
{ GM David Paravyan played this position twice @@StartBracket@@#1, #2 @@EndBracket@@ in 2020, and in both games, he had no trouble getting a comfortable position. }
12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Bd3 Bg4
{ Black could be in trouble if we don't play this obvious move, but it is impossible to miss this natural response. White cannot move the queen to c2 now as Black will gladly give up the pawn to break White's kingside to expose White's king. White did not go for this venture and played the solid  14.Be3  and after  14...Nb4  Black was fine in the game 1/2-1/2 Esipenko, A @@StartBracket@@2654@@EndBracket@@ -Paravyan, D @@StartBracket@@2629@@EndBracket@@ Caleta 2020 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 10: Semi-Tarrasch (5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bc4)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bc4 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3 Nc6 7. Bc4
{ One of the most common moves in this position. White builds pressure on the knight on d5. }
7... cxd4
{ Black plays thematically. White will now have to deal with the isolated pawn. Black now gets a strategic advantage while White fights for a dynamic advantage. }
8. exd4 Be7
{ Keeping it simple and logical. Black wants to finish castling first. There are many games with  8...Bb4  but White sacrifices a pawn after  9.O-O  , and the position gets unnecessarily wild. }
9. O-O O-O
{ This is the main position. Black has various plans at their disposal, and it is of utmost importance that we understand the details here.   This is a perfect moment to take a break and clarify the position. Strategically speaking, Black is better due to the weak pawn on d4. However, White's pieces got more free space, and Black must deal with the less-than-perfect c8 bishop. If Black can consolidate the position, they will have a strategic advantage.   White naturally will try to stop and create some havoc on the board, but as we shall see, Black will manage to survive.   There are some move order details and plans that we should know:   ➥ Black can often play Bf6 to restrict the queen on d1, but this move makes less sense if White has already played Qe2 and is ready to answer Bf6 with Rd1.   ➥ Black can opt for a b6-Bb7 plan but must be careful to do so only after taking on c3 first. Otherwise, White takes Nxd5-exd5, and in a symmetrical structure, Black gets a weakness on c6.   ➥ There are also plans with a6-b5, which would ideally work with White's queen on e2 as that discourages White from opening up the e-file by exchanging on d5.   Before I confuse you any further, let us now look at some variations to get more clarity :@@EndBracket@@ }
10. Re1
{ The major move in this position. White waits for Black to reveal their plan and makes a standard developing move.   The first step to learning what NOT to do will be crucial here. So let me ask all of the readers to see the famous game Botvinnik - Alekhine from Avro 1938.   Before making the next move, please take a look at the game, you can also find the game in  Kasparov's book 'My great Predecessors volume 2' @@StartBracket@@Game 36, which you can find here @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/my-great-predecessors-part-2/course/25417/@@EndBracket@@LinkEnd@@@@. You can also check the Model Games chapter of this course where I have included this game to make sure no one misses it :@@EndBracket@@ Without knowing the details of this game, it would be difficult to understand and develop a sense of danger in this seemingly harmless and peaceful position. }
10... Bf6
{ Black threatens to play Nb6 and take the pawn on d4. From my previous comment after  10.Re1  ,  you know that  10...b6  is a mistake due to  11.Nxd5  exd5  12.Bb5  occurred in the famous game Botvinnik - Alekhine,  Avro 1938.   If you have seen the model game or read the notes from MGP by Kasparov, then you should also know that playing  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3  b6  is not good either when White has the extremely powerful  12.h4  . Modern engine's evaluation bar starts to dance after  12...Bxh4  13.Nxh4  Qxh4  14.Re3  when White's attack gets brutal. Both these moves @@StartBracket@@10...b6 and 10...Nxc3@@EndBracket@@ are bad, and this has been established long back. Modern engines are just confirming the same. }
11. Re4
{ This absurd idea of keeping the rook in the center was a shocker for me when I saw it for the first time. There is only one single game that reached this position, and the game was happening right beside my board back in 2000 in a closed event :-@@EndBracket@@ White mixed up the move order. This idea is pretty interesting after the inclusion of  11.Bb3  Nde7  . Playing this move directly gives black an advantage. }
11... b6 { Continuing with the normal way of developing the bishop. } 12. a3
{ The engine thinks the best move in the position is to go back Re1 :@@EndBracket@@ }
12... Nxc3 13. bxc3 Bb7
{ This move is stronger than  13...e5  , which Sasikiran played against Vladimirov in Hyderabad 2000. Black develops normally and keeps an eye on the rook on e4. }
14. Rg4
{ Trying to justify Re4 move, but there is no hint of attack for White. } 14...
Ne7
{ Black will play Rc8 next. White's queenside is broken, and there is no attack on the kingside. The rook on g4 has become a burden. Black can anyway play g6-Nf5 to consolidate the kingside further. Black remains clearly better. }
