{ Keeping it simple and logical. Black wants to finish castling first. There are many games with  8...Bb4  but White sacrifices a pawn after  9.O-O  , and the position gets unnecessarily wild. }
9. O-O O-O
{ This is the main position. Black has various plans at their disposal, and it is of utmost importance that we understand the details here.   This is a perfect moment to take a break and clarify the position. Strategically speaking, Black is better due to the weak pawn on d4. However, White's pieces got more free space, and Black must deal with the less-than-perfect c8 bishop. If Black can consolidate the position, they will have a strategic advantage.   White naturally will try to stop and create some havoc on the board, but as we shall see, Black will manage to survive.   There are some move order details and plans that we should know:   ➥ Black can often play Bf6 to restrict the queen on d1, but this move makes less sense if White has already played Qe2 and is ready to answer Bf6 with Rd1.   ➥ Black can opt for a b6-Bb7 plan but must be careful to do so only after taking on c3 first. Otherwise, White takes Nxd5-exd5, and in a symmetrical structure, Black gets a weakness on c6.   ➥ There are also plans with a6-b5, which would ideally work with White's queen on e2 as that discourages White from opening up the e-file by exchanging on d5.   Before I confuse you any further, let us now look at some variations to get more clarity :@@EndBracket@@ }
10. Re1
{ The major move in this position. White waits for Black to reveal their plan and makes a standard developing move.   The first step to learning what NOT to do will be crucial here. So let me ask all of the readers to see the famous game Botvinnik - Alekhine from Avro 1938.   Before making the next move, please take a look at the game, you can also find the game in  Kasparov's book 'My great Predecessors volume 2' @@StartBracket@@Game 36, which you can find here @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/my-great-predecessors-part-2/course/25417/@@EndBracket@@LinkEnd@@@@. You can also check the Model Games chapter of this course where I have included this game to make sure no one misses it :@@EndBracket@@ Without knowing the details of this game, it would be difficult to understand and develop a sense of danger in this seemingly harmless and peaceful position. }
10... Bf6
{ Black threatens to play Nb6 and take the pawn on d4. From my previous comment after  10.Re1  ,  you know that  10...b6  is a mistake due to  11.Nxd5  exd5  12.Bb5  occurred in the famous game Botvinnik - Alekhine,  Avro 1938.   If you have seen the model game or read the notes from MGP by Kasparov, then you should also know that playing  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3  b6  is not good either when White has the extremely powerful  12.h4  . Modern engine's evaluation bar starts to dance after  12...Bxh4  13.Nxh4  Qxh4  14.Re3  when White's attack gets brutal. Both these moves @@StartBracket@@10...b6 and 10...Nxc3@@EndBracket@@ are bad, and this has been established long back. Modern engines are just confirming the same. }
11. Bb3
{ This was popular for White at some point until Black found a clear way of getting a comfortable position. White gets away from the Nb6 threat. }
11... Nde7
{ Directly charging on the d4-pawn and bringing more force towards it with Nf5 coming next. }
12. Bf4
{ Kramnik played this pawn sacrifice against Meier, which was a one-game try, and no one followed this path again. }
12... Bxd4
{ This is the simplest route to get a balanced position.  12...Nxd4  is equally playable when White keeps some compensation which will suffice for equality but nothing more than that. }
13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Bc4 Ng6
{ The easiest way to get an equal position. In the game Kramnik - Meier,  Dortmund 2012, Black played  14...Nec6  15.Rc1  Qf6  and got a difficult position with all three results possible. I don't like to spend a lot of time and energy on something highly unlikely to occur in a game. It is good to know that there are many ways to keep the game going here, and 14...Ng6 is immediate equality. Depending on the tournament situation and mood, we can take the call what to play if, by some miracle, this position comes on board. }
15. Be3 e5 16. Bxd4
{ Otherwise, Black remains a pawn up, and White won't get enough compensation. }
16... Qxd4 { Simplifying the position further. } 17. Qxd4 exd4 18. Nb5 Bd7
{ White gets back the pawn, and the position liquidates completely and is likely to end in a draw soon. }
