10... Bf6
{ Black threatens to play Nb6 and take the pawn on d4. From my previous comment after  10.Re1  ,  you know that  10...b6  is a mistake due to  11.Nxd5  exd5  12.Bb5  occurred in the famous game Botvinnik - Alekhine,  Avro 1938.   If you have seen the model game or read the notes from MGP by Kasparov, then you should also know that playing  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3  b6  is not good either when White has the extremely powerful  12.h4  . Modern engine's evaluation bar starts to dance after  12...Bxh4  13.Nxh4  Qxh4  14.Re3  when White's attack gets brutal. Both these moves @@StartBracket@@10...b6 and 10...Nxc3@@EndBracket@@ are bad, and this has been established long back. Modern engines are just confirming the same. }
11. Bb3
{ This was popular for White at some point until Black found a clear way of getting a comfortable position. White gets away from the Nb6 threat. }
11... Nde7
{ Directly charging on the d4-pawn and bringing more force towards it with Nf5 coming next. }
12. Re4
{ This weird move was played a few times too. The rook swing doesn't look particularly scary at this point, but it should not come as a surprise. It is always better to know such moves/ideas well in advance. }
12... b6
{ The usual way of developing our bishop. This time the bishop on b7 will also harras the rook on e4. }
13. g4
{ I thought I was crazy to analyze this, and no one will play like this, but it turns out White has already tried this once! This is the only move that could bother me as Black. After all, White plays for mate with g5-Rh4 ideas. }
13... Nd5
{ When someone plays from the flank, we should play in the center. I am sure I have heard that several times :@@EndBracket@@ }
14. g5 Be7 15. Rh4 { White tries their best to play for mate. } 15... Na5
{ This move is pretty much the coldest shower White can get. White wanted to play Bc2 to attack h7, and Black practically forces White to do so. }
16. Bc2 g6 { With a simple question... How do you intend to attack now? } 17.
Qf1
{ The best way to continue the attack. Playing  17.Ne4  would be an empty move as the square f6 is well guarded. Black could continue with  17...Bb7  then. }
17... f5
{ A great counterattacking move that takes care of everything. Black is now ready to meet  18.Qh3  with  18...Rf7  .   18.gxf6  Bxf6  19.Rg4  e5  opens up the position, and the White king comes into danger. Black has no problems in the position. }
