12. a3 { A non-committal move. White wants to play Qd3 next. } 12... Bb7
{ The most natural way of developing the bishop. } 13. Qd3
{ This occurred in Levon - Anish in 2014 but lost popularity soon after, as Black has no issues here. The idea is to play Nfg5 next. }
13... Nce7
{ Once again, the thematic knight maneuver. Gaining full control over the d5 square and opening up the bishop on b7. }
14. Nfg5 { White continues his attack. } 14... Bxg5 15. Nxg5 Nf6
{ We see the point of 13... Nce7. White is missing the thematic d5. } 16. Nxf7
{ Practically forced. Otherwise, black would have played Bd5, and white would get into a strategically worse position. }
16... Rxf7 17. Bxe6 Bd5 { Forcing white to take on f7 } 18. Bxf7+ Bxf7
{ Materially speaking, White is doing fine. But the Bishop is weak, and the central pawn is weak. Black knight will come to d5, and white king might come under attack as the pawn on g2 is weak as Black's light-squared Bishop has no match. }
