10... Bf6
{ Black threatens to play Nb6 and take the pawn on d4. From my previous comment after  10.Re1  ,  you know that  10...b6  is a mistake due to  11.Nxd5  exd5  12.Bb5  occurred in the famous game Botvinnik - Alekhine,  Avro 1938.   If you have seen the model game or read the notes from MGP by Kasparov, then you should also know that playing  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3  b6  is not good either when White has the extremely powerful  12.h4  . Modern engine's evaluation bar starts to dance after  12...Bxh4  13.Nxh4  Qxh4  14.Re3  when White's attack gets brutal. Both these moves @@StartBracket@@10...b6 and 10...Nxc3@@EndBracket@@ are bad, and this has been established long back. Modern engines are just confirming the same. }
11. Ne4
{ The most logical move. White keeps an eye on the bishop on f6 and questions Black's idea behind their last move. }
11... b6
{ Now and ONLY now, Black should play b6 when White cannot take on d5 with the knight. Once again, if you have not seen the game Botvinnik - Alekhine from 1938 after getting two reminders, this is your third reminder to do so for getting a better understanding of the position. We should never allow Nxd5 while playing b6. }
12. Nxf6+
{ It looks tempting to take the bishop, and this is the main move in this position. However, this moves creates zero issues for Black, and we get a lovely position. }
12... Nxf6
{ Now Black has the most straightforward plan of playing Bb7-Nce7 and taking full control of the d5 square. }
13. Bg5
{ It looks intimidating that White took Black's good bishop and now pins the knight on f6, which will be very difficult to get rid of. In reality, these all are nothing but an optical illusion, as we shall see in the next couple of moves. }
13... Bb7
{ Natural and easy to understand. Black ignores White's threats and continues to develop logically. }
14. Ne5
{ This particular move has been played only once, as it leads to immediate equality. It is White who is in danger of getting into a worse position so, in my opinion, this move is a good decision by White to bail out with equality. White sacrifices a pawn on d4 and gives a classic threat of Ba6. }
14... Qxd4
{ The simplest route to equality. We can also keep the game complex with  14...Nxd4  15.Ng4  Kh8  . When White gets some compensation for the pawn and computer evaluation remains 0.00, but in a practical game, all three results would be possible. }
15. Bxf6
{ The only way to make it complex.  15.Nxc6  Qxc4  would lead nowhere and Black remains one pawn up. }
15... gxf6 16. Nxf7
{ 16.Nxc6  will once again be met by  16...Qxc4  when Black remains one pawn up. }
16... Qxc4
{ Eliminates the bishop and kills White's attacking prospect completely. } 17.
Nd6 { Otherwise, White would remain a piece down for nothing. } 17... Qd4
{ Black now gets into an endgame. } 18. Nxb7 Qxd1
{ Black compromised the pawn structure in front of the king, so exchanging queens is important. }
19. Raxd1 e5
{ Defending the pawn on e6 and creating a square on d4 for the c6-knight. } 20.
Nd6 Rad8
{ Black is ready to put the knight on d4. White can play Nf5, but then Black brings the King to e6 via f7. The position remains equal. }
