14. Rc1
{ Several GMs played this move, including a few 2700+ players. This move is once again the most natural, White develops the rook to an open file. It might sound strange, but after this standard move by White, Black now gets the advantage! The move  14.a3  is also equally popular, but we don't need to learn anything extra in this case. The novelty that I am proposing works even stronger against the  14.a3  plan, and we can continue playing  14...h6  as we do in 14.Rc1 variation. Black's play remains identical. }
14... h6
{ A strong novelty that changes the evaluation of this entire position. In every single game that reached this position, Black played the automatic  14...Rc8  , which is much weaker than the text move. }
15. Bh4
{ White might pretend to be content and curious to see what changes with the inclusion of h6-Bh4. }
15... Ne7
{ If you already have Part I of this course which covered the Nimzo Indian extensively, then you might remember in the Karpov system of Nimzo, I was recommending this maneuver many times. The difference of including h6-Bh4 gets clear as Black threatens to play Nf5 with a tempo. }
16. Ne5
{ White must be precise now, not to get into a terrible position. After the naive  16.Bxf6  gxf6  it is the White king that comes into danger. White will never get to play d5 while the bishop is on b7, and the rook on g8 @@StartBracket@@after Black moves the king to h7@@EndBracket@@ will create a massive attack on the kingside. The king on h7 remains super safe as Black can block the diagonal anytime we want. }
16... Nf5 { Forcing White to take on f6. } 17. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ Now  17...gxf6  would be a blunder due to  18.Nxf7  followed by Bxe6. Black now has multiple targets. He can attack g2 with moves like Qg5/Nh4. There are simple developing moves like Rad8, creating pressure against the pawn on d4. The engine manages to hold the position and gives Black only a microscopic edge, but I think Black will get a substantial advantage in a practical game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 10: Semi-Tarrasch (5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bc4)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bc4 - Alternative"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3 Nc6 7. Bc4
{ One of the most common moves in this position. White builds pressure on the knight on d5. }
7... cxd4
{ Black plays thematically. White will now have to deal with the isolated pawn. Black now gets a strategic advantage while White fights for a dynamic advantage. }
8. exd4 Be7
{ Keeping it simple and logical. Black wants to finish castling first. There are many games with  8...Bb4  but White sacrifices a pawn after  9.O-O  , and the position gets unnecessarily wild. }
9. O-O O-O
{ This is the main position. Black has various plans at their disposal, and it is of utmost importance that we understand the details here.   This is a perfect moment to take a break and clarify the position. Strategically speaking, Black is better due to the weak pawn on d4. However, White's pieces got more free space, and Black must deal with the less-than-perfect c8 bishop. If Black can consolidate the position, they will have a strategic advantage.   White naturally will try to stop and create some havoc on the board, but as we shall see, Black will manage to survive.   There are some move order details and plans that we should know:   ➥ Black can often play Bf6 to restrict the queen on d1, but this move makes less sense if White has already played Qe2 and is ready to answer Bf6 with Rd1.   ➥ Black can opt for a b6-Bb7 plan but must be careful to do so only after taking on c3 first. Otherwise, White takes Nxd5-exd5, and in a symmetrical structure, Black gets a weakness on c6.   ➥ There are also plans with a6-b5, which would ideally work with White's queen on e2 as that discourages White from opening up the e-file by exchanging on d5.   Before I confuse you any further, let us now look at some variations to get more clarity :@@EndBracket@@ }
10. Re1
{ The major move in this position. White waits for Black to reveal their plan and makes a standard developing move.   The first step to learning what NOT to do will be crucial here. So let me ask all of the readers to see the famous game Botvinnik - Alekhine from Avro 1938.   Before making the next move, please take a look at the game, you can also find the game in  Kasparov's book 'My great Predecessors volume 2' @@StartBracket@@Game 36, which you can find here @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/my-great-predecessors-part-2/course/25417/@@EndBracket@@LinkEnd@@@@. You can also check the Model Games chapter of this course where I have included this game to make sure no one misses it :@@EndBracket@@ Without knowing the details of this game, it would be difficult to understand and develop a sense of danger in this seemingly harmless and peaceful position. }
10... a6
{ Some 2020 correspondence games went this way. Also mentioned by Kasparov in MGP as the possibly best alternative. It is indeed possible to play this way and make our lives easier. After @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/2n1p3/3n4/2BP4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Qe2  also, we are going for a6. I have no particular objection to this move, but I felt this makes the position dull, and we don't play for three results. I generally dislike positions where only we need to be precise, and our opponents can play anything. However, that doesn't make this line bad, so I decided to give this as an alternate option. Black wants to play b5 next. }
11. Bb3
{ Any other move doesn't scare Black as they would then continue with the plan of playing b5. White naturally does not want to play a4 and weaken the square on b4. }
11... b5 12. Nxd5
{ This was the point of playing Bb3. White now takes on d5 with his knight. }
12... exd5
{ The machine gives a slight edge, but Black is likely to hold without much difficulty. }
13. a4
{ Stopping Bg4 by attacking  b5  and  d5  . After  13...Bg4  14.axb5  axb5  15.Rxa8  Qxa8  Black loses the central pawn with  16.Bxd5  . }
13... Be6 14. axb5 axb5 15. Rxa8 Qxa8
{ I don't see Black getting into huge trouble here, and objectively the position is equal. However, if I could pick a color, I would rather be White. On a second thought, if the condition of the tournament is that as White, I have to win, and as Black, a draw will suffice @@StartBracket@@or it is an armageddon@@EndBracket@@, then I would pick Black without a second thought. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 11: Semi-Tarrasch (5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bd3)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 Nc6 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bd3
{ The most popular move in the position. White doesn't create any pressure on the d5 knight, but anticipates an isolated pawn structure after cxd4-exd4, keeping the bishop on the ideal diagonal.  7.a3  cxd4  8.exd4  Be7  9.Bd3  transposes to  7.Bd3  line. }
7... Be7
{ Since there is no pressure on the d5 knight yet, there is no need to make a commital decision. Black will have to opt for Be7-O-O in any case, so better to start with that. Whether to take cxd4 or play Nxc3-b6 or direct b6 or some other plans on the queenside can be decided later based on White's response. }
8. O-O
{ The most natural and popular move. However, the move  8.a3  is very tricky, and Black should not fall for White's trap with  8...O-O?  as after  9.Nxd5  Qxd5  10.Qc2  the threats of Bxh7 and Bxe4 are annoying.   The easiest way to deal with  8.a3  is to play  8...cxd4  9.exd4  O-O  . Now White can't try the same trick as the d4 pawn hangs. Thus they must play  10.O-O  , and we transpose to the mainline starting with 8.O-O. }
8... O-O
{ Black doesn't show their cards and stays flexible. Based on White's play, Black can decide whether to play Bf6/cxd4/b6/Nxc3-b6. For now, White must solve the issue with the dark-squared bishop. This is a critical junction when White gets a plethora of moves, and most of them are equally good, but give no advantage to White :@@EndBracket@@ }
9. Qc2
{ Tempting but a clear mistake. In general Black should be aware of the following tactic that usually works when White skips the prophylactic a3 move. }
9... Ndb4
{ This is an improvement over the speed chess game between Ponkratov - So where Black played  9...Nf6  with an equal game. }
10. Bxh7+ Kh8 { White loses the bishop after g6. } 11. Qb1 g6 12. Bxg6 fxg6 13.
Qxg6
{ Wesley probably avoided this entire line, fearing some perpetual, but White is not getting any. }
13... Rf6 14. Qh5+ Kg7
{ White is not getting any perpetual, and ironically the king will come into danger soon due to the open files on the kingside. Black wouldn't mind exchanging queens. After the queen trade also, White's king will be in danger as Black's rooks will start dominating the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 11: Semi-Tarrasch (5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bd3)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bd3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 Nc6 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bd3
{ The most popular move in the position. White doesn't create any pressure on the d5 knight, but anticipates an isolated pawn structure after cxd4-exd4, keeping the bishop on the ideal diagonal.  7.a3  cxd4  8.exd4  Be7  9.Bd3  transposes to  7.Bd3  line. }
7... Be7
{ Since there is no pressure on the d5 knight yet, there is no need to make a commital decision. Black will have to opt for Be7-O-O in any case, so better to start with that. Whether to take cxd4 or play Nxc3-b6 or direct b6 or some other plans on the queenside can be decided later based on White's response. }
8. O-O
{ The most natural and popular move. However, the move  8.a3  is very tricky, and Black should not fall for White's trap with  8...O-O?  as after  9.Nxd5  Qxd5  10.Qc2  the threats of Bxh7 and Bxe4 are annoying.   The easiest way to deal with  8.a3  is to play  8...cxd4  9.exd4  O-O  . Now White can't try the same trick as the d4 pawn hangs. Thus they must play  10.O-O  , and we transpose to the mainline starting with 8.O-O. }
8... O-O
{ Black doesn't show their cards and stays flexible. Based on White's play, Black can decide whether to play Bf6/cxd4/b6/Nxc3-b6. For now, White must solve the issue with the dark-squared bishop. This is a critical junction when White gets a plethora of moves, and most of them are equally good, but give no advantage to White :@@EndBracket@@ }
9. Be4
{ Trying to hit the knight on d5 and give Black an isolated pawn by following up with dxc5. }
9... Nf6
{ 9...Nxc3  10.bxc3  Qc7  is also strategically solid, and perfectly playable as happened in the game Caruana - Grischuk, 2017. By playing 9...Nf6 Black practically forces White to take on c6. }
10. Bxc6
{ Any other bishop retreat would have been answered with b6 when White will have no justification for playing Be4. }
10... bxc6
{ Black's doubled pawns are temporary. We will soon open up the position with cxd4-c5. }
11. Na4
{ After  11.dxc5  Ba6!  12.Re1  Bxc5  Black gets excellent piece activity and a pair of bishops that compensates more than enough for the broken pawn structure. }
11... cxd4 12. exd4
{ 12.Nxd4  Qc7  makes no sense for White as the knight will soon be kicked away from d4, and Black takes control over the d-file. The light-squared bishop has no match. Engine evaluation of -1 feels right. }
12... Ba6 13. Re1 Rc8
{ Both sides got a weak pawn, but Black has the bishop pair. We can play c5 next to open up the position. White is unable to play  14.Nc5  as after  14...Bxc5  15.dxc5  Qxd1  16.Rxd1  Be2  Black takes on f3 and breaks White's kingside. The current position remains equal. }
