[White "Chapter 11: Semi-Tarrasch (5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bd3)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bd3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 Nc6 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bd3
{ The most popular move in the position. White doesn't create any pressure on the d5 knight, but anticipates an isolated pawn structure after cxd4-exd4, keeping the bishop on the ideal diagonal.  7.a3  cxd4  8.exd4  Be7  9.Bd3  transposes to  7.Bd3  line. }
7... Be7
{ Since there is no pressure on the d5 knight yet, there is no need to make a commital decision. Black will have to opt for Be7-O-O in any case, so better to start with that. Whether to take cxd4 or play Nxc3-b6 or direct b6 or some other plans on the queenside can be decided later based on White's response. }
8. O-O
{ The most natural and popular move. However, the move  8.a3  is very tricky, and Black should not fall for White's trap with  8...O-O?  as after  9.Nxd5  Qxd5  10.Qc2  the threats of Bxh7 and Bxe4 are annoying.   The easiest way to deal with  8.a3  is to play  8...cxd4  9.exd4  O-O  . Now White can't try the same trick as the d4 pawn hangs. Thus they must play  10.O-O  , and we transpose to the mainline starting with 8.O-O. }
8... O-O
{ Black doesn't show their cards and stays flexible. Based on White's play, Black can decide whether to play Bf6/cxd4/b6/Nxc3-b6. For now, White must solve the issue with the dark-squared bishop. This is a critical junction when White gets a plethora of moves, and most of them are equally good, but give no advantage to White :@@EndBracket@@ }
9. Qe2 { White wants to get Rd1 quickly. Magnus played this move thrice. } 9...
Ndb4
{ Black attacks the bishop on d3 and the pawn on d4. We are also threatening to play b6-Ba6 after White moves the bishop. }
10. Be4 b6
{ With the bishop on e4, this move works better. It is important not to take on d4 as after the mass exchange when White plays Rd1 Black will be missing Qh4. }
11. Rd1 Ba6 12. Qe1 cxd4 { Clarifying the center. } 13. exd4
{ After  13.Nxd4  Nxd4  14.Rxd4  Qc7  White can't take on  c8  due to the fork on c2. }
13... Nd5
{ With the bishop on b1, White can still think of creating some kingside attacking plans with Qe4. But with the bishop being on e4, it is completely useless. White should rather take on d5 and bailout with equality now. }
