9. Qe2 { White wants to get Rd1 quickly. Magnus played this move thrice. } 9...
Ndb4
{ Black attacks the bishop on d3 and the pawn on d4. We are also threatening to play b6-Ba6 after White moves the bishop. }
10. Bb1 b6
{ Threatening Ba6. With the bishop on b1, taking on d4 is also a nice option. After  10...cxd4  11.exd4  Nxd4  12.Nxd4  Qxd4  White gets some compensation that will give him an equal position but not more. For example, after  13.Rd1  Qh4  or @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp2bppp/4p3/8/1n1q4/2N5/PP2QPPP/RBBR2K1 b - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Be4  f5  14.Rd1  Qe5  Black queen remains safe, and a timely e5 will free the position up completely. }
11. Rd1 { There was no time for  11.a3  as  11...Ba6  wins material. } 11...
Ba6 12. Qe1 cxd4 13. exd4
{ White must accept getting an isolated pawn. After  13.Nxd4  Nxd4  14.Rxd4  Qc7  computer screams -1.5. If in doubt, ask White's queenside pieces :@@EndBracket@@ }
13... Rc8
{ Calmly finishing the development. The only thing that remains to be checked is if White can create a kingside attack. }
14. Qe4 g6
{ The only thing black has to look out for is if White can create some play on the dark squares in the kingside. }
15. Bh6 Re8
{ What now? Black intends to play Bf6-Ne7 making the kingside rock solid. } 16.
a3 Nd5
{ Black consolidated his position completely and had no problem in the game 1/2-1/2 Yu,Y @@StartBracket@@2738@@EndBracket@@ -Ding,L @@StartBracket@@2801@@EndBracket@@ Ningbo 2019. }
