9. Nxd5
{ Aiming to play against the isolated pawn after  9...exd5  10.dxc5  . } 9...
Qxd5
{ At first sight, it feels weird to allow e4 with a tempo, but Black has a cunning idea against it. }
10. Qc2
{ Naroditsky played this move in 2021. This keeps a threat on h7 and Be4 ideas. }
10... Qh5
{ Getting away from both the threats mentioned in the previous move. } 11. Be4
{ After  11.Be2  cxd4  12.Nxd4  Black can take  12...Nxd4  as the queen on c2 is under attack, and after  13.exd4  Qh4  White gets an isolated pawn. }
11... cxd4 12. Nxd4
{ 12.exd4  Bd7  gives White an isolated pawn and not enough compensation for it. }
12... Bd6 13. f4
{ Not to create further weaknesses, playing  13.h3  or  13.g3  would have been wiser. Although Black still gets a comfortable position after  13...Nxd4  and White ends up with an isolated pawn. }
13... Nxd4
{ In the game, Naroditsky, D @@StartBracket@@2623@@EndBracket@@ - Burke, J @@StartBracket@@2554@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2021 Black played  13...Bd7  , which allowed White to avoid getting an isolated pawn. }
14. exd4 Rb8
{ Black threatens Bd7. White must justify their reckless play that created multiple weaknesses. }
15. Qa4 { Trying to stop Bd7. } 15... a6
{ Sooner or later, the bishop on c8 will come out, and White will end up with two pawn weaknesses on f4 and d4. The engines give an advantage to Black for obvious reasons. }
