9. Re1
{ White is hoping for  9...cxd4  10.exd4  when the rook will get activated on e1. }
9... b6
{ Black is not obliged to take on d4. This is the reason Black did not commit to the queenside and started with Be7-O-O. There is no need to take on d4 anymore. }
10. Nxd5
{ 10.Qc2  Ndb4  gets White into immediate trouble. As either, they have to give the bishop on d3 for the knight or lose the bishop entirely after  11.Bxh7  Kh8  followed by g6.   10.a3  Bb7  11.Qc2  is a possibility, but Black plays  11...h6  and will refrain from taking on d4 and continue developing with Rc8 when White faces difficulties developing the queenside pieces. }
10... exd5
{ Grabbing the chance of activating the light-squared bishop while White's bishop on c1 remains shut. }
11. Bb5
{ This position occurred in the game Artemiev - Wesley in online speed chess. }
11... Qd6
{ This move is stronger than Wesley's Bb7. Black can keep the bishop on the better diagonal and develop it on g4 or f5. White still has issues with developing the queenside pieces. }
12. b3 a6
{ Asking White to decide what to do with the light-squared bishop. If it goes back, what was the point of coming to b5? If White takes, Black gets the bishop pair advantage and a free position to play for. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 11: Semi-Tarrasch (5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bd3)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bd3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 Nc6 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bd3
{ The most popular move in the position. White doesn't create any pressure on the d5 knight, but anticipates an isolated pawn structure after cxd4-exd4, keeping the bishop on the ideal diagonal.  7.a3  cxd4  8.exd4  Be7  9.Bd3  transposes to  7.Bd3  line. }
7... Be7
{ Since there is no pressure on the d5 knight yet, there is no need to make a commital decision. Black will have to opt for Be7-O-O in any case, so better to start with that. Whether to take cxd4 or play Nxc3-b6 or direct b6 or some other plans on the queenside can be decided later based on White's response. }
8. O-O
{ The most natural and popular move. However, the move  8.a3  is very tricky, and Black should not fall for White's trap with  8...O-O?  as after  9.Nxd5  Qxd5  10.Qc2  the threats of Bxh7 and Bxe4 are annoying.   The easiest way to deal with  8.a3  is to play  8...cxd4  9.exd4  O-O  . Now White can't try the same trick as the d4 pawn hangs. Thus they must play  10.O-O  , and we transpose to the mainline starting with 8.O-O. }
8... O-O
{ Black doesn't show their cards and stays flexible. Based on White's play, Black can decide whether to play Bf6/cxd4/b6/Nxc3-b6. For now, White must solve the issue with the dark-squared bishop. This is a critical junction when White gets a plethora of moves, and most of them are equally good, but give no advantage to White :@@EndBracket@@ }
9. Re1
{ White is hoping for  9...cxd4  10.exd4  when the rook will get activated on e1. }
9... b6
{ Black is not obliged to take on d4. This is the reason Black did not commit to the queenside and started with Be7-O-O. There is no need to take on d4 anymore. }
10. Nxd5
{ 10.Qc2  Ndb4  gets White into immediate trouble. As either, they have to give the bishop on d3 for the knight or lose the bishop entirely after  11.Bxh7  Kh8  followed by g6.   10.a3  Bb7  11.Qc2  is a possibility, but Black plays  11...h6  and will refrain from taking on d4 and continue developing with Rc8 when White faces difficulties developing the queenside pieces. }
10... exd5
{ Grabbing the chance of activating the light-squared bishop while White's bishop on c1 remains shut. }
11. dxc5
{ White now tries to play against Black's hanging pawns or isolated pawn, depending on how Black recaptures. }
11... bxc5
{ Black has hanging pawns, but it is quite difficult to attack them. White's bishop on c1 is still suffering. Black will play natural moves like Bg4/Be6, Qb6, Rb8/Rd8, etc. We have an easy game, and Black did not have any problem in the game, 1/2-1/2 Radjabov,T @@StartBracket@@2765@@EndBracket@@ -Nepomniachtchi,I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020 }
