[White "Chapter 11: Semi-Tarrasch (5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bd3)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Bd3 #16"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 Nc6 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bd3
{ The most popular move in the position. White doesn't create any pressure on the d5 knight, but anticipates an isolated pawn structure after cxd4-exd4, keeping the bishop on the ideal diagonal.  7.a3  cxd4  8.exd4  Be7  9.Bd3  transposes to  7.Bd3  line. }
7... Be7
{ Since there is no pressure on the d5 knight yet, there is no need to make a commital decision. Black will have to opt for Be7-O-O in any case, so better to start with that. Whether to take cxd4 or play Nxc3-b6 or direct b6 or some other plans on the queenside can be decided later based on White's response. }
8. O-O
{ The most natural and popular move. However, the move  8.a3  is very tricky, and Black should not fall for White's trap with  8...O-O?  as after  9.Nxd5  Qxd5  10.Qc2  the threats of Bxh7 and Bxe4 are annoying.   The easiest way to deal with  8.a3  is to play  8...cxd4  9.exd4  O-O  . Now White can't try the same trick as the d4 pawn hangs. Thus they must play  10.O-O  , and we transpose to the mainline starting with 8.O-O. }
8... O-O
{ Black doesn't show their cards and stays flexible. Based on White's play, Black can decide whether to play Bf6/cxd4/b6/Nxc3-b6. For now, White must solve the issue with the dark-squared bishop. This is a critical junction when White gets a plethora of moves, and most of them are equally good, but give no advantage to White :@@EndBracket@@ }
9. a3
{ The main move. White decides to take the same policy as Black and remains non-committal. The pawn on a3 is useful in IQP positions, and it also helps White play Qc2 in the future without fearing Nb4. }
9... cxd4
{ There are many ways to deal with 9.a3, but I like this move as it is most consistent. White cannot trick us with  8.a3  move order in this case. We play cxd4 whenever White opts for a3. Simple and easy to remember. }
10. exd4
{ Once again, we get the typical IQP positions where Black gets the static advantage of having a better pawn structure, and White gets more free space for the pieces. If Black can finish development on the queenside freely, they will be better, so White tries to play energetically to create a counter before Black can consolidate. }
10... Bf6
{ It might look tempting to immediately solve the light-squared bishop issue with  10...b6  , but White goes  11.Qc2  and the threats on h7 and c6 force Black to play  11...Nf6  . Black can play that way, but the lines are very complex where White has multiple ways to test Black, we must know and play precise moves to make a draw.  I like to avoid such one-sided lines. A good example could be the Vidit - Nepo game in 2021 when Black got into immediate trouble right after the opening. I like the text move more. Playing Bf6 Black aims for the d4 pawn and clears the e7 square for the knights. This is the most logical and the top choice of modern engines and recent games both over the board and in correspondence. }
11. Be4
{ The most popular move. White protects the pawn on  d4  and centralizes the bishop.  11.Ne4  was tried in some online games, but Black remains a pawn up after  11...Bxd4  12.Neg5  Nf6  , and there is no attack after  13.Nxd4  Nxd4  when at best White can hope for equality.   White also tried  11.Be3  , hoping Black would take the bad bishop and fix the pawn structure. Obviously, black would not do anything like that and both  11...Nce7  , playing against the isolated pawn, and  11...Nxc3  12.bxc3  b6  playing against the c3-pawn remains pleasant for Black. White is left with a horrible bishop on e3 and some pawn weaknesses in either case. }
11... Nce7
{ This is a standard plan, to consolidate the knight on d5 and bring more support to the key square. Here, it is especially strong since White is also missing any Ne4 ideas. }
12. h4
{ A typical move in IQP positions, and in recent times pretty much in every position :@@EndBracket@@ Recently this move was played by Anish against Sam Shankland. }
12... Bd7 13. Ng5
{ After  13.h5  Bc6  , it is difficult to deal with the Nxc3 threats, and Black creates play faster in the center. The computer already gives a substantial advantage for Black. It is nice to note that after a long think, the engine feels the best way for White here to play is  13.Qd3  h6  14.Bh7+  Kh8  15.Be4  :-@@EndBracket@@ Obviously, if Black wants, they can repeat with  15...Kg8  . }
13... g6
{ White pushed too far artificially, and Black already took over. The attack here is nothing but an illusion. }
14. h5
{ White continues to expand on the kingside. In Megaranto - Wang Yue,  2017, Black played  14...Bc6  , which gives him a slight edge, but Black has an even stronger move here. }
14... Nf5 { Attacking g5 and d4 simultaneously. } 15. Qg4
{ Most likely, Black did not play  14...Nf5  due to this move, and probably did not see what to do next. }
15... Nde3
{ This pretty tactic eliminates White's attacking knight on g5 and breaks the pawn structure. Black gets a better position as White remains with a bad pawn structure and stays behind in development. }
