12. Ne5
{ More than 30 games reached this position. White would like to play Ng4 or even stronger Qd3, provoking some pawn moves on the kingside and switching the queen to g3 or h3. }
12... Ng6
{ Black challenges the knight on e5. This move has never been played so far. It is not surprising since, at first sight, it's not clear how to respond after f4. }
13. Qh5
{ Looks very tempting, but there is no attack as long as the knight stays on g6. Black will now cunningly trade the right pieces. }
13... Nxc3 14. bxc3 Bxe5
{ Eliminating both knights and at the same time killing White's attack. } 15.
dxe5 Qa5
{ Black not only keeps an eye on the c3 and e5 pawn @@StartBracket@@note that it is impossible to take the e5 pawn just yet@@EndBracket@@ but also poses the fine strategic threat of playing f5 when White won't be able to en-passant the pawn as the queen on h5 hangs. Black will then collect the weak pawns on c3/e5. There are ideas like Bd7-Bc6 also to eliminate White's good bishop. }
