1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 Nc6
{ This position often also occurs in the English opening from the following move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  c5  2.c4  Nf6  3.Nc3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e3  e6  . }
6. dxc5
{ White allows Black to save a tempo by taking on c5 directly from f8.  6.Be2  has been played a few times when Black can take  6...dxc4  7.Bxc4  , and we get a mirror image of 6.dxc5 lines. Also, if we compare with the 6.a3 line where we are taking on c4, we will see White is losing one extra tempo of  a3  . Thus 6.Be2/Bd3 makes no sense. }
6... Bxc5
{ Of course, Black is more than happy to develop his bishop with a single tempo in the center. }
7. a3
{ After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/2pp4/2PP4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.a3  , sometimes Black plays  6...Be7  @@StartBracket@@not that we are playing it, and this is just for comparison@@EndBracket@@, and then after  7.dxc5  Bxc5  we get the same position with White to play. In fact, there are more than two hundred games in this position with White to play. }
7... O-O 8. b4 Bd6
{ The bishop is ideal on d6 to facilitate Ne5 ideas at some point. } 9. cxd5
{ After  9.Bb2  a5  10.b5  Ne5  Black gets a free play with a lead in development and has zero weakness. }
9... exd5
{ White is way behind development to take advantage of the isolated pawn. } 10.
Be2
{ Of course, the d5 pawn cannot be touched due to Bb4 at the end when White loses the queen. }
10... a5
{ Black wants to play Ne5, but before getting there he provokes White to make some weakness in the queenside. }
11. b5 Ne5
{ Black will develop the bishop on e6 or g4 and brings the rook to c8 to put pressure on the c-file. White would love to have the pawn back on b3 to cover the c4 square, but that is not feasible. Black gets ample counterplay here. }
