[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 12: Semi-Tarrasch (5.e3 Nc6 6.a3/dxc5)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 Nc6
{ This position often also occurs in the English opening from the following move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  c5  2.c4  Nf6  3.Nc3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e3  e6  . }
6. a3
{ White remains non-commital in the center but prepares dxc5-Bxc5-b4 ideas. }
6... dxc4
{ Before White can implement their original idea of taking on c5 and playing b4, Black does the same. }
7. Bxc4 a6
{ One can argue that when White played dxc5 and a3, we were happy, and now we are playing dxc4-a6 with one tempo down @@StartBracket@@White got an extra a3@@EndBracket@@, yet we are happy. So, where is the logic in all of that? The explanation is straightforward. As Black, we don't mind getting easy equality and consider this to be a good outcome from the opening, while from White's perspective, that's not ideal. }
8. O-O
{ The most natural move. Any other bishop with the c4 bishop would be answered with b5 when White will eventually castle, and we will transpose.  8.dxc5  Qxd1  followed by Bc5 gives Black a comfortable position to play. }
8... b5 { Of course! Why else did we play a6 in the previous move! } 9. Bd3
{ The only other sensible move. Black has an easy plan of Bb7-Be7-O-O, and White is yet to solve issues with the dark-squared bishop. }
9... Bb7
{ This was a tough choice to make. Black had two equally good options. We could also play against the isolated pawns by going  9...cxd4  10.exd4  Be7  , Black has no problem. The idea of playing Bb7 and not taking on d4 is to restrict the bishop on c1. }
10. a4
{ There were some games played in this direction. White tries to provoke Black to create some weaknesses on the queenside. }
10... b4 11. Ne4
{ It looks like White succeeded in creating weaknesses on the queenside and the king is also safer than Black's king. The next move that I propose gives a cold shower to White's strategy and also questions their entire logic. }
11... Qd7
{ A spectacular multipurpose move. It is prophylaxis against White's main threat of Nxc5 that we will see in the mainline. It may sound weird, but we have also made a provision of O-O-O in some cases :@@EndBracket@@ }
12. Nxc5
{ Hard to suggest something else. Playing  12.Nxf6  gxf6  would only help Black to create an attack on g2! Black can always castle long, and the king will be super safe on  b8  as the b-file is not easy to open. }
12... Bxc5 13. dxc5 O-O-O
{ Another brilliant move. Anticipating the queen trade and foreseeing an endgame, Black rightly keeps the king on the queenside where White will be vulnerable. }
14. Be2 { 14.Bc2  Qxd1  will lead to same position. } 14... Qxd1 15. Bxd1
{ After  15.Rxd1  Rxd1  16.Bxd1  Rd8  Black will get back the pawn on c5 by the f6 knight while White will struggle with their development. }
15... Ne4
{ The pawn on c5 is falling. White does have a pair of bishops, but both are not playing now. Black's king is ideally placed on the queenside and has nothing to complain about. }
