{ This was a tough choice to make. Black had two equally good options. We could also play against the isolated pawns by going  9...cxd4  10.exd4  Be7  , Black has no problem. The idea of playing Bb7 and not taking on d4 is to restrict the bishop on c1. }
10. dxc5 { With the idea to play b4, and get the c1 bishop out from b2. } 10...
Bxc5 11. b4 Bd6 { The bishop is ideally placed on d6 to facilitate Ne5 ideas. }
12. Bb2
{ White is now seriously threatening to play Ne4. Although we will get a symmetrical position after  13...O-O  , it gives White an edge after they go  14.Ne4  . }
12... Ne5 { Do not allow White to play Ne4 with the bishop on b2! } 13. Be2
{ Not willing to allow Black to get the bishop on e5, White played this move in the game Santos - Gelfand from 2021. }
13... Qb8
{ Increasing the pressure on the h2-pawn and insisting that White should take on e5. Black had no weaknesses in the position and had no issue in the game: 0-1 @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Santos Latasa, J @@StartBracket@@2608@@EndBracket@@-Gelfand,B @@StartBracket@@2675@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2021. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 12: Semi-Tarrasch (5.e3 Nc6 6.a3/dxc5)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.a3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 Nc6
{ This position often also occurs in the English opening from the following move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  c5  2.c4  Nf6  3.Nc3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e3  e6  . }
6. a3
{ White remains non-commital in the center but prepares dxc5-Bxc5-b4 ideas. }
6... dxc4
{ Before White can implement their original idea of taking on c5 and playing b4, Black does the same. }
7. Bxc4 a6
{ One can argue that when White played dxc5 and a3, we were happy, and now we are playing dxc4-a6 with one tempo down @@StartBracket@@White got an extra a3@@EndBracket@@, yet we are happy. So, where is the logic in all of that? The explanation is straightforward. As Black, we don't mind getting easy equality and consider this to be a good outcome from the opening, while from White's perspective, that's not ideal. }
8. O-O
{ The most natural move. Any other bishop with the c4 bishop would be answered with b5 when White will eventually castle, and we will transpose.  8.dxc5  Qxd1  followed by Bc5 gives Black a comfortable position to play. }
8... b5 { Of course! Why else did we play a6 in the previous move! } 9. Ba2
{ The most popular move. White is trying their best to open up the game with d5 while Black's king remains in the center. }
9... Bb7
{ It is important to get ready for the d5 break, which is the only way for White to open up the center while keeping the queens alive. Black will now castle after playing Be7. }
10. dxc5
{ Mixing up ideas. What is the point of keeping the bishop on a2 if White doesn't want to fight for d5? If the idea was to take on c5, then the bishop is better placed on e2/ d3, keeping an eye on Black's queenside pawns. Here the bishop is staring at the rock of e6, which can't be broken. }
10... Bxc5 11. b4 Bd6
{ Even in a bullet game, the world champion shows subtleties and chooses the best square. He rightly did the opposite of White. Keeping the bishop in an ideal square where it keeps its eye on both wings. }
12. Bb2 O-O
{ The position is almost symmetrical, but the Black bishop on d6 is much better than the bishop on a2. Black will play Qe7-Rfd8-a5 etc and White's light-squared bishop will have difficulties finding its ideal square. 1/2-1/2 Tang, A @@StartBracket@@2538@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen,M  @@StartBracket@@2862@@EndBracket@@ Lichess. org INT 2021. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 12: Semi-Tarrasch (5.e3 Nc6 6.a3/dxc5)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Sidelines: 5.e3 Nc6 6.a3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 Nc6
{ This position often also occurs in the English opening from the following move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  c5  2.c4  Nf6  3.Nc3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e3  e6  . }
6. a3
{ White remains non-commital in the center but prepares dxc5-Bxc5-b4 ideas. }
6... dxc4
{ Before White can implement their original idea of taking on c5 and playing b4, Black does the same. }
7. Bxc4 a6
{ One can argue that when White played dxc5 and a3, we were happy, and now we are playing dxc4-a6 with one tempo down @@StartBracket@@White got an extra a3@@EndBracket@@, yet we are happy. So, where is the logic in all of that? The explanation is straightforward. As Black, we don't mind getting easy equality and consider this to be a good outcome from the opening, while from White's perspective, that's not ideal. }
8. O-O
{ The most natural move. Any other bishop with the c4 bishop would be answered with b5 when White will eventually castle, and we will transpose.  8.dxc5  Qxd1  followed by Bc5 gives Black a comfortable position to play. }
8... b5 { Of course! Why else did we play a6 in the previous move! } 9. Ba2
{ The most popular move. White is trying their best to open up the game with d5 while Black's king remains in the center. }
9... Bb7
{ It is important to get ready for the d5 break, which is the only way for White to open up the center while keeping the queens alive. Black will now castle after playing Be7. }
10. d5
{ The most direct move to question Black's strategy. Levon played this thrice in rapid games as White, with a 100% score. It might look intimidating, but it has nothing to do with the outcome of the opening. }
10... exd5 11. Nxd5 Bd6
{ This is the safest way to play without memorizing a bunch of unusual moves. However, if Black is willing to go for a more complex line, we could also play  11...c4  when White's only try would be playing  12.e4  and Black would unleash the bold  12...Nxe4  13.Re1  Bc5!!  This sacrifices an entire piece but after  14.Rxe4  Ne7  , it turns out White has nothing better than giving the piece back, and Black gets a good position. }
12. e4 Nxd5 { Getting away from Bg5 ideas. } 13. Qxd5 O-O 14. Qh5
{ It looks scary at first sight, but in reality, Black is clearly better at this point. He just needs to stop White's immediate threats. }
14... Qc7
{ In the game Levon - Ding Black opted for  14...Qf6  and after  15.Bg5!  he got into some trouble with his queen. }
15. Bd5
{ 15.Ng5  h6  was leading nowhere, and Black was threatening to shut the bishop on a2 with c4. }
15... Nd4 { A nice move that exchanges all of White's active pieces. } 16. Nxd4
cxd4
{ Black has a nice central passed pawn, and all of White's attack disappeared. The engine gives a clear advantage to Black, but white should be able to hold. However, that is not our concern :@@EndBracket@@. }
