13. d5 Nxd5
{ Time to give back the piece, but to make sure the safety of our king remains intact. }
14. Rxd5 Qc7
{ The pawn on e6 makes sure that nothing goes wrong with the king on e8. Black is ready to play Be7-O-O next. }
15. Rd3
{ This move was played against me in Wijk aan Zee 2021 by Bjerre. White wants to take on c3 with the rook, and if Black takes on b2 he gets the bishop out from b2. }
15... Be7 { Black is ready to castle and naturally gets a fine position. } 16.
Rxc3 O-O
{ Black has zero weaknesses, and nothing to complain about from the opening. The only thing that needs checking is if White gets a kingside attack right away. }
17. Ng5
{ Not the best move, but definitely the most critical one. White creates a direct attack on the kingside. Any other move would give Black an easy choice with Bf6 and then we develop the rest of our pieces harmoniously. }
17... Bf6
{ In the game I opted for  17...h6  which is a mistake, and this simple move would have given an advantage to Black instantly. }
18. Rh3 { There is no other way for White to justify their previous move. }
18... Qe5
{ Being indulged in a long calculation with 17...h6, I totally overlooked this simple resource of exchanging the queens and getting a better position. White is now forced to trade queens due to the back rank issues. }
19. Qxe5 Bxe5 { Getting away from Nh7 fork. } 20. Nxh7 Rfd8
{ White's knight is totally misplaced on h7, and is in a difficult situation because of the back rank issues. The pawn on b2 remains a target while White's queenside pieces are still underdeveloped. }
