12. exd4
{ Sacrificing a piece temporarily.  12.Nxd4  bxc3  13.Nxc6  Qc7  forces White to go back with  14.Nd4  when Black gains another tempo by attacking the h2 pawn with  14...Bd6  and takes the lead in development as the bishop on c1 remains jobless. }
12... bxc3
{ Not fearing any ghosts! Black accepts the challenge of the piece sacrifice. }
13. d5 Nxd5
{ Time to give back the piece, but to make sure the safety of our king remains intact. }
14. Bxd5 Nd4
{ An important resource that kills White's attack completely. Black eliminates White's bishop on d5. }
15. Rxd4 Bxd5
{ Without the light-squared bishop, White has no hope to create any attack, and they should now be careful not to get worse. }
16. bxc3 Bc5
{ Developing on the 17th move. Yet, Black did not face any problem, thanks to our tactical and dynamic play. }
17. Rg4 Qf6
{ Black has a pair of bishops, and is ready to castle next, while  18.Bg5  can be answered with  18...Bxf3  . In the 2021 correspondence game, players agreed to a draw soon. This position was also reached in the game ½-½ Gelfand, B @@StartBracket@@2703@@EndBracket@@ - Leko, P @@StartBracket@@2690@@EndBracket@@ Batumi 2018. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Deep-Dive: The Semi-Tarrasch Endgames "]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline: Overview Part 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4
{ The main move in the Semi-Tarrasch. White grabs the center with a tempo. }
6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+
{ Schlechter started playing in this manner back in the early 20th century. One of the classic games is Rubinstein - Schlechter from San Sebastian 1912. }
9. Bd2 Bxd2+
{ After showing a fantastic game from the White side against Schlechter in 1912, where Black played  9...Qa5  , Rubinstein himself opted for this line as Black in 1924, where he opted for the correct  9...Bxd2  . }
10. Qxd2 O-O
{ This is the starting position of the Main Semi Tarrasch. It gets frustrating to see so many options in the opening @@StartBracket@@especially for our opponents@@EndBracket@@ when we don't understand the reasoning behind the moves, and there is no clarity.   The biggest trouble most players face is memorizing a bunch of moves without understanding a thing about WHY the moves are being played.  White has a strong center while Black has a majority on the queenside. Black usually develops the bishop from b7 and attacks White's pawn on e4. Any kind of piece exchange is generally fine for Black. This is one of our aims, trading pieces if possible.   Apart from the queenside majority, another strength in Black's position is that they have zero weaknesses in the position. White lacks targets. In the current position, White has various rook moves apart from many bishop moves and h4. Before we proceed any further, let us pause and understand the structure, pros and cons, and possible endgames. Let us now take a break and see which endgames favor us. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Deep-Dive: The Semi-Tarrasch Endgames "]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline: King Pawn Endgame"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6k1/p4ppp/1p2p3/8/3PP3/8/P4PPP/6K1 w - - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Hypothetically, if all of the pieces are traded, and we get to a king and pawn ending, intuitively, it feels Black should be winning due to their outside passed pawns, but White's king reaches the center quickly, and soon we reach a deadlock position. I purposefully kept the pawn on b6 since Black will play this move in most cases. }
10. Kf1 Kf8 11. Ke2 Ke7 12. Kd3 b5 13. Kc3 a5
{ White cannot break on the queenside, and Black cannot break in the center. A ceasefire situation occurs now. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Deep-Dive: The Semi-Tarrasch Endgames "]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline: Queen Pawn Endgame"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3q2k1/p4ppp/1p2p3/8/3PP3/8/P2Q1PPP/6K1 w - - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14. d5
{ In a queen pawn endgame, White can create a passed pawn much faster than Black. Shouldn't that give them a clear edge? Absolutely not! The reasoning is simple, White's passed pawn is near to Black's king, and it's a piece of cake to deal with. On the other hand, Black's potential passed pawn will be miles away from White's king. }
14... exd5 15. exd5 Qd6
{ The game is likely to end in a draw, but I would rather be on the Black side of this endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Deep-Dive: The Semi-Tarrasch Endgames "]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline: Rook Pawn Endgame"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/p4ppp/1p2p3/8/3PP3/8/P4PPP/R4RK1 w - - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The percentage of getting a rook and pawn endgame is the highest compared to any other endgame.   Just like the queen pawn endgame, here the logic remains the same. It is much easier to deal with a central passed pawn that is closer to the king, compared to the outside passed pawn that is far from the king. }
10. Rac1 Rfd8 11. Rfd1
{ This move is to show how easily White can get into danger. It was important to play  11.Rc4  and after  11...b5  12.Rb4  a5  13.Rxb5  Rxd4  , the position fizzles out completely to a draw. }
11... Rac8
{ White now has issues with guarding the d4 pawn and the c-file, and they have to part with something now. The central passed pawn will again not be dangerous as it is close to Black's king. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
