[White "Deep-Dive: The Semi-Tarrasch Endgames "]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline: Major Piece Endgame"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/p4ppp/1p2p3/8/3PP3/8/P2Q1PPP/R4RK1 w - - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Let's imagine if the minor pieces are exchanged. Nothing changes compared to the previous endgames we saw, and Black gets a comfortable position with almost any sensible move. }
10. Rfd1 Qd6
{ For e5, Black is ready with Qd5, and if White plays d5, then the queen is nicely placed on d6 to block the pawn, and Black can start with Rad8. }
11. Rac1 Rac8 { As usual, we are happy to trade. } 12. h3 h6
{ Slowly but surely, Black will now start expanding on the queenside. White will have to keep watching the central pawns and stop the queenside march. Once again, I would pick Black here despite the computer evaluation of 0.00 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Deep-Dive: The Semi-Tarrasch Endgames "]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline: Minor Piece Endgame"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1n4k1/pb3ppp/1p2p3/8/3PP3/3B1N2/P4PPP/6K1 w - - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

10. Kf1
{ The general advice is, 'if you have more space, then trade major pieces so that your king can march forward and you can expand with your pawns.' It would be true if, in return, Black did not have the outside pawn majority. White's pawns are not marching forward now. }
10... Kf8 11. Ke2 Ke7 12. Ke3
{ Bringing the king in the center seems reasonable. } 12... Ba6
{ Keep trading :@@EndBracket@@ } 13. Ne5 Bxd3 14. Kxd3 b5 15. Kc3 a5
{ The knight on e5 will be kicked out, and then it will be Black's turn to bring the king and gain more space. The evaluation remains 0.00 as both sides are unable to make significant progress. }
