{ It is unfair to analyze this position which is highly unlikely to come. White exchanged the bishop in a perfect scenario, Black has committed b6, the knight is on b8, and it is White to play where they can play Ne5 and restrict the knight on b8. Too many good things happened, yet White doesn't have any hint of advantage. }
10. Ne5
{ For example, if it was Black to play, they would have played Nd7, and the knight would have never landed on e5. }
10... Qe8
{ Immediate Nd7 would have allowed Nc6, so Black prepares it by getting away from the Nc6 tempo. }
11. Rc1 Nd7 { Happy to trade :@@EndBracket@@ } 12. Nc6 Nc5
{ The point of Qe8 gets clear here. } 13. d5 f5
{ Blowing up the center and getting a comfortable position. } 14. e5 Qd7
{ Thanks to the knight on c6, White won't be able to play d6. The position remains equal. This line became a bit specific because we gave too many good deals to White. It still underlines how beneficial it is for Black to trade pieces. }
