11. Bb5
{ Provoking a6 Rubinstein style. Although Rubinstein never had this particular position as White,  this idea of provoking a6 was made popular by him from a similar but different position in this line. In 1912 the game between Rubinstein - Schlechter saw @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3ppp/4p3/8/1b1PP3/5N2/P2B1PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qa5  10.Rb1  Bxd2  11.Qxd2  Qxd2  12.Kxd2  O-O  13.Bb5  . In case you have not seen this game, this is the moment to pause and check that game. It is a classic and will help improve general understanding of the game and realize what we should not allow in this opening as Black. }
11... a6 12. Be2
{ 12.Bd3  Nc6  will be a typical idea against the bishop on d3. } 12... b5
{ That's the way Black takes care of the b6 square and targets the pawn on e4. }
