11. Rc1
{ White is waiting for Black to reveal their plan on which central pawn they want to attack. Based on that, White will develop their bishop. }
11... b6 { Without the bishop on d3, Black refrains from play Nc6. } 12. Bd3
{ The point! Black is missing Nc6 now. } 12... Bb7 13. O-O Nd7
{ White avoided Nc6 ideas with Rc1-Bd3, but in return, he committed Rc1. Why is c1 not a perfect place for the rook? If you have paid attention to the first part of this introduction and gone through the endgame positions, then you already know the answer! White would ideally like to avoid any piece trade, but in return, they committed with Rc1 :@@EndBracket@@   You will get a clearer picture in the main file that will give a clear conception of how to play these positions. }
