1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O
{ Welcome back again to Part 2 of the Semi-Tarrasch Introduction. I hope by now, you got clarity that typically, any endgames are fine for Black. White usually refrains from trading pieces and tries to maintain the strong center and create play in the center and kingside. White has different ways to develop the bishop here. }
11. Bc4
{ The main move in the position. White develops the bishop actively and aims to play d5 in the future. }
11... Nd7
{ An important move order detail. Black should always watch out for the d5 breaks. A careless  11...b6  would have allowed the thematic  12.d5  , and White would take over. }
12. O-O b6 13. Rad1
{ 13.d5  was played a few times, but after  13...Nc5  , White must protect the e4 pawn, and Black gets a nice blockade on d6 after the exchange on  d5  . The move  13.d5  is used more in shorter time control, hoping to catch Black with some move order tricks. We will make sure no such things happen :@@EndBracket@@ }
13... Bb7 14. Rfe1
{ We could also get this position from @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p2n1ppp/1p2p3/8/2BPP3/5N2/P2Q1PPP/R4RK1 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Rfe1  Bb7  14.Rad1  move order. }
14... Rc8 15. Bb3
{ Finally, White got the ideal setup for the thematic d5 break.  White has some typical ideas like:  1@@EndBracket@@ d5-exd5-e5 pawn sacrifice to get the knight to d4 and create a kingside attack.   2@@EndBracket@@ To get h4-h5, Black will never allow h6 to happen, so once White plays h5, Black stops it with h6. White can try further with g4-g5.   3@@EndBracket@@ To keep waiting with Qe3 or Re3-Qe1 etc., and keep the central/kingside plans flexible.   The first and foremost rule from the Black side is not to play for a draw :@@EndBracket@@ We are not worse, neither are we defending.   The position is dynamically balanced, and Black needs to stay active while waiting for the chance to pounce.   First of all, let me remind you once again that any piece exchanges are usually fine for Black. Especially the queens. So, moves like Qf4 are often answered with Qf6/Qc7. }
15... h6
{ A very subtle move by Black. We want to play Nf6, but for now, this move wasn't available due to d5. However, with the inclusion of h6-h3, we can enter the same line. Confusing? Let's have a look at that. }
16. d5 { We should always look out for this thematic idea. } 16... exd5 17.
exd5
{ After  17.e5  Re8  White is not getting Nd4 easily as Black will keep on putting pressure on the e5 pawn. }
17... Qf6
{ White's pawn is not moving further due to the attack on f3. This makes the bishop on b3 bad. With Nc5-Rfd8 coming next, Black gets a fine position. }
