[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 13: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Rc1/Rd1/Rb1)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline  11.Rd1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O
{ We will see various rook moves in this file. In the introduction, the reasoning behind the rook moves is already explained. White waits for Black to commit with the b6/Nc6 plan before deciding on where to develop the light-squared bishop. }
11. Rd1
{ Anish played this move twice in Chessable Masters Rapid 2020 against Nepo. White waits for Black to make a move and then decides what to do with the f1 bishop. Since the rook comes to d1 in the mainline anyway, it makes sense to put it there right away. }
11... Bd7
{ Immediately exploiting the placement of White's rook. Black intends to attack it with Ba4 next. This move is almost unheard of. There is only one game played by a 2300+ player.   Black usually opts for  11...b6  when White goes  12.Bd3  and claims that they are ready for  12...Nc6  13.Qe3  Nb4  with  14.Bb1  .   Black could play  11...b6  12.Bd3  Ba6  or  11...b6  12.Bd3  Nd7  and according to engines, those are also doable, but I like this fresh idea a lot more as it forces White to take some decisions immediately. }
12. Bd3
{ The move Bd3 weakens the pawn on d4, and Black should attack it with Nc6. Currently, Currently, our bishop is blocking our queen from putting pressure on the d4 pawn, so the next move becomes obvious. }
12... Ba4
{ Getting a tempo and clearing the queen's path to attack d4 with Nc6 next. }
13. Rb1 Nc6
{ It is now difficult to defend the pawn on  d4  . For example, the usual way of protecting the pawn would be Qe3, but here  14.Qe3  runs into  14...Qa5+  when White will have to make some compromises. }
14. d5
{ Opening up the game with their own king in the center is not exactly what one wishes for. }
14... exd5 15. exd5 Re8+
{ Of course, Black would not leave such a chance of developing the rook with a check and tempo. }
16. Be2 Ne7 { Now going for the d5 pawn. } 17. Rb4
{ 17.d6  Nf5  loses the pawn. } 17... b5 18. Rd4
{ White should have bailed out with  18.O-O  Qxd5  , and after exchanging on d5, they could take on b5, and eventually, the game would fizzle out to an equal endgame. }
18... Nf5
{ The only game where Black played 11...Bd7 went with  18...Rc8  , but after the text move, Black gets a better position. White's pawn on d5 will be nicely blocked with the knight on d6. }
