1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O
{ We will see various rook moves in this file. In the introduction, the reasoning behind the rook moves is already explained. White waits for Black to commit with the b6/Nc6 plan before deciding on where to develop the light-squared bishop. }
11. Rd1
{ Anish played this move twice in Chessable Masters Rapid 2020 against Nepo. White waits for Black to make a move and then decides what to do with the f1 bishop. Since the rook comes to d1 in the mainline anyway, it makes sense to put it there right away. }
11... Bd7
{ Immediately exploiting the placement of White's rook. Black intends to attack it with Ba4 next. This move is almost unheard of. There is only one game played by a 2300+ player.   Black usually opts for  11...b6  when White goes  12.Bd3  and claims that they are ready for  12...Nc6  13.Qe3  Nb4  with  14.Bb1  .   Black could play  11...b6  12.Bd3  Ba6  or  11...b6  12.Bd3  Nd7  and according to engines, those are also doable, but I like this fresh idea a lot more as it forces White to take some decisions immediately. }
12. Bc4
{ The bishop on c4 usually helps White to play d5. However, an important detail here is White's king is still in the center. }
12... Bc6 13. d5
{ 13.Qe3  Qa5  14.Rd2  Nd7  gives Black a fine position when Black can continue with the standard Rac8-Rfd8 and keep Nb6 ideas in the air. }
13... exd5 14. O-O
{ This is White's big idea. Now they will be better if they get another move and take on d5. Black now plays an important move that disturbs White's balance. }
14... Ba4 { Forcing White to play Bb3 otherwise, they lose material. } 15. Bb3
Bxb3 { Black is usually happy to trade. } 16. axb3 Qd6
{ The queen is nicely placed on d6, anticipating exd5. } 17. Qxd5
{ After  17.exd5  Nd7  White will not get to move the Black queen easily, since  18.Nd4  fails to  18...Qxd5  , and after  18.Nh4  g6  , the d5 pawn remains nicely blocked while Black looks forward to a nice endgame. }
17... Qxd5 18. exd5
{ Does the pawn look scary on d5? Think about any piece trade that could benefit White with the pawn on d5 :@@EndBracket@@ That pawn could also come into great danger since it is so close to Black's king. }
18... Nd7 19. d6 Rfd8
{ The engine gives 0.00, but in a practical game, all three results are possible. I would prefer to be Black here as I don't see anything immediate happening with the pawn on d6, and in the long run, it could be a potential target for Black's king. }
