1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O
{ We will see various rook moves in this file. In the introduction, the reasoning behind the rook moves is already explained. White waits for Black to commit with the b6/Nc6 plan before deciding on where to develop the light-squared bishop. }
11. Rd1
{ Anish played this move twice in Chessable Masters Rapid 2020 against Nepo. White waits for Black to make a move and then decides what to do with the f1 bishop. Since the rook comes to d1 in the mainline anyway, it makes sense to put it there right away. }
11... Bd7
{ Immediately exploiting the placement of White's rook. Black intends to attack it with Ba4 next. This move is almost unheard of. There is only one game played by a 2300+ player.   Black usually opts for  11...b6  when White goes  12.Bd3  and claims that they are ready for  12...Nc6  13.Qe3  Nb4  with  14.Bb1  .   Black could play  11...b6  12.Bd3  Ba6  or  11...b6  12.Bd3  Nd7  and according to engines, those are also doable, but I like this fresh idea a lot more as it forces White to take some decisions immediately. }
12. Be2
{ Keeping the bishop hidden so that it cannot be attacked easily. White is also ready to meet  12...Bc6  with  13.d5  . The computer's top choice is to play  12.Rb1  and after  12...Bc6  13.Bd3  we transpose to the mainline starting from  12. Be2 . }
12... Ba4
{ Removing the rook from the center before going for the central pawns. } 13.
Rb1 Bc6 14. Bd3
{ We could also reach the same position from @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp1b1ppp/4p3/8/3PP3/5N2/P2Q1PPP/3RKB1R w K - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Rb1  Bc6  13.Bd3  move order. }
14... Nd7
{ It was also possible to play the very dynamic  14...f5  . The engine gives the line with  15.d5  exd5  16.exf5  Re8  17.Be2  Qf6  when Black gets a pawn, and White plays for compensation. I like the text move more because of its simplicity. In no other variation in this system, we are playing  f5  , so practically, it makes life easier not to add such a move that works only in one particular position. Especially when simple moves suffice. }
15. O-O
{ White is ready to meet Nf6 with Rfe1 now. They also threaten the cunning d5. }
15... h6
{ Getting away from any d5 ideas. White will not have Bxh7 ideas at the end. }
16. Rfc1
{ With a rook already on b1, it makes sense to get the other rook on c1, but there is no weakness in Black's position. One of the main strengths of this entire system. }
16... Rc8
{ Keeping it simple. White did not manage to get any break in the center, and Black continues to develop harmoniously. }
17. Qe3 Qe7
{ White runs out of concrete plans now as there are again no potential targets. Let us see a sample variation. }
18. h3 Rfd8 { Keeping knight jump options open and developing the last piece. }
19. a4 { With the rooks on the queenside, White tries to gain space there. }
19... Nf6 { Protecting the pawn on b7 and attacking a4. } 20. a5 Be8
{ Looking forward to trading some pieces and opening up options like Qa3. White can try to advance on the kingside, but our king remains safe on f8 while we create a counter on the queenside. The engines say the position is equal, which seems fair enough although all three results are possible as the position is dynamic. }
