1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O
{ We will see various rook moves in this file. In the introduction, the reasoning behind the rook moves is already explained. White waits for Black to commit with the b6/Nc6 plan before deciding on where to develop the light-squared bishop. }
11. Rc1
{ Waiting for Black to play b6 and then aiming to play Bd3 when Black won't have Nc6 ideas. }
11... b6
{ I have also tried  11...Nc6  , but I like this move more which goes as per our strategy of attacking the pawn on e4. }
12. Bb5
{ This move is rarely played, although, there is some logic behind it. After Bb5 usually Black has the idea of playing a6 followed by b5, so here White is arguing that Black has already committed to b6. }
12... Bb7 13. Qe3 Nd7
{ It is surprising to see that this natural move was never played before. } 14.
O-O Rc8
{ The disadvantage of having rook on the c-file. Black is happy to trade :@@EndBracket@@ }
15. Rxc8
{ It makes no sense to avoid the trade now. If White wanted to play Rd1, then they should have played it in some different move order without wasting a tempo. By playing Rxc8, White tries to gain a tempo by bringing the other rook to c1 as Black can't take on c8 with the rook. }
15... Qxc8 16. Rc1 Qd8
{ Cold-blooded. Black knows White has no targets, and the more pieces they exchange, the more beneficial for Black. The c7 square remains under control, and Black threatens Nf6 next. Computer evaluation of 0.00 with the top choices being h3/h4/Bf1/a4 shows that White has no way to give pressure. }
17. e5
{ Although not the top choice of the machine, I felt that this is more human. To play e5 when Black is miles away from getting the knight to d5. }
17... Nb8
{ Black aims to get Na6-Nc7/Nb4 and Nd5. Ideas like a6-b5 or Qd5-Rc8 are also possible. Black has a fine position. }
