{ Waiting for Black to play b6 and then aiming to play Bd3 when Black won't have Nc6 ideas. }
11... b6
{ I have also tried  11...Nc6  , but I like this move more which goes as per our strategy of attacking the pawn on e4. }
12. Bd3
{ This is the whole point of starting with 11.Rc1. Black is missing Nc6 ideas. }
12... Bb7
{ Black admits that they can't play Nc6 and opts for the Bb7 plan. Black's argument is the combination of Bd3-Rc1 doesn't go together. The rook on c1 is never ideally placed as Black is generally happy to trade rooks. The bishop on d3 hinders the thematic d5 breaks. It sometimes helps White play on the queenside with a4-a5, but then the rook is needed on a1. }
13. O-O { White continues in the same path. } 13... Nd7
{ White has multiple options at this point. They can try to play on the kingside with h4 ideas, they can try on the queenside with a4 ideas, they could start kingside/center plans with Qe3/Qf4, or could develop the rook in the center first.   In any case, Black is not the slightest worried at this point. The main two moves in this position are  14.Qe3  and  14.Qf4  . }
14. e5
{ This positionally ugly-looking move was played twice at the GM level. White directly invites Black to shatter the pawn structure, which Black should not refuse obviously. }
14... Bxf3
{ Otherwise, White restricts the knight on d7 without giving any concessions. }
15. gxf3 b5
{ In both games that reached this position, continued with  15...Qh4  . I like this move much more. Black gains space on the queenside and also makes a path for the knight to d5 via b6. }
16. Kh1
{ White could not play  16.Bxb5  due to the pin on the d-file, Black can take  16...Nxe5  . }
16... Rc8 { Keep trading. A key motto of this line :@@EndBracket@@ } 17. Rxc8
{ After  17.Rg1  Rxc1  White won't be able to maintain the rook on the g-file with  18.Qxc1  as the d3 bishop hangs after  18...Nxe5  . }
17... Qxc8 18. Bxb5
{ White got a horrible pawn structure, but now in return, they got a pawn. }
18... Qb7 { Double attack on f3 and b5. } 19. Qd3
{ 19.Bxd7  Qxf3  was an immediate perpetual. } 19... Nb6
{ White has too many weaknesses to guard. Interestingly, even if we take the queens off the board, Black still has ample compensation with Rd8-Nd5-Nf4-g5 ideas. Engines give 0.00, but any day I would take Black here, who is very active and got more than enough compensation for a pawn. }
