18... Rxb8 19. Rc7
{ Since any endgame is fine for Black @@StartBracket@@Remember the introduction files?@@EndBracket@@ White must try to do something immediately. }
19... Nf6
{ Now we see the point of starting with h6. Ng5 ideas are not available anymore. }
20. Ne5 Bxe4 { Black keep exchanging pieces. } 21. Bxe4 Nxe4
{ Five GM-level games reached this position, and Black didn't have any issues in any of them. It is not surprising since almost any endgames are fine for Black due to their majority in the queenside. }
22. Rxf7
{ After  22.Rxa7  Rd8  23.f3  Nc3  , the position fizzled out totally, and the game Bu-Leko 2019 ended in a draw soon. }
22... a5
{ White's rook and knight look nice, but there is no mating net, and meanwhile Black starts pushing the assets on the queenside. }
23. Rc7 b5 24. f3 Nf6
{ Two games reached this position, and in both Wojtaszek - Sarana and Gelfand - Kramnik,  Black opted for  24...Nd6  , but the text move is much stronger as Black aims for Nd5 ideas. }
25. Ra7 a4
{ With Nd5 coming next, Black creates ample counterplay on the queenside. White's active rook and a strong knight on e5 compensates for that, so the position remains dynamically balanced in human eyes and 0.00 in the silicon world. }
