[White "Chapter 13: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Rc1/Rd1/Rb1)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline  11.Rc1 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O
{ We will see various rook moves in this file. In the introduction, the reasoning behind the rook moves is already explained. White waits for Black to commit with the b6/Nc6 plan before deciding on where to develop the light-squared bishop. }
11. Rc1
{ Waiting for Black to play b6 and then aiming to play Bd3 when Black won't have Nc6 ideas. }
11... b6
{ I have also tried  11...Nc6  , but I like this move more which goes as per our strategy of attacking the pawn on e4. }
12. Bd3
{ This is the whole point of starting with 11.Rc1. Black is missing Nc6 ideas. }
12... Bb7
{ Black admits that they can't play Nc6 and opts for the Bb7 plan. Black's argument is the combination of Bd3-Rc1 doesn't go together. The rook on c1 is never ideally placed as Black is generally happy to trade rooks. The bishop on d3 hinders the thematic d5 breaks. It sometimes helps White play on the queenside with a4-a5, but then the rook is needed on a1. }
13. O-O { White continues in the same path. } 13... Nd7
{ White has multiple options at this point. They can try to play on the kingside with h4 ideas, they can try on the queenside with a4 ideas, they could start kingside/center plans with Qe3/Qf4, or could develop the rook in the center first.   In any case, Black is not the slightest worried at this point. The main two moves in this position are  14.Qe3  and  14.Qf4  . }
14. Qe3
{ By protecting f3, White is giving a serious positional threat of e5 now. }
14... Nf6
{ Stopping e5. There are two reasons why we go Nf6 for Qe3 and not h6 like in the Qf4 variation.  1@@EndBracket@@ After the thematic  15.d5  exd5  16.e5  Black gets to open up the b7 bishop with a return pawn sacrifice of  16...d4  that works only with the queen on e3.   2@@EndBracket@@ Trying to play like in the Qf4 variation is problematic here and that is visible after  14...h6  15.e5  Rc8  16.Nd2  , Black's break with f6 is weak as the queen is safe on e3 since the rook does not attack it from f8. }
15. Ne5
{ Makes a lot of sense for White, now that Black moved the knight from d7. Playing  15.e5  would be a strategical error as Black gets the knight to d5 instantly with  15...Nd5  .  Doubling on the c-file with  15.Rc2  /Rc3 helps Black as they are happy to trade pieces and will continue to play  15...Rc8  .   The same goes for the waiting move like  15.h3  when Black continues their strategic idea of exchanging pieces with  15...Rc8  . }
15... Qe7 { Getting ready for Rac8-Rfd8. } 16. f3
{ A nice strategical move. By keeping the f3-e4 pawn structure, White restricts Black's minor pieces.  16.Rc3  was played by Sam against Leko in Bundesliga 2019, but as always, doubling on the c-file helps Black to exchange a few more pieces. Black has no problem after  16...Rac8  and trading a few more pieces.  16.Rfd1  Rac8  17.f3  Rfd8  18.Bb5  transposes to the mainline starting with 16.f3. }
16... Rfd8
{ Black could also start with Rac8, and we will reach a similar position. } 17.
Bb5
{ After  17.Rc2  Rac8  18.Rfc1  h6  Black had no issue in the game Hammer - Vallejo,  Sharjah 2017. Black once again had zero weakness, and at the right time, they will transfer the knight to d6 like in the mainline that we will see now. }
17... Rac8
{ Aronian-Kramnik had this position twice, and in both games, Black had no problems holding. Also, in 2020 Correspondence chess, this position occurred, and Black had no issues. It is natural since White could not make any significant progress on the center or kingside while Black managed to finish the development peacefully. White has restricted Black's minor pieces by forming the f3-e4 pawn structure so, it is important to know the Ne8-Nd6 idea that takes care of everything. }
18. a4
{ In 2016, Levon played  18.Bc6  , and after  18...Ne8!  he admitted his mistake and went back  19.Ba4  and Black had no problem after  18...Nd6  . The move 18.a4 was his improvement from the previous game. }
18... Ne8
{ In the game Levon - Kramnik from 2017, Black started with  18...h6  , and after  19.h3  opted for Ne8-Nd6 plan. There is nothing wrong with that, but why not play it directly! }
19. Nc6
{ Let's see what happens if White tries to take Black's bishop. Against any other move, Black would have played Nd6. }
19... Bxc6 20. Bxc6 Rc7
{ White either gets into an annoying pin, or they must allow further trades. Black's knight will be nicely placed on d6, and we get a pleasant endgame with no weaknesses. The engine evaluates the position as 0.00, which seems fair enough. }
