[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 14: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Be2/Bd3/Bb5)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline 11.Be2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Be2
{ White is reluctant to put the bishop on b5 or c4 where it can be attacked easily; not willing to put it on d3 either which might give Black a tempo with Nc6. Hence the modest Be2. }
11... b6 { It makes sense to target the e4 pawn ASAP. } 12. O-O Bb7
{ Now, Qf4 and Qe3 are the only sensible moves. The disadvantage of keeping the bishop on e2 is visible here. White is missing Rfe1 to protect the pawn on e4. }
13. Qf4 Nc6
{ This is more practical from a preparation point of view. This way, there is no room for confusion. We go Nc6 irrespective of White's 13.Qf4/Qe3. With the queen on f4, the move 13...Nd7 also works fine since in many lines, when White goes e5, Black gets a timely f6, creating counterplay in the center, and the queen on f4 becomes a target. A good question is, why bother about these details when we can play similar moves irrespective of Qe3/ Qf4? :@@EndBracket@@ }
14. Rfd1
{ Nothing changes with  14.Rad1  as Black continues with a similar plan and goes for  14...Rc8  like we will be doing against 14.Rfd1. }
14... Rc8
{ Black finished the development while White has not created any threats in the center or the kingside. Black is happy to trade queens or any pieces, for that matter. So, moves like Qf6 come to mind next. }
15. Rac1
{ 15.d5  exd5  16.exd5  might look scary at first sight. It is indeed scary and gets into a clearly worse position, but only for White :@@EndBracket@@ Black goes  16...Ne7  17.d6  Nd5  and White eventually loses material. }
15... Ne7
{ There was nothing wrong with  15...Qf6  either. It is now time to trade and get a comfortable endgame either way. }
