[White "Chapter 14: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Be2/Bd3/Bb5)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline 11.Be2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Be2
{ White is reluctant to put the bishop on b5 or c4 where it can be attacked easily; not willing to put it on d3 either which might give Black a tempo with Nc6. Hence the modest Be2. }
11... b6 { It makes sense to target the e4 pawn ASAP. } 12. O-O Bb7
{ Now, Qf4 and Qe3 are the only sensible moves. The disadvantage of keeping the bishop on e2 is visible here. White is missing Rfe1 to protect the pawn on e4. }
13. Qe3
{ Queen is better placed here. White is now ready for e5 after Nd7. White needs to wait until Black plays Nd7 and only then play e5.     The point is, from d7 it won't be easy for Black to get to d5 as playing b5-Nb6 won't be easy. On the other hand, if White plays @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p4ppp/1p2p3/8/3PP3/5N2/P2QBPPP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.e5  it would be a huge positional mistake, when can then Black play  12...Nc6  with the idea of Ne7, taking full control of the d5 square. The engine gives a clear advantage to Black. }
13... Nc6 { 13...Nd7  14.e5  was the point of White's play. } 14. Rad1
{ This move is usually connected with d5 ideas. The question is then, why does White keep the bishop on e2 if they intend to fight for d5? }
14... Rc8
{ Making natural moves and waiting for White to show their idea. Black completely consolidated the position before White could start any attack. }
15. d5 { This move must be checked in every possible manner. } 15... exd5 16.
exd5
{ The thematic e5 ideas work only with the knight on d7 when White can play Nd4. Here, with the knight on  c6  , the pawn sacrifice makes no sense.  16.Rxd5  Qe7  leads nowhere, and White will have to deal with Nb4 threats. }
16... Nb4 17. d6
{ Was seen in the game 1-0 Banusz, T @@StartBracket@@2514@@EndBracket@@-Juhasz, K @@StartBracket@@2232@@EndBracket@@ Harkany 2009, and here instead of getting a -3 position, Black made one reckless move and got into a +3 position. From White's perspective, it would have been wiser to play  17.Qb3  a5  18.d6  Rc5  when he will eventually lose the  d6  pawn, but the game is not lost yet. }
17... Nd5
{ The most natural move. Blocking the d-file, attacking the queen, attacking the d6 pawn, and threatening Nc3 as well. How many more reasons do we need to play this move? In the game, shockingly Black, played the reckless  17...Nxa2  and was immediately lost once White played  18.d7  . }
18. Qa3
{ Only way to keep the pawn alive since  18.Qe5  was losing to  18...Re8  . }
18... Nc3 { The knight starts showing its strength. } 19. Rd2 Rc5
{ White has no way to save the pawn, and the position becomes dead lost. } *

