1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Be2
{ White is reluctant to put the bishop on b5 or c4 where it can be attacked easily; not willing to put it on d3 either which might give Black a tempo with Nc6. Hence the modest Be2. }
11... b6 { It makes sense to target the e4 pawn ASAP. } 12. O-O Bb7
{ Now, Qf4 and Qe3 are the only sensible moves. The disadvantage of keeping the bishop on e2 is visible here. White is missing Rfe1 to protect the pawn on e4. }
13. Qe3
{ Queen is better placed here. White is now ready for e5 after Nd7. White needs to wait until Black plays Nd7 and only then play e5.     The point is, from d7 it won't be easy for Black to get to d5 as playing b5-Nb6 won't be easy. On the other hand, if White plays @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p4ppp/1p2p3/8/3PP3/5N2/P2QBPPP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.e5  it would be a huge positional mistake, when can then Black play  12...Nc6  with the idea of Ne7, taking full control of the d5 square. The engine gives a clear advantage to Black. }
13... Nc6 { 13...Nd7  14.e5  was the point of White's play. } 14. Rac1
{ Played by Duda in a rapid game against Wei Yi in 2018. In general Black should be happy to see White's rook on c1, which facilitates Black's strategy of exchanging pieces. }
14... Rc8
{ With pleasure! Black is looking forward to make business with the c1 rook. }
15. h4
{ 15.Rfd1  is a very sensible move, and it transposes to a line that is covered from 14.Rfd1 move order. }
15... Qd6
{ It was also possible to start the trading immediately with moves like Ne7, but waiting is also a good idea. Let White expand further. }
16. h5 h6
{ Never allow h6. I am sure you have seen this statement quite numerous times by now. I want this to get imprinted in your mind :P }
17. Rfd1
{ White runs out of ideas now. There is no attack, and Black can start trading anytime we want to. }
17... Rfd8
{ Wei Yi keeps waiting. According to engines  18...Nb4  was good enough, but I also like the text move where Black is totally ready for any kind of d5 breaks and finished the development comfortably. It remains our choice when we would like to start trading. With zero weaknesses in the position, Black has nothing to worry about. 1/2-1/2 Duda, J @@StartBracket@@2724@@EndBracket@@-Wei, Y @@StartBracket@@2734@@EndBracket@@ Liaocheng 2018. }
