{ White is reluctant to put the bishop on b5 or c4 where it can be attacked easily; not willing to put it on d3 either which might give Black a tempo with Nc6. Hence the modest Be2. }
11... b6 { It makes sense to target the e4 pawn ASAP. } 12. O-O Bb7
{ Now, Qf4 and Qe3 are the only sensible moves. The disadvantage of keeping the bishop on e2 is visible here. White is missing Rfe1 to protect the pawn on e4. }
13. Qe3
{ Queen is better placed here. White is now ready for e5 after Nd7. White needs to wait until Black plays Nd7 and only then play e5.     The point is, from d7 it won't be easy for Black to get to d5 as playing b5-Nb6 won't be easy. On the other hand, if White plays @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p4ppp/1p2p3/8/3PP3/5N2/P2QBPPP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.e5  it would be a huge positional mistake, when can then Black play  12...Nc6  with the idea of Ne7, taking full control of the d5 square. The engine gives a clear advantage to Black. }
13... Nc6 { 13...Nd7  14.e5  was the point of White's play. } 14. Rfd1
{ Keeping his rook on a1 flexible. This is the most popular move in the position. White refrains from getting into the c-file and initiating rook trades. }
14... Rc8 15. Rac1
{ It is difficult to suggest some other plans. With the bishop on e2, there is not much White can do in the center. They could stop Nb4 ideas with  15.a3  , but it only becomes a burden after Black goes  15...Qd6  . }
15... Qd6 16. h4
{ The central break is not attractive for White. After  16.d5  exd5  , nothing really works.  17.exd5  Ne7  will lose the pawn on d5.   @@StartFEN@@2r2rk1/pb3ppp/1pnq4/3p4/4P3/4QN2/P3BPPP/2RR2K1 w - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17.e5  Qe7  makes zero sense as White will be missing Nd4 ideas since Black's knight is on c6.   Taking with @@StartFEN@@2r2rk1/pb3ppp/1pnq4/3p4/4P3/4QN2/P3BPPP/2RR2K1 w - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Rxd5  Qe7  will manage to get some more pieces to exchange and make Black happier. }
16... Rfd8 17. a3 { White stops Nb4 ideas in the future. } 17... h6
{ White lacks any coordination to create any attack either on the kingside or in the center. Black remains very solid and will soon start exchanging rooks. In the game ½-½ Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2786@@EndBracket@@ - Ding,L @@StartBracket@@2773@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2017 Black had no problems. }
