[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 14: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Be2/Bd3/Bb5)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline 11.Bb5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bb5
{ Provoking Black to play a6 and claiming the b6 square will get weaker. }
11... a6
{ Black accepts the challenge and goes on to prove that a6 is a useful move. }
12. Bd3
{ This position we could also get with the pawn on a7, which is one of the mainline. Both  12.Bc4  and  12.Ba4  gives Black a free useful tempo with  12...b5  . }
12... Nc6
{ We are almost exclusively playing Nc6 against Bd3 to attack the pawn on d4. Especially when White rook is still on a1, which means moves like  13.Qe3  can be answered with  13...Nb4  and White would not like to play Bb1 with the rook on a1. }
13. Bc2 { Black will play in a similar manner after  13.Qc3  Bd7  . } 13... Bd7
{ Waiting for White to castle before trading the queens with Qa5. We don't want White's king in the center in the endgame. }
14. O-O
{ White can't wait forever. Black did not sign any contract for playing Qa5 next. We should increase the pressure with moves like Rc8, and sooner or later, White will be forced to castle. }
14... Qa5
{ Black joyfully looks forward to an endgame. If you have gone through the introduction part, then you know exactly what I mean here. }
15. Qe3 { Naturally, White would like to avoid this particular trade. } 15...
Rac8 16. Bb3
{ Finally, the bishop arrives where it belongs. The bishop on b3 helps White to play for the thematic d5 breaks. }
16... Qa3
{ The queen is perfectly placed on a3 where it cannot be attacked, and it pins the bishop on b3 and threatens moves like Na5. Black gets excellent counterplay in the queenside, and White has no threats in the center. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 14: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Be2/Bd3/Bb5)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline 11.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bd3 Nc6
{ Typically Black attacks on d4 with the White bishop on d3. } 12. Qc3
{ Black now has two different ways of trading queens, and both are equally good. We can either play Qd6-Qb4 or Bd7-Qa5. It is important to wait for White to castle first before trading the queens. We don't want White's king in the center when we intend to play the endgame. }
12... Bd7
{ It is hard to choose between two equally good moves, but since in most cases we play Bd7-Qa5, I thought we should stick with that. }
13. O-O Qa5
{ Now is the time to initiate the trade. Black is more than happy to get into an endgame.  14.Qxa5  Nxa5  15.Ne5  gains a tempo but immediately gets into a worse position after Black goes  15...Rfd8  . White struggles to save the d-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 14: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Be2/Bd3/Bb5)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline 11.Bd3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bd3 Nc6
{ Typically Black attacks on d4 with the White bishop on d3. } 12. e5
{ I am surprised to see this move has been played quite a few times. The move e5 works well only when Black knight doesn't have access to the d5 square. With Nd7-b6 formation, White usually plays e5. Here Black gets a nice position easily. }
12... Ne7
{ I am also equally surprised to see that only two games out of more than 30 games that reached this position continued in this manner. The most popular move by Black here is  12...Qa5  , which is a strategic mistake. We should wait for White to castle before trading the queens. The move  12...Ne7  seems most logical. Black is getting ready to bring the bishop out and eventually take control of the d5-square. }
13. h4
{ One game continued in this way, but such radical play never scares Black. We are way too solid for such an attack. }
13... Bd7 14. Rh3 { 14.h5  h6  leads nowhere for White. } 14... Bc6
{ Targetting the pawn on d4. Although it cannot be taken immediately due to Bxh7 ideas at the end. }
15. Rg3 Bxf3 16. gxf3
{ 16.Rxf3  Ng6  was a better choice for White when they are only worse but not losing yet. }
16... Ng6 17. h5 Qxd4
{ The only move that doesn't lose and the only move that wins the game. Bxh7 ideas are not possible anymore, and White is losing material here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 14: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Be2/Bd3/Bb5)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline 11.Bd3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bd3 Nc6
{ Typically Black attacks on d4 with the White bishop on d3. } 12. e5
{ I am surprised to see this move has been played quite a few times. The move e5 works well only when Black knight doesn't have access to the d5 square. With Nd7-b6 formation, White usually plays e5. Here Black gets a nice position easily. }
12... Ne7
{ I am also equally surprised to see that only two games out of more than 30 games that reached this position continued in this manner. The most popular move by Black here is  12...Qa5  , which is a strategic mistake. We should wait for White to castle before trading the queens. The move  12...Ne7  seems most logical. Black is getting ready to bring the bishop out and eventually take control of the d5-square. }
13. O-O Bd7
{ White got themselves into a strategically worse position with the weak pawn on d4. Black will put pressure on it with Bc6 next. White has to be very creative now to get an equal position. }
14. Ng5 h6 15. Ne4
{ Being over creative with  15.Nh7  Re8  16.Nf6  gxf6  17.exf6  loses to the cold-blooded  17...Ng6  when White remains a piece down for nothing. }
15... Bc6 16. Nd6 Nc8 { Keep trading is the usual motto of this line. } 17. Nc4
{ Only move that is not losing for White. } 17... Nb6
{ Black could also continue the game with practically any other move, but this one forces repetition after  18.Nd6  Nc8  .   17...Bb5  is an interesting option to keep the game going. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 14: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Be2/Bd3/Bb5)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline 11.Bd3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bd3 Nc6
{ Typically Black attacks on d4 with the White bishop on d3. } 12. Bc2
{ White can reach this position with the pawn on a6 or a7, depending on their choice. }
12... Bd7
{ Waiting for White to castle! It is not the top choice or the most popular move in the position. However, for clarity and to avoid further confusion, I would like to keep this as the main move.  Black gets a good position with both  12...Bd7  and the popular and top choice of the machine  12...Qe7  . My only issue with the move  12...Qe7  is that it works only in this variation and would not work in the @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3ppp/4p3/8/3PP3/5N2/P2Q1PPP/R3KB1R w KQ - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bb5  a6  12.Bd3  variation. If someone can keep this in mind and doesn't mind having two different solutions in similar-looking variations, they can opt for  12...Qe7  , which I am giving as an alternative option. }
13. O-O Qa5
{ Now the king is away from the center. Black joyfully invites White to enter into an endgame. }
14. Qe3
{ Obviously, after the queen trade, White will be suffering. White's main strength is to play the middlegame. }
14... Rac8 15. Bb3 Qa3
{ We have seen a similar position in @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3ppp/4p3/8/3PP3/5N2/P2Q1PPP/R3KB1R w KQ - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bb5  a6  12.Bd3  line when Black pawn was already on a6. That favors Black. This could be the reason why specialists like Ding, Xiong, and Keymer prefer to play Qe7 ideas against direct Bd3 lines. However, I dug further and realized that even with the pawn on a7, Black is doing fine. }
16. d5
{ The difference is clear here. With the pawn on a6, the pawn would not be hanging. }
16... exd5 17. exd5 Na5 { It turns out Black can simply sacrifice the pawn! }
18. Qxa7 Qc5
{ A fantastic strategic move. Despite being a pawn down, Black wants to get to an endgame. }
19. Qxc5 { Forced. } 19... Rxc5
{ Black goes for the central pawn. It turns out this pawn on d5 is falling by force. The black king is way too close to it. }
20. Rfd1
{ After  20.d6  Nxb3  21.axb3  Rd8  Black goes Bc6-Rb5-Kf8, and White eventually loses the extra pawn. Engine evaluation of 0.00 seems fair. }
20... Bg4 21. d6 Rd8
{ No, we are not begging for a draw. We are simply going to gobble the pawn on d6. }
22. Rd4 Bxf3 23. gxf3 Nxb3 24. axb3 Rc6
{ The king will come to the e-file. White will have to give perpetual not to get into an uncomfortable position. The game ends in a draw now. }
