[White "Chapter 14: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Be2/Bd3/Bb5)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline 11.Bd3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bd3 Nc6
{ Typically Black attacks on d4 with the White bishop on d3. } 12. Bc2
{ White can reach this position with the pawn on a6 or a7, depending on their choice. }
12... Bd7
{ Waiting for White to castle! It is not the top choice or the most popular move in the position. However, for clarity and to avoid further confusion, I would like to keep this as the main move.  Black gets a good position with both  12...Bd7  and the popular and top choice of the machine  12...Qe7  . My only issue with the move  12...Qe7  is that it works only in this variation and would not work in the @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3ppp/4p3/8/3PP3/5N2/P2Q1PPP/R3KB1R w KQ - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bb5  a6  12.Bd3  variation. If someone can keep this in mind and doesn't mind having two different solutions in similar-looking variations, they can opt for  12...Qe7  , which I am giving as an alternative option. }
13. Rb1
{ The only game that reached this position continued with this natural move. White attacks on b7 before castling. White will castle once Black has committed to b6 and will then be missing Qa5 ideas. }
13... Rc8
{ This is a strong novelty over the only game that reached this position, Salgado Lopez, I @@StartBracket@@2604@@EndBracket@@ -Oparin, G @@StartBracket@@2654@@EndBracket@@ Toledo 2021,  which went with  13...a5  . }
14. Rxb7
{ White accepts the challenge and grabs the pawn. After  14.O-O  , Black would play the typical  14...Qa5  , offering the trade when the white king is not in the center. }
14... Na5
{ Offering another pawn sacrifice now! Black plays against White's uncastled king. }
15. Rb1
{ This is a human response, trying to avoid complications and playing safe. }
15... Nc4 16. Qb4 { White is one move away from castling. } 16... a5 17. Qb3
{ Only move that doesn't lose on the spot. } 17... a4 18. Qb4
{ Once again the only move that doesn't lose on the spot. } 18... Ne3
{ We first got our pawn to a4 and only then opted for this move. The pawn on a4 is much stronger than the pawn on a7. }
19. fxe3 Rxc2 20. O-O Rxa2
{ Now it is clear why the inclusion of a5-a4 was important. Black keeps a strong protected outside passed pawn. }
