1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bd3 Nc6
{ Typically Black attacks on d4 with the White bishop on d3. } 12. Bc2
{ White can reach this position with the pawn on a6 or a7, depending on their choice. }
12... Qe7
{ Semi-Tarrasch specialists like Ding, Xiong, and Keymer opted for this move, and they don't mind having two different solutions for @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3ppp/4p3/8/3PP3/5N2/P2Q1PPP/R3KB1R w KQ - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bd3  and  11.Bb5  a6  12.Bd3  . Black wants to play Rd8 next. So far, it is simple and not obvious what changes with an extra a6. }
13. O-O Rd8 14. Qe3
{ Getting away from the pin. This move was played by the world champion in 2020 Wijk aan Zee. }
14... b6 15. Rfd1 Bb7
{ Black finishes the development peacefully while White does not have any breaks in the center. }
16. Rac1 Rac8
{ Black finished development while White does not have any clear way to break the center. Soon some trading will take place on the c-file. Black had no problem in the game: 1/2-1/2 Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2872@@EndBracket@@-Xiong,J @@StartBracket@@2712@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2020. }
