[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 14: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Be2/Bd3/Bb5)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline 11.Bd3 - Alternative #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bd3 Nc6
{ Typically Black attacks on d4 with the White bishop on d3. } 12. Bc2
{ White can reach this position with the pawn on a6 or a7, depending on their choice. }
12... Qe7
{ Semi-Tarrasch specialists like Ding, Xiong, and Keymer opted for this move, and they don't mind having two different solutions for @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3ppp/4p3/8/3PP3/5N2/P2Q1PPP/R3KB1R w KQ - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bd3  and  11.Bb5  a6  12.Bd3  . Black wants to play Rd8 next. So far, it is simple and not obvious what changes with an extra a6. }
13. O-O Rd8 14. d5
{ This is the variation that does not work with the pawn on a7, but works with the pawn on a6 :@@EndBracket@@ We shall see more on this as we go forward in this line. The move  14.e5  was played in blitz once, but Black had a fine position after  14...b6  and soon took control over the d5 square.   The natural  14.Rad1  would be a mistake when Black has  14...e5  , and after  15.d5  Bg4  they dominate on the dark squares with the knight coming to d4 soon. }
14... Nb4
{ 14...exd5  15.exd5  Nb4  also reaches the same position as the mainline after  16.Bb3  . }
15. Bb3 exd5 16. exd5 Nxd5
{ Exploiting the pin on the d-file. This move liquidates the position instantly. }
17. Bxd5 Be6 18. Rae1
{ After  18.Rfe1  Qf6!  Black takes over as the  a1  rook hangs after  19.Re5  Rxd5  . }
18... Qc5 { Both sides are playing only moves that don't lose the game. } 19.
Rxe6 { Once again the only move that doesn't lose. } 19... Rxd5
{ Again forced. Now, it looks like White is losing, but once again they only have one move to escape. }
20. Rc1 Qb5
{ Another only move!  20...Rxd2  21.Rxc5  wins for White when they have back rank under control, and the d2 rook is under attack. Finally, we have reached the position which solves the mystery of pawn being on a7 and  @@StartFEN@@r5k1/1p3ppp/p3R3/1q1r4/8/5N2/P2Q1PPP/2R3K1 w - - 2 21@@EndFEN@@ a6. With the pawn on a6, White would be winning here with  21.Rb6!!  This is the reason why I prefer 12...Bd7 over 12...Qe7. There is no headache to remember when it works and when it doesn't :@@EndBracket@@ }
21. Qe1
{ 21.Qe2  or  21.Qe3  will reach the same position after  21...fxe6  . } 21...
fxe6 22. Qxe6+ { The sequence of forced moves continues... } 22... Kh8 23. Ng5
{ Once again the only move to escape with a draw. } 23... Qd7
{ The smoke has cleared, and White will have to give perpetual. } 24. Nf7+ Kg8
25. Nh6+ Kh8
{ 1/2-1/2Mendonca, L @@StartBracket@@2536@@EndBracket@@-Keymer,V @@StartBracket@@2630@@EndBracket@@ chess24. com INT 2021 }
