[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. h4
{ Nowadays, this is one of the trendy ways for White to play. Black should know how to deal with the kingside expansion. }
11... b6
{ Black's play remains natural and easy. Targetting White's central pawns. }
12. h5
{ 12.Rd1  is the top choice of engines which is covered in a different file from  11. Rd1 move order. }
12... h6 { Rule of thumb: Never allow White to play h6. Never ever! } 13. g4
{ Going for the most natural follow-up. White wants to mate Black. Without developing properly, this is not a wise thing to try. However, it was played by Fabi in a rapid game, which indicates there will be some merit to it. }
13... Bb7
{ Attacking in the center when White is trying to play on the flank. Sounds reasonable. }
14. Qe3
{ Happened in the game. Let us also take a look at what happens if White goes completely crazy with  14.g5  . }
14... Nc6
{ Developing with threats. Black wants to play Nb4 now with the idea of getting to c2. }
15. a3
{ An unfortunate obligation for White. Both  15.Rg1  and  15.g5  was losing to  15...Nb4  , with the threat of Nc2, after which Black will also take in charge of the c-file with Rc8. }
15... b5
{ Black keeps playing energetically and stops White from progressing on the kingside. Now, Qa5+ is a serious threat. }
16. Be2
{ Here in the game Caruana - Dominguez Black played the move  16...a6  , which is fine but loses the momentum. This position demands more energetic play like Black's previous moves. }
16... f5
{ According to engines, there are plenty of options available to get a balanced position for Black. I like the text move as it is the most dynamic and principled response. Counter attacking when White's king is in the center. }
17. g5 { There is no time to waste. White goes for Black's king. } 17... fxe4
18. Qxe4 Nxd4
{ This forces a draw immediately. If Black wants a complex game with all three results possible, then  18...Rf7  is a nice option. }
19. Qxb7 Nxf3+ 20. Bxf3 Qd3
{ The bishop is under attack while Black also threatens to play Qc3 next. } 21.
Qxa8 Qc3+ 22. Ke2 Qc4+ { Or  22...Qb2  ends with a perpetual. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 15: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.h4)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline 11.h4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. h4
{ Nowadays, this is one of the trendy ways for White to play. Black should know how to deal with the kingside expansion. }
11... b6
{ Black's play remains natural and easy. Targetting White's central pawns. }
12. Bd3
{ This strange move order was tried by David Paravyan in 2021. White plays something similar to the 11.Bd3 system but only after including h4-b6. Let's check what changes with this inclusion. }
12... Nc6
{ In the game, Black played  12...Bb7  , but we are normally opting for Nc6 in most cases, attacking the d4 pawn. }
13. Qe3 { Perhaps this was the point, as Black now misses Qa5+. } 13... Nb4
{ However, if we compare with 11.Rc1 or 11.Rd1 line, then we can see White won't be able to play Bb1 happily with the rook still stuck on a1. }
14. Bb1
{ Obviously no other choice, White cannot afford to give up a powerful attacking piece @@StartBracket@@the bishop@@EndBracket@@ after playing h4. }
14... Ba6 { Making sure White cannot castle easily. } 15. a3
{ Any other move loses for White. It is important to note  15.Qa3  loses to the brilliant  15...Rc8  as White can't take on b4 due to the check on c1. }
15... Nc6 16. h5 h6 { Never never never allow White to play h6. } 17. Bd3
{ White now wants to bail out and offers a trade to safeguard the king. } 17...
Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Rc8
{ Once again, Black gets a pleasant position. White has no attacking prospects, and Black managed to initiate some trades. The pawn on h5 could also become a potential target apart from the central pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 15: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.h4)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline 11.h4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. h4
{ Nowadays, this is one of the trendy ways for White to play. Black should know how to deal with the kingside expansion. }
11... b6
{ Black's play remains natural and easy. Targetting White's central pawns. }
12. Rd1
{ This is a strange move order. White starts with h4 then decides not to play in the kingside immediately. Black's play remains simple and logical. }
12... Bb7 13. Bd3
{ 13.Qf4  Qf6  only helps Black as he is happy to trade always. } 13... Nd7
{ Black wants to bring more pressure on the e4 pawn with Nf6, and get the rook to c8 next. }
14. Rh3
{ Sooner or later White must show some ideas on the kingside. After  14.h5  h6  15.g4  f5  the center blows up and White is busted with an exposed king in the center. }
14... Rc8
{ Black was spoilt with choice here. There were too many moves available to get a fine position. I like this one to show that White has no concrete plans on the kingside.  14...h6  15.Rg3  Kh8  or  14...Nf6  15.e5  Bxf3  16.gxf3  Nd5  or  14...Qe7  also gives fine position to Black, and according to the human eye and engines, Black has zero problems in all of them. }
15. Rg3
{ In this very rare case, White gives a positional threat: exchanging pieces. The move Qg5 could be annoying as after the trade White takes on g5 with the pawn and the pawn on h7 could become a potential target.   The inclusion of  15.h5  h6  helps Black as there won't be any Qg5 threats, and we can play Kh8 after Rg3. }
15... f5
{ Striking in the center. Black is ready to play Qe7 if White attacks with Qh6. After  16.e5  Bxf3  Black picks up the pawn on h4. }
16. Ng5 { White goes for the e6 pawn. } 16... fxe4
{ We will see whose king comes under fire now :@@EndBracket@@ It is definitely not White who has the visa to attack freely. }
17. Nxe6 Qxh4 { Allowing Rg7 with a check as the king on h8 remains safe! } 18.
Rxg7+ Kh8 { White has to find the only move now not to lose the game } 19. Bf1
{ Not a good sign if this turns out to be the only move to save the game. }
19... Rce8 20. d5 e3 21. Qxe3 Bxd5 22. Rxd5 Rxe6
{ And the game is drawn after  23.Rxh7+  Qxh7  24.Qxe6  Qb1+  25.Rd1  Qb4+  26.Ke2  Qb5+  26.Ke1  Qb4+  27.Rd2  Qb1+  28.Ke2  Qb5+  29.Ke1  . }
*

