[White "Chapter 16: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Bc4 Nd7 - Sidelines)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline 11.Bc4 Nd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7
{ Better than the b6 move order, as this avoids d5. After  11...b6  12.d5  White gets a clearly better position as Black can't take on d5 since Bxd5 traps the rook on a8. Black is now ready to play b6-Bb7 next. }
12. O-O { 12.d5  Nb6  would be a disaster for White. } 12... b6
{ Black wants to gain tempo with Bb7 attacking e4 followed by Rc8 attacking c4. }
13. e5
{ Trying to play against the knight on d7, but it weakens the d5 square drastically, making Black's play easier. }
13... Bb7 14. Qe3
{ Protecting the knight on e3. After  14.Qf4  Rc8  White cannot play  15.Bd3  due to the fine tactical shot of  15...Nc5  , using the pin on the d-file, and once White moves the bishop from d3, Black takes on f3 when White cannot take back with the queen as the d4 pawn hangs. }
14... Rc8 { Black keeps developing the pieces with tempo. } 15. Bd3 h6
{ Black's standard plan will be Nb8-Bd5-Nc6, and in the process, they will also keep an eye on Bxf3-Qxd4 ideas. White's tempting plan of Nd2-Ne4 is immediately met by Qg5 when White will be obliged to exchange queens. }
