[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 16: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Bc4 Nd7 - Sidelines)"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch - Mainline 11.Bc4 Nd7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7
{ Better than the b6 move order, as this avoids d5. After  11...b6  12.d5  White gets a clearly better position as Black can't take on d5 since Bxd5 traps the rook on a8. Black is now ready to play b6-Bb7 next. }
12. O-O { 12.d5  Nb6  would be a disaster for White. } 12... b6
{ Black wants to gain tempo with Bb7 attacking e4 followed by Rc8 attacking c4. }
13. d5
{ White strikes in the center immediately. This move is not so popular, but Black must be cautious about dealing with it. Anish played this move in 2020 twice@@StartBracket@@#1, #2. @@EndBracket@@. }
13... Nc5
{ The most practical and safest way to deal against this move. The computer's top choice is  13...Nf6  but after  14.Qf4  exd5  Black needs to remember some insanely complex lines for  15.Rfd1  and  15.Rad1  . I don't mind the intricate lines, but what annoyed me is for these different rook moves on move 15, Black must have a completely different kind of solution. On the other hand, 13...Nc5 is logical and much easier to play when we don't need to remember a series of only moves. }
14. Rad1 exd5
{ Black gives White the option of taking d5 with a pawn or bishop. } 15. Bxd5
{ With the rook on  d1  , this move makes more sense. After  15.exd5  Qd6  16.Nd4  a6  Black gets a strong blockade on d6 while White's bishop on c4 remains bad. }
15... Bb7 { Happy to exchange pieces. } 16. Ne5
{ One of the top choices of the engines, but Black is way too solid for such a direct attack. White threatens to take on f7. }
16... Qe7 { Attacking the knight on e5, and the pawn on e4. } 17. Qd4
{ White kept all of the pieces in the center, and Black will keep targetting them now :@@EndBracket@@ }
17... Rae8 { Hitting the knight on e5 while keeping the f7 pawn protected. }
18. f4 { White holds on to the knight on e5. } 18... Kh8
{ Black threatens to play f6 and Nxe4. White cannot maintain the center any further. }
19. Rf3
{ A devilish trick to stop f6. Now  19...f6  would lead to mate after  20.Ng6  hxg6  21.Rh3  . }
19... Ne6
{ White will have to give up the bishop or move the queen away. Black will then chase the knight away with f6. There is no attack on the kingside while White's center comes under pressure. The engine gives 0.00, but in a practical game, I would take Black, as White's army starts to surrender space as they move back into their camp. }
