13. d5
{ White strikes in the center immediately. This move is not so popular, but Black must be cautious about dealing with it. Anish played this move in 2020 twice@@StartBracket@@#1, #2. @@EndBracket@@. }
13... Nc5
{ The most practical and safest way to deal against this move. The computer's top choice is  13...Nf6  but after  14.Qf4  exd5  Black needs to remember some insanely complex lines for  15.Rfd1  and  15.Rad1  . I don't mind the intricate lines, but what annoyed me is for these different rook moves on move 15, Black must have a completely different kind of solution. On the other hand, 13...Nc5 is logical and much easier to play when we don't need to remember a series of only moves. }
14. Qf4
{ This move was played by Leko in 2018. White removes the queen first, trying to get Rad1 next. }
14... Qf6
{ What I like about this entire opening is the simplicity in Black's play. Having a good structure and pawn formation for any endgame, we want to exchange pieces almost in any situation. }
15. Qe3
{ After  15.Qxf6  gxf6  16.Rfe1  Rd8  Black gets a lovely endgame where both White's minor pieces are restricted. The engines already slightly prefer Black's position. }
15... Bb7
{ White was apparently threatening to play e5-d6 but it turns out this favors Black. }
16. e5 Qg6 { Keeping an eye on the g2 pawn. } 17. Rfd1
{ 17.d6  f6  will be similar to the game when Black gets good initiative on the kingside. }
17... Rad8 18. d6 f6 { Breaking White's pawn chain instantly. } 19. exf6 Rxf6
{ The attack on the kingside is serious. The engine's top choice is  20.Ne1  Rf5  with the idea of Bd5, which wins the pawn on d6. Black was clearly better in the game: Krejci, J @@StartBracket@@2551@@EndBracket@@-Sabuk, P @@StartBracket@@2372@@EndBracket@@ the Czech Republic 2018. }
