1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7
{ Better than the b6 move order, as this avoids d5. After  11...b6  12.d5  White gets a clearly better position as Black can't take on d5 since Bxd5 traps the rook on a8. Black is now ready to play b6-Bb7 next. }
12. O-O { 12.d5  Nb6  would be a disaster for White. } 12... b6
{ Black wants to gain tempo with Bb7 attacking e4 followed by Rc8 attacking c4. }
13. d5
{ White strikes in the center immediately. This move is not so popular, but Black must be cautious about dealing with it. Anish played this move in 2020 twice@@StartBracket@@#1, #2. @@EndBracket@@. }
13... Nc5
{ The most practical and safest way to deal against this move. The computer's top choice is  13...Nf6  but after  14.Qf4  exd5  Black needs to remember some insanely complex lines for  15.Rfd1  and  15.Rad1  . I don't mind the intricate lines, but what annoyed me is for these different rook moves on move 15, Black must have a completely different kind of solution. On the other hand, 13...Nc5 is logical and much easier to play when we don't need to remember a series of only moves. }
14. Rfe1
{ 14.Qd4  exd5  15.exd5  Qd6  16.Rfe1  transposes to 14.Rfe1 lines. White keeps the rook on e1, anticipating exd5-exd5 positions when the rook on e1 occupies the open file. }
14... exd5 15. exd5
{ 15.Bxd5  Bb7  transposes to a line that is covered from 13.Rfe1 move order. }
15... Qd6
{ Of course, Black is not going to allow White to play d6. It is not easy to remove the queen from d6, and the bishop on c4 remains passive. }
16. Qd4
{ The most challenging move in the position. Played by Anish and Yu Yangyi. White realized the queen on  d6  would not move quickly, so he improved his queen position, taking more space in the center.  16.Rac1  Bb7  is covered from 13.Rac1 move order.   16.Rad1  Bg4  allows Black to remove the knight from f3 when White is left with a bad bishop on c4 against a good knight on c5. }
16... Ba6
{ This obvious thematic move turns out to be a novelty! In both games that reached this position, Black opted for Bb7. With Ba6 Black sticks to their basic strategy of exchanging pieces. }
17. Bxa6
{ It is most logical to put Black's knight in the corner. After  17.Ne5  Rfe8  more pieces will get exchanged as Black threatens to play Nd7. }
17... Nxa6 18. Rad1
{ White claims that all of the pieces are centralized, so they should be better. Neither I nor the engines are impressed with this. }
18... Rad8
{ The isolated pawns must not be blocked, they must be captured! Black prepares to take the pawn on d5 with Nb4/Nc7 ideas. }
19. Re2
{ After the tempting  19.Ne5  Nb4  White loses the pawn on d5.  19.Qa4  Nc7  20.Qxa7  Nxd5  fizzles out to a draw instantly. }
19... Nc7 20. Red2
{ All White's major pieces are busy defending the pawn on d5. } 20... Qc5
{ Life becomes easier when we have one straightforward plan: Exchange pieces. }
21. Qxc5 bxc5 22. d6
{ The tempting Ne5-Nc6 idea does not work due to  22.Ne5  Rfe8  23.Nc6  Rxd5  and White loses the pawn due to back rank issues. }
22... Nb5 23. d7 { Once again,  23.Ne5  Rfe8  would be difficult for White. }
23... f6
{ The pawn on d7 will be gone, but in return, White will get the c5 pawn. The position becomes dead drawn. }
