1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7
{ Better than the b6 move order, as this avoids d5. After  11...b6  12.d5  White gets a clearly better position as Black can't take on d5 since Bxd5 traps the rook on a8. Black is now ready to play b6-Bb7 next. }
12. O-O { 12.d5  Nb6  would be a disaster for White. } 12... b6
{ Black wants to gain tempo with Bb7 attacking e4 followed by Rc8 attacking c4. }
13. Rac1
{ As mentioned in the introduction files, the rook is not ideally placed on c1. It helps Black to trade the rooks, and usually, any kind of piece trade favors Black. }
13... Bb7 14. d5
{ The only way to justify White's play. Any other move Black would play Rc8 and will be delighted to trade the rooks. The rook on c1 prevents Black from playing  14...exd5  15.Bxd5  Nc5  due to  16.Rxc5! }
14... Nc5 { Black plays Nc5 without taking on d5 and attacks e4. } 15. dxe6
{ Trying to break Black's pawn structure. } 15... fxe6
{ Black doesn't mind breaking the pawn structure since it is difficult for White to save the central pawn. }
16. Qe3 Bxe4 17. Bxe6+
{ 17.Ng5  Bd5  18.Rfd1  Qe8  fizzles out to an evenly balanced endgame. Although with the queenside majority, I would rather be Black. }
17... Nxe6 18. Qxe4 Nf4
{ The knight on f4 is super strong. After:  19.Rcd1  Qe8   Or  19.Ne5  Qd4!  20.Qxd4  Ne2  21.Kh1  Nxd4  Black gets a nice endgame with nothing to worry about. }
