{ Black goes for the pawn on e4 when White is not ready to play d5, and playing e5 allows Nd5 with a tempo. }
15. Qe1
{ Trying to get Rd1-d5 ideas next. Doubling on the e-file with  15.Rae1  makes no sense as Black will be happy to trade if the e-file opens up. After  15...Rc8  16.Bb3  h6  Black has nothing to worry about. Black threatens to play b5-a5-a4 next while White misses any serious ideas. }
15... Rc8 16. Bb3 b5
{ Seeing White has no threats, Black continues the queenside expansion with a5-a4 ideas. }
17. d5 { 17.Rd1  Qb6  only helps Black's queen to move to a better square. }
17... exd5 18. e5 d4
{ According to engines, practically any sensible move gives Black a fine position. I like this dynamic way of solving everything instantly. }
19. Rd1 dxe3 { Black gets two rooks for the queen now. } 20. Rxd8 exf2+ 21.
Qxf2 { 21.Kxf2  Ne4  followed by taking on d8 gives Black a fine position. }
21... Rfxd8
{ Black keeps two rooks for the queen as White can't get a piece after  21.exf6  Rc1  22.Ne1  Re8  and the knight on e1 falls. Black had no problem in the game 1/2-1/2 Lagarde, M @@StartBracket@@2647@@EndBracket@@-Janik, I @@StartBracket@@2508@@EndBracket@@ Larisa 2021. }
