cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7
{ Better than the b6 move order, as this avoids d5. After  11...b6  12.d5  White gets a clearly better position as Black can't take on d5 since Bxd5 traps the rook on a8. Black is now ready to play b6-Bb7 next. }
12. O-O { 12.d5  Nb6  would be a disaster for White. } 12... b6
{ Black wants to gain tempo with Bb7 attacking e4 followed by Rc8 attacking c4. }
13. Rfe1
{ It is the most popular move in the position. White is protecting the pawn even before it is under attack.  13.Bd3  Bb7  14.a4  and  13.a4  Bb7  14.Rfe1  and  13.a4  Bb7  14.Bd3  Nf6  15.Rfe1  all of the lines mentioned above transposes to  13. Rfe1 variation. }
13... Bb7 14. d5
{ Trying to break the center immediately. White is not ready yet for such direct combat and can't pose Black even the slightest problem. }
14... exd5 15. Bxd5 Nc5
{ Once again, this move becomes possible as White does not have a rook on c1 to take Rxc5. }
16. Rad1 Re8 { Keeping an eye on e4 and ready to take on d5. } 17. h3
{ Black is delighted to play endgames, so  17.Bxb7  Qxd2  18.Rxd2  Nxb7  doesn't bother them when  19.Rd7  Nc5  gives a crucial tempo. }
17... Bxd5 18. exd5 Qd6
{ The pawn on d5 is not moving anywhere.  19.Nd4  Qxd5  and  19.Nh4  g6  both don't bother Black. As usual, the endgames are fine for Black when the pawn on d5 remains very close to the king on g8. Black had no issues in the game 1/2-1/2 Xu, Z @@StartBracket@@2506@@EndBracket@@-Xu, X @@StartBracket@@2573@@EndBracket@@ Xinghua 2021. }
