{ Once again, a move that has never been played. This course is not just about playing novelties but also anticipating novelties. We should always stay one step ahead of our opponent. Moreover, I give these kinds of lines to give you a better perception of the middlegame. Not just in this position, but in general Black should be aware of how to deal with such wild attacks. }
19... a5
{ A very practical move. There is no need to stop White's kingside advance. They are also weakening their king. According to the engines, Black is also fine after  19...Nxg4  20.Rec1  Qe7  21.Qf4  f5!  22.Rc7  fxe4  23.Rxe7  Rxf4  24.Rbxb7  exd3  , and it ends with some perpetual. I'm not particularly eager to allow White's rooks on the seventh rank, and in general, I would like to keep winning chances here from Black. Playing a5 is much easier than we did for 18.g4 lines. }
20. g5
{ White cannot play  20.h4  as after  20...Nxg4  the knight on g4, gets complete stability. After  21.Rec1  Qb8  22.e5  Ra7  there is no way to get rid of the knight from g4, and Black is close to winning. }
20... hxg5 21. Nxg5 Rfd8
{ Striking in the center, and stopping e5 ideas. After  22.e5  Rxd4  23.exf6  Rg4  24.Kf1  Bg2  35.Ke2  Qe5  White loses the knight on g5. }
22. Qe3 { Renewing the threat of e5. } 22... Ng4
{ Double attack on e3 and h2. } 23. Qh3 { Double attack on g4 and h7. } 23...
Nh6
{ The knight on h6 alone is stopping the attack on the kingside. Black still puts pressure on the center, and the position remains dynamically balanced. }
