[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 17: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Bc4 Nd7 - Mainline)"]
[Black "Mainline 11.Bc4 Nd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7 12. O-O b6 13. Rfe1 Bb7 14.
Rad1
{ It is one of the ideal setups for White. With this piece formation, White is best prepared for the central break with d5. It is also difficult for Black to exchange any piece, and white wants to play the middlegame without trading a single piece. }
14... Rc8 15. Bd3
{ This move has been played a few times, but clearly, it is not the ideal formation for White. The bishop on d3 hinders the d-file, and White usually doesn't play for the d5 break. The rook on d1 is useless with the bishop on d3, and rook on a1 would have helped them play for a4-a5 ideas. }
15... h6
{ Just like 15.Bb3 lines, Black plays in the same manner. Waits for White to show their plans. }
16. h3 { White also waits for Black to show their plans. } 16... Nf6
{ A very typical plan is to play Qc7 with the idea of bringing the f8 rook out and to keep Qc3 ideas in hand. Anytime, White plays Rc1 Black will move the queen and threaten to exchange the rooks. }
17. d5
{ Not the best move according to engines, but moves like Ra1 or Rb1 with 0.00 evaluation don't look intimidating. }
17... exd5 18. e5
{ This is a very thematic idea by White. They sacrifice a pawn and want to get a lovely blockade with Nd4. If White manages to get this with impunity, Black will end up with a dead bishop on b7 while its counterpart will become a monster on d3. }
18... Ne4 { Shutting the bishop on d3. } 19. Qf4 Qe7
{ Getting away from the Bxe4 threat and threatening to play f6 next. } 20. Nd4
{ If it was White to move, then they would have won the game with Nf5 now. }
20... Qg5
{ There are multiple advantages of playing h6. We can see one right now. Without the pawn on h6, Black would have been lost due to Rxe4, but here the queen on g5 remains protected. }
21. Qh2 { White wants to keep the queens and threatens to play h4 next. } 21...
Qh4
{ Forces White to give up the bishop on d3 for the knight on e4. White gets to bailout with Nf5-Nd6-Nxb7 ideas, reaching a major piece endgame, but clearly, Black has nothing to worry about. }
*

