1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7 12. O-O b6 13. Rfe1 Bb7 14.
Rad1
{ It is one of the ideal setups for White. With this piece formation, White is best prepared for the central break with d5. It is also difficult for Black to exchange any piece, and white wants to play the middlegame without trading a single piece. }
14... Rc8 15. Bd3
{ This move has been played a few times, but clearly, it is not the ideal formation for White. The bishop on d3 hinders the d-file, and White usually doesn't play for the d5 break. The rook on d1 is useless with the bishop on d3, and rook on a1 would have helped them play for a4-a5 ideas. }
15... h6
{ Just like 15.Bb3 lines, Black plays in the same manner. Waits for White to show their plans. }
16. Bb1
{ Giving justification to the setup. White now wants to target the h7 square with the queen. }
16... Qc7
{ A typical idea by Black. We want to play Qc3 and welcome White to play  17.Rc1  Qd6  when the threat of rook exchange will seriously spoil White's attacking prospects. }
17. d5
{ White goes for the thematic d5 break to open up the light-squared bishop. }
17... exd5 18. exd5
{ With the knight on d7, the move e5 is not scary. Black would play Rfe8, and by attacking the pawn on e5, they will stop White from playing Nd4. Also, thematic counter pawn sacrifice with d4 becomes a strong option. }
18... Rfd8
{ The engine finds various ways for White to get a 0.00 position. I could not find a single variation that might scare Black. Moves like  19.Qd3  is met by  19...Nf6  . Playing d6 only helps Black to open up the bishop on b7.   After  19.Bf5  Qd6  The pawn on d5 will soon come under tremendous pressure. The pawn on d5 has become an obligation.   The attractive but careless  19.Re7  Qd6  immediately worsens the position for White when they will lose the  d5  pawn soon. }
