cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7 12. O-O b6 13. Rfe1 Bb7 14.
Rad1
{ It is one of the ideal setups for White. With this piece formation, White is best prepared for the central break with d5. It is also difficult for Black to exchange any piece, and white wants to play the middlegame without trading a single piece. }
14... Rc8 15. Bb3 { The main move. The bishop on b3 facilitates the d5 break. }
15... h6
{ A lovely move order finesse. Black waits for White to show their plans.  If Black rushes with  15...Nf6  then after  16.d5  exd5  17.exd5  Re8  18.d6  gives White some pressure. Black is now claiming that White got everything they wanted, yet they can't strike. The move h6 is politely telling your opponent, 'I am not intimidated with your play. Please show me your plans'. Black also deliberately keeps the rook on f8, which protects the f7 pawn once the center blows up and/or White knight comes to e5 in the future. }
16. h4
{ White gains space on the kingside and tries to scare Black with some kingside attacking plans. }
16... Re8
{ This position usually comes from 15.Re1 16.h4 h6 move order. Black keeps waiting for White to show their idea. }
17. g4
{ The most direct follow-up of White's previous move. White is not hiding their intentions and wants to attack the kingside with g4-g5. }
17... Qf6
{ Developing with a tempo and bringing the queen closer to Black's king. } 18.
Qe3
{ White could also protect the knight with Kg2, but on the kingside, nothing can scare Black since g5 will be answered with Qg6, and in the meantime, Black can put pressure on the center with Rfd8, and on the queenside with b5-a5 ideas in the future. }
18... Qg6 { Attacking the pawn on g4 } 19. Qf4
{ White could play  19.g5  , but there are no further threats. Black could continue the queenside play with  19...b5  with a5-a4 ideas. }
19... Qf6
{ The engine gives many other solutions with 0.00 evaluation. Claiming that White has no attack on the kingside. However, this move seals White's fate instantly. Playing  20.Qg3  would allow  20...Rc3  when Black completely takes over.   White now must repeat with  20.Qe3  Qg6  not to be worse. }
