[White "Chapter 17: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Bc4 Nd7 - Mainline)"]
[Black "Mainline 11.Bc4 Nd7 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7 12. O-O b6 13. Rfe1 Bb7 14.
Rad1
{ It is one of the ideal setups for White. With this piece formation, White is best prepared for the central break with d5. It is also difficult for Black to exchange any piece, and white wants to play the middlegame without trading a single piece. }
14... Rc8 15. Bb3 { The main move. The bishop on b3 facilitates the d5 break. }
15... h6
{ A lovely move order finesse. Black waits for White to show their plans.  If Black rushes with  15...Nf6  then after  16.d5  exd5  17.exd5  Re8  18.d6  gives White some pressure. Black is now claiming that White got everything they wanted, yet they can't strike. The move h6 is politely telling your opponent, 'I am not intimidated with your play. Please show me your plans'. Black also deliberately keeps the rook on f8, which protects the f7 pawn once the center blows up and/or White knight comes to e5 in the future. }
16. Qf4
{ White is getting ready to play d5 and also keeps the idea of h4-g4-g5 open. }
16... Qc7
{ One of the most standard way of dealing with Qf4 ideas. Don't let the queen stay on f4 and challenge it with the exchange threat. }
17. Qxc7 Rxc7 18. d5
{ Trying to create an immediate play in the center before Black can consolidate his position. }
18... Nc5
{ We had a similar position with the inclusion of h4-Rfe8. Black was taking exd5 followed by Rcc8. That option doesn't work here, obviously, as White is faster to get their rook on e7. }
19. d6 Rcc8
{ With the rook on f8, d7 is not a fork. This is the reason Black is happy to play Nc5 without the inclusion of h4-Re8. }
20. e5
{ It might look intimidating with the pawns on e5-d6, but in reality, they are not going anywhere. }
20... Bxf3 { Breaking the structure. } 21. gxf3 g5
{ The knight on c5 has no challenge, while the bishop on b3 has no role. There are no clear plans for White. On the other hand, Black will bring the king to g7 and break with f6 at the right moment. Although engines call it equal, I like Black's position from a practical point of view }
