14... Rc8 15. Bb3 { The main move. The bishop on b3 facilitates the d5 break. }
15... h6
{ A lovely move order finesse. Black waits for White to show their plans.  If Black rushes with  15...Nf6  then after  16.d5  exd5  17.exd5  Re8  18.d6  gives White some pressure. Black is now claiming that White got everything they wanted, yet they can't strike. The move h6 is politely telling your opponent, 'I am not intimidated with your play. Please show me your plans'. Black also deliberately keeps the rook on f8, which protects the f7 pawn once the center blows up and/or White knight comes to e5 in the future. }
16. h3
{ The most popular move. White also waits for Black to show their plan. } 16...
Nf6
{ Why did we reject 15...Nf6 and play the same after the inclusion of h3-h6? For 15.Nf6, we said 16.d5 was the problem, so we should first start with this move. }
17. d5 { We will now see why h3-h6 inclusion favors Black. } 17... exd5 18. e5
{ This move was played only once by GM Aravindh. I was on the Black side and got a comfortable position soon. }
18... Ne4 { Getting to e4 with a tempo. } 19. Qf4 Nc5
{ Black is ready to play Ne6 while  20.Nd4  Qg5  threatens a queen trade. We see one advantage of having the pawn on h6. It protects the g5-square. }
20. Re3
{ It would have been wiser to play Nd4 and allow some trades when White would eventually take on d5 and get to an equal endgame. However, the text move looks tempting as White tries to continue the attack on the kingside. }
20... Ne6
{ Black gets the knight to e6. White will have to move the queen, and whenever they move the knight from f3, Black will get Qg5 ideas. Black is already better here when White doesn't get enough compensation for the pawn. Aravindh,C @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@-Ganguly, S @@StartBracket@@2625@@EndBracket@@ chess24. com INT 2021 }
