17. d5 { We will now see why h3-h6 inclusion favors Black. } 17... exd5 18.
exd5 { Creating a passed pawn and trying to push it immediately. } 18... Re8
{ The most natural move to exchange pieces. } 19. d6
{ Playing just like in the 15...Nf6 variation where we concluded White was better. }
19... Bxf3 20. gxf3 Qd7
{ Finally, we see the benefit of including h6 and h3. The pawn on h3 is under attack, and Black is in time for Rcd8 next. }
21. Qf4
{ Setting a nice trap with  21...Qxh3  22.Re7  , which would be winning for White. }
21... Rcd8
{ Black is not in a rush. They attack the pawn on d6 with the Rxe1 threat. }
22. Re3
{ After  22.Rxe8  Nxe8  White will be worse as there is no way to save the pawn on d6. }
22... Rxe3 23. fxe3 { Once again  23.Qxe3  Ne8  will drop the pawn on d6. }
23... Qxh3
{ The exact position with the pawns on h2 and h7 would be winning for White, but with an exposed king, Black gets enough counterplay, and the position remains dynamically balanced. The computer calls it 0.00 as expected : @@EndBracket@@ }
