17... Qc7
{ We have seen this theme several times previously. Black wants to trade queens. }
18. Qh4 { White gets away from the trade and renews the threat of d5. } 18...
Rfe8
{ Anticipating d5, Black keeps the rook on e8. Once d5 is played, the e-file opens up after Black takes on d5, which is the most logical way to deal with d5 ideas. }
19. d5
{ Definitely, the first move we should check for White. Can White break in the center now? }
19... exd5 20. e5
{ After  20.exd5  Rxe1  21.Nxe1  Rd8  White will have difficulties saving the pawn on d5. }
20... Ne4 { Keeping an eye on e5 stops White from moving the knight from f3. }
21. Bxd5 Bxd5 22. Rxd5 Nc5
{ Black lost all sense of danger and played the highly illogical  22...Nc3  23.Rd4  Nxa2  in the game 1-0 Martirosyan, H @@StartBracket@@2607@@EndBracket@@-Arvola, B @@StartBracket@@2494@@EndBracket@@ Batumi 2019. Obviously, if Black plays that recklessly and keeps the knight on a2, he is bound to get crushed. It was important to get the knight back on e6 to control the critical d4-square. }
23. Red1
{ After  23.Nd4  Nd3  White loses the pawn on e5 and Black gets a clear better position. }
23... Ne6
{ The knight on e6 takes care of everything for Black's king. Black is now ready to penetrate on the queenside with Qc2 next. }
24. Rd7 Red8
{ It was also possible to play  24...Qc2  25.Qh5  Rf8  when White's attack comes to a dead end. However, the cool  Red8  also pours cold water in White's attacking plan. }
