{ White stays loyal to their kingside attacking plans. After  21.a3  a4  22.Ba2  Qc2  23.Bb1  Qb2  Black continues to dominate the queenside, with Rc1 coming next. }
21... Kh7
{ A strong improvement over the game 1-0 Edouard, R @@StartBracket@@2614@@EndBracket@@-Alavi Moghaddam, S @@StartBracket@@2445@@EndBracket@@ Europe Echecs INT 2021 where Black played  21...Kh8  . We will see the difference between Kh7 and Kh8 in the 22.Ree3 variation. Even optically, the king looks safer on h7. }
22. Ree3
{ Who couldn't tempt themselves for making such an attacking move with the idea of the brilliant Rxg7-Kxg7-Rg3 and mate! }
22... Bxe4
{ Very important tactical resource. I can totally imagine many strong players falling for this amazing trick. }
23. Rxe4
{ Rxg7 ideas were not working anymore as black will always have the Bg6 resource. }
23... Qc1+ { An important intermediate move to make the next move possible. }
24. Kh2 g5
{ This is why it was important to play Kh7 instead of Kh8. The pawn on h6 remains protected. }
25. Reg4
{ Only move not to lose immediately and hoping to mate black after  25...gxh4  26.Rg7  Kh8  27.Nxf7  . }
25... Rg8
{ Black takes care of the g7 square and threatens to take the queen on h4 now. }
26. Rxg5 Rxg5 27. Nxf7 { Both h6 and g5 are under attack now. } 27... Rxg3
{ The queen keeps the pawn on h6 protected. } 28. fxg3 Kg7
{ The attack has stopped, and Black keeps the material advantage. Once the knight moves from f7, Black will exchange queens with Qg5. }
