[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 17: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Bc4 Nd7 - Mainline)"]
[Black "Mainline 11.Bc4 Nd7 #20"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7 12. O-O b6 13. Rfe1 Bb7 14.
Rad1
{ It is one of the ideal setups for White. With this piece formation, White is best prepared for the central break with d5. It is also difficult for Black to exchange any piece, and white wants to play the middlegame without trading a single piece. }
14... Rc8 15. Bb3 { The main move. The bishop on b3 facilitates the d5 break. }
15... h6
{ A lovely move order finesse. Black waits for White to show their plans.  If Black rushes with  15...Nf6  then after  16.d5  exd5  17.exd5  Re8  18.d6  gives White some pressure. Black is now claiming that White got everything they wanted, yet they can't strike. The move h6 is politely telling your opponent, 'I am not intimidated with your play. Please show me your plans'. Black also deliberately keeps the rook on f8, which protects the f7 pawn once the center blows up and/or White knight comes to e5 in the future. }
16. h3
{ The most popular move. White also waits for Black to show their plan. } 16...
Nf6
{ Why did we reject 15...Nf6 and play the same after the inclusion of h3-h6? For 15.Nf6, we said 16.d5 was the problem, so we should first start with this move. }
17. Qf4
{ Supporting the pawn on e4 and threatening to play d5 next. After  17.Qd3  Re8  Black gets a nice maneuver with Re7-Rc7-Rc3 in the future. }
17... Qc7
{ We have seen this theme several times previously. Black wants to trade queens. }
18. Qh4 { White gets away from the trade and renews the threat of d5. } 18...
Rfe8
{ Anticipating d5, Black keeps the rook on e8. Once d5 is played, the e-file opens up after Black takes on d5, which is the most logical way to deal with d5 ideas. }
19. Ne5
{ White tries to bring the rook to g3 to pursue the kingside attacking plans. }
19... b5 { Ignoring White's plan and going for a queenside attack! } 20. Rd3 a5
{ I love this attitude by Black, ignoring White's kingside attacking plans and continuing our own queenside advance by attacking the bishop on b3. }
21. Rg3
{ White stays loyal to their kingside attacking plans. After  21.a3  a4  22.Ba2  Qc2  23.Bb1  Qb2  Black continues to dominate the queenside, with Rc1 coming next. }
21... Kh7
{ A strong improvement over the game 1-0 Edouard, R @@StartBracket@@2614@@EndBracket@@-Alavi Moghaddam, S @@StartBracket@@2445@@EndBracket@@ Europe Echecs INT 2021 where Black played  21...Kh8  . We will see the difference between Kh7 and Kh8 in the 22.Ree3 variation. Even optically, the king looks safer on h7. }
22. a4
{ This is a wise decision. I can totally see White players getting excited here and playing under the illusion of a significant attack which could easily cost them a full point. }
22... bxa4 23. Bxa4 Rf8
{ Funnily enough, White is already almost worse. It is quite hard to stop Black from taking on e4. }
24. Ng4 Nxe4
{ Eliminates the central pawn. There were many other ways to get a balanced position, but this move is the most direct. }
25. Nxh6 Qd8 { Forcing a queen trade. } 26. Qxd8
{ After  26.Rxe4  Bxe4  27.Qxe4  Kxh6  there is no mate, and Black remains an exchange up. }
26... Rcxd8 27. Nxf7 { White now barely escapes with a draw. } 27... Rxf7 28.
Bc2 Rxd4
{ White gets the knight on e4, but after the mass exchange on e4, Black gets to a rook and pawn endgame with an outside passed pawn and a rook behind it. If anyone should be afraid, it is White. }
