[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 17: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Bc4 Nd7 - Mainline)"]
[Black "Mainline 11.Bc4 Nd7 #23"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7 12. O-O b6 13. Rfe1 Bb7 14.
Rad1
{ It is one of the ideal setups for White. With this piece formation, White is best prepared for the central break with d5. It is also difficult for Black to exchange any piece, and white wants to play the middlegame without trading a single piece. }
14... Rc8 15. Bb3 { The main move. The bishop on b3 facilitates the d5 break. }
15... h6
{ A lovely move order finesse. Black waits for White to show their plans.  If Black rushes with  15...Nf6  then after  16.d5  exd5  17.exd5  Re8  18.d6  gives White some pressure. Black is now claiming that White got everything they wanted, yet they can't strike. The move h6 is politely telling your opponent, 'I am not intimidated with your play. Please show me your plans'. Black also deliberately keeps the rook on f8, which protects the f7 pawn once the center blows up and/or White knight comes to e5 in the future. }
16. Re3 { White wants to play Qe2/Qe1 next and then aim for the d5 break. }
16... Nf6
{ White skipped playing h3, and Black takes full advantage of that by attacking the e4 pawn and keeping Ng4 ideas open. }
17. Qe1 { As  17.Qe2  Ng4  was losing material, White keeps the queen on e1. }
17... Re8
{ Once White plays d5, it is likely that the e-file will get opened up. Black is getting ready for that. }
18. h3
{ White got the setup. Now, they really are threatening d5+e5 since there is no Ng4. }
18... Qc7 { The queen is aiming for a nice square on f4. } 19. d5
{ Now that Ng4 ideas are not available, White goes for the d5 break.  19.Ne5  b5  leads nowhere for White when Black keeps expanding on the queenside. }
19... exd5 20. e5
{ Finally, White got the break while stopping Ng4, and they are also ready for  20...Ne4  with  21.Nd4  when Black can't take on e5 due to the pin on the e-file after f3. }
20... Nd7 { A lovely way to restrict the knight on f3. } 21. Ba4
{ Neither:  21.e6  fxe6  22.Rxe6  Nf6   Nor  21.Bxd5  Bxd5  22.Rxd5  Nf8  could bother Black as White's attack fizzles out, and Black remains solid. }
21... Bc6 22. Bxc6
{ White doesn't mind exchanging the bishop to gain a tempo with Nd4 next. }
22... Qxc6 23. Nd4
{ White now goes for the kingside attack with Rg3-Nf5 ideas. } 23... Qg6
{ Black plays boldly and invites White to gain another tempo with Rg3. The point is  24.Rg3  loses to the cold-blooded  24...Rxe5  , Black remains two pawns up. Without Rg3, there is no attack, and Black has no problem in the position.   24.Nb5  Rc2  doesn't look scary either. }
