[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 17: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Bc4 Nd7 - Mainline)"]
[Black "Mainline 11.Bc4 Nd7 #24"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7 12. O-O b6 13. Rfe1 Bb7 14.
Rad1
{ It is one of the ideal setups for White. With this piece formation, White is best prepared for the central break with d5. It is also difficult for Black to exchange any piece, and white wants to play the middlegame without trading a single piece. }
14... Rc8 15. Bb3 { The main move. The bishop on b3 facilitates the d5 break. }
15... h6
{ A lovely move order finesse. Black waits for White to show their plans.  If Black rushes with  15...Nf6  then after  16.d5  exd5  17.exd5  Re8  18.d6  gives White some pressure. Black is now claiming that White got everything they wanted, yet they can't strike. The move h6 is politely telling your opponent, 'I am not intimidated with your play. Please show me your plans'. Black also deliberately keeps the rook on f8, which protects the f7 pawn once the center blows up and/or White knight comes to e5 in the future. }
16. Re3 { White wants to play Qe2/Qe1 next and then aim for the d5 break. }
16... Nf6
{ White skipped playing h3, and Black takes full advantage of that by attacking the e4 pawn and keeping Ng4 ideas open. }
17. Qe1 { As  17.Qe2  Ng4  was losing material, White keeps the queen on e1. }
17... Re8
{ Once White plays d5, it is likely that the e-file will get opened up. Black is getting ready for that. }
18. h3
{ White got the setup. Now, they really are threatening d5+e5 since there is no Ng4. }
18... Qc7 { The queen is aiming for a nice square on f4. } 19. d5
{ Now that Ng4 ideas are not available, White goes for the d5 break.  19.Ne5  b5  leads nowhere for White when Black keeps expanding on the queenside. }
19... exd5 20. e5
{ Finally, White got the break while stopping Ng4, and they are also ready for  20...Ne4  with  21.Nd4  when Black can't take on e5 due to the pin on the e-file after f3. }
20... Nd7 { A lovely way to restrict the knight on f3. } 21. Ba4
{ Neither:  21.e6  fxe6  22.Rxe6  Nf6   Nor  21.Bxd5  Bxd5  22.Rxd5  Nf8  could bother Black as White's attack fizzles out, and Black remains solid. }
21... Bc6 22. Bc2
{ Sarana's big idea. Provoke bishop to c6 then come back to c2.  22.Rc3  Nc5  leads nowhere for White. }
22... Nf8
{ The knight heads for its ideal square on e6. In the only game that reached this position, Black played  22...d4  and after  23.Nxd4  Rxe5  24.Nf5  got into big trouble in Sarana, A @@StartBracket@@2649@@EndBracket@@ -Praggnanandhaa, R @@StartBracket@@2618@@EndBracket@@ Riga 2021. }
23. Nd4 Ne6 { Not letting the knight stay on d4. } 24. Nf5 d4
{ This is the right moment to strike with d4. Now the position becomes extremely wild, and both sides will be playing with fire. }
25. Rg3
{ The most human move, going for an attack on the kingside. After  25.Nxd4  Black can either play:  The solid  25...Nxd4  26.Rxd4  Bd5  with a balanced position when the c2 bishop is under attack.   - Or they can choose the dynamic  25.Nxd4  25...Bxg2  26.Nxe6  fxe6  27.Bg6  Bd5  when the bishop on d5 becomes a gigantic monster after  28.Bxe8  Rxe8  Black gets huge compensation. I would go for the second option :@@EndBracket@@ }
25... Bxg2
{ Showing zero respect towards White's attack! Black has their own plans of attacking the kingside :@@EndBracket@@ }
26. Bb3
{ After the automatic  26.Nxh6  Kf8  White gets into huge trouble with both minor pieces hanging. }
26... Ba8
{ The bishop has done its job and exposed White's king. Now it is time to come back and keep attacking from the long diagonal. }
27. Nxh6+ Kf8 28. Nf5 { Only move that doesn't lose instantly. } 28... Qc5
{ We are ready to meet Nd6 with Nf4 now } 29. Nd6
{ Now that Black's king is more secure than White's king, White tries to grab some material. }
29... Nf4 30. Nxf7
{ Once again, the only move that doesn't lose the game. White could not afford to give the e5 pawn. }
30... Bd5
{ By attacking the knight on f7, Black also attacks the pawn on e5. White must find another only move to stay in the game. }
31. Qd2
{ Not at all an easy move, and absolutely forced if white wants to stay in the game. }
31... Bxb3 32. axb3 Nxh3+ { Grabbing a pawn before taking on f7. } 33. Rxh3
Kxf7
{ Finally, the smoke is clear. Both kings got exposed, but there are not enough pieces left to create an attack. Although Black is a pawn-up, White gets enough play to balance it out. Engine evaluation of 0.00 seems fair at this point. }
