16. Re3 { White wants to play Qe2/Qe1 next and then aim for the d5 break. }
16... Nf6
{ White skipped playing h3, and Black takes full advantage of that by attacking the e4 pawn and keeping Ng4 ideas open. }
17. d5
{ Now it gets pretty forced. White clearly says that they are ready for the d5 break, but Black also claims so. Let's see who is right here. }
17... exd5 18. e5 Ne4 { Black got Ne4 with a tempo. } 19. Qe1
{ Threatening to take on e4. } 19... Qe7
{ Getting away from the pin and ready to return the pawn by allowing Bxd5. }
20. Nd4
{ The most principled move. White threatens to play f3 and play against Black's bad bishop on b7. After  20.Bxd5  Bxd5  21.Rxd5  Nc5  Black gets a fine endgame, with Rfd8 coming next. }
20... Qh4
{ A fantastic way to stop White from playing f3. Naturally, White is not happy to trade queens in a pawn-down position. }
21. g3 Qe7
{ One of the important strategic maneuvers that we should keep in mind. Whenever White plays g3, the attacking prospect on the kingside reduces drastically. Now there is no way to attack g7 as no major piece can come to the g-file. }
22. f3 Nc5 23. f4
{ Not the best move, but this will give an idea of how helpless White is on the kingside attacking plans once they have committed to g3. }
23... Rfd8 { Ignoring White's threat completely. } 24. f5 Ne4
{ The pawn on e5 is under attack, so White can't play f6. } 25. e6 f6
{ The pawn on f5 stops White from playing Nf5. The pawn on g3 makes sure no major piece would ever come to the g-file. Black's king remains safe on the kingside. It can hide on h7, and while White prepares something long-term, which is not visible yet, Black can continue to push the queenside pawns. The engine thinks Black is better, and I can't find an argument otherwise. }
