16. Re3 { White wants to play Qe2/Qe1 next and then aim for the d5 break. }
16... Nf6
{ White skipped playing h3, and Black takes full advantage of that by attacking the e4 pawn and keeping Ng4 ideas open. }
17. d5
{ Now it gets pretty forced. White clearly says that they are ready for the d5 break, but Black also claims so. Let's see who is right here. }
17... exd5 18. e5 Ne4 { Black got Ne4 with a tempo. } 19. Qe1
{ Threatening to take on e4. } 19... Qe7
{ Getting away from the pin and ready to return the pawn by allowing Bxd5. }
20. Nd4
{ The most principled move. White threatens to play f3 and play against Black's bad bishop on b7. After  20.Bxd5  Bxd5  21.Rxd5  Nc5  Black gets a fine endgame, with Rfd8 coming next. }
20... Qh4
{ A fantastic way to stop White from playing f3. Naturally, White is not happy to trade queens in a pawn-down position. }
21. g3 Qe7
{ One of the important strategic maneuvers that we should keep in mind. Whenever White plays g3, the attacking prospect on the kingside reduces drastically. Now there is no way to attack g7 as no major piece can come to the g-file. }
22. f3 Nc5 23. Nf5 { Trying to get the knight to d6. } 23... Qe6 24. Nd6 Rc7
{ Black is ready to take on b3, which stops White from executing Nxb7-Bxd5 ideas. }
25. f4 Nxb3
{ After the intermediate  26.f5  Qd7  27.axb3  Black can play  27...Ba8  with a double threat of f6 and d4-Rc2 when the engine thinks Black is already taking over.  Once again, the pawn on g3 is the culprit of White's position, stopping any major piece from coming to the g- file. }
26. axb3 d4 { Opening up the bishop. } 27. Rxd4 Ba8
{ After Qd7-Qc6 happens, it is not clear who is attacking whom :@@EndBracket@@ Machine calls it equal, but I would rather be Black here with such a fantastic bishop. If White's pawn would be on g2 and they could play Rg3, that would be great for White, but it is not feasible. The world rapid champion got this position in Titled Tuesday and went on to win the game 0-1 Lazavik,D @@StartBracket@@2439@@EndBracket@@ -Abdusattorov,N @@StartBracket@@2627@@EndBracket@@ Chess. com INT 2021 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 17: Semi-Tarrasch - (11.Bc4 Nd7 - Mainline)"]
[Black "Mainline 11.Bc4 Nd7 #28"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7 12. O-O b6 13. Rfe1 Bb7 14.
Rad1
{ It is one of the ideal setups for White. With this piece formation, White is best prepared for the central break with d5. It is also difficult for Black to exchange any piece, and white wants to play the middlegame without trading a single piece. }
14... Rc8 15. Bb3 { The main move. The bishop on b3 facilitates the d5 break. }
15... h6
{ A lovely move order finesse. Black waits for White to show their plans.  If Black rushes with  15...Nf6  then after  16.d5  exd5  17.exd5  Re8  18.d6  gives White some pressure. Black is now claiming that White got everything they wanted, yet they can't strike. The move h6 is politely telling your opponent, 'I am not intimidated with your play. Please show me your plans'. Black also deliberately keeps the rook on f8, which protects the f7 pawn once the center blows up and/or White knight comes to e5 in the future. }
16. Re3 { White wants to play Qe2/Qe1 next and then aim for the d5 break. }
16... Nf6
{ White skipped playing h3, and Black takes full advantage of that by attacking the e4 pawn and keeping Ng4 ideas open. }
17. d5
{ Now it gets pretty forced. White clearly says that they are ready for the d5 break, but Black also claims so. Let's see who is right here. }
17... exd5 18. exd5 { 18.Qe1  Re8  transposes to 17.Qe1 line. } 18... Qd6
{ Of course, we are not going to allow White to play d6. Now there is only one question, is White getting Nf5-d6 or not. The evaluation of the position will be dependent on this factor. }
19. Nh4
{ The best way to get to f5. After  19.Nd4  Qd7  Black stops Nf5 ideas and also attacks the pawn on d5. With the knight on h4, White is ready to meet  19...Qd7  with  20.d6  . }
19... Rfe8
{ An extremely logical and vital move. Black could be lost without this move, but it is also the most natural move in the position. Black wants to trade pieces and take control of the e7 square so that Nf5-Ne7 doesn't become a threat. }
20. Nf5 { This forces Black to know some only moves. } 20... Qd7
{ This position reached four times in tournament games. Keymer, who is a specialist of this line got this position twice. Black attacks the knight on f5 and asks White to show their attacking plans. }
21. Nxh6+
{ The most direct way of attacking, but Black is way too active to deal with such an attack. }
21... gxh6 22. Rg3+ Kh7 { Of course the pawn on h6 needs protection. } 23. Bc2+
Rxc2 { Eliminating further pieces. } 24. Qxc2+ Kh8
{ White doesn't have enough pieces to continue the attack. } 25. Qc1
{ 25.Qd2  also gets to similar lines after  25...Kh7  . } 25... Kh7
{ Keeping the pawn on h6 protected once again. } 26. Rh3
{ 26.Qc2  Kh8  repeats the position. } 26... h5
{ Black is now totally protected, and threatens to take Bxd5. } 27. Rf3 Nxd5
{ Not fearing any ghosts, and taking the central pawn. } 28. Qc2+ Kg7 29. Rg3+
Kf8
{ Nf4 is a serious threat, and White should be precise now, not to lose the game. }
30. Qh7 Re2
{ Black's king remains surprisingly super safe in the center due to the active pieces and a solid knight on d5. Engines give 0.00 evaluation. Black would not mind getting the king to d6 if needed with the queen on e6 when nothing can attack the king further. White's king is also not safe and must watch out for back rank threats. The position remains extremely wild, with all three results possible. }
