[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Catalan: Overview"]
[Black "1) Catalan: Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3
{ White can enter Catalan in mainly two different ways: With or without committing to Nf3.   According to a quick internet research the following can be found: 'The Catalan derives its name from Catalonia after tournament organizers at the 1929 Barcelona tournament asked Savielly Tartakower to create a new variation in homage to the area's chess history. It had been played a few times before Tartakower's usage in the tournament, however: Réti–Leonhardt, Berlin 1928, for instance, transposed into an Open Catalan. '   White's main strength usually is the Catalan bishop on g2. In many variations, on the other hand, Black's main issue is where to develop the c8-bishop and to perfectly time c5 in order to open up the position.  As we will see throughout the repertoire, Black will solve all of these potential issues with logical moves that are easy to understand and will never enter a position that says 'Black should hold.' We either get a dynamic position with all three results possible, or we make it completely equal.   There is no way we accept any slight but long-term pressure that every Catalan player enjoys. }
3... d5 4. Bg2
{ 4.cxd5  was played a few times, but it makes no sense to dissolve the center and activate Black's bishop on c8 that often becomes Black's main issue. After  4...exd5  5.Nf3  c6  I already prefer Black who has zero weaknesses and gets free play.   4.Nf3  gets us back to the mainline covered from 3.Nf3 move order. }
4... dxc4
{ At the first chance given we take the pawn and play c5 next to blow up the center completely. }
5. Qa4+
{ This is the only independent move against the dxc4 lines. White could transpose to the mainline with  5.Nf3  . }
5... Nbd7
{ By delaying Nf3 White avoids Bd7-b5-c5 ideas. With knight on f3 Black's Bd7 move becomes much strong. }
6. Qxc4 c5
{ A crucial move order detail. Black wants to play a6-b5-c5 eventually, but it is ideal to start in this manner. Playing an early a6 gives an extra option of Be3-Qc1 ideas that Fabiano used to beat Anand once. }
7. Nf3 a6
{ This position could be reached from either the 3.g3/Nf3 move order, and it is covered in a different file named 'early Qa4 lines.' }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Catalan: Overview"]
[Black "2) Catalan: Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3
{ This move order is the most popular way to get to the Catalan system. I started working on Catalan during the world championship matches while helping Anand. It mainly began from the Topalov match back in 2010 when Team Anand prepared the Catalan from both sides. The entire team also started employing various new ideas found during these matches, in their tournaments after the match. Many of those ideas are still fresh, as we will see throughout the repertoire. Very rarely do we follow long forced lines and in most cases,  we create our theory and make the repertoire unique. }
4... dxc4 { At the first chance, we take on c4 and get ready to play c5 next. }
5. Bg2
{ We have discussed  5.Qa4  briefly via the 3.g3 move order. An entire chapter is dedicated only to early  Qa4  lines to clear the move order issues and get the utmost clarity of these Qa4 lines. }
5... c5
{ It was the main system that Team Anand prepared as Black against the Catalan and was happy to play this against Topalov, Gelfand, and later also against Magnus. }
6. O-O
{ 6.Qa4  Nbd7  gets us back to the 'Early Qa4 lines' where the Qa4+ move has been considered in every possible way. }
6... Nc6
{ Black delays castling but strikes in the center as fast as possible. Here we have got a bunch of different directions for White. }
7. Qa4
{ The main move according to a number of games. The position often gets very wild. White pins the knight on c6 and plans to play Ne5 next. }
7... Bd7 8. Qxc4 b5
{ A typical counter-attacking move that is very common in this position.   Black rapidly creates play against White's queen. White must keep the d4 pawn protected, which means they have two sensible squares to retreat apart from taking the pawn on b5 which is worse as it allows Nxd4.   Either way Black keeps attacking White's queen with c4 or b4.   The positions are easy to play but Black should have clarity and a clear conception. In the main files, the lines are broken down move by move with clear explanations.   The lines are full of fresh ideas and are divided into various chapters to make them easier to understand. }
*

