{ We have discussed  5.Qa4  briefly via the 3.g3 move order. An entire chapter is dedicated only to early  Qa4  lines to clear the move order issues and get the utmost clarity of these Qa4 lines. }
5... c5
{ It was the main system that Team Anand prepared as Black against the Catalan and was happy to play this against Topalov, Gelfand, and later also against Magnus. }
6. O-O
{ 6.Qa4  Nbd7  gets us back to the 'Early Qa4 lines' where the Qa4+ move has been considered in every possible way. }
6... Nc6
{ Black delays castling but strikes in the center as fast as possible. Here we have got a bunch of different directions for White. }
7. dxc5
{ The most popular choice. GM Srinath recommends this in his latest Catalan course for White. White hopes to get an endgame with a microscopic edge. We will not allow that to happen in any of the lines. }
7... Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bxc5
{ This endgame is quite popular.   If Black is not aware of how to rearrange the pieces or takes the position lightly, then they can get into serious trouble against a prepared opponent.   I have played this with both colors like almost all the members of Team Anand. I have broken down this endgame into different chapters to give the readers a clear conception of the intricacies and details. Once you go through the files, it will be easy to understand the logic behind every move, and playing this position will become easier. }
