[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 18: Open Catalan, early Qa4 lines"]
[Black "Early Qa4 lines: 4.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 dxc4 5. Bg2
{ 5.Qa4  Nbd7  6.Bg2  and  6.Qxc4  a6  7.Bg2  is covered from  4. Bg2 move order.   5.Qc2  is weaker than 5.Qa4 as apart from allowing Black to transpose with  5...Nbd7  6.Qa4  .   White also allows an even stronger option after  5.Qc2  of  5...a6  when after  6.Qxc4  b5  Black gets the bishop to b7 and is ready to play Nbd7-c5 with no trouble whatsoever. }
5... c5 6. Qa4+
{ The last chance to give Qa4+ before Black plays Nc6. The point of this move is to meet  6...Nc6  with  7.Ne5  . }
6... Nbd7
{ Our response remains the same all of the time. We meet Qa4+ with Nbd7.  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.Qxc4  a6  and  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.O-O  a6  9.Qxc4  are covered from a different move order. }
7. O-O { 7.Qxc4  is covered from 4.Bg2 move order. } 7... a6 8. Nc3
{ The only independent move as both  8.Qxc4  and  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Qxc4  is covered in the mainline from the  4. Bg2 move order. }
8... Rb8 { Renewing the threat of b5. } 9. Bf4
{ This move was played only once by Speelman in 1981 and didn't have many followers. Trying to grab the exchange by allowing a pawn storm on the queenside is indeed scary for White. }
9... b5 10. Qd1 cxd4
{ Black goes for an exchange sacrifice that gives us great compensation. Improvising on Speelman - Andersson game that continued with  10...Rb6  . }
11. Nxd4 Bb7 { Eliminating the Catalan bishop and making the king on g1 weak. }
12. Bxb8
{ White accepts the challenge and takes the exchange. Otherwise, Black is doing well materially speaking. }
12... Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Qxb8
{ Black gets terrific compensation for the exchange. We have an extra pawn and a dark-squared bishop for the rook.   The queenside pawns are well expanded, while White's knights are not stable and can be attacked at any time. The Black knight from d7 is ready to jump on c5 or e5. The queen will come to b7 with a tempo; Black can either focus on the queenside with Be7-O-O and bring the rook or opt for even the dynamic h5-h4 with a kingside attack. }
