[White "Chapter 18: Open Catalan, early Qa4 lines"]
[Black "Early Qa4 lines: 4.Bg2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Qa4+
{ This is the most precise move order if White wants to get to the Qa4 lines. In this move order, White can stop Black from playing Bd7-Qc4-b5 which, would have been possible with the knight on f3. }
5... Nbd7
{ Life is easier when we don't have to remember different moves for different move orders. As per our repertoire, we will be playing Nbd7 every single time White gives a check on a4. }
6. Nf3 { This position could also come from 3.Nf3 or the 4.Nf3 move order. }
6... a6 7. Ne5
{ Another try to stop Black from playing b5. After  7.Nc3  Rb8  8.Qxc4  b5  9.Qd3  Bb7  10.O-O  c5  11.Bf4  Rc8  12.dxc5  Bxc5  we reach the main position which can come via various move orders. This particular transposition we will be seeing multiple times. }
7... c5 { Striking in the center immediately. } 8. dxc5
{ 8.Qxc4  cxd4  would dissolve the center and the knight on e5 will be eliminated, and the position remains equal. White tries his best to stop Black from playing b5 by taking on c5. }
8... Bxc5 9. Nxc4 Rb8
{ Nothing can stop Black from playing b5 next and we are already better at this point, taking a lead in the development. }
