[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 18: Open Catalan, early Qa4 lines"]
[Black "Early Qa4 lines: 4.Bg2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Qa4+
{ This is the most precise move order if White wants to get to the Qa4 lines. In this move order, White can stop Black from playing Bd7-Qc4-b5 which, would have been possible with the knight on f3. }
5... Nbd7
{ Life is easier when we don't have to remember different moves for different move orders. As per our repertoire, we will be playing Nbd7 every single time White gives a check on a4. }
6. Nf3 { This position could also come from 3.Nf3 or the 4.Nf3 move order. }
6... a6 7. Qxc4
{ If we want to save memory space, the easiest solution would be to play  7...c5  that transposes to 7.Qxc4 lines. However, it is also possible to exploit the move order issues and get a simple and nice position with the following move... }
7... b5
{ 7...c5  transposes to our repertoire and that is always possible.  7...b5  is just an additional option that is available in this move order. }
8. Qc6 { Otherwise, Bb7-c5 would happen instantly, and Black would be fine. }
8... Rb8
{ This move offers a pawn sacrifce idea.  8...Ra7  followed by Bb7 is a way to avoid the pawn sacrifice and get a balanced position. }
9. Bf4 Bb7 { The point of Rb8 was to sacrifice this pawn on c7. } 10. Qxc7
{ No other choice, otherwise Black would play Rc8-c5. } 10... Bb4+
{ Perfect timing as White is unable to play  11.Nc3  due to  11...Qxc7  12.Bxc7  Rc8  and Black will win a piece. }
11. Nbd2 Qxc7 12. Bxc7 Rc8 { Now Black takes control of the c-file. } 13. Bf4
Rc2 14. Rb1
{ After  14.a3  Bxd2  15.Bxd2  Rxb2  there is no way to trap the rook on b2, and it remains active.  16.Bb4  can be answered with  16...Nd5  when Black gets ample counter due to our active pieces. }
14... Bxd2+
{ A counter-intuitive move! Black gives up the bishop to delay White from castling. }
15. Bxd2 O-O { White is unable to castle as the bishop on d2 hangs. } 16. Nh4
Ne4
{ White will have to give up the light-squared bishop, and Black gets great compensation in return.   This position occurred in a correspondence game in 2021 where Black had no trouble. Once again, let me highlight that this is an additional solution for us. We could transpose to the mainline by playing 7...c5 instead of 7...b5. }
