[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 18: Open Catalan, early Qa4 lines"]
[Black "Early Qa4 lines: 4.Bg2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Qa4+
{ This is the most precise move order if White wants to get to the Qa4 lines. In this move order, White can stop Black from playing Bd7-Qc4-b5 which, would have been possible with the knight on f3. }
5... Nbd7
{ Life is easier when we don't have to remember different moves for different move orders. As per our repertoire, we will be playing Nbd7 every single time White gives a check on a4. }
6. Qxc4
{ This is once again a very subtle move order, and Black must be careful to understand the difference of delaying Nf3. We will see that in our next move. }
6... c5
{ It is crucial to avoid any move order trick by White. After the natural  7...a6  Fabiano used a very interesting idea of going  8.Be3  b5  9.Qc1  against Anand in the 2018 Olympiad. Later he developed the knight from h3 instead of f3 to keep the bishop on g2 open. By playing, 7...c5 Black avoids those ideas and practically forces White to develop the knight on f3 next. }
7. dxc5
{ This move was seen only once in a GM-level game when Fedoseev played this move against Duda in Wijk 2019. }
7... Bxc5 { Stopping Be3 ideas and ready to castle/a6-b5 ideas next. } 8. Nc3
{ 8.Nf3  a6  is covered in 7.Nf3 move order. } 8... a6
{ Threatening b5 that cannot be stopped with a4 as usual, since the rook on a1 hangs after the exchange on b5. }
9. Qb3 { White stops Black from playing b5 but this is not permanent. } 9...
Ra7 { Renewing the threat of b5. } 10. Na4
{ After  10.a4  b6  Black gets the bishop to b7 killing White's bishop on g2 and also gets a lead in development. The position becomes slightly better for Black. }
10... Qa5+
{ As  11.Bd2  runs into  11...Bxf2  , White was forced to compromise the position and Black was better and eventually won the game in 0-1 Fedoseev, V @@StartBracket@@2724@@EndBracket@@-Duda, J @@StartBracket@@2738@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2019. }
