[Black "Early Qa4 lines: 4.Bg2 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Qa4+
{ This is the most precise move order if White wants to get to the Qa4 lines. In this move order, White can stop Black from playing Bd7-Qc4-b5 which, would have been possible with the knight on f3. }
5... Nbd7
{ Life is easier when we don't have to remember different moves for different move orders. As per our repertoire, we will be playing Nbd7 every single time White gives a check on a4. }
6. Qxc4
{ This is once again a very subtle move order, and Black must be careful to understand the difference of delaying Nf3. We will see that in our next move. }
6... c5
{ It is crucial to avoid any move order trick by White. After the natural  7...a6  Fabiano used a very interesting idea of going  8.Be3  b5  9.Qc1  against Anand in the 2018 Olympiad. Later he developed the knight from h3 instead of f3 to keep the bishop on g2 open. By playing, 7...c5 Black avoids those ideas and practically forces White to develop the knight on f3 next. }
7. Nf3
{ The idea that Fabiano used for 6... a6 won't work here.   Since after  7.Be3  Black has the strong  7...Nd5  and after  8.Bxd5  Nb6  White is missing Bc6+, an option he had when Black played a6 instead of c5. }
