{ Now Black goes for the usual a6-b5 plan to attack the queen and develop the bishop on b7. It is important to note that playing  8.a4  doesn't stop Black from playing  8...b5  since the rook on a1 will be hanging after the exchange on b5. }
8. Qb3
{ This move has been played rarely, but it is quite important. Black must understand the tricks here, and be careful not to fall for the trap. }
8... cxd4
{ There are two reasons why we play  8...cxd4  after  8.Qb3  and do not play  8...b5  like we are doing against  8.Qc2  . First of all, with the queen on b3 Black gets a tempo by playing Nc5. Secondly, playing  8...b5  would be a mistake as then White goes  9.Ne5  and Black is unable to play  9...Nd5  as White has more control on the d5 square. }
9. Nxd4 Nc5 10. Qe3
{ Only thrice, this position arrived on the board. But the average rating of these three players who were White is 2667 :@@EndBracket@@ It typically shows that the variation might look ugly, with moving queen so many times, but there might be something deeper than that, and engines are not saying Black is better. }
10... Nd5 { Black keeps gaining one tempo after another by chasing the queen. }
11. Qd2
{ Out of the first 11 moves, the queen is moving for the 5th time! Naturally, this doesn't look attractive yet some strong players and theoreticians played this so we should be prepared for such ideas. }
11... b5
{ Solving the issue of developing the light-squared bishop. If the bishop gets to b7 with impunity then White will have a difficult time explaining their weird anti-positional play so far. }
12. Nc3 Bb7
{ Just in time, Black got everything in the right place. One might ask, what was the point behind such an artificial play by White, moving the queen five times? The answer lies in the next two moves by White. }
13. Nxd5 Bxd5 { Of course Black doesn't want to take with the pawn. } 14. Nc6
{ This is the whole point of this system. Without this move, White cannot create any complications and, Black gets a good position by playing simple moves. Here things are concrete and, it is important to understand the details. The next 3-4 moves will be critical to get a good middlegame. }
14... Qd6
{ Qd7 was played once by my friend. The Catalan author from the White side, GM Srinath opted for the more precise 14... Qd6. Stopping White from getting back his knight to e5. A person who writes a course from the White side usually knows how to deal with it against the Black side :@@EndBracket@@   Although this game was played in December 2019, Srinath still knew what he was doing.   14...Bxg2  might look tempting but it gets into a worse position for Black after  15.Nxd8  Rxd8  16.Qa5  Bxh1  17.f3  and the bishop on h1 doesn't come out. }
15. Bxd5 exd5
{ White indeed managed to spoil Black's pawn structure, and gave him an isolated pawn. In return, he had to exchange the good bishop and keep the queenside pieces sleeping with an odd queen on d2. }
16. Nd4 g6
{ I like this more than Srinath's  16...Ne4  which is also doable. Black restricts White's knight on d4 which now has no good square to jump around. Black intends to play Bg7-O-O while White gets some difficulties developing the queenside. Black also got rid of the bad bishop against White's good bishop. Unless White creates something immediately, Black will get a super comfortable middlegame. }
17. Qe3+
{ Trying to interfere with Black's plan. After  17.O-O  Bg7  18.Qe3  Ne6  19.Nxe6  Qxe6  although the position is equal, practically, it is White who should be more careful as he gets behind the development. }
17... Be7
{ Black is in no rush. We know the bishop will get to its ideal diagonal after O-O-Bf6. The queen on e3 is no better than the queen on d2. It will anyways come under attack soon. }
18. Qh6
{ After  18.O-O  O-O  Black will get Bf6-Rfe8 with a very active position. }
18... Bf8
{ There are other ways also to keep the game going but just for the sake of proving Black's stability of this position this move will suffice. White must either allow Bg7-O-O and give Black a free play or repeat the position with  18.Qe3  Be7  which will be a wise decision at this point. }
