[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 18: Open Catalan, early Qa4 lines"]
[Black "Early Qa4 lines: 4.Bg2 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Qa4+
{ This is the most precise move order if White wants to get to the Qa4 lines. In this move order, White can stop Black from playing Bd7-Qc4-b5 which, would have been possible with the knight on f3. }
5... Nbd7
{ Life is easier when we don't have to remember different moves for different move orders. As per our repertoire, we will be playing Nbd7 every single time White gives a check on a4. }
6. Qxc4
{ This is once again a very subtle move order, and Black must be careful to understand the difference of delaying Nf3. We will see that in our next move. }
6... c5
{ It is crucial to avoid any move order trick by White. After the natural  7...a6  Fabiano used a very interesting idea of going  8.Be3  b5  9.Qc1  against Anand in the 2018 Olympiad. Later he developed the knight from h3 instead of f3 to keep the bishop on g2 open. By playing, 7...c5 Black avoids those ideas and practically forces White to develop the knight on f3 next. }
7. Nf3
{ The idea that Fabiano used for 6... a6 won't work here.   Since after  7.Be3  Black has the strong  7...Nd5  and after  8.Bxd5  Nb6  White is missing Bc6+, an option he had when Black played a6 instead of c5. }
7... a6
{ Now Black goes for the usual a6-b5 plan to attack the queen and develop the bishop on b7. It is important to note that playing  8.a4  doesn't stop Black from playing  8...b5  since the rook on a1 will be hanging after the exchange on b5. }
8. Qc2
{ Getting away from the c4 square by anticipating b5 and now White pretends to stop b5 by giving threats on a8 rook. A very rare move  8.Qd3  happened recently in 2021 FIDE Grand Prix. Black then took  8...cxd4  and after  9.Nxd4  Nc5  10.Qe3  we get to the position that is covered from 8.Qb3 move order. }
8... b5
{ This move is pretty much a slap on the face for White as we openly take on the challenge by ignoring the g2 bishop completely. Black prepares Bb7 without fearing Ne5 ideas. }
9. dxc5 { White first takes on c5 before attacking the rook on a8. } 9... Bxc5
10. Ne5
{ The big point of White's move order is to prevent Black from playing Nd5 when White can take on d7. However, this move order allows Black to use a nice trick that solves all the issues in the position. }
10... Rb8
{ Allowing the fork on c6! It turns out there is no way for White to take that advantage. }
11. Nxd7
{ Wise decision. After  11.Nc6  Qc7  12.Nxb8  Bxf2!  forces White to play  13.Kd1  and then after  13...Qxb8  White faces huge problems with his king in the center. }
11... Nxd7
{ O-O and Bb7 coming next which guarantees Black a decent position to play for. 1/2-1/2 Bluebaum,M @@StartBracket@@2672@@EndBracket@@-Donchenko,A @@StartBracket@@2658@@EndBracket@@ Bad Wiessee 2020 }
