[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 19: Open Catalan (7.Na3)"]
[Black "Open Catalan (7.Na3) #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O
{ 6.Na3  or  6.Nbd2  would eventually transpose to the mainline after  6...Nc6  7.Nxc4  cxd4  8.O-O  . }
6... Nc6 7. Na3
{ White develops the knight and would like to take on c4 with the a3-knight.  7.Nbd2  cxd4  8.Nxc4  gets us to the same position as the mainline that we will be seeing. }
7... cxd4
{ Black is currently two pawns up, out of which one will fall immediately, but Black won't give up the second one so easily. }
8. Nxc4 Bc5
{ Developing and bringing more support to the pawn on d4. Black is now ready to castle. }
9. b3
{ Trying to get a quick Bb2 and hit the pawn on d4. A move that doesn't have that many games but played by Magnus and Fabiano. Black must take this move seriously. }
9... O-O 10. Bb2
{ In 2019 this position occurred in Caruana - Harikrishna, and Shirov - Nihal. At this point, there are many ways to play. I like the solution given by both Leela and Stockfish that has a straightforward route to get a comfortable position. }
10... Qc7
{ It is important to put the queen on this not-so-obvious c7 square instead of the natural Qe7. The point is we need Rd8 after White takes Nxd4, and with the queen on e7, White would have the tactical shot of Nxc6 attacking the queen on e7 that won't work with the queen on c7. }
11. Nxd4
{ After  11.Rc1  Black will save his pawn with  11...Rd8  when  12.a3  is met by  12...a5  . }
11... Rd8
{ Now we see why the queen is better placed on c7 instead of e7. White is missing the Nxc6 trick. }
12. Nb5 { Only move to save the piece. } 12... Qe7
{ Now we come back to the natural e7 square and once again attack the queen on d1. Black will play e5 next to control the center and open up the light-squared bishop. The knight on b5 can be pushed away with a6 if needed. Black gets a comfortable position. }
