[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 19: Open Catalan (7.Na3)"]
[Black "Open Catalan (7.Na3) #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O
{ 6.Na3  or  6.Nbd2  would eventually transpose to the mainline after  6...Nc6  7.Nxc4  cxd4  8.O-O  . }
6... Nc6 7. Na3
{ White develops the knight and would like to take on c4 with the a3-knight.  7.Nbd2  cxd4  8.Nxc4  gets us to the same position as the mainline that we will be seeing. }
7... cxd4
{ Black is currently two pawns up, out of which one will fall immediately, but Black won't give up the second one so easily. }
8. Nxc4 Bc5
{ Developing and bringing more support to the pawn on d4. Black is now ready to castle. }
9. Bf4 { White prepares Rc1 and also keeps the knight jumps to e5 open. } 9...
O-O
{ It is better to castle first before going for the f4 bishop with Nd5 when White could play Be5 attacking d4 and g7. }
10. Nfe5
{ There is a subtle difference between the knight jumps and we should be aware of that. For  10.Nce5  we should not change on e5 as after Bxe5 the pawn on d4 will be hanging. There we could just play  10...Bd7  and White will not be able to take the pawn on d4. }
10... Nxe5
{ This time the knight on f3 is gone. This means the pawn on d4 is secured, and we can safely take on e5. }
11. Bxe5 Ng4
{ Getting rid of the bishop from e5, further securing the pawn on d4. } 12. Bf4
Qe7
{ Black is a pawn up, and there is no way to get it back for White. The center remains under Black's control as White can't stop e5. }
