[White "Chapter 19: Open Catalan (7.Na3)"]
[Black "Open Catalan (7.Na3) #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O
{ 6.Na3  or  6.Nbd2  would eventually transpose to the mainline after  6...Nc6  7.Nxc4  cxd4  8.O-O  . }
6... Nc6 7. Na3
{ White develops the knight and would like to take on c4 with the a3-knight.  7.Nbd2  cxd4  8.Nxc4  gets us to the same position as the mainline that we will be seeing. }
7... cxd4
{ Black is currently two pawns up, out of which one will fall immediately, but Black won't give up the second one so easily. }
8. Nxc4 Bc5
{ Developing and bringing more support to the pawn on d4. Black is now ready to castle. }
9. Bf4 { White prepares Rc1 and also keeps the knight jumps to e5 open. } 9...
O-O
{ It is better to castle first before going for the f4 bishop with Nd5 when White could play Be5 attacking d4 and g7. }
10. Rc1
{ Giving an indirect pressure on the bishop on c5 by threatening Nce5. } 10...
Nd5
{ This is our typical resource with the bishop on f4. The bishop lacks a good square to maintain the pressure on the d4 pawn. }
11. Nce5 Nxf4
{ It was also possible to play  11...Bb6  and according to engines that is better for Black. However, the move played in the game is also slightly better for Black. Grabbing the first opportunity to take the bishop on f4. }
12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. gxf4 Bb6
{ Keeping the pawn on d4 protected. Black doesn't mind giving up the c6 pawn, which will open up the bishop on c8. Not only does Black has a bishop-pair advantage, but we will also have some attacking prospect on the kingside due to White's broken pawn structure. }
14. Ne5 Bb7
{ The queen is now ready to go on h4 and attack the pawn on f4. White can take the c6 pawn whenever he wants and Black is happy to give the same to open up his light-squared bishop. I had this position against Peter Leko in 2017 World Rapid. I was better at this point but the game eventually ended in a draw. 1/2-1/2 Leko,P @@StartBracket@@2691@@EndBracket@@ -Ganguly,S @@StartBracket@@2650@@EndBracket@@ Riadh 2017. }
