1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O
{ 6.Na3  or  6.Nbd2  would eventually transpose to the mainline after  6...Nc6  7.Nxc4  cxd4  8.O-O  . }
6... Nc6 7. Na3
{ White develops the knight and would like to take on c4 with the a3-knight.  7.Nbd2  cxd4  8.Nxc4  gets us to the same position as the mainline that we will be seeing. }
7... cxd4
{ Black is currently two pawns up, out of which one will fall immediately, but Black won't give up the second one so easily. }
8. Nxc4 Bc5
{ Developing and bringing more support to the pawn on d4. Black is now ready to castle. }
9. Bd2
{ Played only once in PRO League 2019. This looks naive and Black has multiple ways to get a comfortable position. }
9... O-O 10. Rc1 { Threatening Nce5. } 10... Nd5
{ Hari played  10..Qe7  and had a comfortable position, but I like this move more which gives Black some edge. The knight on d5 nicely blocks the bishop on g2. }
11. Na5
{ Black was ready for  11.Nce5  with  11...Nxe5  12.Nxe5  Bd6  when White would have to prove the compensation against the extra pawn. }
11... Bb6
{ Simplest! Black returns the pawn and gets an easy position to play. } 12.
Nxc6 bxc6 13. Rxc6 Bb7
{ Black's pieces are better placed and he has more space, which gives him a slightly better position to play for. }
