[White "Chapter 19: Open Catalan (7.Na3)"]
[Black "Open Catalan (7.Na3) #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O
{ 6.Na3  or  6.Nbd2  would eventually transpose to the mainline after  6...Nc6  7.Nxc4  cxd4  8.O-O  . }
6... Nc6 7. Na3
{ White develops the knight and would like to take on c4 with the a3-knight.  7.Nbd2  cxd4  8.Nxc4  gets us to the same position as the mainline that we will be seeing. }
7... cxd4
{ Black is currently two pawns up, out of which one will fall immediately, but Black won't give up the second one so easily. }
8. Nxc4 Bc5
{ Developing and bringing more support to the pawn on d4. Black is now ready to castle. }
9. Qc2
{ Once played by Hikaru back in 2012,  but this move never got any popularity since Black can handle this with the most logical moves.  9.Qb3  with the idea to bring Rd1 quickly is not scary as after  9...O-O  10.Rd1  Qe7  Black will get the rook to d8 to consolidate the center and moves like Ng4 would scare White as the pawn on f2 remains a target. }
9... O-O { Obviously the most natural move in the position. } 10. Nce5 Nxe5
{ This is the simplest way to get a comfortable position. In the game Hikaru - Kaidanov,  Black played  10...Bb6  which is not the best way. }
11. Qxc5
{ Otherwise Black remains a pawn up when White gets zero compensation. } 11...
Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 { White's main compensation is the pair of bishops. } 12... d3
{ Breaking White's structure. Black threatens d2 while  13.Rd1  is met by  13...dxe2  . }
13. exd3 Qxd3 14. Be3 Nd5
{ After this move the light-squared bishop is dead. White will sooner or later must take on d5. The position will remain symmetrical but after the exchange on d5, the king on g1 might not feel as safe as its counterpart. }
