[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 19: Open Catalan (7.Na3)"]
[Black "Open Catalan (7.Na3) #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O
{ 6.Na3  or  6.Nbd2  would eventually transpose to the mainline after  6...Nc6  7.Nxc4  cxd4  8.O-O  . }
6... Nc6 7. Na3
{ White develops the knight and would like to take on c4 with the a3-knight.  7.Nbd2  cxd4  8.Nxc4  gets us to the same position as the mainline that we will be seeing. }
7... cxd4
{ Black is currently two pawns up, out of which one will fall immediately, but Black won't give up the second one so easily. }
8. Nxc4 Bc5
{ Developing and bringing more support to the pawn on d4. Black is now ready to castle. }
9. a3
{ Not hiding the intentions. White gives a direct threat of playing b4 and moving the bishop from c5. }
9... a5
{ Of course, we are not going to allow White to play b4. The stability of the bishop on c5 is important for our central pawn on d4. }
10. Bd2
{ This move lost its popularity after the game Eljanov - Giri from Tata Steel 2016. White wants Rc1 and keeps the bishop safe on d2 for now. }
10... O-O 11. Rc1
{ The point of Bd2 gets clear as White gives a silent threat of taking Nxa5. }
11... Bd6
{ Various other moves give Black a comfortable position, but I like the one Anish played in the game. Black threatens to play e5 now and will make sure he keeps the extra pawn. }
12. Nxd6
{ After  12.e3  e5  13.exd4  e4!  is the way to go, when Black will recapture on d4 with the knight. }
12... Qxd6 13. e3
{ At this point, Anish played the logical 13...e5 . This gives Black a balanced position, but it turns out Black could fight for more. }
13... d3 { With e5-e4 coming, White's next move is sort of obligatory. } 14.
Nd4 Nxd4 15. exd4 Nd5
{ There is no need to take the pawn on d4 and allow White to play actively. Black takes control over the d5 square and will play Bd7-Bc6 next which promises him a long-term strategic edge. }
