[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 19: Open Catalan (7.Na3)"]
[Black "Open Catalan (7.Na3) #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O
{ 6.Na3  or  6.Nbd2  would eventually transpose to the mainline after  6...Nc6  7.Nxc4  cxd4  8.O-O  . }
6... Nc6 7. Na3
{ White develops the knight and would like to take on c4 with the a3-knight.  7.Nbd2  cxd4  8.Nxc4  gets us to the same position as the mainline that we will be seeing. }
7... cxd4
{ Black is currently two pawns up, out of which one will fall immediately, but Black won't give up the second one so easily. }
8. Nxc4 Bc5
{ Developing and bringing more support to the pawn on d4. Black is now ready to castle. }
9. a3
{ Not hiding the intentions. White gives a direct threat of playing b4 and moving the bishop from c5. }
9... a5
{ Of course, we are not going to allow White to play b4. The stability of the bishop on c5 is important for our central pawn on d4. }
10. b3
{ 10.Bf4  is similar to 9.Bf4 as the inclusion of a3-a5 doesn't change anything in favour of White. }
10... Qe7
{ There are different ways to get a balanced position. I find this one the simplest. The mainline is to play  10...O-O  , which is also perfectly fine. I encourage the readers to look at some of the games played in that direction. White usually plays  11.Bb2  and Black has options like Re8/h6/Qc7 etc. It is also possible to play in the same manner like 9.b3 and go for 10...Qc7 but here, if we compare the line with 9.b3, then we will see at the end White gets his knight to b5, and Black won't have the a6 option as he is committed to a5 already. However, still Black is very solid there, and GM Fridman tried it twice. I like  10...Qe7  as it immediately forces White to liquidate the queenside. }
11. Bb2
{ There was no way to stop e5 ideas. After any knight jump on e5, Black would trade and play O-O-Rd8 quickly when White won't be able to get back the sacrificed pawn. }
11... e5 12. b4
{ The only way to keep the game balanced. Any other move, White will be worse as he doesn't get back the pawn. }
12... axb4
{ Now the queenside gets completely eliminated for White. This is the reason we opt for this line only with the inclusion of a3-a5. }
13. axb4 Rxa1
{ This position was only reached twice in tournament games, and White has tried both Qxa1 and Bxa1 here. }
14. Qxa1 Nxb4 15. Ncxe5 O-O
{ Black castled peacefully, and now although White gets back the pawn, they can't hope for any advantage. }
16. Bxd4 b6 { With Bb7 coming next, the position remains balanced. } *

