[White "Chapter 20: Open Catalan (7.Ne5)"]
[Black "Open Catalan 7.Ne5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Ne5
{ The second most popular move in the position. White opens up the bishop on g2 and tries to go for a direct assault. }
7... Bd7
{ Black coolly protects the knight on c6, and we are not afraid of giving up the bishop on d7. After all, we are a pawn up. If White wastes two tempos with Ne5-Nxd7 to take the bishop, which was not doing much on c8, why should Black object to that! }
8. Nxc6
{ Trying to damage the pawn structure, but it will come with the price of exchanging all White's active pieces. We will reach the same position after  8.Bxc6  Bxc6  9.Nxc6  bxc6  . }
8... Bxc6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6
{ Black's pawn structure is bad but we are a pawn up while White is way too underdeveloped to create any attack. }
10. Qa4
{ After  10.dxc5  Qxd1  11.Rxd1  Bxc5  12.Nd2  O-O-O!  Black pins the rook on d1. We will play c3 if needed to break White's pawn structure and gets a very comfortable endgame. }
10... cxd4 11. Qxc6+ Nd7
{ Black's main strength in the center usually happens due to the pawn on d4. Black is now ready to play e5 to give more protection once White takes on c4. }
12. Qxc4
{ Otherwise, Rc8 was coming when White would not get the c4 pawn back. } 12...
e5
{ Black keeps the control in the center. We can develop the queenside rook with a tempo by going Rc8 next. There is no way for White to stop Black from castling with Be7-O-O. }
*

