1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Ne5
{ The second most popular move in the position. White opens up the bishop on g2 and tries to go for a direct assault. }
7... Bd7
{ Black coolly protects the knight on c6, and we are not afraid of giving up the bishop on d7. After all, we are a pawn up. If White wastes two tempos with Ne5-Nxd7 to take the bishop, which was not doing much on c8, why should Black object to that! }
8. Nxd7 { White gets the bishop but remains a pawn down for a while. } 8...
Qxd7 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Qc2 { 10.Qa4  Nd4  11.Qxc4  would be similar. } 10... Nd4
{ 10...Rc8  or  Nb4  would also give Black an advantage. I wanted to keep Nd4 as we can do the same for Qa4 or Qc2. }
11. Qxc4
{ It's a blunder and the best move was to play  11.Qd1  which I refuse to analyse :P }
11... Rc8
{ The engine gives a shocking -3 for Black, which gets clear when we see that there is no way to save the a1 rook. After  12.Nc3  Nc2  Black gives a double threat of Bxf2 and Nxa1. }
