[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 20: Open Catalan (7.Ne5)"]
[Black "Open Catalan 7.Ne5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Ne5
{ The second most popular move in the position. White opens up the bishop on g2 and tries to go for a direct assault. }
7... Bd7
{ Black coolly protects the knight on c6, and we are not afraid of giving up the bishop on d7. After all, we are a pawn up. If White wastes two tempos with Ne5-Nxd7 to take the bishop, which was not doing much on c8, why should Black object to that! }
8. Nxc4 { Trying to gain control over the d6 square with Bf4 next. } 8... cxd4
{ The concept of the line remains similar. We attack in the center and when given a chance, we take the pawn on d4 and keep it protected. }
9. Bf4
{ There is no other way to fight for compensation as White is not getting back the pawn otherwise. }
9... Be7
{ The main move in terms of the number of games is  9...Nd5  , which is also doable, but I like this move more. This was Team Anand's solution for the Topalov match when we were ready with Catalan from both sides. A novelty that we found in 2009 remained secret until it was finally played in 2019. It proudly shows how much ahead of time team Anand was in terms of preparation. We will soon see the novelty in the mainline. For now, let's say that Black keeps developing and is not scared to allow Nd6+ . }
10. Nd6+
{ White has just no other way to claim any compensation for the loss of the central pawn. }
10... Kf8
{ The knight on d6 is not stable at all. Black is threatening e5 now. } 11.
Nxb7
{ There is no other way to keep the knight intact. White has now gained backed the pawn but the knight is in danger. }
11... Qb6 12. Nd6
{ Thanks to the pin on the a8 rook, White is not scared of e5 as they can play Nc4-Nxe5 when the a8 rook hangs. }
12... Qc5 { A nice way to remove the knight from d6. } 13. Ne4
{ This move was played a few times. White saves the knight but Black keeps the pair of bishops. }
13... Nxe4 14. Bxe4 e5
{ This move is to gain more central control. It is equally dynamic and interesting to play  14...g5  and after  15.Bd2  Rb8  White will have difficulty saving the b2 pawn. Black gets more space, and it is easier to play from the Black side. }
15. Bd2 f5
{ Black gets total domination in the center. Although the computer calls it even, I think in a practical game it is much easier to play from the Black side. }
