{ The concept of the line remains similar. We attack in the center and when given a chance, we take the pawn on d4 and keep it protected. }
9. Bf4
{ There is no other way to fight for compensation as White is not getting back the pawn otherwise. }
9... Be7
{ The main move in terms of the number of games is  9...Nd5  , which is also doable, but I like this move more. This was Team Anand's solution for the Topalov match when we were ready with Catalan from both sides. A novelty that we found in 2009 remained secret until it was finally played in 2019. It proudly shows how much ahead of time team Anand was in terms of preparation. We will soon see the novelty in the mainline. For now, let's say that Black keeps developing and is not scared to allow Nd6+ . }
10. Nd6+
{ White has just no other way to claim any compensation for the loss of the central pawn. }
10... Kf8
{ The knight on d6 is not stable at all. Black is threatening e5 now. } 11.
Nxb7
{ There is no other way to keep the knight intact. White has now gained backed the pawn but the knight is in danger. }
11... Qb6 12. Nd6
{ Thanks to the pin on the a8 rook, White is not scared of e5 as they can play Nc4-Nxe5 when the a8 rook hangs. }
12... Qc5 { A nice way to remove the knight from d6. } 13. Nd2
{ Preparing a quick Rc1. } 13... e5
{ The standard way to remove the knight from d6. } 14. Rc1
{ This is an interesting novelty that has never been played until now. It makes sense to know the details as it is one of the top three choices by engines with similar evaluation. }
14... Qxd6
{ Black is having an extra piece now, but due to the pin on a8, White manages to create counterplay. }
15. Nc4 Qb4
{ There are other retreats too but I find this to be the simplest. } 16. a3
{ White could also take on e5 directly, but Black would play similarly as he will do after the inclusion of a3-a4. }
16... Qb5 17. a4 Qb4 18. Nxe5
{ White takes on e5 finally, but this time with the pawn on a4 instead of a2. Black's play is identical in both cases. }
18... Nxe5 19. Bxa8 Bd6
{ Materially speaking, Black is doing well, and their pieces are harmoniously placed in the center with good central control. The pawn on a4 hangs, and Black intends to play Ke7 where the king remains safe and Black rook gets a tempo by attacking the bishop on a8. White needs to find some precise moves to keep the game balanced. }
