1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Ne5
{ The second most popular move in the position. White opens up the bishop on g2 and tries to go for a direct assault. }
7... Bd7
{ Black coolly protects the knight on c6, and we are not afraid of giving up the bishop on d7. After all, we are a pawn up. If White wastes two tempos with Ne5-Nxd7 to take the bishop, which was not doing much on c8, why should Black object to that! }
8. Nxc4 { Trying to gain control over the d6 square with Bf4 next. } 8... cxd4
{ The concept of the line remains similar. We attack in the center and when given a chance, we take the pawn on d4 and keep it protected. }
9. Bf4
{ There is no other way to fight for compensation as White is not getting back the pawn otherwise. }
9... Be7
{ The main move in terms of the number of games is  9...Nd5  , which is also doable, but I like this move more. This was Team Anand's solution for the Topalov match when we were ready with Catalan from both sides. A novelty that we found in 2009 remained secret until it was finally played in 2019. It proudly shows how much ahead of time team Anand was in terms of preparation. We will soon see the novelty in the mainline. For now, let's say that Black keeps developing and is not scared to allow Nd6+ . }
10. Nd6+
{ White has just no other way to claim any compensation for the loss of the central pawn. }
10... Kf8
{ The knight on d6 is not stable at all. Black is threatening e5 now. } 11.
Nxb7
{ There is no other way to keep the knight intact. White has now gained backed the pawn but the knight is in danger. }
11... Qb6 12. Nd6
{ Thanks to the pin on the a8 rook, White is not scared of e5 as they can play Nc4-Nxe5 when the a8 rook hangs. }
12... Qc5 { A nice way to remove the knight from d6. } 13. b4
{ A highly interesting move, found by team Anand. But Gelfand had the first opportunity to use this against Adams back in 2008. White sacrifices a pawn to create open files to attack Black's queen. }
13... Qxb4 { No other choice, we need to grab this pawn. } 14. a3 Qc5
{ Once again renewing the threat on d6. So, by sacrificing a pawn on b2, White got his pawn to a3. That creates an important difference. As White takes control over the b4 square, which is not accessible for Black's queen anymore. }
15. Qb3
{ A new idea found around 2009 but was only played in 2018 when Wojtaszek @@StartBracket@@more commonly known as Radek@@EndBracket@@ used this idea to win a nice game against Adams. Radek contributed hugely to the entire Catalan repertoire for team Anand and had many interesting new ideas that we could use during and after the match.  This move which is very difficult to meet for the first time practically gave a lot of trouble to Adams. The idea is straightforward if we compare it with Leko - Kramnik started with  13.Qb3  Bxd6  14.Rc1  Qb4!  By sacrificing the pawn and gaining an extra a3 move, White stopped this Qb4 resource that was used by Kramnik. }
15... Qh5
{ An amazing counter novelty, that was found by Team Anand back in 2009. In a rare line, the move Qb3 was unique and we were ready to play this as White. However, in case Team Topalov would also find this, we were also ready with this amazing idea of Qh5 as a counter novelty. The point is Black secures the king with g5-Kg7 and also starts attacking the kingside with Ng4.   Not an easy move to find if not known. Adams blundered immediately with the natural  15...Na5  against Radek when  16.Qb4  wins on the spot which was also part of our preparation. I wish I could say 15...Qh5 is still a great novelty, but this won't be the case as it was finally played in 2019 by Fridman, who is a great expert in this line and was later followed twice at GM level. }
16. Rc1
{ This obvious-looking move was played twice, which loses on the spot. Black won both games in Socko - Moranda 2021 and Arnaduov -Fridman 2019. }
16... Rb8
{ This move order is more precise than the direct g5, which was played by Fridman and gives Black a clear advantage. }
17. Qc2 g5
{ The computer evaluation of -3 is not exaggerating since White is losing material at this point. Note that he can't take on c6 due to Ng4 threats. 0-1 Socko,B @@StartBracket@@2619@@EndBracket@@-Moranda,W @@StartBracket@@2622@@EndBracket@@ Opole 2021 }
