{ In the World Teams 2019, I had no idea that my teammate Adhiban prepared this line as White and was unaware of the brilliant  Qh5  move that was found by Team Anand long back. I was playing on the third board against Onischuk, which was also a Catalan. I was shocked to see this position on board 1, which is just lost for White. Only if I knew Adhiban is choosing this direction I would have warned him about the existence of this move. White could still bailout after  15...Qh5  but not with  16.Qc4? }
16... g5
{ It was a huge relief when Swiercz played  16...Nd5  and missed the direct win with  16...g5  . Eventually, Adhiban managed to hold on board one while I won a smooth game against Onischuk from the White side of the Catalan. }
17. Bxc6
{ The computer says  17.g4  is the best move when after  17...Qxg4  18.Bg3  Bxd6  19.Bxd6  Kg7  Black is completely winning due to his material advantage and domination. This is not something Black was worried about in the game. }
17... Ng4
{ It must be somewhere along this line Black failed to find the direct win. }
18. h4 gxf4 19. Bxa8 Bxh4
{ White now gets mated one way or the other. Black has too many pieces near White's king. }
