[White "Chapter 20: Open Catalan (7.Ne5)"]
[Black "Open Catalan 7.Ne5 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Ne5
{ The second most popular move in the position. White opens up the bishop on g2 and tries to go for a direct assault. }
7... Bd7
{ Black coolly protects the knight on c6, and we are not afraid of giving up the bishop on d7. After all, we are a pawn up. If White wastes two tempos with Ne5-Nxd7 to take the bishop, which was not doing much on c8, why should Black object to that! }
8. Na3
{ Compared to the 7.Na3 lines here White forced Black's bishop on d7 before bringing the other knight to the game. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/2p5/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nbd2  cxd4  8.Nxc4  transposes to the mainline. }
8... cxd4
{ Our response, for now, remains the same. We take the pawn on d4 and are ready to give up the pawn on c4. }
9. Naxc4 Be7
{ So with this move order, White wants to trick us, which we are not going to fall for.  9...Bc5  the is mainline in terms of the number of games, and White usually responds with  10.Qb3  . The move that we are playing prepares nicely against White's main Qb3 idea. We will see that now in the mainline. }
10. Bf4 { Stopping Qc7 ideas and getting ready for Qb3 next. } 10... Rc8
{ Black cashes in on the fact that White delayed Qb3 and allowed us to finish our queenside development. It was also important to avoid the devilish trap that White had in mind in the case of  10...Nh5  when White wanted the tricky  11.Bg5!!  Bxg5  12.Nd6  and taking on f7 next when Black loses either the rook on h8 or the bishop on g5.   It was also equally important not to castle immediately as that does not address White's threat and after  10...O-O  11.Qb3  it would be difficult to take care of the queenside pawns. }
11. Nxd7
{ This move was seen in 2021 Tata Steel Masters. White takes the bishop and tries to pick up the d4 pawn next. }
11... Qxd7 { Black keeps the central pawn protected. } 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5
{ Here Black has many good options. Stockfish and Leela prefer different moves, and honestly, it is extremely hard to choose just one of them. Both are equally good, and depending on personal taste, one can decide which direction to opt for. }
13... d3
{ This move is preferred by Leela and was also played by Tari in Tata Steel Masters 2021. He had blitzed out every single move before this, and also this movie was played in 33 seconds which indicates that he was still in his preparation. Both are equally playable. }
14. Qxd3
{ White tries his best to stop Black from castling. This way he keeps a target on  b7  by eliminating the queen on d7.  14.exd3  O-O  will be totally fine for Black when White will be left with a weak d3 pawn and Black will play Rfd8-Nd5 next. }
14... Qxd3 15. exd3 b6
{ Black is now just one move away from castling and getting a comfortable position. }
16. Bb7
{ The most critical. White once again tries their best to stop Black from castling. }
16... Rd8
{ 16...Rc2  17.Rac1  would have given White complete control over the c-file. }
17. Bc6+
{ Finally, White managed to stop Black from castling with precise play. } 17...
Kf8
{ The only problem for White is that there is no way to take advantage of the fact that Black has not castled. We are approaching the endgame now. Tari was still blitzing out his moves showing the depth and clarity of his preparation. At this point, Stockfish gives a microscopic edge to White while Leela thinks it is completely equal.  From a human point of view, this looks comfortable for Black with Bd6-Ke7 on the way. I can't imagine Black having any trouble here. 1/2-1/2 Donchenko,A @@StartBracket@@2668@@EndBracket@@-Tari,A @@StartBracket@@2625@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2021 }
