[White "Chapter 20: Open Catalan (7.Ne5)"]
[Black "Open Catalan 7.Ne5 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Ne5
{ The second most popular move in the position. White opens up the bishop on g2 and tries to go for a direct assault. }
7... Bd7
{ Black coolly protects the knight on c6, and we are not afraid of giving up the bishop on d7. After all, we are a pawn up. If White wastes two tempos with Ne5-Nxd7 to take the bishop, which was not doing much on c8, why should Black object to that! }
8. Na3
{ Compared to the 7.Na3 lines here White forced Black's bishop on d7 before bringing the other knight to the game. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/2p5/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nbd2  cxd4  8.Nxc4  transposes to the mainline. }
8... cxd4
{ Our response, for now, remains the same. We take the pawn on d4 and are ready to give up the pawn on c4. }
9. Naxc4 Be7
{ So with this move order, White wants to trick us, which we are not going to fall for.  9...Bc5  the is mainline in terms of the number of games, and White usually responds with  10.Qb3  . The move that we are playing prepares nicely against White's main Qb3 idea. We will see that now in the mainline. }
10. Bf4 { Stopping Qc7 ideas and getting ready for Qb3 next. } 10... Rc8
{ Black cashes in on the fact that White delayed Qb3 and allowed us to finish our queenside development. It was also important to avoid the devilish trap that White had in mind in the case of  10...Nh5  when White wanted the tricky  11.Bg5!!  Bxg5  12.Nd6  and taking on f7 next when Black loses either the rook on h8 or the bishop on g5.   It was also equally important not to castle immediately as that does not address White's threat and after  10...O-O  11.Qb3  it would be difficult to take care of the queenside pawns. }
11. Qb3 { Going as per the plan of attacking the pawn on b7. } 11... Nd5
{ Typical plan in this line, going for the bishop on f4. } 12. Qxb7 Nxe5
{ This ideal move order disallows Qe4, which would have been an option if  12...Nxf4  13.gxf4  Nxe5  14.Nxe5  Rc7  where White can play  15.Qe4! }
13. Nxe5 Rc7
{ Chasing the queen away before taking on f4.  An important intermediate move, Black will take on f4 and castle next. There is nothing to complain about in the position. He keeps his central pawn alive and White got a broken structure on the kingside. Ideas like Bd6-Qh4 are available and this gives Black a fighting position that is dynamically balanced. A couple of games reached this position. In 2010 Svidler - Bacrot Black had no issues and ten years later in a 2020 correspondence game, Black also didn't have any issues confirming the stability of Black's position. }
