12. Bf4 Qd8
{ A cool move. The job for Qc7 is done and it is now time to get back to the safest square where the queen cannot be harassed. }
13. Bxc6+ bxc6 { Black is a pawn up and is one move away from castling. } 14.
Ne5
{ The most critical choice. After  14.Qa4  O-O  15.Qxc6  Rc8  Black is nicely developed with good center control and has nothing to worry about. The game Shirov - Landa from 2017 ended in a draw after  16.Qa4  Nd5  when White realized there is nothing fun playing this position from the White side.   In the game, Adly, A @@StartBracket@@2596@@EndBracket@@-Fridman, D @@StartBracket@@2626@@EndBracket@@ Warsaw 2021 White played  14.Rfd1  and after  14...c5  15.Be5  O-O  16.e3  Nd5  Black was clearly better with f6 threat coming next. }
14... c5
{ Once the knight comes to c6, White will get some strategic edge. So Black must save the central pawns, which are our strength. }
15. Qa4+
{ Makes sense to break Black's castling. The check from b5 would make no sense as in the future Black will gain a tempo with Qb6. }
15... Kf8
{ Black lost the ability to castle, but we still keep one healthy extra pawn and good control over the center. Nd5 is coming next. }
16. e3
{ This move was played a few times, especially in correspondence chess. White wants to blow up the center but Black has a nice logical way to deal with this. }
16... Qe8
{ A multipurpose move. Black would obviously love to trade queens. He is also getting away from any kind of Nc6 fork and now is ready to play Nd5. }
17. Qxe8+
{ Every single game that reached this position went in this direction. Understandably, White did not move the queen when he was not thrilled to deal with Nd5 ideas. }
17... Kxe8
{ Now the king is not looking so bad in the center when the endgame is coming. }
18. exd4 cxd4 19. Rfd1 Nd5
{ Black's knight got a fantastic place, and now White knight will be kicked out by f6 or Bf6 depending on White's response. Black's king in the center is not bad at all anymore. Black can look forward to the endgame. }
