{ Black is least bothered about getting mated and gobbles up the knight. The same motif with  16.Nc8  doesn't work due to  16...Kd8  wins on the spot as Black takes the knight on c8 as well. }
16. Nf5+
{ A double-check was the only way to make sure Black doesn't take the queen. }
16... Kf6 17. Qe7+
{ 17.Qxd4  e5!  is important and then Black takes the knight on f5 and keeps the huge material advantage. }
17... Kg6
{ This is the key move. Based on this the entire line works. Otherwise, Black would be lost. Pay attention to our amazing defender on g2! The knight from g2 is doing an incredible job by stopping White from playing Nh4!! What a spectacular defensive piece :@@EndBracket@@ }
18. Nxd4
{ After  18.Nd6  Rhf8  White cannot stop Black from playing Qd8 which forces a queen trade and Black is totally winning at that point. }
18... Rhe8
{ Look at the poor queen on e7 which is struggling to find a square apart from going back all the way to a3. }
19. Qa3 { There was not a single square available apart from this one. } 19...
e5
{ With the king on g6, Black keeps attacking and chasing away White's pieces. }
20. Rac1
{ 20.Qd3  e4  was lost for White as Black would eventually save the extra piece with Bh3. }
20... Qb6 21. Nf3
{ It is interesting that despite the engine evaluation of about -7, both games that reached this position ended in a draw. The reasoning is clear as Black decided to opt for only a slight advantage position by trading the queen with  21...Qb4  . Black has a much stronger move here that wins the game. }
21... Bh3
{ Cold-bloodedly Black saves the piece and will play Qb4 next. f6 at some point will kill the knight on f3 which will lack any target. It is important to understand that saving the knight on g2 also completely restricts its counterpart as there is no Nh4 happening anymore. The evaluation of -7 confirms that Black is clearly winning which is not surprising at all. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 20: Open Catalan (7.Ne5)"]
[Black "Open Catalan 7.Ne5 #20"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Ne5
{ The second most popular move in the position. White opens up the bishop on g2 and tries to go for a direct assault. }
7... Bd7
{ Black coolly protects the knight on c6, and we are not afraid of giving up the bishop on d7. After all, we are a pawn up. If White wastes two tempos with Ne5-Nxd7 to take the bishop, which was not doing much on c8, why should Black object to that! }
8. Na3
{ Compared to the 7.Na3 lines here White forced Black's bishop on d7 before bringing the other knight to the game. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/2p5/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nbd2  cxd4  8.Nxc4  transposes to the mainline. }
8... cxd4
{ Our response, for now, remains the same. We take the pawn on d4 and are ready to give up the pawn on c4. }
9. Naxc4 Be7
{ So with this move order, White wants to trick us, which we are not going to fall for.  9...Bc5  the is mainline in terms of the number of games, and White usually responds with  10.Qb3  . The move that we are playing prepares nicely against White's main Qb3 idea. We will see that now in the mainline. }
10. Qb3
{ The main move. White attacks the pawn on b7 and doesn't allow castling.   10.e3  was played twice. The simplest solution could be to take  10...dxe3  11.Bxe3  and play  11...Nd5  when sooner or later White will have to take on d5 with the bishop to regain the pawn. Once the light-squared bishop is gone it is White who should be more careful. }
10... Qc7
{ This move would be a disaster with the bishop on c5, and it only works with the bishop on e7. We will soon see the point in the mainline. At first sight, it looks naive to allow Bf4, but that's precisely what we look forward to. }
11. Bf4
{ Definitely the most critical. For a long time, this entire line was dubious for Black due to this very direction. }
11... Nh5
{ There were almost no games during the world championship match between Anand and Topalov when we found this direction. We prepared Catalan from the White side and were also ready from the Black side if needed. Anand and his team kept playing this variation of dxc4-c5 successfully and continue to do so. }
12. Nxc6
{ Otherwise, White loses the bishop on f4 and breaks the structure for nothing. }
12... Nxf4 13. Nxe7 Nxg2
{ The first time we saw this position, the entire team was thrilled to discover this aesthetically beautiful position. It was never played at a GM level before back then.   At first glance, it looks ugly for Black since, after Kxe7 Black is going to have huge trouble. Upon a closer look, it gets clear that Black has no intention to take Kxe7, but he wants to play the super cool Qc5 next, giving the king complete immunity. Let's not forget that currently, Black enjoys an extra pawn, and we also got the g2 bishop while keeping our light-squared bishop alive. }
14. Qb4
{ Very tempting, but it's a blunder. White protects the knight and threatens Nd6+. This move was played 4 times, thrice by Grandmasters and once by a 2374 player. It shows how easy it is to fall for this. The move is tempting but loses on the spot. }
14... a5
{ Only move to win the game and also the only move to not to lose the game :@@EndBracket@@ There is no time, and Black must attack the queen immediately. }
15. Nd5
{ I worked with my childhood friend Pentala Harikrishna on many occasions, and he was also aware of this entire line. In Batumi Olympiad when Egyptian GM Adly Ahmed walked straight into this line it was a pleasant surprise and a completely free point.  15.Nd5  was a desperate measure but it is hard to suggest anything as everything is lost at this point. }
15... exd5 16. Nd6+ Kf8
{ Hari keeps his cool and walks toward the g8 square where the king would be completely safe.. }
17. Qa3 Kg8
{ Ra6 is a serious threat that will pick up the hostile knight on d6. } 18.
Rac1 Qb6
{ Very precise. Black is ready to counter  19.Kxg2  with  19...h5  and after Rh6 White will lose the knight on d6. }
19. Qc5 Qxc5 20. Rxc5 Bh3
{ Now the knight on g2 is saved. Black will play h5-Rh6-Rd8 next. Hari is a great endgame player and plays particularly well when he has an extra piece. He had no issue winning this game 0-1 Adly,A @@StartBracket@@2620@@EndBracket@@-Harikrishna,P @@StartBracket@@2743@@EndBracket@@ Batumi 2018. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 21: Open Catalan (7.Qa4 Bd7 8.dxc5)"]
[Black "Open Catalan: 7.Qa4 Bd7 8.dxc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. dxc5
{ Gelfand and his team played this move several times. This seemingly harmless-looking move is not as naive as it looks. White gives up his center and simplifies the position. If Black is not careful enough in the next few moves, he might get into some nagging pressure. }
8... Bxc5
{ I think this is the easiest. The move  8...Na5  is quite popular too but after  9.Qa3  Rc8  10.b4  cxb3  11.axb3  Rxc5  12.Bd2  the position gets complicated where Black must make a few not-so-natural moves. It is still doable but when a simple logical move works then why bother to memorize a bunch of unusual moves! }
9. Qxc4 Be7
{ I like the bishop here. Black also tried  9...Bb6  and managed to equalize, but often Black would have to give up the bishop on b6 for knight, and that is something I wanted to avoid in general. }
10. Nc3
{ A natural developing move.  10.e4  O-O  11.Nc3  and  10.Rd1  O-O  11.Nc3  transposes to 10.Nc3 line that we will be seeing now. }
10... O-O 11. Rd1
{ This move order is more popular. Though once White plays e4 we will transpose to the 11.e4 line. }
11... Rc8
{ The most natural way of developing. White is not having any immediate threats on the d7 bishop so there is no need to unpin the queen yet. }
12. Bg5
{ Indirectly bringing more pressure on the bishop on d7.  12.e4  transposes to the lines starting with 11.e4. White also tried the naive  12.Be3  when Black could either play the dynamic and direct  12...Na5  -Nc4 getting another tempo against the bishop on e3 and pawn on b2, or the move  12...a6  that happened in the game Harika - Ju Wenjun,  2016. In both cases, Black gets a comfortable position. }
12... h6
{ There is no need to be scared about the bishop on d7. No one can attack it. }
13. Bxf6
{ Any other move would make no sense of playing Bg5 one move earlier. } 13...
Bxf6 14. Ne4
{ The only move that could bother Black. It looks scary at first sight, and this is why White opted for the Bg5-Bxf6 line. Now White threatens to take on f6 and is also ready to jump with Nd6. This position was reached twice in tournament games. Once, it was played by 2536 players, and once Wang Yue played this as White when he had a 2749 rating. Both games were in the classical format, and in both games, Black missed the win! The engine gives an evaluation of -1.11 at this point. The reason to mention these details was to show how tricky the position is. Just when it seems White has everything under control and putting some pressure, it is precisely at that moment when Black is winning. }
14... Bxb2
{ Burning all of the bridges. Black ignores the pin on the d-file and takes the pawn on b2. }
15. Rab1 { There was no other choice for White. } 15... Nd4
{ The most obvious move and not difficult to spot. Black counterattacks. } 16.
Qd3
{ In both games, players likely left at this point, assuming White is better since it is not obvious how to save the piece.  16...Bb5  17.Qxb5  is not clear either. }
16... Ba4
{ An unexpected resource! Black attacks the rook on d1 instead of trying to save anything. }
17. Nxd4 { Only move.  17.Rxb2  Nxf3  loses material as the rook on d1 hangs. }
17... Bxd4
{ Very important.  17...Bxd1  18.Rxb2  will spoil the party when White gets material advantage. }
18. Qxd4 { White now gets two minor pieces for a rook. } 18... Bxd1 19. Qxd1
{ 19.Rxd1  Qxd4  20.Rxd4  Rfd8!  loses on the spot when White is obliged to change rooks and the lonely pawn on  a2  won't survive.  21.Nd6  Rc1  22.Bf1  Rc6  doesn't help either and White is dead lost at that point. }
19... Qxd1+ 20. Rxd1 Rfd8
{ In general, when one side has a rook and two minor pieces against two rooks, it is advisable to exchange one pair of rooks. The logic is before that trade, one side had two or three different kinds of pieces against one. After the trade, the single rook will become more potent as it has no match.   Of course, this is very generic advice, and everything depends on the position. Here this wise advice helps. After exchanging one pair of rooks, Black's rook will invade and take the pawn on a2, and White can do very little about it. }
21. Nd6
{ White tries their best to avoid the trade, but this puts him in a deadly pin. Moving the rook from d1 would lose a piece after Black plays f5 and traps the knight on e4. Exchanging the rook will seal the fate of the pawn on a2 and White loses. }
21... b5
{ White is never getting out from this pin as Black will stop him from playing e4-e5.  22.e4  f6  23.f4  Rc5  will be the end of White's dream to stabilize the knight on  d6  . Computer evaluation of -2 looks justified at this point. }
