[White "Chapter 21: Open Catalan (7.Qa4 Bd7 8.dxc5)"]
[Black "Open Catalan: 7.Qa4 Bd7 8.dxc5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. dxc5
{ Gelfand and his team played this move several times. This seemingly harmless-looking move is not as naive as it looks. White gives up his center and simplifies the position. If Black is not careful enough in the next few moves, he might get into some nagging pressure. }
8... Bxc5
{ I think this is the easiest. The move  8...Na5  is quite popular too but after  9.Qa3  Rc8  10.b4  cxb3  11.axb3  Rxc5  12.Bd2  the position gets complicated where Black must make a few not-so-natural moves. It is still doable but when a simple logical move works then why bother to memorize a bunch of unusual moves! }
9. Qxc4 Be7
{ I like the bishop here. Black also tried  9...Bb6  and managed to equalize, but often Black would have to give up the bishop on b6 for knight, and that is something I wanted to avoid in general. }
10. Nc3
{ A natural developing move.  10.e4  O-O  11.Nc3  and  10.Rd1  O-O  11.Nc3  transposes to 10.Nc3 line that we will be seeing now. }
10... O-O 11. Qb3
{ Bareev played this scarce move in 1995. For a good reason, there was no follower of this line. White tries to build pressure against the pawn on b7. }
11... Qc7
{ In the above-mentioned game Black opted for  11...Qb6  and White managed to break Black's pawn structure with  12.Qxb6  . There is no need to allow White to break our pawn structure. }
12. Nb5
{ One of the ways to disturb Black's queen.  12.Bf4  e5  doesn't look attractive for White as they must move the bishop after  13.Nb5  Qa5  White is unable to take on e5 as the knight on  b5  hangs and after  14.Bd2  Qd8  White's pieces are lacking targets and will soon be kicked away. }
12... Qb6 13. Be3
{ Engines top choice of  13.Nc3  admits the mistake and allows Black to shatter White's pawn structure with  13...Qxb3  . Black has no issue in such a position. However, it is essential to know the antidote for  13.Be3  , which at first sight creates some problems against the queen on b6. }
13... Na5
{ Counter attack is the best defense! The queen on b2 and the knight on b5 are attacked at the same time. }
14. Bxb6 Nxb3 15. axb3 Bxb5
{ Black will pick up the pawn on e2, leaving White with a doubled pawn.  White must be very precise to achieve equality. }
