[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 21: Open Catalan (7.Qa4 Bd7 8.dxc5)"]
[Black "Open Catalan: 7.Qa4 Bd7 8.dxc5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. dxc5
{ Gelfand and his team played this move several times. This seemingly harmless-looking move is not as naive as it looks. White gives up his center and simplifies the position. If Black is not careful enough in the next few moves, he might get into some nagging pressure. }
8... Bxc5
{ I think this is the easiest. The move  8...Na5  is quite popular too but after  9.Qa3  Rc8  10.b4  cxb3  11.axb3  Rxc5  12.Bd2  the position gets complicated where Black must make a few not-so-natural moves. It is still doable but when a simple logical move works then why bother to memorize a bunch of unusual moves! }
9. Qxc4 Be7
{ I like the bishop here. Black also tried  9...Bb6  and managed to equalize, but often Black would have to give up the bishop on b6 for knight, and that is something I wanted to avoid in general. }
10. Nc3
{ A natural developing move.  10.e4  O-O  11.Nc3  and  10.Rd1  O-O  11.Nc3  transposes to 10.Nc3 line that we will be seeing now. }
10... O-O 11. e4
{ Taking control of the center but temporarily blocking the bishop on g2. Black is always ready to meet Bg5 ideas with h6 when White will have to give up the bishop. }
11... Rc8
{ So far, all logical and natural moves for Black. There is nothing much to explain about. Developing pieces in their ideal square and having zero weaknesses in the position. }
12. Qe2 { Getting away from the c8 rook and creating threats of e5 and Rd1. }
12... Bc5
{ This move is a strong novelty as of today. But I believe it will be played soon. Black stops Rd1 by targetting the f2 pawn.   13.Rd1  Ng4  is the main idea of this move.   The natural question that comes to mind is what about  13.h3?  Then Black goes  13...e5  .   The next logical question is, why not play  12...e5?  The answer is  13.Rd1  creates an issue.   The final question is, what Black gets by including  12...Bc5  13.h3  and after  13...e5  14.Rd1  , what changes? The answer is Black now has  14...Nd4  which would not have been possible without the inclusion of h3-Bc5. After  15.Nxd4  exd4  , the knight on c3, comes into the attack, and Black will play Re8 next. They get a fine position. }
13. e5
{ The most challenging move. White removes the f6 knight and creates a central square for his knight on c3.  13.h3  and  13.Rd1  were discussed already in the previous move. If White plays,  13.Bg5  then Black goes  13...h6  when White must give up his bishop as otherwise it is getting trapped. }
13... Nd5 14. Ne4
{ 14.Nxd5  would be a huge positional mistake. After Black plays  14...exd5  , he gets a clear advantage due to multiple reasons. The pawn on e5 becomes an easier target than the pawn on d5. Moves like Re8-Bg4/Bf5 will come rapidly. White is clearly underdeveloped, and he is not ready for such open combat at this point. }
14... Nd4
{ Without this resource, the move  12...Bc5  makes no sense. Of course, Black did not go to c5 to give White a free tempo and come back. This is the key move that takes care of Black's position. }
15. Nxd4 Bxd4 16. Nd6
{ It is hard to suggest any other alternatives.  16.Qh5  g6  loses the e5 pawn.   16.Bg5  Qb6  only helps Black to build more pressure on White's pawns. }
16... Rc6
{ A brilliant move that shows Black is tactically alert. Any other rook move would run into the brilliant Bh6, which doesn't work anymore with the rook on c6 as we shall see next. }
17. Rd1
{ 17.Bh6  with the idea of Qg4 doesn't work here due to  17...Rxd6  when Black wins either after  18.Qg4  Bxe5  or  18.exd6  gxh6  19.Qg4  Bg7  .   Taking the pawn on b7 now also gets into a worse position for White after  17.Nxb7  Qc7  18.Nd6  Rc2  when Black takes complete control of the game with his super active pieces.   Black is not scared of moves like  17.Nf5  when he can always play  17...exf5  18.Bxd5  Rc5  and White loses the e5 pawn. }
17... Qb6
{ The bishop on d4 is doing an amazing job of attacking various pawns. This should not be moved. }
18. Nf5 exf5 19. Bxd5
{ By including, 17.Rd1 Qb6 White made sure Black doesn't get Rc5 ideas. } 19...
Rcc8
{ The bishop on d4, cannot be attacked easily. It continues to put pressure on White's pawns. The same cannot be said about White's bishop on d5, which will soon be moved away with Be6. Black gets a fine position now. }
