1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4
b5
{ A nice move to attack the queen, and gain more space. White is unable to take  10.Qxb5  as after  10...Nxd4  White can't save the e2 pawn since  11.Qc4  runs into  11...Bb5  .   White needs to keep the d4-pawn protected. Thus, in this position, they have two alternatives,  10.Qc3  and  10.Qd3  . Right now we will focus only on  10.Qc3  . }
9. Qc3
{ Whether White keeps the queen on d3 or c3, Black will attack it further with c4 or b4. So it is White who decides which pawn push to be allowed. In this case, they chose the b-pawn. }
9... b4
{ Gaining further space and tempo by attacking the queen yet once again. } 10.
Qd3
{ Now we reach the same position as the 9.Qd3 line except, the pawn is on b4. This means Black does not have the c4 move. 9.Qc4 has never been played as Black would then go 9...Na5 and c4 would also come in the future with a tempo. }
10... Rc8
{ A standard move in this Qa4 line. Black gets away from the pin on the long diagonal. }
11. Bf4
{ Radek played this once against Hari in Batumi Olympiad. It was an interesting theoretical discussion. Both are my good friend, and I have worked with them on several occasions. Although Radek blitzed out most of his moves, Hari also knew what he was doing, and despite taking slightly more time, he played it logically and precisely and had no issues at all. }
11... cxd4
{ This is a standard way to dissolve the center. Black is two moves away from castling, but there is no way for White to exploit that. }
12. Nbd2 { Aiming for the d6 square via c4. } 12... Nd5
{ Stopping White's plan of getting to d6 by eliminating the bishop on f4. } 13.
Be5
{ White gives up the bishop as there was no other choice. But makes sure that the structure is not ruined, and Black must give away the knight on c6 that was defending the pawn on d4. }
13... Nxe5
{ Of course, we take the bishop, that was the whole point of our previous move. }
14. Nxe5 Be7
{ Hari's moves are simple and super logical. Black wants to castle next. Bishop is safely placed on e7. For example, Bc5 would not be so secure as White could go Nb3. }
15. Bxd5
{ A very interesting decision. White realizes that by normal moves like Rac1 they won't cause any trouble. As Black will continue to play naturally and castle. By taking the knight on d5, White gives Black an isolated pawn and tries to get some blockade on d4. }
15... exd5
{ Black has a worse structure but a pair of bishops. As we will see, Hari never got into any issues with his natural and logical moves. }
16. Ndf3
{ Makes sense to capture the pawn with the knight rather than the queen. As Black will be able to chase it away anytime he wants. }
16... O-O 17. Nxd4
{ It looks like the knights are very nicely placed, which is a fact but, Black has a pair of bishops, and the position is open. This gives him ample counter that compensates everything. Radek blitzed out until this point. @@LinkStart@@https://chess24.com/en/watch/live-tournaments/@@LinkEnd@@ olympiad-batumi-2018-open/11/ }
17... Bf6
{ Hari plays with perfect logic. This move practically forces White to take Black's bad bishop on d7. }
18. Nxd7
{ Otherwise, White is getting worse. For example, after  18.Nef3  Bh3  both, black bishops will become monsters, Black can then follow up with Qe7-Re8 having a clear advantage with more space and initiative. }
18... Qxd7
{ Now the bishop on f6 is definitely no worse than the knight on d4. } 19. e3
Rc4
{ Black got enough counterplay and anytime if he wants and only if he wants. 1/2-1/2 Wojtaszek,R @@StartBracket@@2727@@EndBracket@@-Harikrishna,P @@StartBracket@@2743@@EndBracket@@ Batumi 2018 }
