1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4
b5
{ A nice move to attack the queen, and gain more space. White is unable to take  10.Qxb5  as after  10...Nxd4  White can't save the e2 pawn since  11.Qc4  runs into  11...Bb5  .   White needs to keep the d4-pawn protected. Thus, in this position, they have two alternatives,  10.Qc3  and  10.Qd3  . Right now we will focus only on  10.Qc3  . }
9. Qc3
{ Whether White keeps the queen on d3 or c3, Black will attack it further with c4 or b4. So it is White who decides which pawn push to be allowed. In this case, they chose the b-pawn. }
9... b4
{ Gaining further space and tempo by attacking the queen yet once again. } 10.
Qd3
{ Now we reach the same position as the 9.Qd3 line except, the pawn is on b4. This means Black does not have the c4 move. 9.Qc4 has never been played as Black would then go 9...Na5 and c4 would also come in the future with a tempo. }
10... Rc8
{ A standard move in this Qa4 line. Black gets away from the pin on the long diagonal. }
11. Bg5
{ This move is not that popular but still was played a few times at the GM level. There are many ways to deal with this move. White is taking the time to develop before capturing on c5. }
11... h6
{ This was my choice against Le Quang Liem in World Rapid 2017. Asking White to give up the bishop immediately as returning makes no sense, and  12.Bh4  g5  loses a piece.   Hari chose to play  11...cxd4  against Sethu, which is also perfectly doable. }
12. Bxf6 { There is simply no other way to justify White's previous move. }
12... Qxf6 { Now, there is no match for Black's dark-squared bishop. } 13. e3
{ Both:  -  13.Nbd2  Nxd4   -  13.dxc5  Qxb2  don't look appealing for White when the center gets dissolved, and Black keeps the double bishop advantage. }
13... cxd4 14. exd4 Be7
{ According to engines, pretty much any sensible move gives Black a fine position. Moves like g6 or g5, with the idea to develop the bishop on the other diagonal, were totally fine. }
15. Nbd2 O-O 16. Rac1 Rfd8
{ Black finished his development while keeping the double bishop advantage and White also got an isolated pawn. 1/2-1/2 Le, Q @@StartBracket@@2737@@EndBracket@@ -Ganguly,S @@StartBracket@@2650@@EndBracket@@ Riadh 2017 }
