1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4
b5
{ A nice move to attack the queen, and gain more space. White is unable to take  10.Qxb5  as after  10...Nxd4  White can't save the e2 pawn since  11.Qc4  runs into  11...Bb5  .   White needs to keep the d4-pawn protected. Thus, in this position, they have two alternatives,  10.Qc3  and  10.Qd3  . Right now we will focus only on  10.Qc3  . }
9. Qc3
{ Whether White keeps the queen on d3 or c3, Black will attack it further with c4 or b4. So it is White who decides which pawn push to be allowed. In this case, they chose the b-pawn. }
9... b4
{ Gaining further space and tempo by attacking the queen yet once again. } 10.
Qd3
{ Now we reach the same position as the 9.Qd3 line except, the pawn is on b4. This means Black does not have the c4 move. 9.Qc4 has never been played as Black would then go 9...Na5 and c4 would also come in the future with a tempo. }
10... Rc8
{ A standard move in this Qa4 line. Black gets away from the pin on the long diagonal. }
11. e4
{ Grabbing the center immediately. This move was played once so far in the game 1/2-1/2 Swapnil, S @@StartBracket@@2516@@EndBracket@@ -Das,A @@StartBracket@@2434@@EndBracket@@ Patna 2017 }
11... Nxd4
{ This move is significantly better than  11...cxd4  that happened in the game. After cxd4, the knight on f3 is attacking the pawn on d4, and the knight on c6 is defending the same, and it also blocks the bishop on d7. Thus it makes sense to get rid of this knight. Hence  11...Nxd4! }
12. Nxd4 cxd4
{ After  13.Qxd4  Bc5  computer bar jumps from clear better to -3! Looking at White's queenside army and seeing threats like Qb6-Bb5 it is hardly surprising. }
13. e5 Nd5
{ Once again  14.Qxd4  Bb5  with the idea of Bc5 next wins for Black due to huge lead in development. }
14. Nd2 Qb6 { Preparing Bb5. } 15. Nc4 Qc5 16. b3 Bb5
{ Black can take the knight on c4 anytime they want. White is not getting the pawn on d4 with Bb2 as Black will always have Nc3 resource. Black's next moves could be Be7-O-O and White remains a pawn down for nothing. }
