[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 22: Open Catalan (7.Qa4 Bd7 8.Qc4 b5 9.Qc3)"]
[Black "Open Catalan 7.Qa4 Bd7 8.Qc4 b5 9.Qc3 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4
b5
{ A nice move to attack the queen, and gain more space. White is unable to take  10.Qxb5  as after  10...Nxd4  White can't save the e2 pawn since  11.Qc4  runs into  11...Bb5  .   White needs to keep the d4-pawn protected. Thus, in this position, they have two alternatives,  10.Qc3  and  10.Qd3  . Right now we will focus only on  10.Qc3  . }
9. Qc3
{ Whether White keeps the queen on d3 or c3, Black will attack it further with c4 or b4. So it is White who decides which pawn push to be allowed. In this case, they chose the b-pawn. }
9... b4
{ Gaining further space and tempo by attacking the queen yet once again. } 10.
Qd3
{ Now we reach the same position as the 9.Qd3 line except, the pawn is on b4. This means Black does not have the c4 move. 9.Qc4 has never been played as Black would then go 9...Na5 and c4 would also come in the future with a tempo. }
10... Rc8
{ A standard move in this Qa4 line. Black gets away from the pin on the long diagonal. }
11. dxc5
{ Opens up the position at the first chance, but it is with some concession as Black would now develop his bishop with one tempo to c5. }
11... Bxc5
{ Obviously, we would like to recapture the pawn with a tempo, and now we are ready to castle. At this point, White tried four different logical moves, but none of them are scary. }
12. Nbd2 { With ideas like Nc4-Nd6 and Nb3-Nc5 in mind. } 12... e5
{ There was nothing wrong with  12...O-O  , but this move is more precise. Which is the top choice of machines and was also played by Anish in October 2021 in the Meltwater tour final. Black not only grabs the center but stops the white knight on d2 to jump on c4/b3. }
13. Ne4
{ Both  13.Nc4  and  13.Nb3  would run into the fork with  13...e4  . Any other move Black would opt for O-O-Qe7-Rfd8, etc when he has good center control and harmonious development. }
13... Nxe4 14. Qxe4 O-O
{ Taking advantage of the exposed queen on e4. Black is ready with Re8 in case of exchange on e5. }
15. Be3
{ 15.Nxe5  Nxe5  16.Qxe5  Re8  would not only lose the e2 pawn but also give Black tremendous activity. }
15... Nd4
{ A very important and energetic move. Once again exploiting White's exposed queen on e4. Anish, as usual, knew what he was doing and kept making the best choice. }
16. Bxd4
{ This is the only way, White can capture the pawn, as after  16.Nxd4  exd4  17.Bxd4  Bc6  Black wins material.   Playing  16.Nxe5  Bf5  doesn't help White either since Black takes on e2 with a check and the pieces remain super active. }
16... exd4 17. Nxd4
{ After,  17.Ne5  Be6  Black keeps the central pawn and double bishop when they would have not a single issue in the position. }
17... Re8
{ Bringing the rook into the game with another tempo. Black now gets great compensation for one pawn. White will have a tough time keeping his pawn on e2 and knight on d4 protected. }
18. Qf4
{ Another way, is to keep the knight protected. White is one move away from consolidating fully with e3. }
18... g5
{ Black's advantage is dynamic so, they must play very energetically. Attacking the queen once again and forcing it to retreat to d2. }
19. Qd2 Bb5
{ Targetting both d4 and e2, at a moment when White is not able to play e3 as the f1 rook hangs. }
20. Rfd1 Bxd4 21. Qxd4 Bxe2 { Gaining another tempo before taking on d4. } 22.
Rd2 Qxd4 23. Rxd4 Rc4
{ The position fizzled out totally, and Black can look forward to a balanced endgame. }
