1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4
b5
{ A nice move to attack the queen, and gain more space. White is unable to take  10.Qxb5  as after  10...Nxd4  White can't save the e2 pawn since  11.Qc4  runs into  11...Bb5  .   White needs to keep the d4-pawn protected. Thus, in this position, they have two alternatives,  10.Qc3  and  10.Qd3  . Right now we will focus only on  10.Qc3  . }
9. Qc3
{ Whether White keeps the queen on d3 or c3, Black will attack it further with c4 or b4. So it is White who decides which pawn push to be allowed. In this case, they chose the b-pawn. }
9... b4
{ Gaining further space and tempo by attacking the queen yet once again. } 10.
Qd3
{ Now we reach the same position as the 9.Qd3 line except, the pawn is on b4. This means Black does not have the c4 move. 9.Qc4 has never been played as Black would then go 9...Na5 and c4 would also come in the future with a tempo. }
10... Rc8
{ A standard move in this Qa4 line. Black gets away from the pin on the long diagonal. }
11. dxc5
{ Opens up the position at the first chance, but it is with some concession as Black would now develop his bishop with one tempo to c5. }
11... Bxc5
{ Obviously, we would like to recapture the pawn with a tempo, and now we are ready to castle. At this point, White tried four different logical moves, but none of them are scary. }
12. Be3
{ An interesting approach by White. They want to trade the dark-squared bishop, which was lacking a good square as we saw in the Bf4/Bg5 variation. White wants to get rid of it and finish developing his queenside pieces. This move was played by many strong players like Duda, Ding, Wang Hao, etc. }
12... Bxe3 13. Qxe3 Qb6
{ There are various ways to deal with this position, and I like this simple move which seems logical to me. Black offers queen trade, and he doesn't mind getting doubled pawns on the b-file as the b4 pawn restricts White's queenside, and the Black king is ideally placed on the center for the upcoming endgame.   13...O-O  is the main move which is also doable.   13...Ng4  was played by Levon in 2021, which is also interesting. However, in my opinion, 13...Qb6 is the easiest among all. }
14. Qxb6
{ If White doesn't take, then we will take on e3 when the pawn on e3 will become weak. White could waste another tempo by moving the queen. But in that case, Black would get a free tempo, and after castling, we would get a fine position. }
14... axb6
{ Now the king in the center is a blessing. Obviously, we are not going to castle and take full advantage of not having castled by playing Ke7. }
15. Nbd2
{ 15.a3  b3  doesn't help White when Black will eventually play Na5 aiming at c4 square with the knight and c2 square with the rook. }
15... Na5 { Simple prophylaxis against Nc4 ideas. } 16. Rfc1 Ke7
{ With Bb5 and Rhd8 coming next, it is White who will have to take care of his weak spots. Black indeed has double pawns but I don't see any way to target them. Engine evaluation of flat 0.00 confirms that Black has no issues here. This position was first time reached in the game: 1/2 @@StartBracket@@19@@EndBracket@@ -1/2 Bluebaum,M @@StartBracket@@2633@@EndBracket@@-Kryvoruchko,Y @@StartBracket@@2705@@EndBracket@@ Brest 2018. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 23: Open Catalan (7.Qa4 Bd7 8.Qc4 b5 9.Qd3)"]
[Black "Open Catalan 7.Qa4 Bd7 8.Qc4 b5 9.Qd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qd3
{ White keeps the queen on d3 this time and avoids the b4 ideas that we saw in the  9.Qc3  lines. However, this move allows the other pawn push. }
9... c4
{ The advantage of having the pawn on b5. There are two major options White has at this point. They can either play Qc2 and aim for a quick e4 or play Qd1 and keep the d4 pawn protected and play for Ne5 ideas. Let's start with the Qd1 plans. }
10. Qc2
{ This is the second most popular move after  10.Qd1  . White's idea is pretty direct after  10.Qc2  . They would like to get a quick e4 and try to break in the center after getting his rook to d1. }
10... Rc8
{ Prophylaxis against Ne5.  10...Be7  is also equally strong and playable. As usual, I would like to keep similar moves as and when possible. Since both Be7 and Rc8 are equally strong and in the case of  10.Qd1  we are playing  10...Rc8  , it makes sense to stick with the same move order in order to avoid any kind of confusion. This way we know our 10th move is Rc8 irrespective of where White moves the queen. }
11. Bg5
{ The second most popular move after  11.e4  . White pins the knight and starts to develop the queenside pieces. White can also start with  11.Nc3  Be7  12.Bg5  that transpose to 11.Bg5. However, it also gives Black another option to attack the c3 knight with  11...b4  , which is equally strong. }
11... Be7
{ Black is now ready to play h6 and take on f6 with the bishop. This way, the queen won't be exposed on f6. }
12. Nc3
{ It is wise for White not to commit  12.e4  when after  12...h6  13.Bxf6  Bxf6  black gets a clear edge thanks to his strong queenside pawns, double bishop, and White's lack of counterplay in the center. }
12... Qb6 { Defending the pawn on b5 and attacking the pawn on d4. } 13. Rad1
O-O
{ The bishop on g5 is not running away, and we can kick it out whenever we feel like, by playing h6. White didn't manage to create any play on the center, and Black is ready to strike on the queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 23: Open Catalan (7.Qa4 Bd7 8.Qc4 b5 9.Qd3)"]
[Black "Open Catalan 7.Qa4 Bd7 8.Qc4 b5 9.Qd3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qd3
{ White keeps the queen on d3 this time and avoids the b4 ideas that we saw in the  9.Qc3  lines. However, this move allows the other pawn push. }
9... c4
{ The advantage of having the pawn on b5. There are two major options White has at this point. They can either play Qc2 and aim for a quick e4 or play Qd1 and keep the d4 pawn protected and play for Ne5 ideas. Let's start with the Qd1 plans. }
10. Qc2
{ This is the second most popular move after  10.Qd1  . White's idea is pretty direct after  10.Qc2  . They would like to get a quick e4 and try to break in the center after getting his rook to d1. }
10... Rc8
{ Prophylaxis against Ne5.  10...Be7  is also equally strong and playable. As usual, I would like to keep similar moves as and when possible. Since both Be7 and Rc8 are equally strong and in the case of  10.Qd1  we are playing  10...Rc8  , it makes sense to stick with the same move order in order to avoid any kind of confusion. This way we know our 10th move is Rc8 irrespective of where White moves the queen. }
11. e4
{ White stays loyal to his direct plan and controls center. White could also include 10.a4 a6 in any variation where on a positive side White activates his rook on a1 but on the other hand, he also weakens the b4 and b3 squares. The knight on c6 becomes very strong now, which cannot be touched on either of these squares. }
11... Be7 { Normal developing move and getting ready to castle. } 12. Qe2
{ White will eventually have to move the queen from c2 to play d5 and avoid Nb4 ideas.  White could also start with  12.Rd1  when Black could either transpose to the mainline with  12...O-O  13.Qe2  or take advantage of the move order and opt for  12...Nb4  13.Qe2  Nd3  . }
12... O-O 13. Rd1
{ There is no other decent way to play in the center.  13.Nc3  b4  is not appealing as the knight must move away from the center.   13.a3  Na5  would allow Black a lovely spot on b3. White's central pawn is not scary unless it starts marching forward. Black will have a free play on the queenside if White waits for long. }
13... Na5
{ To give an idea of how dangerous this position can be for White, it will suffice to say that engine thinks if it is Black to play right now, then after b4, the evaluation goes up to -2 :@@EndBracket@@ White needs to respond fast on the center. }
14. Ne5
{ This move makes a lot of sense when White is threatening to play d5, which will be winning for him. If it was his move now, then d5 would be devastating. But before we get there, Black has a unique way to stop d5. }
14... b4
{ White's plan was to attack the bishop on d7 with his rook by going d5. Black counters by playing b4 with the idea to go for that same rook with Ba4 next. }
15. Nxd7
{ To give an idea about how tricky the position is for White, l would like to point out that any other move apart from this would have given Black -1 position :@@EndBracket@@ For example, the evaluation goes up to -3 after  15.d5  Ba4!  If we compare the development of pieces, then it is hardly surprising. }
15... Qxd7
{ Black is ruthless on the queenside. Now he wants to play c3-c2. His queenside pawns are far more dangerous than White's pawn on the center, and above everything else, White is hugely underdeveloped and needs to find precise moves to equalize. }
*

