{ After the careless  15.exd5  , Black has multiple ways to win. According to engines  15...Bc5  is more than -3 when White lost all his domination in the center and must protect against f2 pawn while his queenside army snores and the queen on e2 remains vulnerable. }
15... Ne8
{ This counterintuitive move is the key to this line! Instead of going to the center with Ne4, Black retreats. The idea is to gain a crucial tempo by playing Nc7 after White takes on d5. }
16. Nc3 { White wants to get his knight on d5. } 16... Nc7
{ It is absolutely obligatory not to allow White to get his knight to d5. Black is now ready to trade. }
17. Nxd5
{ There are no other serious alternative. White needs to go for this. } 17...
Nxd5 18. Rxd5 Nc6
{ Since the evaluation of this position is crucial for the entire line, let us go a bit deeper here to understand what options White got here. It will be sufficient to know until here for the opening purpose but I would like to continue here further to give a better understanding of the upcoming middlegame. }
19. Ng5
{ This bailout move was played in a correspondence game in 2019, and things soon fizzled out to a draw. }
19... Bxg5 20. Bxg5 Qxg5 21. Rxd7 Qxe5
{ After some natural moves Black managed to eliminate the central pawn for White and currently has an extra pawn. }
22. Qxe5 Nxe5 23. Rd5
{ White must go for the pawn on b5. Otherwise, b4-c3 would be devastating for White. Here the players agreed for a draw in a correspondence game in 2019 }
23... Rfe8 24. Rxb5 g6
{ No need to hurry in the endgame. Black keeps ideas like Rb8 and Nd3 in his hand and will create pressure on the b2 pawn. For now, just making a nice square for the king. The position remains equal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 23: Open Catalan (7.Qa4 Bd7 8.Qc4 b5 9.Qd3)"]
[Black "Open Catalan 7.Qa4 Bd7 8.Qc4 b5 9.Qd3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qd3
{ White keeps the queen on d3 this time and avoids the b4 ideas that we saw in the  9.Qc3  lines. However, this move allows the other pawn push. }
9... c4
{ The advantage of having the pawn on b5. There are two major options White has at this point. They can either play Qc2 and aim for a quick e4 or play Qd1 and keep the d4 pawn protected and play for Ne5 ideas. Let's start with the Qd1 plans. }
10. Qc2
{ This is the second most popular move after  10.Qd1  . White's idea is pretty direct after  10.Qc2  . They would like to get a quick e4 and try to break in the center after getting his rook to d1. }
10... Rc8
{ Prophylaxis against Ne5.  10...Be7  is also equally strong and playable. As usual, I would like to keep similar moves as and when possible. Since both Be7 and Rc8 are equally strong and in the case of  10.Qd1  we are playing  10...Rc8  , it makes sense to stick with the same move order in order to avoid any kind of confusion. This way we know our 10th move is Rc8 irrespective of where White moves the queen. }
11. e4
{ White stays loyal to his direct plan and controls center. White could also include 10.a4 a6 in any variation where on a positive side White activates his rook on a1 but on the other hand, he also weakens the b4 and b3 squares. The knight on c6 becomes very strong now, which cannot be touched on either of these squares. }
11... Be7 { Normal developing move and getting ready to castle. } 12. Qe2
{ White will eventually have to move the queen from c2 to play d5 and avoid Nb4 ideas.  White could also start with  12.Rd1  when Black could either transpose to the mainline with  12...O-O  13.Qe2  or take advantage of the move order and opt for  12...Nb4  13.Qe2  Nd3  . }
12... O-O 13. Rd1
{ There is no other decent way to play in the center.  13.Nc3  b4  is not appealing as the knight must move away from the center.   13.a3  Na5  would allow Black a lovely spot on b3. White's central pawn is not scary unless it starts marching forward. Black will have a free play on the queenside if White waits for long. }
13... Na5
{ To give an idea of how dangerous this position can be for White, it will suffice to say that engine thinks if it is Black to play right now, then after b4, the evaluation goes up to -2 :@@EndBracket@@ White needs to respond fast on the center. }
14. d5
{ The most logical play. White strikes in the center. This critical position was reached only once in an OTB tournament. However, in the correspondence world, there has been some discussion in this direction. After  14.e5  Nd5  Black completely takes over when White would have no play on the center, and Black will get free play on the queenside. }
14... exd5 15. e5
{ After the careless  15.exd5  , Black has multiple ways to win. According to engines  15...Bc5  is more than -3 when White lost all his domination in the center and must protect against f2 pawn while his queenside army snores and the queen on e2 remains vulnerable. }
15... Ne8
{ This counterintuitive move is the key to this line! Instead of going to the center with Ne4, Black retreats. The idea is to gain a crucial tempo by playing Nc7 after White takes on d5. }
16. Nc3 { White wants to get his knight on d5. } 16... Nc7
{ It is absolutely obligatory not to allow White to get his knight to d5. Black is now ready to trade. }
17. Nxd5
{ There are no other serious alternative. White needs to go for this. } 17...
Nxd5 18. Rxd5 Nc6
{ Since the evaluation of this position is crucial for the entire line, let us go a bit deeper here to understand what options White got here. It will be sufficient to know until here for the opening purpose but I would like to continue here further to give a better understanding of the upcoming middlegame. }
19. a4
{ Attacking the tail and going for the c4-pawn. If White plays slow with  19.a3  to stop Nb4 ideas, then Black easily unpins himself with  19...Qe8  when it is not easy for White to create any attack in the center or kingside while Black's play on the queenside is pretty straightforward. }
19... Nb4 20. Rd1 Qe8 { Unpinning and threatening to take on a4. } 21. axb5
Bxb5 { c3 is coming next. } 22. Nd4 Nd3
{ This knight is more important than the bishop on b5 right now. The knight on d3 keeps an eye on the f2 pawn, c1 bishop, e5 pawn, and in the future will target the b2 pawn as well. Black had no problem in a correspondence game from 2020, which is not surprising }
