[White "Chapter 23: Open Catalan (7.Qa4 Bd7 8.Qc4 b5 9.Qd3)"]
[Black "Open Catalan 7.Qa4 Bd7 8.Qc4 b5 9.Qd3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qd3
{ White keeps the queen on d3 this time and avoids the b4 ideas that we saw in the  9.Qc3  lines. However, this move allows the other pawn push. }
9... c4
{ The advantage of having the pawn on b5. There are two major options White has at this point. They can either play Qc2 and aim for a quick e4 or play Qd1 and keep the d4 pawn protected and play for Ne5 ideas. Let's start with the Qd1 plans. }
10. Qd1
{ Keeping the pawn on d4 protected and aiming for quick Ne5 ideas or Re1-e4 ideas. }
10... Rc8 { Not allowing Ne5 } 11. Nc3
{ This move never gained popularity, but it was tried once by Gelfand against Anand in 2013. We had it covered obviously since the Topalov match, and Anand had no trouble in this game. }
11... b4
{ This is the disadvantage of having played Nc3 early. Now the knight goes to the edge of the board. If White started with @@StartFEN@@2rqkb1r/p2b1ppp/2n1pn2/1p6/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w k - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11.a3  then  11...Na5  would have given him trouble due to the weak b3 square. }
12. Na4 Be7
{ Logical and strong. Black's pawns look very formidable on the queenside, and is now ready to castle and bring more pieces on the queenside. }
13. Bg5 h6
{ Once again very logical. Although the engine says 13...O-O is stronger, and it might be true. I would still keep h6 as the main move to make sure the line is easier to understand and does not get confused with other positions. We are meeting Bg5 with h6 almost all the time.   Why make an exception here when this also gives us a slight edge. This way we reduce the chance of mixing up when to play h6 and when to castle.   In my opinion, it is a smart way to work and as you can see, five-time world champions also follow this approach :P }
14. Bxf6 Bxf6
{ Once again, engine thinks gxf6 was minutely stronger, and I follow the same reasoning: why bother to waste energy on something that we can refute with the most logical moves? :@@EndBracket@@ }
15. a3 O-O
{ By playing the most obvious, and logical moves Black got a fine position with a pair of bishops. Moves like Nxd4 are threatened, as the knight on a4 is loose. Black had zero trouble in 1/2-1/2 Gelfand,B @@StartBracket@@2740@@EndBracket@@ -Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2780@@EndBracket@@ Zuerich 2013 }
