1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qd3
{ White keeps the queen on d3 this time and avoids the b4 ideas that we saw in the  9.Qc3  lines. However, this move allows the other pawn push. }
9... c4
{ The advantage of having the pawn on b5. There are two major options White has at this point. They can either play Qc2 and aim for a quick e4 or play Qd1 and keep the d4 pawn protected and play for Ne5 ideas. Let's start with the Qd1 plans. }
10. Qd1
{ Keeping the pawn on d4 protected and aiming for quick Ne5 ideas or Re1-e4 ideas. }
10... Rc8 { Not allowing Ne5 } 11. b3
{ Trying to break Black's pawn chain on the queenside. } 11... Be7
{ 11...Na5  has been played a few times, which also gives Black a fine position. Once again, I would like to keep the similar moves as long as it has a similar evaluation. Makes it far easier to understand. }
12. a4
{ An interesting try to break Black's queenside. This was played once by GM Ragger in 2015. }
12... Na5
{ White attacked the tail on b5 and Black returns the favor by attacking the tail on b3. }
13. bxc4
{ 13.axb5  Nxb3  14.Rxa7  Qb6  gives Black a tempi on the rook, allowing them to take on  b5  and keep the strong passed c-pawn. }
13... bxc4 14. Ne5 O-O
{ I like this simple move rather than Nd5-Nb4 ideas that happened in the game Ragger - Maze, Helsingor 2015. Once Black castles there, he is ready to start playing on the queenside with Nb3 or Nd5-Nb4 ideas. The engine already gives a slight advantage to Black, which is justified when we look at the pawn on c4 and threats like Nb3. }
