[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 23: Open Catalan (7.Qa4 Bd7 8.Qc4 b5 9.Qd3)"]
[Black "Open Catalan 7.Qa4 Bd7 8.Qc4 b5 9.Qd3 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qd3
{ White keeps the queen on d3 this time and avoids the b4 ideas that we saw in the  9.Qc3  lines. However, this move allows the other pawn push. }
9... c4
{ The advantage of having the pawn on b5. There are two major options White has at this point. They can either play Qc2 and aim for a quick e4 or play Qd1 and keep the d4 pawn protected and play for Ne5 ideas. Let's start with the Qd1 plans. }
10. Qd1
{ Keeping the pawn on d4 protected and aiming for quick Ne5 ideas or Re1-e4 ideas. }
10... Rc8 { Not allowing Ne5 } 11. Re1
{ White shows his hands very clearly. They want to play e4. } 11... Be7
{ It gets so much easier when our moves are logical and natural. We want to castle. }
12. e4 O-O
{ Not fearing d4-d5 which is the only way to fight for. As  14.e5  Nd5  leads nowhere when Black's queenside pawns are so much stronger than White's central pawns. }
13. d5
{ At first sight, it looks like Black just blundered, and he will have to give up a piece as both dxc6 and d6 are threatened. }
13... exd5 14. exd5 Nb4
{ Keeping a target on the c2 square and also attacking d5. Without this move Black would have been lost. }
15. d6
{ In the game 0-1 Ju, W @@StartBracket@@2583@@EndBracket@@-Tan, Z @@StartBracket@@2502@@EndBracket@@ Teheran 2017 from World Cup, White played  15.Ne5  and after  15...Bf5  Black was clearly winning, since there was no way to stop Nc2 and Bc5-Nd3 ideas. }
15... Bxd6 { Forcing White queen to leave the guard of c2 square. } 16. Qxd6
Nc2
{ Not only, Black gets back the material, but also keeps the queenside majority. White will now have to waste some moves to trap the knight on a1. }
17. Na3 { 17.Be3  Nxa1  18.Na3  would transpose to the mainline. } 17... Nxa1
{ This particular position has never reached in a tournament game but it has been lying within my notes from the match since 2009 :P White basically has four different moves with his bishop to attack the knight. He should be very precise not to get worse. }
18. Bg5
{ From 0.00 after a natural-looking move, the evaluation is now -3.5. I just wanted to highlight how dangerous the position is for White :@@EndBracket@@ }
18... Bg4 19. Qxd8 Rfxd8 20. Rxa1
{ Now White is clearly better, if and only if Black did not have his next move, which wins on the spot. }
20... c3
{ The double attack after the exchange on c3 is losing for White, and he also can't leave the pawn on c3, which is about to queen. Hence White is lost here. }
