[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 23: Open Catalan (7.Qa4 Bd7 8.Qc4 b5 9.Qd3)"]
[Black "Open Catalan 7.Qa4 Bd7 8.Qc4 b5 9.Qd3 #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qd3
{ White keeps the queen on d3 this time and avoids the b4 ideas that we saw in the  9.Qc3  lines. However, this move allows the other pawn push. }
9... c4
{ The advantage of having the pawn on b5. There are two major options White has at this point. They can either play Qc2 and aim for a quick e4 or play Qd1 and keep the d4 pawn protected and play for Ne5 ideas. Let's start with the Qd1 plans. }
10. Qd1
{ Keeping the pawn on d4 protected and aiming for quick Ne5 ideas or Re1-e4 ideas. }
10... Rc8 { Not allowing Ne5 } 11. Bg5 Be7
{ One can say that weren't we playing h6 every time after Bg5? Yes, we were but our bishop was always on e7 in such cases. We would like to recapture on f6 with the bishop and not expose our queen on f6. Hence we start with Be7 intending to play h6 next. }
12. Nc3
{ Black was ready for  12.Ne5  as the queen isn't pinned anymore. So he could just play  12...Nxe5  13.dxe5  Nd5  and get a comfortable game. }
12... b4 13. Bxf6 { The only way to get the knight to the center. } 13... gxf6
{ This move is significantly stronger than the normal Bxf6 so I decided to make this an exception. However, if someone forgets and plays the most natural-looking  13...Bxf6  14.Ne4  Be7  then also Black will have a comfortable position and only White should be bothered about Black's double bishop. By playing 13...gxf6 Black declares that he is not happy with equality anymore. }
14. Ne4 O-O
{ A very calm move. Black rightly understood that with the dark-squared bishop and the light-squared bishop looking on the queenside, there is no way White can create any hint of an attack on the kingside. Meanwhile, Black threatens to play f5 and kick the knight out from e4. Chinese Grandmaster Bu Xiangzhi played this twice. }
15. Rc1 { Going for the c4 pawn. } 15... Na5
{ Those pawns on the queenside are assets for Black, and there is no way Black will give up those pawns unless they get something huge in return. }
16. Qd2 { Giving a subtle threat of Nc5 to attack the pawn on b4. } 16... Bc6
{ Attacks the knight on e4 while stopping it come to c5. } 17. Qf4
{ 17.Nc5  Bxf3  18.Bxf3  Bxc5  wins a piece due to the pin on the d-file. }
17... f5
{ The knight must go back as  18.Neg5  h6  19.Nh3  Kh7  leads nowhere for White. Black keeps the bishop pair and the strong pawns on the queenside while White has nothing to claim compensation for these in return. Hence Black stands better. }
