10... Rc8 { Not allowing Ne5 } 11. Bg5 Be7
{ One can say that weren't we playing h6 every time after Bg5? Yes, we were but our bishop was always on e7 in such cases. We would like to recapture on f6 with the bishop and not expose our queen on f6. Hence we start with Be7 intending to play h6 next. }
12. Nc3
{ Black was ready for  12.Ne5  as the queen isn't pinned anymore. So he could just play  12...Nxe5  13.dxe5  Nd5  and get a comfortable game. }
12... b4 13. Bxf6 { The only way to get the knight to the center. } 13... gxf6
{ This move is significantly stronger than the normal Bxf6 so I decided to make this an exception. However, if someone forgets and plays the most natural-looking  13...Bxf6  14.Ne4  Be7  then also Black will have a comfortable position and only White should be bothered about Black's double bishop. By playing 13...gxf6 Black declares that he is not happy with equality anymore. }
