[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 24: dxc5 Endgame(9.Nfd2/Nc3)"]
[Black "dxc5 endgame: 9.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5
{ One of the most popular choices in recent times. White wants to get an endgame without risk and play for two results. As we will see throughout this course, Black will never allow such a scenario. }
7... Qxd1
{ We should not allow White to take on d8 when black will have to make the uncomfortable choice of either breaking our castle or retreating the knight from c6. Hence we take the queen first. }
8. Rxd1 Bxc5
{ For now, Black has an extra pawn. In order for White to win the pawn back, they must make some concessions. }
9. Nc3
{ The knight on c3 is not ideal, but White's argument here is that they avoided c3 for Black.   9.Bg5  makes no sense when Black can go  9...Ng4  and White won't be able to play  10.e3  due to  10...h6  when the bishop on g5 will end up trapped. }
9... Bd7
{ An important move. Black should not play in a naive way like  9...O-O  when after  10.Nd2  White will get exactly what they wanted.   By playing  9...Bd7  Black is ready to meet  10.Nd2  with  10...Na5  when White knight on c3 gets restricted by the bishop on d7. }
10. Nd2 Na5
{ Of course, we are not giving the pawn away for free. Now we see the point of 9... Bd7 that stops White's knight from jumping to the queenside. }
11. Nde4
{ Aiming for the d6 square and attacking the bishop on c5 in the process. }
11... Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Bb4
{ This is the best square. Now White cannot attack the knight on a5 with Bd2, and playing a3 doesn't make sense as it gives away the b3 square for the knight. }
13. Nd6+ Bxd6 14. Rxd6 Bc6
{ Black is in time to exchange the Catalan bishop, and also keeps the extra pawn. By the time White takes the pawn, Black will activate the rooks, and the position will remain equal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 24: dxc5 Endgame(9.Nfd2/Nc3)"]
[Black "dxc5 endgame: 9.Nc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5
{ One of the most popular choices in recent times. White wants to get an endgame without risk and play for two results. As we will see throughout this course, Black will never allow such a scenario. }
7... Qxd1
{ We should not allow White to take on d8 when black will have to make the uncomfortable choice of either breaking our castle or retreating the knight from c6. Hence we take the queen first. }
8. Rxd1 Bxc5
{ For now, Black has an extra pawn. In order for White to win the pawn back, they must make some concessions. }
9. Nc3
{ The knight on c3 is not ideal, but White's argument here is that they avoided c3 for Black.   9.Bg5  makes no sense when Black can go  9...Ng4  and White won't be able to play  10.e3  due to  10...h6  when the bishop on g5 will end up trapped. }
9... Bd7
{ An important move. Black should not play in a naive way like  9...O-O  when after  10.Nd2  White will get exactly what they wanted.   By playing  9...Bd7  Black is ready to meet  10.Nd2  with  10...Na5  when White knight on c3 gets restricted by the bishop on d7. }
10. Bf4
{ Was played by Dubov once. White is focusing on rapid development and getting all his pieces out.  10.Bg5  can be answered, with  10...h6  when White will have to give up the bishop for a knight. }
10... Rc8
{ Bringing indirect support for the c4 pawn, and now Black is ready to castle. }
11. Rac1
{ White finished his development. Now Black has an improvement over Dubov,D- Lu,S 2016 game. }
11... b6
{ The machine thinks  11...O-O  is also fine, and Black has no issues there. I agree with that, but I also like the text move. Which has a subtle point of keeping the king in the center for a while.  11...a6  was played in the above-mentioned game, which is not the ideal move in this position. }
12. Nd2 Na5
{ Our usual response for Nd2. We don't give up this pawn so easily. } 13. Nde4
{ White now aims for Black's dark square bishop. } 13... Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Ba4
{ Gaining a tempo and getting ready to castle next. } 15. Rd2 O-O
{ White has compensation but nothing more than that. } *

