[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 24: dxc5 Endgame(9.Nfd2/Nc3)"]
[Black "dxc5 endgame: 9.Nfd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5
{ One of the most popular choices in recent times. White wants to get an endgame without risk and play for two results. As we will see throughout this course, Black will never allow such a scenario. }
7... Qxd1
{ We should not allow White to take on d8 when black will have to make the uncomfortable choice of either breaking our castle or retreating the knight from c6. Hence we take the queen first. }
8. Rxd1 Bxc5
{ For now, Black has an extra pawn. In order for White to win the pawn back, they must make some concessions. }
9. Nfd2
{ This highly interesting move was first played at a GM level by Women World Champion Ju Wenjun in 2016. It soon became popular when Magnus used this move to beat Harikrishna in World Rapid 2017. White wants to take the pawn on c4 with the f3 knight so that the bishop on g2 remains open. }
9... Nd4
{ 9...Na5  is almost exclusively played, and this move is very rare.  Out of about 50 games, 46 times  9...Na5  was played while only  9...Nd4  was only played 4 times. I think it's just a matter of time before this move will get more popular.  It's much more dynamic and fun to play from the Black side. Black attacks e2 and also threatens to play Nc2, practically forcing White's next move. }
10. Nc3 Nd5
{ The big point. Once again targetting the pawn on e2 by attacking the knight on c3. This position reached only twice in tournaments so far. }
11. Kf1
{ This move could be an instinct to protect the e2 pawn, but it has a huge drawback. It comes under a fork on e3. }
11... Nc2 { The threat of Nxa1 and Ne3+ forces White's next move. } 12. Nde4
{ Stops Ne3 ideas and attacks on c5. } 12... Nxa1 13. Nxd5
{ 13.Nxc5  was also possible, but eventually, White will have to take on d5, and then we will transpose. }
13... exd5 14. Nxc5 Nc2
{ The knight is coming out, and Black remains an exchange up. White keeps some compensation, but still, Black's position is preferable. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 24: dxc5 Endgame(9.Nfd2/Nc3)"]
[Black "dxc5 endgame: 9.Nfd2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5
{ One of the most popular choices in recent times. White wants to get an endgame without risk and play for two results. As we will see throughout this course, Black will never allow such a scenario. }
7... Qxd1
{ We should not allow White to take on d8 when black will have to make the uncomfortable choice of either breaking our castle or retreating the knight from c6. Hence we take the queen first. }
8. Rxd1 Bxc5
{ For now, Black has an extra pawn. In order for White to win the pawn back, they must make some concessions. }
9. Nfd2
{ This highly interesting move was first played at a GM level by Women World Champion Ju Wenjun in 2016. It soon became popular when Magnus used this move to beat Harikrishna in World Rapid 2017. White wants to take the pawn on c4 with the f3 knight so that the bishop on g2 remains open. }
9... Nd4
{ 9...Na5  is almost exclusively played, and this move is very rare.  Out of about 50 games, 46 times  9...Na5  was played while only  9...Nd4  was only played 4 times. I think it's just a matter of time before this move will get more popular.  It's much more dynamic and fun to play from the Black side. Black attacks e2 and also threatens to play Nc2, practically forcing White's next move. }
10. Nc3 Nd5
{ The big point. Once again targetting the pawn on e2 by attacking the knight on c3. This position reached only twice in tournaments so far. }
11. Bxd5
{ Not only Black can transpose to the mainline, but also this gives Black an extra option which might be better than transposing. }
11... exd5 12. Nxd5
{ After  12.e3  Nc2  13.Rb1  Bg4  Black wins on the spot as White has no match for Black's double bishop and piece activity. }
12... Bg4
{ I like this more than transposing with  12...O-O  when after  13.Ne4  Rd8  14.Nxc5  Rxd5  , we will get back to the mainline. }
13. Nc7+
{ There is no other way for White. He has already burned the bridges. He must go for the a8 rook now. }
13... Kd7 14. Nxa8 Nxe2+
{ It's a funny position where Black will move his knight on different squares based on where White puts his king. }
15. Kf1
{ This could be a nice tactic training. Where should Black move the knight? Does  15...Nxg3  still win, as mentioned for 14.Kh1 variation? }
15... Nd4
{ 15...Nxg3  would have been a huge blunder. The difference is seen in the following variation:  16.hxg3  Bxd1  17.Nc7!  Kxc7  18.Ne4  when the double threat of Bf4-Rd1 and Nxc5 would be winning for White since there is no way to defend the piece. The difference between king on h1 and king on f1 is Black does not have Bf3+ at the end of the above-mentioned variation. }
16. f3
{ 16.Re1  Rxa8  is completely winning for Black when white's rooks are dead and likely to come under a fork soon. }
16... Bh3+
{ This is the reason why this line only works with the king on f1 and not on h1. Black would not gain a tempo with this check. }
17. Ke1 Nc2+
{ Black now has a minimum draw with Nd4-Nc2 perpetual, and also there are ways to keep the game going with Re8 and keep compensation. }
