17. Nf3
{ White is a pawn up and just one move away to complete his development and claim a winning advantage. }
17... Bxf3+
{ Why on Earth should Black give up his bishop and also bring White's king forward when we are entering an endgame? The idea is very specific, as can be seen in the next move. }
18. exf3
{ After  18.Kxf3  too, Black would have played similarly, and White would be forced to give up an exchange. The line could continue with  18...Ne1  19.Rxe1  Bxe1  20.Bg5  Rd4  when White keeps compensation, but Black has nothing to worry about. }
18... Ne1+ 19. Kh1 Nxf3
{ The material is equal, and Black is threatening to get Nd2/Rac8 moves. The position remains completely equal and is likely to end in a draw. }
