[White "Chapter 25: dxc5 Endgame (9.Nbd2 -11.Bb2/Ne1)"]
[Black "dxc5 endgame: 9.Nbd2 - 11.Bb2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8.
Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 c3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Bb2
{ This is another critical line. The move  11.c4  does not have any independent value as  11...Bd7  12.Nb3  transposes to the mainline that is covered extensively in a different chapter.   12.Bb2  Be7  transposes to the line that we will be seeing now. }
11... Bd7
{ Natural and suits our repertoire. Black is finishing development, keeping in mind that White has some strategic weaknesses. }
12. Ne1
{ Not committing c4 immediately and getting the knight to d3 to attack the bishop on c5 first. }
12... Be7 { Keeping the flexibility of the rooks. } 13. Nd3
{ This position is so harmless that it gets difficult to suggest just one line : -@@EndBracket@@ The engine thinks any normal way to develop the rooks is fine. Usually, there are two ways to do it: Rfd8-Rac8 or Rfc8. Black can pick whatever he wants as per his taste. The only game that reached this position went with Rfd8 and we can stick to that. }
13... Rfd8 14. c4 Be8
{ Nothing would have changed in terms of evaluation if Black played  14...Rac8  or  14...b6  . The position remains absolutely fine for Black. He has no weakness and is about to bring his last piece into the game. The only game that reached this position ended in a draw in another 3 moves when White realized he has absolutely no target to play against. ½-½ Sunilduth Lyna, N @@StartBracket@@2624@@EndBracket@@ -Sadhwani, R @@StartBracket@@2555@@EndBracket@@ Biel 2021 }
