[White "Chapter 25: dxc5 Endgame (9.Nbd2 -11.Bb2/Ne1)"]
[Black "dxc5 endgame: 9.Nbd2 - 11.Ne1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8.
Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 c3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Ne1
{ The second most popular move after  11.Nb3  . White wants to get the knight to  d3  with a tempo. }
11... Rd8
{ Makes perfect sense to take over the d-file when White clearly doesn't want to fight for that.  11...Bd7  12.Rb1  is annoying because Black is unable to play  12...b6  as  13.Nb3  wins material. }
12. Nd3 Be7 13. Ne4
{ Trading pieces should benefit Black generally, but there are some specific details here. }
13... Nxe4 14. Bxe4 f5
{ An important inclusion. White must go back to g2 or h1 as  15.Bf3  runs into  15...e5  . }
15. Bg2 Bd7
{ Black now consolidate his position. What was the point of including f5-Bg2? We can see that in the following combination... }
16. Rb1 b6
{ With the inclusion of f5-Bg2, White is unable to play  17.Nb4  Rac8  18.Rxd7  as after  18...Rxd7  19.Nxc6  Black gets  19...Rd1  when White is missing Kg2. This is the reason why we needed White's bishop on g2 or h1 and not on e4. }
17. Ne5 Nxe5 { Black is fine in the upcoming combination. } 18. Bxa8 Rxa8 19.
Bf4 Ba4
{ After  20.Bxe5  Bxd1  21.Rxd1  Rd8  White ends up with a worse pawn structure and Black has nothing to worry about. }
