[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8.
Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 c3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Nb3 Be7
{ Many moves have been tried, at this point, over a period of time. So far mainly  12.c4  and  12.Nfd4  gained popularity. We will see all other lines apart from these two moves here. }
12. Bb2 { Keeping both ideas of c4 and Nfd4 open. } 12... Bd7
{ Black's plan remains very standard. Keep developing. } 13. Nfd4
{ Mixing up plans. If White wanted to play Nfd4, it was more critical to do it without Bb2.  13.c4  is covered in the 12.c4 move order, which is in a different file. }
13... Rfc8
{ The inclusion of Bb2 - Bd7 gives Black an important tempo, and they can bring the other rook to c8 while White is not on time to create enough threats with Nb5-Nd6 ideas. }
14. Nb5 Nd8
{ Thanks to the inclusion of Bb2, Black got an extra tempo and is on time to get Bc6. Once Bc6 happens, the good bishop on g2 will be gone, and White can't create any pressure on the queenside. }
15. Nd6 Bxd6 16. Rxd6 Bc6
{ Once the bishop is gone, there is no pressure on the queenside from White, and Black will slowly start to create a play on the queenside where they have a better structure. Playing  17.f3  doesn't make sense as it blocks the bishop on g2. Black can continue with  17...Nd5  and then aim for the c4 square via e3 or b6. }
