{ Once again aimed against b6 plans. This move was played only once, as of today @@StartBracket@@4 December 2021@@EndBracket@@. It was played by Anish against Levon in 2021. So we can be assured that soon it could become very popular. }
13... Rac8
{ In the game,  13...Rad8  was played, which I didn't like much. It feels natural to develop with Rac8-Rfd8, and of course, we refrain from playing b6 once White has shown his hands clearly by playing a4. }
14. Be3
{ Makes sense to keep the bishop on e3, aiming at Black's queenside pawns.  14.a5  Rfd8  15.Be3  transposes to the line we will be seeing now. }
14... Rfd8
{ Continuing with similar plan of finishing development peacefully. } 15. a5 e5
{ Black takes the advantage of White's bishop placement. This time White did not bother to stop e5 and Black grabs the chance to activate his light square bishop. }
16. Nfd2 { going for the pawn on a7. } 16... Be6
{ I like this active plan. Black invites White to take his a7 pawn, but on condition that he must give away his light square bishop. }
17. Bxc6 Rxc6 18. Bxa7 h5
{ In Alpha Zero style! White gets tied down to defend his pawns, and Black enjoys his double bishop advantage. He is not in rush at all and shows that he can play slowly, and his compensation is long and strategic. }
19. Bb6 Ra8
{ It would be very difficult for White to untangle his position. None of the pieces are having a good square to occupy. The bishop on b6 will be chased away with Nd7. Playing c5 doesn't improve the bishop's position on b6. The knights are unable to jump, and this is a big issue for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 27: dxc5 Endgame (9.Nbd2-11.Nb3 Be7 12.c4)"]
[Black "dxc5 endgame 9.Nbd2 -11.Nb3 Be7 12.c4 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8.
Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 c3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Nb3 Be7 12. c4
{ This is the second most popular move after  12.Nfd4  . White keeps their plans flexible. They can now develop the bishop on e3/f4/b2 or play a4-a5 or go for c5. Primarily, for now, they stopped Black from getting Nd5 ideas. }
12... Bd7
{ Black also has various plans at their disposal. Depending on how White develops Black will decide on their plans. Black's plans are as follows: Rac8-Rfd8-Be8 ideas, Rfc8-Be8-Nd8 ideas, playing b6 and restricting the knight on b3, playing e5, and taking the d4 square from White's knights.  Let us understand the position clearly. White's pieces have more free space, but Black has a better pawn structure. So, White's nature of advantage is dynamic while Black's advantage is static. That means if Black can finish the development and White doesn't take any action, then Black might even take over. }
13. Bb2
{ By far the most popular move. White stops e5 and gets ready to play c5 after Rac8. The seeming threat of Bxf6 and taking on d7 is not a threat as we will see in the next move. }
13... Rfc8
{ This move is very rare. More than 200 games reached this position, and this move was played only about 10 times so far.   However, it is gaining rapid popularity, and in the World Rapid and Blitz, every time this position was reached, Black opted for this move. Now that White committed to Bb2 and stopped the e5 plan, Black gets the forces to the queenside and goes for Be8 plans.   This is not a blunder. Black invites White to take on f6 and take on d7.   After  13...Rac8  White plays  14.c5  and gets a better version of a4 lines when they didn't have to play a4-a5 to stop Black from playing b6.   The traditional mainline is to play  13...Rfd8  when the line goes with  14.Nfd4  Rac8  15.Nb5  and White get a double bishop advantage by playing Nd6. Those positions are also playable, but I like this rare concrete approach, and I feel soon this will become the mainline instead of the traditional Rfd8. }
14. Bxf6
{ Obviously, this is the first move that we must consider. After all, Black's last move was some sort of sacrifice. Hikaru chose this move against Pragg in an online rapid tournament in 2021. }
14... Bxf6 15. Rxd7
{ There is no way back. White gave the bishop so they must go ahead and take the piece. }
15... Bxa1 16. Nxa1 Rd8
{ Without this resource this entire line would not work. Black exchanges White's active rook.   White has various ways to choose how they want to exchange, but he can't escape the trade. }
17. Rxd8+ Rxd8
{ Once a pair of rooks is gone, White cannot match Black's active rook. The pawns on the queenside become a target. }
18. Nb3 Rd1+ 19. Bf1 Rb1
{ White has to be precise now to maintain the balance. Rb2 will win the a-pawn next. }
20. Nfd2 Rb2
{ According to the engine White holds with precise play, but it is clear that with a passed a-pawn it is White who should be careful not to lose this position. The obvious a3/a4 gets into huge trouble after Black plays Nd4, trade a pair of knights, and then picks up the a-pawn and pushes their own a-pawn forward. }
*

