{ Moving away from Bxf6-Rxd7 ideas just in case and ready to charge with a5-a4 next. This position reached only twice in tournament games, and in both games, White opted for  15.Nfd2  . }
15. Rac1
{ This normal developing move gives Black time to expand on the queenside. }
15... a5
{ A lovely way to fix White's a-pawn and create more space for the rook on a8. }
16. Nfd2
{ After  16.a3  a4  17.Nbd2  Na5  White loses the c5-pawn.   Playing  16.a4  is also not attractive when the pawn on a4 will always be under target with Black's bishop on e8. }
16... a4 17. Nd4 a3
{ Both of White's queenside pawns have become a target, and it is not easy for White to play when they don't have any clear targets. }
