{ Consistent with the previous move. White aims to get the knight to d6.   After  15.Ne5  or  15.Nfd4  Black would gladly trade the knights and then exchange the light-squared bishop with  Bc6  , leaving White with weak kingside pawns. }
15... b6
{ Just on time. The evaluation of this variation is important for our 13...Rfc8 line. }
16. cxb6
{ Once again, the most critical line. White will get Nc4 with a tempo. After  16.Rac1  Nd5  Black is already slightly better since the pawn on a2 becomes a clear target, and White will not be able to take cxb6-axb6 for this reason. }
16... axb6
{ White must do something immediately. Otherwise, Black will play b5 and stop White from playing Nc4. }
17. Nc4
{ White makes sure either they pick up the pawn or get the knight to d6. }
17... Rab8 18. Nd6
{ White will get one of the bishops, and Black can decide which one to keep. }
18... Bxd6
{ The nature of the position is changing. White will get the static advantage of the bishop pair with no weaknesses. In return, Black gets the dynamic advantage by activating their rooks. So now time and speed are critical for Black. }
