16... axb6
{ White must do something immediately. Otherwise, Black will play b5 and stop White from playing Nc4. }
17. Nc4
{ White makes sure either they pick up the pawn or get the knight to d6. }
17... Rab8 18. Nd6
{ White will get one of the bishops, and Black can decide which one to keep. }
18... Bxd6
{ The nature of the position is changing. White will get the static advantage of the bishop pair with no weaknesses. In return, Black gets the dynamic advantage by activating their rooks. So now time and speed are critical for Black. }
19. Rxd6 Na5
{ By threatening Rc2/Nc4, Black practically forces White to take on a5. It is also possible to play  19...Nd5  and after  20.Bxd5  exd5  21.Rxd5  f6  I don't think Black is ever going to lose the position, but there is no need for us to get there. There is a much better option. }
20. Nxa5 bxa5
{ Thanks to the active rooks, Black gets enough compensation for the bishop pair. }
21. Be5
{ White activates the bishop and plans to play Ra6 next. After  21.Rd2  Nd5  Black gets full compensation for White's bishop pair due to the active pieces. }
21... Rb4
{ Planning Ne4 ideas and keeping Ra4 options open. The pawn on a2 is an easier target than the pawn on a5. }
22. Rad1
{ 22.Ra6  a4  doesn't scare Black when the a4 pawn gets complete immunity. White now threatens Rd8, which would be fatal if Black doesn't take action. }
22... h6
{ Simple and effective. Black removes Rd8 threats by creating space for the king. }
23. Rd8 { White goes for the bishop on e8. } 23... Rxd8 24. Rxd8 Rb1+
{ Forcing White to play Bf1 before taking a measure with the pin on the back rank. }
25. Bf1 Kh7
{ This is the saving trick for Black. Now everything fizzles out. Black wants Bb5 next. }
26. Bxf6 Bb5 { Double attack on f6 and e2. } 27. Rb8 gxf6 28. a4
{ White's last trick is based on the pin. } 28... Bd3
{ Black unpins themselves and has no problems. } *

