[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 28: dxc5 Endgame (9.Nbd2-11.Nb3 Be7 12.Nfd4)"]
[Black "dxc5 endgame 9.Nbd2-11.Nb3 Be7 12.Nfd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8.
Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 c3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Nb3 Be7 12. Nfd4
{ One of the traditional lines in the dxc5 endgame. White builds pressure on Black's knight on c6 and opens up the bishop on g2. Giving Black two major options to choose from. }
12... Nxd4
{ This seems more straightforward than  13...Bd7  , which is the other main alternative at this point. Fabiano played this in the 2021 World Cup, and the lines seem much simpler as compared to  13...Bd7  lines. We repair White's pawn structure but get a queenside majority and neutralize White's pressure on the d- file. }
13. cxd4
{ The only sensible way to fight for an advantage. After  13.Nxd4  Rd8  , it is hard to create any pressure for White. Black is threatening to play ...e5 and  14.Bf4  is met with  14...Nd5  . }
13... Nd5
{ This is important. We need to make sure the g2 bishop doesn't get an open diagonal for free. }
14. e4
{ Here White clearly says that they don't care about Nc3 tempo and rather invites Black to get there. This move was played by Svidler once. }
14... Nc3
{ Obviously, there is no other way around. We accept the challenge and enter the enemy camp. }
15. Rd3
{ If White doesn't attack the knight immediately, then Black will have time to stabilize it with Bd7-Rc8 ideas. }
15... Ne2+ 16. Kh1
{ Unfortunate, but no choice.  16.Kf1  would allow  16...Nxc1  17.Rxc1  b6  when Black's threat of Ba6 pin becomes annoying for White and Black gets the advantage. }
16... b6
{ Getting ready for  Ba6  and also restricting the knight on b3. It was possible to play  16...Nxc1  where Black gets equality. If we are looking for simplicity then that is a very decent choice. After,  17.Rxc1  Rd8  White keeps some space advantage, but Black's pair of bishops and queenside majority compensates that }
17. Bd2
{ Like  14.Bb2  , this move also threatens to go for the e2-knight. Here White breaks the connection for Black to support the knight on e2 with Rc2 in the future. }
17... Ba6 18. Re3 Bc4
{ Now we see the disadvantage of keeping the bishop on d2. Black targets the pawn on d4. }
19. e5 Rac8
{ The machine also suggests the highly interesting  19...a5  that sacrifices an exchange and gives Black good compensation. Here White can't trap the knight on e2 as Black will always have the exit route by playing Bxb3 and Nxd4. The position remains dynamically balanced. }
*

