16... b6
{ Getting ready for  Ba6  and also restricting the knight on b3. It was possible to play  16...Nxc1  where Black gets equality. If we are looking for simplicity then that is a very decent choice. After,  17.Rxc1  Rd8  White keeps some space advantage, but Black's pair of bishops and queenside majority compensates that }
17. Bb2
{ It feels like the knight on e2 will be trapped, but that's not the case here. The knight on e2 is doing an important job, by controlling c1 square, it makes sure the battle of the c-file will be won by Black. }
17... Ba6 18. Re3 Rac8 { White is not able to stop Rc2 idea. } 19. Rb1 Rc2 20.
Na1 { At this point, Svidler rightly decided to repeat the moves. } 20... Rd2
21. Nb3 Rc2
{ 1/2-1/2 Svidler, P @@StartBracket@@2729@@EndBracket@@ -Wojtaszek,R @@StartBracket@@2737@@EndBracket@@ Sochi 2015 }
