[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 28: dxc5 Endgame (9.Nbd2-11.Nb3 Be7 12.Nfd4)"]
[Black "dxc5 endgame 9.Nbd2-11.Nb3 Be7 12.Nfd4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8.
Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 c3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Nb3 Be7 12. Nfd4
{ One of the traditional lines in the dxc5 endgame. White builds pressure on Black's knight on c6 and opens up the bishop on g2. Giving Black two major options to choose from. }
12... Nxd4
{ This seems more straightforward than  13...Bd7  , which is the other main alternative at this point. Fabiano played this in the 2021 World Cup, and the lines seem much simpler as compared to  13...Bd7  lines. We repair White's pawn structure but get a queenside majority and neutralize White's pressure on the d- file. }
13. cxd4
{ The only sensible way to fight for an advantage. After  13.Nxd4  Rd8  , it is hard to create any pressure for White. Black is threatening to play ...e5 and  14.Bf4  is met with  14...Nd5  . }
13... Nd5
{ This is important. We need to make sure the g2 bishop doesn't get an open diagonal for free. }
14. Bb2
{ 14.a4  b6  15.Bb2  f5  transposes to 14.Bb2 line that we will be seeing now. 14.a4 was the actual move order for Jumabaev - Caruana,  World Cup 2021 }
14... f5
{ The whole point of this line. Block the bishop on g2: for that, we need to stabilize the knight on d5. Hence we stop White from playing e4. Next, we want to restrict the knight on b3 by going b6. No need to do anything against the bishop on b2 as it is self restricted :@@EndBracket@@ }
15. Rac1 b6
{ Now restrict the knight. Right now all of White's minor pieces are restricted. }
16. Nd2
{ Trying to reroute the knight to a better square. This is better than  16.e4  fxe4  17.Bxe4  that occurred in a tournament game when Black could play  17...Bd7  , and claim an advantage with a queenside majority and a strong knight on d5. }
16... Bd7 17. Nc4 Rfc8
{ White can plant the knight on e5, but after Be8 there is no concrete plan for him. Sooner or later, Black will push the queenside pawns. White's bishops remain restricted, and Black gets enough counterplay. }
*

