[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8.
Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 c3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Nb3 Be7 12. Nfd4
{ One of the traditional lines in the dxc5 endgame. White builds pressure on Black's knight on c6 and opens up the bishop on g2. Giving Black two major options to choose from. }
12... Nxd4
{ This seems more straightforward than  13...Bd7  , which is the other main alternative at this point. Fabiano played this in the 2021 World Cup, and the lines seem much simpler as compared to  13...Bd7  lines. We repair White's pawn structure but get a queenside majority and neutralize White's pressure on the d- file. }
13. cxd4
{ The only sensible way to fight for an advantage. After  13.Nxd4  Rd8  , it is hard to create any pressure for White. Black is threatening to play ...e5 and  14.Bf4  is met with  14...Nd5  . }
13... Nd5
{ This is important. We need to make sure the g2 bishop doesn't get an open diagonal for free. }
14. Na5 { With the idea to play Nc6 after b6. } 14... Bb4
{ Wesley tried the very interesting pawn sacrifice with  14...Bd7  , but I wasn't comfortable with Black's position after  15.Nxb7  Ba4  16.Rd3! }
15. Bd2 Nc3 { Now the game becomes forcing for a while. } 16. Nxb7 Nxe2+
{ Black could not take on d1 due to Bxb4. } 17. Kf1 Nc3
{ White can move the knight anywhere, Black will just go Rb8. } 18. Bxc3 Bxc3
19. Rac1 Bxb7
{ Getting into an opposite color bishop endgame with rooks and a dead drawn position. }
20. Bxb7 Rab8
{ White can keep the bishop or trade it, but either way, it is a dead draw and the game ended right here in 1/ 2-1/2 Rapport,R @@StartBracket@@2726@@EndBracket@@-Yu,Y @@StartBracket@@2751@@EndBracket@@ Shenzhen 2019 }
