{ The only sensible way to fight for an advantage. After  13.Nxd4  Rd8  , it is hard to create any pressure for White. Black is threatening to play ...e5 and  14.Bf4  is met with  14...Nd5  . }
13... Nd5
{ This is important. We need to make sure the g2 bishop doesn't get an open diagonal for free. }
14. Bd2
{ The main move. White restricts the knight on d5 and gets ready to play e4 next. }
14... f5
{ Once again similar concept. Block the bishop on g2 by maintaining the knight on d5. }
15. Na5
{ The critical move.  Black already restricted White's bishop on g2, given a chance they would also restrict the knight on b3 with b6.   After  15.Nc5  b6  16.Nd3  Ba6!  Black is in time to get the bishop out and restrict the knight again by keeping an eye on the e2 pawn.   15.f3  does not scare Black as they can ignore the threat of e4 when they can simply play Nf6 and the bishop on g2 will still remain shut. Thus they can play  15...b6  and continue the plan to restrict the knight on b3. }
15... b6
{ The move order is important here. We want to play both b6 and Bf6, but we must carefully choose the right move order.   If we start with  15...Bf6  , then after  16.e3  b6  White has  17.Nc4  retreat when Black's Ba6 ideas are not dangerous since it won't attack the pawn on e2. }
16. Nc6 { 16.Nc4  Ba6  would put the pawn on e2 under pressure. } 16... Bf6 17.
Rac1 { Stabilizing the knight on c6. } 17... Bb7
{ Timing is important. Black should not give White any time to consolidate. We should constantly harass the knight on c6. }
18. Rc2 Rfc8 { Following the same method of going for the knight on c6. } 19.
Rdc1 Kf7
{ Bringing another piece to join the feast of attacking the knight on c6. } 20.
e3 Ke8
