[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 28: dxc5 Endgame (9.Nbd2-11.Nb3 Be7 12.Nfd4)"]
[Black "dxc5 endgame 9.Nbd2-11.Nb3 Be7 12.Nfd4 #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8.
Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 c3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Nb3 Be7 12. Nfd4
{ One of the traditional lines in the dxc5 endgame. White builds pressure on Black's knight on c6 and opens up the bishop on g2. Giving Black two major options to choose from. }
12... Nxd4
{ This seems more straightforward than  13...Bd7  , which is the other main alternative at this point. Fabiano played this in the 2021 World Cup, and the lines seem much simpler as compared to  13...Bd7  lines. We repair White's pawn structure but get a queenside majority and neutralize White's pressure on the d- file. }
13. cxd4
{ The only sensible way to fight for an advantage. After  13.Nxd4  Rd8  , it is hard to create any pressure for White. Black is threatening to play ...e5 and  14.Bf4  is met with  14...Nd5  . }
13... Nd5
{ This is important. We need to make sure the g2 bishop doesn't get an open diagonal for free. }
14. Bd2
{ The main move. White restricts the knight on d5 and gets ready to play e4 next. }
14... f5
{ Once again similar concept. Block the bishop on g2 by maintaining the knight on d5. }
15. Na5
{ The critical move.  Black already restricted White's bishop on g2, given a chance they would also restrict the knight on b3 with b6.   After  15.Nc5  b6  16.Nd3  Ba6!  Black is in time to get the bishop out and restrict the knight again by keeping an eye on the e2 pawn.   15.f3  does not scare Black as they can ignore the threat of e4 when they can simply play Nf6 and the bishop on g2 will still remain shut. Thus they can play  15...b6  and continue the plan to restrict the knight on b3. }
15... b6
{ The move order is important here. We want to play both b6 and Bf6, but we must carefully choose the right move order.   If we start with  15...Bf6  , then after  16.e3  b6  White has  17.Nc4  retreat when Black's Ba6 ideas are not dangerous since it won't attack the pawn on e2. }
16. Nc6 { 16.Nc4  Ba6  would put the pawn on e2 under pressure. } 16... Bf6 17.
e3
{ To make sure the knight can move once it is attacked. Srinath's Chessable course for White ends here with the following comment:   'At the outset White's advantage doesn't look great as the Knight on  c6  doesn't look stable. Indeed, it is only a small advantage. However, it is still an advantage.  17...Bb7  18.Nb4  Rfd8  19.a4  is a natural continuation after which White would likely continue with a5. The Knights and the light square Bishops are likely to be traded, leaving a position where White has these five connected pawns vs Black, whose e6 pawn and the a7 pawn will be on the weaker side. This gives White a slight edge and that typical two-results position. If White doesn't want to exchange too much and keep the position more alive, then Nd3 is also an option'.  However, we shall see Black has nothing to worry about in the upcoming position and can look forward to having a nice game. }
17... Bb7
{ Black, as usual, is not giving White any time to consolidate the position. }
18. Nb4 Rfc8
{ The most natural-looking move. Black keeps the other rook on a8, where it is better placed to push the queenside pawns. }
19. a4
{ According to Srinath, this position is better for White, but I strongly disagree with this assessment. Let's see how the game can develop. }
19... Rab8
{ An important move. White would love to take on d5 once Black plays a5. Black would rather wait for White to move the knight from b4 and only then think about fixing the a4 pawn by going a5. Black gives a positional threat of taking the knight on b4 and exchanging the light-squared bishop. We want to exchange all of the active pieces for White and leave them with the bad dark-squared bishop. }
20. Nd3 a5
{ Once White can't take on d5, we can happily fix the target on a4. With the bishop on d2 being half-dead and another bishop on g2 getting totally restricted with our knight on d5, White should be careful not to get worse. }
