22... Rb7
{ It was also possible to play  22...bxa5  23.Bxa5  a6  , but I like the text move more. Black's play is quite simple here. Keep the king on f7, play h5-g6, keep all the pawns on the White square and see how exactly White is playing. If I have to pick a color in this position, I would pick Black.  I agree with Leela's evaluation of 0.00. This is what Stockfish also gets after some deep search, but in a practical game, I would rather be Black here. }
23. Rac1
{ Any other generic moves, like  23.h4  , can be answered with  23...h5  .   And in the case of  23.Be1  we are ready with  23...Kf7  . White has no targets at this stage, and common sense tells us that Black cannot possibly be worse here. }
23... Rxc1 24. Rxc1 bxa5 25. Bxa5 Kf7
{ Black has a better bishop and an outside passed pawn. We can be happy with this endgame. }
