1. d4 Nf6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 { 3.Nf3  c5  4.Bg2  transposes to the mainline. }
3... c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. O-O h6 6. Bf4 e6 7. Nxd4 g5 8. Be5 Nbd7 9. Bxf6 Nxf6 10.
c4 dxc4
{ Black is happy to release the tension on the center and open up the game. After all, he has double bishops. }
11. Qa4+ Bd7 12. Qxc4 Qb6
{ It is obvious that White cannot create an attack on the center, and Black will play Bg7 - 0-0 shortly. More importantly White will also have to deal with Rc8 ideas that gain a tempo against White's queen. This position occurred in a few correspondence games, and Black never lost a single one and won one game. That also underlines the solidity of Black's position. }
