1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Bg5 dxc4 5. e4 c5 6. Nc3 cxd4 7. Qxd4 Qxd4 8.
Nxd4 a6 9. Bxc4 h6
{ An important improvement over the Dubov - Radjabov game that was played in 2021 Opera Euro Rapid. Radjabov played  9...Nbd7  , which allowed White to consolidate with  10.f3  . It is very important to start chasing White's pieces immediately. }
10. Bd2
{ The bishop lacks a good square.  10.Be3  Ng4  Black gets another tempo, and after White moves the bishop again, Black could go Bc5 when White will have problems with the d4-knight and f2-pawn. }
10... Bc5
{ Another developing move with a tempo. Once again,  11.Be3  is met with  11...Ng4  . }
11. Nb3 Ba7
{ The knight got into a bad square at b3 while Black took control over the important diagonal. White can't play aggressive moves like  12.O-O-O  as after  12...Ng4  , there will be no good way to stop Nf2. }
12. f3 { A sensible move to protect the e4 pawn. } 12... Nc6
{ Black keeps the option of playing Bd7-Rc8 and b5-e5-Be6 open.   Both of these plans are very solid and give Black a fine position. There is no way White can counter both of them.  The reason this line has not gained enough popularity might be because after move 9, at first glance, Black looked hugely under-developed. Only with further analysis and understanding do we see that although White is ahead in development, their pieces are wrongly developed. Soon Black takes advantage of White's strategically wrongly placed pieces by attacking them and getting our pieces developed on the right squares, in the right direction. }
