[White "Training Positions"]
[Black "Position #35"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. g3 cxd4
{ Black now takes control of the center. Both:  6.Nxd4  e5  and  6.Qxd4  Nc6  come with a tempo for Black. }
6. Nxd4
{ 6.Qxd4  Nc6  Black will first kick back the queen, and then he will get complete domination in the center by playing d4-e5. }
6... e5 { Gaining control in the center with tempo. } 7. Nf3 d4
{ Without this move, Black could even be worse as he won't be able to maintain the hold in the center. We will not miss a chance of gaining a free tempo in the center. }
8. Nb5
{ 8.Nxe5  Qd6  loses a piece due to the double attack on c3 and e5. White doesn't save it after  9.Qa4  Nbd7  10.Nxd7  Bxd7  11.Nb5  since  Qc6  attacks the rook on h1 and a6 comes next to pick up the knight on  b5  .  10.Nb5  Qb4  also loses the knight on e5 after the queen trade. White could take the rook on a8, but the knight gets trapped there, and Black wins material. }
8... Nc6
{ Stockfish evaluation of -3 might seem like an exaggeration on move 9, but how will White deal with a6-e4 threats? The engine thinks it is best to give up the piece at this point. Dubov had no problem winning the game in 0-1 Onischuk,A @@StartBracket@@2662@@EndBracket@@ -Dubov,D @@StartBracket@@2661@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2015. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Training Positions"]
[Black "Position #36"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. dxc5 Bxc5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bg5 d4
{ Of course, we will not allow that to happen and charge in the center immediately. }
8. Bxf6
{ 8.Ne4  Nxe4  9.Bxd8  Bb4  wins the game. This pattern has been known for centuries, not just in this line but in multiple openings. It is one of the basic traps that one should be aware of. }
8... Qxf6 9. Nd5
{ 9.Ne4  Bb4  10.Nfd2  Qe7  gives Black a fantastic position with a bishop pair and a development advantage. }
9... Qd8
{ White is now obliged to break their pawn structure by allowing  10.e4  dxe3  , and Black gets a clearly better position. }
