[Black "Position #37"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. dxc5 Bxc5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. e3 Nc6 8.
a3 O-O 9. b4 d4
{ This brilliant move was missed in the game mentioned above. Black opens up the center and goes for White's king. }
10. Nb5
{ The only move that saves White's game, and it is not the most obvious one. The natural  10.bxc5  loses to  10...dxc3  when the bishop on c1 gets buried. }
10... Bb6 { Maintaining the support of the pawn on d4. } 11. Nbxd4 Nxd4 12.
Nxd4
{ White is naturally not ready to open the e-file and uses the knight on d4 as a shield. }
12... Bg4 { Attacking the queen to remove the support system on d4. } 13. Be2
{ After  13.Qd3  Re8  or  13.Qd2  Ne4  White gets into a lost position when they cannot castle soon. }
13... Bxe2 14. Nxe2
{ A safer choice would have been  14.Qxe2  and after  14...Bxd4  Black gets back the pawn with activity, but the position remains equal. }
14... Qxd1+ 15. Kxd1
{ The queens are off, but White's king still remains exposed. } 15... Rfd8+ 16.
Ke1 Rac8
{ Engines hold this position with utmost precision, but it would be challenging for White to deal with such counterplay in a practical game, especially when they lost the ability to castle. }
