[White "Training Positions"]
[Black "Position #42"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bg5 cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 7. Ndb5 a6
{ It is important to get rid of the knight on b5 first before kicking out the knight on c3. After  7...d4  8.Bxf6  White's knight from c3 would have jumped to d5. Black has also set a remarkable trap for White in the case of  8.Nd5  . }
8. Qa4
{ Everything else at this point would be -2 in Black's favor. This is the only way to stop Black from playing d4.  8.Nxd5  might look very tempting with the idea of  8...axb5  9.Nxf6  gxf6  10.Qxd8  Kxd8  11.Bxf6  and White wins. However, the absolutely stunning  9...Qxf6!!  wins the game after  10.Bxf6  Bb4  and Black first picks up the queen, then the bishop on f6 and remains one piece up. }
8... Bd7 { Threatening to play d4 again. } 9. cxd5
{ 9.e4  was played a few times, but it loses after  9...Nc6!  10.Nxd5  axb5  11.Qxa8  Bb4  12.Kd1  Qxa8  and Black is ready to meet Nc7 with Ke7, and we get a material advantage with a winning position. }
9... Qb6 { Threatening to take the piece. } 10. Be3 Bxb5
{ Only move that doesn't lose and only move that gives advantage. However, this move is not rocket science, and I am sure no one is going to miss this one :@@EndBracket@@ }
11. Bxb6 { Otherwise White remains one piece down. } 11... Bxa4 12. Nxa4 Bb4+
{ A very important move. Black finally punishes White for ignoring the development. }
13. Kd1 { 13.Nc3  Nxd5  would win material, so this becomes an obligation. }
13... Nbd7
{ The final touch. There is no rush to take on d5 and allow White to play e4. Currently, that is under control. Black now threatens to take on d5, which cannot be stopped. White's king in the center comes under pressure now. }
