exd4 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Bb3 Bf6 11. Ne4 b6 12. Nxf6+ Nxf6 13. Bg5 Ne7
{ In Part One of this course, we saw a similar motif in the Karpov-Nimzo variation. Black welcomes White to take on f6 when we take back with the g-pawn, and after the bishop comes to b7 and the rook comes to g8, White will regret taking on f6. By playing Ne7, Black completely stopped White from playing d5, and with Bb7 coming next, we get a good position. }
