exd4 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. a3 Nxc3
{ A mature decision! From targetting one weakness @@StartBracket@@d4@@EndBracket@@ Black now aims for another weakness @@StartBracket@@c3@@EndBracket@@. }
11. bxc3 b6
{ If we compare this with the Karpov-Nimzo @@StartBracket@@covered in part one of this course@@EndBracket@@, then Black is not only a few tempos up, but managed to take on c3 while retaining the dark-squared bishop. Usually, Black takes on c3 with the bishop, and even there, we are doing fine.   From a practical point of view, I already like Black here as there are no weaknesses while White has a bad pawn structure. }
12. Bd3 { Getting away from c4, where the bishop was vulnerable. } 12... Bb7
13. Re1 Rc8
{ Black finished the development while White could not create any attack. This leaves White with a strategic weakness on c3 without any compensation against it. The engine claims equality, but I feel from a practical point, it is easier to play from Black here. }
