1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 Nc6 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bd3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. a3 cxd4 10. exd4 Bf6 11. Re1 Bd7
{ The plan is to regroup with Nce7 and Bc6. The move order is important. Starting with Bd7, Black keeps Ne4 ideas in control as the pawn on d4 will fall. It is also possible to play  11...Nxd4  and after  12.Nxd4  Bxd4  13.Bxh7  Kxh7  14.Qxd4  Nxc3  15.Qxc3  f6  the position should be holdable without much trouble, but as said in the introduction, I dislike positions where we have to hold with precise play. Either way, we get a completely equal position or a position with all three results possible. Hence, although I believe Black won't have many issues to hold the position mentioned above, it made no sense for me to give that even as an alternative. }
