[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 Nc6 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bd3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. a3 cxd4 10. exd4 Bf6 11. Bc2 Nce7 12. Ne4 b6
{ Finishing his development calmly in the best possible manner. } 13. Qd3
{ White has an illusion that they have created some threats on the kingside. }
13... a5
{ Many other moves gave Black a good position, but I really like this punch-in-the-face move. Black allows every possible knight jump for White and cooly plays a move on the queenside. Black is threatening Ba6, and any knight jump doesn't bother us.   For example, after  14.Nxf6  Nxf6  there are no threats for White, while Black wants to play Ba6 next. Any other knight jump will be blocked with g6. Incredibly, White cannot create a sensible knight jump for a double attack. They can, of course, play  14.Nd6  g6  15.Nxc8  , but after  15...Rxc8  , all attacks are over, and White is once again left with a bad pawn structure. }
