cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Rc1 b6 12. Bd3 Bb7 13. O-O Nd7 14. e5
Bxf3 15. gxf3 b5
{ In both games that reached this position, continued with  15...Qh4  . I like this move much more. Black gains space on the queenside and also makes a path for the knight to d5 via b6. }
16. Kh1
{ White could not play  16.Bxb5  due to the pin on the 'd' file, Black can take  16...Nxe5  . }
16... Rc8 { Keep trading. One of the key motto of this line :@@EndBracket@@ }
17. Rxc8
{ After  17.Rg1  Rxc1  White won't be able to maintain the rook on the g-file with  18.Qxc1  as the d3 bishop hangs after  18...Nxe5  . }
17... Qxc8 18. Bxb5
{ White got a horrible pawn structure, but now in return, they got a pawn. }
18... Qb7 { Double attack on f3 and b5. } 19. Qd3
{ 19.Bxd7  Qxf3  was an immediate perpetual. } 19... Nb6
{ White has too many weaknesses to guard. Interestingly, even if we take the queens off the board, Black still has ample compensation with Rd8-Nd5-Nf4-g5 ideas. Engines give 0.00, but any day I would take Black here, who is very active and got more than enough compensation for a pawn. }
