1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. h4 b6 12. h5 h6 13. g4 Bb7 14. Qe3 Nc6
{ Developing with threats. Black wants to play Nb4 now with the idea of getting to c2. }
15. a3
{ An unfortunate obligation for White. Both  15.Rg1  and  15.g5  was losing to  15...Nb4  , with the threat of Nc2, after which Black will also take in charge of the c-file with Rc8. }
15... b5
{ Black keeps playing energetically and stops White from progressing on the kingside. Now, Qa5+ is a serious threat. }
16. Be2
{ Here in the game Caruana - Dominguez Black played the move  16...a6  , which is fine but loses the momentum. This position demands more energetic play like Black's previous moves. }
16... f5
{ According to engines, there are plenty of options available to get a balanced position for Black. I like the text move as it is the most dynamic and principled response. Counter attacking when White's king is in the center. }
17. g5 { There is no time to waste. White goes for Black's king. } 17... fxe4
18. Qxe4 Nxd4
{ This forces a draw immediately. If Black wants a complex game with all three results possible, then  18...Rf7  is a nice option. }
19. Qxb7 Nxf3+ 20. Bxf3 Qd3
{ The bishop is under attack while Black also threatens to play Qc3 next. } 21.
Qxa8 Qc3+ 22. Ke2 Qc4+ { Or  22...Qb2  ends with a perpetual. } *

