1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 c5 4. Be2 Nc6 5. O-O Bf5 6. dxc5 e6 7. Nd4 Bxc5
{ Black is ready to break the pawn structure and give up the bishop. This looks illogical, but the key factor is that the bishop on c1 is having trouble getting out. }
8. Nxf5 exf5
{ White is never getting e4 in this game ever now. The only route for the c1 bishop remains via b2. }
9. b3
{ It is not the best move in the position but a human response. The best option according to the engine is  9.Qd3  Qd7  10.c4  when Black plays  10...Ne5  and has no problem as they can either play d4 next and play against e2 bishop or take twice on c4 and collect the light-squared bishop. }
9... O-O 10. Bb2 d4
{ Breaking the center at the right moment when White is behind the development. }
11. exd4 Nxd4
{ Black dominates the center while White's queenside pieces are not coming out.  12.Bd3  looks natural, but after  12...Qd6  , it gets insanely challenging to withstand the pressure in the open files with Rad8 coming and kingside attacking plans with Ng4-g3-Qh6. Black stands clearly better now. }
