Rb8 9. Bf4 b5 10. Qd1 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bb7
{ Eliminating the Catalan bishop and making the king on g1 weak. } 12. Bxb8
{ White accepts the challenge and takes the exchange. Otherwise, Black is doing well materially speaking. }
12... Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Qxb8
{ Black gets terrific compensation for the exchange. We have an extra pawn and a dark-squared bishop for the rook.   The queenside pawns are well expanded, while White's knights are not stable and can be attacked at any time. The Black knight from d7 is ready to jump on c5 or e5. The queen will come to b7 with a tempo; Black can either focus on the queenside with Be7-O-O and bring the rook or opt for even the dynamic h5-h4 with a kingside attack. }
