1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Qa4+ Nbd7 6. Nf3 a6 7. Qxc4 b5 8.
Qc6 Rb8 9. Bf4 Bb7 10. Qxc7 Bb4+ 11. Nbd2 Qxc7 12. Bxc7 Rc8 13. Bf4 Rc2 14. Rb1
Bxd2+
{ A counter-intuitive move! Black gives up the bishop to delay White from castling. }
15. Bxd2 O-O { White is unable to castle as the bishop on d2 hangs. } 16. Nh4
Ne4
{ White will have to give up his light square bishop, and Black gets great compensation in return.   This position occurred in a correspondence game in 2021 where Black had no trouble. Once again, let me highlight that this is an additional solution for us. We could transpose to the mainline by playing 7...c5 instead of 7...b5. }
