1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Qa4+ Nbd7 6. Qxc4 c5 7. Nf3 a6 8.
Qb3 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nc5 10. Qe3 Nd5 11. Qd2 b5 12. Nc3 Bb7 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Nc6
Qd6 15. Bxd5 exd5 16. Nd4 g6
{ I like this more than Srinath's  16...Ne4  which is also doable. Black restricts White's knight on d4 which now has no good square to jump around. Black intends to play Bg7-O-O while White gets some difficulties developing the queenside. Black also got rid of the bad bishop against White's good bishop. Unless White creates something immediately, Black will get a super comfortable middlegame. }
17. Qe3+
{ Trying to interfere with Black's plan. After  17.O-O  Bg7  18.Qe3  Ne6  19.Nxe6  Qxe6  although the position is equal, practically, it is White who should be more careful as he gets behind the development. }
17... Be7
{ Black is in no rush. We know the bishop will get to its ideal diagonal after O-O-Bf6. The queen on e3 is no better than the queen on d2. It will anyways come under attack soon. }
18. Qh6
{ After  18.O-O  O-O  Black will get Bf6-Rfe8 with a very active position. }
18... Bf8
{ There are other ways also to keep the game going but just for the sake of proving Black's stability of this position this move will suffice. White must either allow Bg7-O-O and give Black a free play or repeat the position with  18.Qe3  Be7  which will be a wise decision at this point. }
