b5 9. Qd3 c4 10. Qc2 Rc8 11. e4 Be7 12. Qe2 O-O 13. Rd1 Na5 14. d5 exd5 15. e5
Ne8
{ This counterintuitive move is the key to this line! Instead of going to the center with Ne4, Black retreats. The idea is to gain a crucial tempo by playing Nc7 after White takes on d5. }
16. Rxd5 Nc7
{ The entire point of coming back to e8 instead of e4. From e4, the knight would have to go back to c5 without gaining a tempo, and here Black gains an important tempo with Nc7. }
17. Rd1 Qe8
{ Unpinning and planning Bf5-Bd3 if given a chance. In one 2021 correspondence game, Black played  17...b4  stopping Nc3 ideas and after  18.Nbd2  Ne6  19.Ne4  c3  the position was wild with all three results possible. This can also be an interesting option if Black is looking for some fire. I find the text move simpler so I'm giving it as a mainline. }
