b5 9. Qd3 c4 10. Qd1 Rc8 11. Bg5 Be7 12. Nc3 b4 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Ne4 O-O 15.
Rc1 Na5
{ Those pawns on the queenside are assets for Black, and there is no way Black will give up those pawns unless they get something huge in return. }
16. Qd2 { Giving a subtle threat of Nc5 to attack the pawn on b4. } 16... Bc6
{ Attacks the knight on e4 while stopping it come to c5. } 17. Qf4
{ 17.Nc5  Bxf3  18.Bxf3  Bxc5  wins a piece due to the pin on the d-file. }
17... f5
{ The knight must go back as  18.Neg5  h6  19.Nh3  Kh7  leads nowhere for White. Black keeps the bishop pair and the strong pawns on the queenside while White has nothing to claim compensation for these in return. Hence Black stands better. }
