Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 c3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Nb3 Be7 12. Nfd4 Nxd4 13. cxd4 Nd5 14.
Bd2 f5 15. Na5 b6 16. Nc6 Bf6 17. e3 Bb7 18. Nb4 Rfc8 19. a4 Rab8 20. a5 Nxb4
21. Bxb4 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 Rb7
{ It was also possible to play  22...bxa5  23.Bxa5  a6  , but I like the text move more. Black's play is quite simple here. Keep the king on f7, play h5-g6, keep all the pawns on the White square and see how exactly White is playing. If I have to pick a color in this position, I would pick Black.  I agree with Leela's evaluation of 0.00. This is what Stockfish also gets after some deep search, but in a practical game, I would rather be Black here. }
23. axb6 axb6 24. h3
{ White is running out of useful plans. Playing g4 is not even a threat as Black can either protect with g6 or play the energetic f4 when White is unable to take due to Rc4 double attack. }
24... Kf7 25. Rab1 b5
{ This position occurred in a 2020 correspondence game where White ran out of any concrete ideas, played  26.Rd3  , and agreed to a draw. Although Black has an outside passed pawn, it is not easy for Black to improve their position either. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Cárdenas, Yusley vs. Gubás, Jan, ICCF 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 c5 4. Bg2 cxd4 5. O-O h6 6. Bf4 e6 7. Nxd4 g5 8. Be5
Nbd7 9. Bxf6 Nxf6 10. c4 dxc4 11. Qa4+ Bd7 12. Qxc4 Qb6
{ Our course ended here with the following comment 'It is obvious that White cannot create an attack on the center, and Black will play Bg7-O-O shortly. More importantly White will also have to deal with Rc8 ideas that gain a tempo against White's queen. This position occurred in a few correspondence games, and Black never lost a single one and won one game. That also underlines the solidity of Black's position.' }
13. Qd3 Bg7
{ Development first! Black intends to castle quickly.   13...Qxb2?!  14.Nc3  Allows White to take lead in the development. }
14. Nd2 O-O 15. Nc4 Qa6
{ 15...Qc7!  16.Rac1  Rac8  was an interesting way to continue the game. Black pins the knight on c4.  17.Qd2  b6⩱  Black keeps the double bishop advantage, and White has nothing in return to claim the compensation for. }
16. a4 { White goes for the queen with b4-b5 ideas. } 16... Rac8
{ Attacking c4, and stopping b4. } 17. b3 Rfd8 18. Qf3 Ne8
{ 18...Nd5  There is nothing wrong with what Black played, but I would prefer the knight on d5.  19.e4  Bxd4  Attacking the rook on a1.  20.Rad1!  20...e5  21.exd5  Qg6⩱  Wtih a pair of bishop advantage, I like Black's position here. }
19. Qe4 Nd6 { Trading the active knight on c4. } 20. Nxd6 Qxd6 21. Rad1 Be8
{ The d1 rook is pinned. White is barely escaping here with equality. } 22. e3
e5 { This forces the game to end in a draw after a series of only moves. } 23.
Nf5 Qxd1 24. Ne7+
{ Otherwise White is lost instantly.   24.Rxd1  Rxd1+  25.Bf1  Rcc1-+ } 24...
Kf8 25. Nxc8 Qxb3 { Now we get to an equal endgame with further changes. } 26.
Nxa7 { 26.Qxb7  Qxb7  27.Bxb7  a5  Could only get scary for White. } 26... Qxa4
27. Qxa4 Bxa4 28. Bxb7 Bc2 29. Rc1 Rd1+ 30. Rxd1
{ Everything fizzled out, and there was nothing left to play for. } *

