1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5 3. d4 Nf6 4. c4 cxd4 5. exd4 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Qb3 dxc4 8.
Bxc4 O-O 9. d5 Nbd7 10. O-O Nb6
{ Our course ended with the following comment: Black now picks up the bishop and gets a bishop pair advantage. White is not worse yet, but they must be precise not to get into a bad position. Black was fine in the game: 1/2-1/2 Vidit,S  @@StartBracket@@2702@@EndBracket@@-Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2773@@EndBracket@@ Kolkata 2018. }
11. Bg5
{ White puts indirect pressure on the e7 pawn.   11.Rd1  It was possible to give more support to the d5 pawn, but after  11...Nxc4  12.Qxc4  Bg4⇆  Black keeps developing with tempo, and gets a fine middlegame. }
11... h6
{ 11...a5!  was an interesting way to play the position. Now either White must allow Black to play a4 or play a4 himself.  12.a4  Qd6⩱  That was the point of including a5-a4. Now it gets difficutl to deal with the Qb4 threat. }
12. Bh4 Nxc4 { Once again a5 was an option like on the 11th move. } 13. Qxc4 e6
{ Anand plays with the simple logic of opening up the position while having the bishop pair advantage. }
14. Rfd1 g5
{ Getting out of the pin before taking on d5.   14...exd5  15.Nxd5  Be6  16.Nxf6+  Qxf6!  Gets to an equal position after  17.Bxf6  Bxc4  18.Bxg7  Kxg7  19.Rd7⇆ }
15. dxe6
{ This is a mistake. White had to retreat this bishop to maintain the balance.   15.Bg3  exd5  16.Qb3!   16.Nxd5  Be6!  must be the reason for rejecting 15.Bg3.  17.Nxf6+  Qxf6∓  Black wins a pawn now.  16...Re8  17.h4=∞  White fights for compensation now due to Black's weak pawn on d5. }
15... Bxe6 16. Qb4 a5 { Counter-attack is the best defense :@@EndBracket@@ }
17. Qa3
{ 17.Qxb7  Qb8  Forcing a queen trade.  18.Qxb8  Rfxb8∓  White's queenside pawns will collapse soon. }
17... Qe8
{ 17...Qb6∓  was good enough to get a clearly better position due to the double bishop advantage and the pressure on the queenside. }
18. Bg3 b5 19. b4 Nd5 { Using the pin on the long diagonal. } 20. Nxd5 Bxd5
{ White is in great danger as his queenside is about to collapse. } 21. Rac1
axb4
{ This move gives away all advantage, and the game fizzles out to a draw.   21...Qe2!  Threatening Bb2  22.Rd2  Qe4  23.bxa5  b4  24.Qe3  Bc3!  This was the point of playing 21...Qe2 and then Qe4. Black forced White to play Rd2 to get this tempo with Bc3.  25.Qxe4  Bxe4  26.Re2  f5∓  The bishops are completely dominating White's rooks. Black remains clearly better. }
22. Qxb4 Bxf3 23. gxf3 Rxa2 { Black can't maintain the pawn on b5 now. } 24.
Re1
{ 24.Kg2=∞  was enough to make a draw when Black can never take advantage of his extra pawn due to White's active pieces. }
24... Qd7
{ 24...Qa8  25.Qxb5  Qxf3  Was a better try but with pawns on the same side, Black is not going to win this endgame after  26.Qc6 }
25. Rb1 { Now Black loses the b-pawn and the game ends in a draw. } 25... Qc6
