11. Ng5
{ Forcing Black to play e6 and shut the bishop on c8. White does not have such luxury at this stage to ignore castling. It was wiser to castle first and try to defend a worse position.   11.O-O  11...Nc6  12.Qa3  b6⩱  Black's play becomes very easy with zero weakness and a clear target on c3. }
11... e6 12. Ba3 { White keeps ignoring their own king. } 12... Rd8 13. O-O
{ Finally, White castles, but already they are close to losing! Computer evaluation of -1.28 and Wesley's lovely play confirms the same. }
13... Nc6 { Developing with a tempo. Black threatens Na5 now. } 14. Be2
{ 14.Bd3  This is less damaging. Though it is unlikely White will be able to save his weak pawns here.  14...h6  15.Ne4  15.Nf3 e5 would be a nightmare against the d4 pawn.  15...b6  16.Rac1  Bb7-+  White has zero compensation for his weakness on c3/c4. Black will play Rac8-Na5-Nc4 and White can do nothing against it. The engines scream -1.57 for Black :@@EndBracket@@ }
14... b6 { Simple and straightforward. How to stop Bb7-Rac8-Na5? } 15. Bf3 Bb7
16. Qa4 h6
{ Wesley remains tactically alert and finds the fastest way to win the game. }
17. Ne4
{ 17.Nh3  Rac8-+  It is all about harmony and weakness. Without being a single pawn down, White's position is -3.5, which is as good as being a piece down! Basically, White cannot do anything about Na5-Nc4, and sooner or later, his queenside is bound to collapse. }
17... Nxd4 18. cxd4 Rxd4 { Due to double attack White loses the knight on e4. }
19. Qb3 Bxe4 20. Bb2
{ 20.Bxe4  Rxe4  21.Rac1  Qe5-+  Black remains two pawns up with huge activity. }
20... Rd3
{ White loses further material. It was time to resign. A perfect game by Wesley. }
