13. Bxe4
{ An impulsive decision. It is understandable White was worried about the knight on e4, but giving up the best bishop he had only worsened the situation.   13.Ne2  g6!  An amazing prophlaxis against White's Ne5 ideas.   13...a5!?  14.Ne5  The only trick White had in the position.  14...Nxe5  15.dxe5  Bxe5  16.Bxe4  16...dxe4  17.Bxe5  Qxe5⩱  Black is still better, but White managed to trade a few pieces.  14.a3  a5  Black controls every part of the board and remains clearly better. }
13... dxe4 14. Nd2 Nf6
{ Black bishops are looking at the kingside while White's bishop is dead on b2. White's king comes into danger now. }
15. Nc4 { 15.f3  Bf5∓ } 15... Bc7
{ The machine likes 15...Bb4, but to keep the bishop on this diagonal, looking at the kingside is more human.   15...Bb4!  16.a3  Bxc3  17.Bxc3  Nd5∓  Black gets to an opposite-colored bishop middlegame when Black's light-squared bishop has no match, and White's dark-squared bishop doesn't have any life. }
16. Ba3 Qe6 17. Rfd1
{ 17.f4!  exf3  18.Rxf3⇆  White managed to activate his pieces, and is back in the game. }
17... Nd5 18. Rac1 Qg6
{ The king on g1 comes into huge danger now when White's entire army is on the queenside. }
19. Kf1 Nxc3
{ 19...Be6  would have left White with zero counter. The engine calls it -3 already. }
20. Qxc3 Be6 21. Ne5
{ It is hard to suggest any decent move for White, when everything is losing for him. }
21... Qf5 { 21...Qh5-+ } 22. Bb2 Bd5
{ It is hard to believe White managed to survive this game. The engine's evaluation is close to -4, which is not surprising. White has zero counterplay. }
23. Qb4 Rab8 24. Qc5
{ White is creating one-move threats, but these are not dangerous and can be paired away easily. }
24... a6 25. Qb4 h5 { Black keeps taking more space on the kingside. } 26. Rc2
Red8 { 26...Re6-+  Would have been a more direct assault. } 27. Qe1 Rd6 28. Bc3
Re6
{ 28...Rh6!!  A brilliant concept. If Black rook gets to g6, White will have a disaster. Black hides his rook on h6, with the idea of playing f6, removing the knight from e5, and then playing Rg6.  29.Bb4  f6  30.Nc4  Rg6-+  With Qg5 coming next, White's position is collapsing. }
29. Bb2 { White runs out of any concrete plans. } 29... Rf6
{ 29...Rh6-+  Once again was the easiest route to win the game like 28...Rh6. }
30. Rdc1 Qe6 31. Kg1 Rf5
{ The concept was right, to remove the knight from g6 and get to the g-file, but the execution was wrong. White now escapes with a tactic. }
32. f4 { Precise moment when Black is unable to take on f3 due to e4 fork. }
32... Rf6
{ 32...exf3  White escapes with series of brilliant and only moves now.  33.e4  33...Bxe4  34.Qxe4  f6  35.Rxc6!!  this move saves the day for White.  35...bxc6  36.Rxc6  36...f2+   @@StartBracket@@  36...Qc8??  37.Ng6+-  @@EndBracket@@  37.Kf1  Bd6  38.g4!!  Another brilliant move to stay in the game.  38...hxg4  39.hxg4  Rg5  40.Bc1⇆  The final touch. White gets the rook now and escapes with a draw. }
33. Bc3
{ There is no kingside attack anymore, and Black lost all his advantage. }
33... Re8 34. Ba5 Bd6 35. Bb4 Bb8 36. Rf2 { 36.Ba5!  Rh6  37.Nc4⇆ } 36... Rh6
