{ If you have gone through the course sincerely, you must remember how I mentioned this game many times. We need to know how NOT to play in some positions. Our course suggests here  10...Bf6  and after  10.Re1  the following was said: 'The major move in this position. White waits for Black to reveal their plan and makes a standard developing move.  The first step to learning what NOT to do will be crucial here. So let me ask all of the readers to see the famous game Botvinnik - Alekhine from Avro 1938.  Before making the next move, please take a look at the game, you can also find the game in Kasparov's book 'My great Predecessors volume 2' @@StartBracket@@Game 36, which you can find here @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/my-great-predecessors-part-2/course/25417/@@EndBracket@@LinkEnd@@@@.  Without knowing the details of this game, it would be difficult to understand and develop a sense of danger in this seemingly harmless and peaceful position'. }
10... b6
{ 10...Bf6!  This is what the course recommends with the following comment 'Black threatens to play Nb6 and take the pawn on d4. From my previous comment after  10.Re1  , you know that  10...b6  is a mistake due to  11.Nxd5  exd5  12.Bb5  occurred in the famous game Botvinnik - Alekhine,  Avro 1938.   If you have seen the model game or read the notes from MGP by Kasparov, then you should also know that playing  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3  b6  is not good either when White has the extremely powerful  12.h4  . Modern engine's evaluation bar starts to dance after  12...Bxh4  13.Nxh4  Qxh4  14.Re3  when White's attack gets brutal. Both these moves @@StartBracket@@10...b6 and 10...Nxc3@@EndBracket@@ are bad, and it has been established long back. Modern engines are just confirming the same. '. }
11. Nxd5 exd5 12. Bb5
{ Despite the symmetrical pawn structure, Black is now doomed to passive defence. Weaknesses on the c-file and a slight discoordination of the black pieces give White an easy game in which he can develop his initiative. @@StartBracket@@Kasparov@@EndBracket@@ }
12... Bd7
{ It feels logical to try to trade the bad bishop, but it gets even worse now.   12...Bb7  13.Bd3±  The bishop on b7 will remain out of play for a long time. }
13. Qa4 Nb8
{ Not a very pleasant sight for Black's pieces.   13...Rc8  14.Bf4+-  Engines are already screaming almost +2 here. Black is likely to drop his queenside pawns soon. }
14. Bf4
{ White is already winning, and it is remarkable how easily and effortlessly Botvinnik managed to outplay the world champion. }
14... Bxb5 15. Qxb5 a6 16. Qa4
{ 16.Qd3  is stronger according to modern engines. It stops Bd6 due to Ng5 threats.  16...Nd7  @@StartBracket@@  16...Nc6  17.Rac1  brings difficult time for the knight on c6. @@EndBracket@@  17.Rac1  17...Ra7  18.Qb3+- }
16... Bd6 17. Bxd6 Qxd6
{ It feels like Black managed to exchange a few pieces and reduce the damage, but his knight on b8 will still struggle to get a good square. }
18. Rac1 Ra7 19. Qc2
{ I read in Botvinnik's book explaining why he chose this variation over  19.Qe8  Rc7  20.Rxc7  Qxc7  21.Qe2  . He mentioned a simple and logical thought: controlling the c-file is more important than the e-file since it is further away from Black's king. }
19... Re7 20. Rxe7 Qxe7 21. Qc7 Qxc7 22. Rxc7 f6
{ Black controls the knight and intends to chase the rook away from c7. At first sight, it doesn't look that hopeless, but Botvinnik shows the issues in Black's position in his systematic method. }
23. Kf1
{ No rush! Wasn't Black threatening to play Rf7? Let's see if that was a threat or not :@@EndBracket@@   23.Rb7?!  Might be winning, but completely uncalled for. Why to give unnecessary counter?  23...Rc8!  24.Kf1  b5±  White is still close to winning, but Black got some play. }
23... Rf7 24. Rc8+ Rf8 25. Rc3
{ Rc7 is not a threat, but if Black moves any of his pieces, it becomes a threat! What an amazing concept. Black is now in complete zugzwang and must play only with his pawns! }
25... g5 26. Ne1
{ The knight heads for the weak f5 square. The rook on c3 alone is dominating all Black's pieces. }
26... h5 27. h4
{ Showing flexibility of the mind. There was nothing wrong with the original idea of Nc2-Ne3-Nf5, but Botvinnik finds a better square after Black's last move. The knight on f4 would be the most hostile. Hence h4. }
27... Nd7
{ Black gets frustrated. It is hard to suggest anything at this point. } 28.
Rc7 Rf7 29. Nf3 { Forcing the g-pawn to move and weaken the f4 square. } 29...
g4 30. Ne1
{ With this lovely maneuver, the f4 square is now available for the knight. }
30... f5 31. Nd3 f4
{ Alekhine tries his best to stop White's knight from coming to f4. } 32. f3
{ The f4 pawn becomes the new weakness in Black's position. } 32... gxf3 33.
gxf3 a5 34. a4 { Of course no counter must be allowed :@@EndBracket@@ } 34...
Kf8 35. Rc6
{ The knight remains forever controlled now. Note that Black can never play Rf6 as after the trade, he loses the pawn on f4. }
35... Ke7 36. Kf2 Rf5 37. b3
{ I remember as a kid, this move made a huge impression on me. Such patience level and showing absolutely no rush. There were 100 ways to win, but Botvinnik is in his element and gives absolutely no counter. He protects the a4 pawn just in case for the future and clearly states that Black has no useful ideas/moves. }
37... Kd8 38. Ke2 Nb8
{ Black hopes for some counter by sacrificing the pawn on b6. } 39. Rg6
{ Not giving allowing the slightest counterplay. After  39.Rxb6  Kc7  Black gets his knight to c6. }
39... Kc7 40. Ne5 { The knight remains dead on b8. } 40... Na6 41. Rg7+ Kc8 42.
Nc6 Rf6 43. Ne7+ { Finally, White goes for the pawn. } 43... Kb8 44. Nxd5 Rd6
45. Rg5 Nb4 46. Nxb4 axb4 47. Rxh5 Rc6
{ 47...Rxd4  48.Rf5+-  The rook on d4 gets totally stuck, and White will start pushing his h-pawn. }
48. Rb5 Kc7 49. Rxb4 Rh6 50. Rb5 Rxh4 51. Kd3
{ Alekhine had seen enough and decided to resign. Beating a world champion with such effortlessness after one simple mistake on move ten is very instructive. It shows how the seemingly harmless-looking position can get so dangerous. Why did I include a losing game in the model games section? Two reasons:   1. It is equally essential for us to understand how not to play.   2. Seeing such games with commentary will help the readers to improve their general understanding of the game, which is one of my main aims. Not to make the readers just an opening expert, but a better player. }
*

