[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Wunderlich, Hans Dieter vs. Dudyev, Vladimir - W-ch27 q01 email, 2007"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nf3 Be7 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8.
Bc4 O-O 9. O-O Nc6 10. Re1 Bf6 11. Ne4 b6 12. a3 Bb7 13. Qd3 Nce7 14. Nfg5 Bxg5
15. Nxg5 Nf6 16. Nxf7 Rxf7 17. Bxe6 Bd5 18. Bxf7+ Bxf7
{ Our course ended here with the following comment: 'Materially speaking, White is doing fine. But the Bishop is weak, and the central pawn is weak. Black knight will come to d5, and white king might come under attack as the pawn on g2 is weak as Black's light-squared Bishop has no match. ' }
19. Bg5 { Hoping to damage the kingside pawn structure. } 19... Qd7
{ Ignoring White's threat completely.   19...Ng6!?  was also possible with the idea to play h6 next.  20.Rad1  h6  21.Bxf6  Qxf6  22.d5  Otherwise Black plays Bd5.  22...Nf4  23.Qd4  Nxd5  24.Qxf6  Nxf6=  Although computer calls it 0.00, from a practical point of view Black can definitely try to press here. }
20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. Qf3
{ 21.Re3  Nd5  22.Rg3+  Bg6⩱  The king remains very safe on f7. Thanks to the knight on d5 there is no entry for White's rooks. The engines like Black slightly better already. }
21... Nd5 22. h3 Kh8 23. Re4 Rc8
{ 23...Bg6!  24.Re2   @@StartBracket@@  24.Rh4  Re8∓  @@EndBracket@@  24...h5⩱  I would never agree for a draw here as Black. White's rooks are totally useless here, and do not have any entry. }
24. Rae1 Rc6 25. R4e2 a5 26. Re4
{ Surprisingly the game ended in a draw. Modern engines prefer black here, and in an OTB game, it is definitely the starting point of a complex game where Black will start pressing for a long time. }
