[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Giri, Anish vs. Shankland, Samuel L - chess24.com INT, 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. d4 d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bd3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. a3 cxd4 10. exd4 Bf6 11. Be4 Nce7 12. h4 Bd7 13. Ng5 g6 14. Nf3 Bc6
{ Our course ended here with the following comment: 'Black got complete control in the center while White doesn't have any attack on any side of the board. Black threatens to take on c3 and exchange a few more pieces so that White's weak pawn structure becomes more prominent. Black was better in the game 1/2-1/2  Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@ -Shankland,S @@StartBracket@@2691@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021.' }
15. Re1 { Protecting e4 to stop Nxc3 ideas. } 15... Rc8
{ 15...Nxc3  16.bxc3  Bxe4  17.Rxe4  Rc8  18.Qe1  Nd5  19.Bh6  Re8  20.Rc1  Rc4⩱  With a strong blockade and multiple weaknesses in White's camp, Black keeps some pressure. }
16. Bh6 Nxc3 17. bxc3 Bxe4
{ Very interesting exchange sacrifice by Sam.   17...Re8  18.Bg5  This nice move keeps the balance for White. Threatening to exchange the bad bishop.  18...Bg7  19.Bxc6  Rxc6  20.h5!  20...Rxc3  21.h6  Bf8  22.Nd2=∞  White keeps compensation, thanks to the pawn on h6, which makes the king on g8 a bit weak. }
18. Bxf8 Nd5
{ This intermediate move was Sam's big point, the pawn on c3 falls. } 19. Bb4
{ 19.Rxe4  Nxc3  20.Qe1  Nxe4  21.Qxe4  Kxf8!  22.Qxb7  Rc7∓ } 19... Bxf3 20.
Qxf3 Bxh4
{ The strong knight in the center and weakness in whites pawn structure gives sufficient compensation.   20...a5  Black cannot trap the bishop yet.  21.Bc5  b6  22.c4!  22...bxc5  23.cxd5∞ }
21. a4 a5 { 21...Bf6  22.a5  Nxb4  23.cxb4  Bxd4  24.Rad1  Rc7=∞ } 22. Bc5 b6
23. c4 { Only move to stay in the game, but an obvious one. } 23... Nf6
{ 23...bxc5?  24.cxd5  exd5  25.dxc5  Rxc5  26.Rac1+-  The position gets opened up, and soon the open files will decide the game in White's favor. }
24. Bxb6 { A temporary sacrifice. White picks up the material in next move. }
24... Qxb6 25. Qf4 Rxc4 26. Qxh4 Nd5
{ 26...Qxd4?!  27.Qxd4  Rxd4  28.Red1⩲  All such endgames are in whites favor as the rook become much more powerful than the knight }
27. Reb1 Qc7 { 27...Qd6  was required  28.Rb7  Qc6  29.Rb8+  Kg7=∞ } 28. Qe4
{ White could test Black a bit more.   28.Qg3!  28...Nf4!   28...Qxg3?  This obvious move would be a blunder.  29.fxg3  Rxd4  30.Rb5+-  would be winning for white as the 'a' pawn falls.  29.Qe3  Nd5  30.Qe5  with same idea to trade queens.  30...Qxe5  31.dxe5  Nc3=∞  Now Black eliminates the 'a' pawn and is likely to build a fortress without difficulty. }
28... Nc3 29. Qa8+ Kg7 30. Rb8 Ne2+ 31. Kf1 Nf4
{ 31...Rc1+  32.Rxc1  Ng3+!!  ends in forced perpetual checks  33.fxg3  Qxc1+  34.Kf2  Qd2+  35.Kf3  Qd3+  36.Kf4  Qxd4+  37.Qe4  Qf2+  38.Qf3  Qd4+  39.Qe4= }
32. Rg8+ Kh6 33. Qe4 { 33.Qf8+  Kh5-+  makes no sense for White. } 33... Rc1+
34. Rxc1 Qxc1+ 35. Qe1 Qc6 { It is important to force f3. } 36. f3 Qc4+ 37. Kg1
Qxd4+ 38. Kh2 { The weak king on h2 gives Black sufficient counterplay. } 38...
Qf6 39. Kh1 Qg5 40. Qg1 Nh5 41. g4 Qh4+ 42. Qh2 Qe1+ 43. Qg1 Qh4+ 44. Qh2 Qe1+
45. Qg1 Qh4+ *

