1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. g3 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 b6 11. Bg2 Bb7 12. O-O O-O 13. Rfc1 Nd7 14. Qd3
Nf6 15. Ne5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Qd5+ 17. f3 Rac8 18. e4 Qb7 19. Qa3 h5
{ Our course ended here with the following comment: ' Fighting and not begging for equality is the spirit to play this variation. Black could play h6 here, and according to every engine, it is fine for Black. In the game, Black opted for h5, which is more dynamic. It takes more space on the kingside. Black will now play Rfd8 next. Ideas like Nxe4 with or without the inclusion of h4 will always be in the air. White's central pawns are not moving further. Black had an excellent position in the game: 1/2-1/2 Aronian,L @@StartBracket@@2775@@EndBracket@@-Ding,L @@StartBracket@@2801@@EndBracket@@ London 2019. }
20. h4 { White wanted to get rid of h4 ideas from Black in the future. } 20...
Rfd8 21. Rxc8
{ 21.Qb2  Ne8  Soon Black will exchange the major pieces leading to a fine balanced endgame  22.a4  Nd6  23.Qa3  Qa6  24.Qa2= }
21... Rxc8 22. Rc1
{ Black is never scared of trading and reaching an endgame due to his pawn structure. Remember the introduction of Semi Tarrasch? }
22... Rc7
{ There was nothing wrong with a direct Rxc1, but why give away the c-file? }
23. Rc3 Qc8 { Now Black takes control of the c-file. } 24. Qxa7
{ Forcing an immediate perpetual.   24.Rxc7  Qxc7  25.Qa4  25...Qc3  According to engines, just too many moves lead to a draw, this is just one of them.  26.Qxa7  Qd2+  27.Kh3  Qd1  28.Qxf7+  Kh7=  The game ends with a perpetual now. }
24... Rxc3 25. Qxf7+ Kh7 26. Qg6+ Kg8
{ 26...Kh8  27.Nf7+  Kg8  28.Nh6+  Kh8  29.Nf7+= } 27. Qf7+ Kh7 28. Qg6+ Kg8 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Rubinstein, Akiba vs. Schlechter, Carl - San Sebastian International Masters-02, 1912"]
[Result "*"]

{ We will be seeing one of the first Semi-Tarrasch games played back in 1912. This classic game has been mentioned and analyzed in various books. Going through this game will definitely improve the general understanding of the game, and it will also help us understand @@StartBracket@@again@@EndBracket@@ how  NOT  to play in the Semi-Tarrasch. }
1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Qa5
{ This is not a part of our repertoire. We are playing 9...Bxd2. However, it is essential to know why we are not playing this. After all, our main concept is to trade as many pieces as possible. So, why not try to exchange queens? }
10. Rb1 { White insists on the trade. } 10... Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2
{ White is even ready to trade queens! The reasoning is simple. White's king is in the center, and due to this reason, the endgame favors him. If you have gone through the course correctly, you would know that Black was never trading queens in this manner when White's king stayed in the center. We would always wait for White to castle first before going for Qa5 ideas. }
11... Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2
{ The placement of the king changes everything about this endgame. White is much faster now. Modern engines already give close to +2 for White! }
12... O-O 13. Bb5
{ A fantastic deep strategic move by the great Akiba. The bishop on b5 will be a nightmare, and if Black moves the bishop from b5 by playing a6, the b6 square becomes weak.   13.Ke3  According to modern engines, this move is even stronger. It doesn't really matter as both are winning.  13...Nc6   @@StartBracket@@  13...b6  14.Rc1  @@EndBracket@@  14.Bb5!  14...Bd7  15.Bxc6!  Bxc6  16.Ne5+-  Once again, we see the power of a centralized king in the endgame. }
13... a6 { 13...b6  14.Rhc1  14...Ba6  15.Ba4+- } 14. Bd3
{ Now the b6 square becomes weak. } 14... Rd8
{ 14...b5  15.Rhc1  15...Ra7  16.Rb2+-  White penetrates through the c-file. }
15. Rhc1 b5
{ 15...Nc6  16.Ke3  Black cannot move his pieces on the queenside.  16...Ra7  17.Rc5  Bd7  18.Rb6+-  is a total domination when Black is tied down completely. }
16. Rc7 Nd7 17. Ke3
{ White's central pawns are nicely protected with his king. } 17... Nf6 18. Ne5
Bd7 19. g4
{ With total domination in the center, and the queenside, White now creates more weaknesses for Black on the kingside. }
19... h6 20. f4
{ The great Akiba keeps playing with simple plans which are impossible to stop :@@EndBracket@@ White keeps taking more space and threatens to play g5 next. }
20... Be8 21. g5 hxg5 22. fxg5 Nh7 23. h4
{ Now the knight is dead on h7. Look at Black's pathetic pieces. Nothing is above the second rank. }
23... Rdc8 24. Rbc1 Rxc7 25. Rxc7 Rd8
{ There are no targets for Black. White's pawns are nicely protected. } 26. Ra7
f6 27. gxf6 gxf6 { 27...Nxf6  28.Rxa6+- } 28. Ng4
{ The knight on h7 still remains shut. } 28... Bh5 29. Nh6+ Kh8 30. Be2
{ Removing the bishop from h5. Black is unable to take on e2 due to the fork on f7. }
30... Be8 { 30...Bxe2  31.Nf7+  Kg8  32.Nxd8+- } 31. Rxa6
{ White now wins the pawn, and the rest is easy. } 31... Kg7 32. Ng4 f5 33.
Ra7+ Kh8 34. Ne5 fxe4 35. Bxb5
{ Once again, the fork on f7 stops Black from taking the bishop. } 35... Nf6
{ 35...Bxb5  36.Nf7+  Kg8  37.Nxd8+- } 36. Bxe8 Rxe8 37. Kf4 Kg8 38. Kg5
{ Activating the king always :@@EndBracket@@ } 38... Rf8 39. Kg6
{ A fascinating game by Rubinstein. Clearly, it shows why it is important not to trade queens while White's king is still in the center. After this great game, Akiba himself played Semi-Tarrasch as Black, but obviously, he didn't play 9...Qa5 and opted for 9...Bxd2, which is recommended in the course.  In fact, Rubinstein was one of the first top players who showed the world Black can play with 9...Bxd2, and the line is rich in its strategic and dynamic play. The great Alekhine soon picked it up, and later many strong elite players tried this line as Black. }
