[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Be2 b6 12. O-O Bb7 13. Qe3 Nc6 14. Rac1
Rc8 15. h4 Qd6 16. h5 h6 17. Rfd1 Rfd8
{ Our course ended here with the following comment: ' Wei Yi keeps waiting. According to engines  18...Nb4  was good enough, but I also like the text move where Black is totally ready for any kind of d5 breaks and finished the development comfortably. It remains our choice when we would like to start trading. With zero weaknesses in the position, Black has nothing to worry about. 1/2-1/2 Duda, J @@StartBracket@@2724@@EndBracket@@-Wei, Y @@StartBracket@@2734@@EndBracket@@ Liaocheng 2018.' }
18. d5
{ White tried to break the center immediately, but Black is ready for that. }
18... exd5 19. Rxd5
{ 19.e5?!  Such ideas work mainly when White gets his knight to d4. With Black knight on c6, it is not that effective.   @@StartBracket@@ After  19.exd5  Ne7  the pawn on  d5  falls.@@EndBracket@@  19...Qe7  20.Bd3  Nb4!  Black is ready to exchange as many pieces as possible  21.Bf5  Rxc1  22.Rxc1  d4!  Frees the bishop on b7, and tricks on g2 will happen soon.  23.Nxd4  Rxd4!  24.Qxd4  Qg5  a small trick does the job and now black plays for only 2 results  25.Rc8+  Only move not to resign.  25...Bxc8  26.Bxc8  Nc6⩱  White loses the e5 pawn, and will have to fight for a draw. }
19... Qe7 20. Rcd1 Rxd5
{ Exchanging pieces makes Black happy usually :@@EndBracket@@   20...Nb4  I like this move even more when White doesn't even get a passed pawn.  21.Rxd8+  (@@StartBracket@@ 21.Rd4 Nc6 leads nowhere for White.@@EndBracket@@)  21...Rxd8  22.Rxd8+  Qxd8⇆  Black gets a fine endgame. }
21. Rxd5
{ 21.exd5  Qxe3  22.fxe3  Nb4  23.d6  Kf8  The d-pawn is never dangerous as it is close to Black's king.  24.Ne5  Nc6!  25.Nxc6  Bxc6  26.Bg4  Rd8=  Black will play Ke8-Bd7 and threaten Kd7 ideas by moving the bishop. To not lose the d-pawn, the game would soon end with repetition. }
21... Nd8 22. Re5 Ne6 { The White pieces lack coordination } 23. Bd1 Rc5
{ 23...Ba6!  24.Bb3  Bc4  25.g3  Qb4  Was more annoying for White, when his rook on e5 becomes odd, and the pressure on the queenside increases. }
24. Bb3 Rxe5 { 24...Qd6⩱ } 25. Nxe5 Qf6 26. Qc3 Kh7
{ 26...Bxe4?  27.Qc8+  Kh7  28.Nxf7!!  Threatening mate in one on h8.  28...Qxf7  29.Bxe6  Qxh5  30.Qg8+  Kg6  31.Bf7++- }
27. f3 Nf4 28. Qc7 Qh4 { Now the game ends with a perpetual. } 29. Bxf7 Qe1+
30. Kh2 Qh4+ 31. Kg1 Qe1+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Svidler, Peter vs. Kramnik, Vladimir - RUS-chT, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7 12. O-O b6 13. a4 Bb7 14. Bd3
Nf6 15. Rfe1 h6 16. a5
{ 16.Qb4  Qc7  17.a5  bxa5  18.Rxa5  Rfb8  is how we get this position in our course. }
16... bxa5
{ 16...a6  This is our choice. In the course,  the following was mentioned: ' It is also possible to play the more popular move  16...bxa5  but after  17.Rxa5  Qc7  White is not obliged to transpose with Qb4, and he can keep his queen less exposed on d2. I like the text move  16...a6  with the idea of b5, which in a way, forces White to take on b6.' }
17. Rxa5 Qc7 18. Qb4
{ Now we are back to our course, where we would have gotten the same position via the 16.Qb4 move order.   18.h3  White was not obliged to expose his queen on b4. This is the reason I chose 16...a6 over 16....bxa5.  18...Rfc8  19.Ne5  Black is still fine, but he didn't get the tempi compared to the Qb4 lines. }
18... Rfb8 19. Qa3 Rc8 20. h3 a6 21. Ne5 Qd8 22. Nf3 Rc7
{ Our course ended with the following comment: 'The position remains equal, but Kramnik decided not to repeat and kept fighting with Rc7.' }
23. Ra4 a5
{ 23...Rac8  24.Bxa6  Rc3  25.Qb2  is possible now as the rook on a5 is not hanging. That's the point of 23.Ra4. }
24. Ne5
{ 24.Rxa5  Bxe4!  25.Bxe4  Rxa5  26.Qxa5  Nxe4  With a favorable pawn structure for Black.  27.Rxe4  Rc1  drops the queen on a5. }
24... Bc6
{ Forcing things in a human way   24...Rac8!?  25.Qb2   @@StartBracket@@  25.Rxa5  Qxd4⩱  @@EndBracket@@  25...Ra8=  typical engine move. The thing is, White cannot improve his position in any way. More or less, every white piece is tied to the defense of the central pawns. }
25. Rxa5 { 25.Nxc6  Rxc6  26.Ra1  26...Rac8!  27.Qb2  Rc3⇆ } 25... Bxe4 26.
Bxe4 Rxa5 27. Qxa5 Nxe4 { Similar tactic like in the 24.Rxa5 variation. } 28.
Kh2 Nc3 29. Rc1 { 29.Ra1  Nd5  30.Rc1  f6  31.Rxc7  Qxc7  32.Qxc7  Nxc7= }
29... Qxd4 { Threatens Qf4. } 30. Qxc7 Qf4+ 31. g3 Qxf2+
{ 31...Qxc1?  32.Qxf7+  Kh7  33.Nd7+-  Black gets into a mating attack. } 32.
Kh1 Ne2 33. Qxf7+
