1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7 12. O-O b6 13. Rad1 Bb7 14.
Rfe1 Rc8 15. Bb3 h6 16. h3 Nf6 17. d5 exd5 18. Qf4 Rc5 19. e5 Ne8 20. Nd4 Nc7
21. Qe3 Ne6 22. f4 Nxd4 23. Rxd4 Qd7
{ Our course ended here with the following comment: 'It is difficult for White to continue the attack. They are not getting f5 easily after  24.Qf2  , a fantastic strategic move would be to play  24...Qf5  , when the only way to get rid of the queen will be to play g4 @@StartBracket@@White is never getting Bc2 as Black plays Rfc8 next@@EndBracket@@, and once g4 is played, Black comes back with the queen, and now it is impossible to put pressure on the g7 pawn @@StartBracket@@thanks to White's pawn on g4@@EndBracket@@. Black then triples on the c-file and pushes the queenside pawns with b5-a5-a4.   In a correspondence game 2020, White could not find anything better than  24.Kh2  and played slowly. Black continued with  24...Rfc8  , and had no problem in the entire game. 1/2-1/2 Denisov, T @@StartBracket@@2210@@EndBracket@@-Sorcinelli, A @@StartBracket@@2303@@EndBracket@@ LSS email 2020.' }
24. Kh2
{ 24.Qf2  24...Qf5  Of course Black is not allowing White to play f5 easily. White will have to play g4 if he wants to get f4.  25.Kh2   25.g4?  Qc8!  Thanks to g4, there is no more kingside attack as the g7 pawn remains safe. Black takes over on the queenside now.  26.f5  Rc1∓  a5  26.Bd1  Bc8!  its important to prevent Bg4-f5 threat.  27.Bg4  Qc2  28.Re2  Qb1  29.Re1  Qc2= }
24... Rfc8 25. Ba4
{ 25.Qd2  R8c7  Black is happily ready to give up the d5 pawn if required. }
25... Qc7 26. Qd2 Rc4
{ Once one pair of rooks are exchanged,  it's only Black who can try. } 27. Bb3
Rxd4 28. Qxd4 Qc5 { Threatening to change more pieces. } 29. Qd3 Qc3 30. Qe2
{ White tries his best to avoid the queen trade. } 30... Re8 { Stopping e6. }
31. Qf2 Kf8
{ Typical computer move. White does not have any threats, so Black improves his king position. }
32. Ba4 { White is running out of ideas already. } 32... Bc6 33. Bb3 Bb5
{ Black rightly decides not to repeat. } 34. Bxd5 Rd8
{ black gets the initiative now, but it is not enough for a correspondence game. }
35. Bf3 Rd2 36. Qg3 Bd7
{ Stops White's idea of attacking with e6.   36...Rxa2??  37.e6  fxe6  38.Rxe6+- }
37. Re2 Rxe2 38. Bxe2 Qxg3+
{ 38...Qd4!?  39.Bg4  g6  40.Bxd7  Qxd7=  Although Black can create an outside passed pawn, the queen ending should still be drawn. }
39. Kxg3 b5 40. Bg4
{ A counterintuitive move saves the game. It turns out Black cannot win the king pawn endgame with the outside majority. }
40... Bxg4 { 40...Bc6  41.Bf3  Bd7  42.Bg4= } 41. hxg4 f6
{ 41...a5??  42.Kf3  Ke7  43.Ke4  b4  44.Kd5+-  Wins for White! } 42. e6 h5 43.
gxh5 { 43.f5  b4!  44.Kf4  a5  45.Ke4  hxg4-+ } 43... f5 44. Kh4 b4 45. g4
{ 45.Kg5  a5  46.Kg6  a4  47.e7+  Kxe7  48.Kxg7  b3  49.axb3  a3-+  Black queens with check. }
45... fxg4 46. Kxg4 a5 47. f5 Ke7 48. Kf4 a4
{ The game ended in a draw here.   48...a4  49.h6!  gxh6  50.Ke5  b3  51.f6+  Ke8  52.axb3  axb3  53.Kd6  b2  54.f7+  Kf8  55.Kd7  b1=Q  56.e7+  Kxf7  57.e8=Q+= }
