1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5 7. Nf3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7 12. O-O b6 13. Rfe1 Bb7 14.
Rad1 Rc8 15. Bb3 h6 16. Re3 Nf6 17. d5 exd5 18. Qe1 Re8 19. e5 Ng4 20. Re2 Ba6
21. Rxd5 Qxd5 22. Bxd5 Bxe2 23. Qxe2 Rc1+ 24. Ne1 Nxe5
{ Our course ended here with the following comment: 'Black plays Kf8 next and moves the knight from e5. This forces White to give up the knight on e1 for free. Engine calls it 0.00, but from a practical point of view, it is easier to play from the Black side. Black won a nice game in 0-1 Aravindh,C @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ -Abdusattorov,N @@StartBracket@@2634@@EndBracket@@ Krasnaya Polyana 2021.' }
25. Kh1 { Getting away from Nf3 checks. } 25... Kf8
{ Black protects the e8 rook, and now he is ready to move the knight from e5. }
26. h3
{ 26.g3!?  The king feels less secured on g2 from a human perspective. For engines both are 0.00  26...Nc4  27.Qg4  Rexe1+  28.Kg2  Ne5  Already White must find the only move not to be worse  29.Qh4!  White needs immediate counter before Black secures his king.  29...Kg8  30.Qd8+  Kh7  31.f4!  Thanks to this move White escapes with a draw now. White attacks the knight, and if the knight moves the pawn on f7 falls.  31...Rc2+!  32.Kh3  Rf2!!  A spectacular resource by Black. White is not able to take on e5 now.  33.Qd6!  Only move to stay in the game.   @@StartBracket@@  33.fxe5  Rxe5  Black threatens a beautiful mate now.  34.Bb3?   @@StartBracket@@  34.Bxf7  is the best move which doesn't get mated, but Black keeps big advantage after  34...Rxf7  .@@EndBracket@@  34...Rh5+  35.Kg4  f5+  36.Kxh5  Rxh2+  37.Qh4  g6  Is a very pretty mate.@@EndBracket@@  33...Ree2  34.fxe5  Rxh2+  35.Kg4  h5+  36.Kg5  Rxe5+!  37.Kf4  Re1=  According to engines there are various way of getting into a perpetual. The easiest would be  38.Be4  g6  35.Bxg6  . }
26... Nc4 { White loses the knight on e1 now. } 27. Qf3 Rcxe1+ 28. Kh2 Ne5 29.
Qa3+ Re7
{ The moves were more or less direct until here, and now White must keep playing actively not to get into a worse position. }
30. f4 Re3 { Chasing the queen out of the comfortable a3 square. } 31. Qc1
{ 31.Qxe3  Ng4+  32.hxg4  Rxe3-+ } 31... Ng6 32. Qc8+
{ 32.f5  Ne5  33.Qc8+  Re8  34.Qa6=  Is the computerised way to maintain the balance. }
32... Re8 33. Qc7 R3e7 { Black rightly decides to fight for advantage. } 34.
Qd6 { At this point, Black is out of danger. } 34... Nh4 35. Bc6
{ 35.Bb3  was required, but its quite inhuman to leave this h1-a8 diagonal when Re2 could become a potential threat  35...Nf5  36.Qd3  g6  Trying to get the king to h7.  37.Qc3  Ng7!  38.Qf6  h5⇆  White has no further attack, but he is active enough to stop Black's attacking plans, and the position remains equal. }
35... Nf5 36. Qd3 Rc8 { With precise tactics Black activated his rooks. } 37.
Be4
{ 37.Bf3  g6  38.Bg4  38...Rc5  39.Bxf5  Rxf5∓  will be a long-term torture. }
37... Ne3
{ The current World Rapid Champion plays with utmost precision and stays tactically alert. }
38. f5
{ 38.Qxe3  Rc4-+   38.Qd6  would have been a better try  38...Nf1+  39.Kg1  Ng3  40.Bd3  Nh5∓  Although Black eventually consolidates, and gets a clear advantage. }
38... Nf1+ 39. Kg1 Ng3
{ The kamikaze knight continues its jump to get the bishop. } 40. Qxg3
{ 40.Bf3  Rc1+  41.Kf2  Nh1  is a very cute mate. } 40... Rxe4 41. Qd6+ Kg8 42.
Qd7 Ra8
{ Doesn't spoil anything, and this is the most human way, but there was a faster way to win the game which is the computer choice.   42...Rc1+  wins by force  43.Kh2  Rf1  44.Qxa7  Re2  45.Qxb6  Rff2  46.Qb8+  Kh7  47.Qb7  Rxa2-+  White will soon lose all his pawns. }
43. Qb7 Ree8 { Black keeps total control. } 44. a4 f6 45. Kh2 a5
{ For the sake of activating the rooks, Black rightly gives up a pawn. } 46.
Qxb6 Re5
{ Freeing the other rook and controlling the key e8 square, which prevents all sorts of perpetual. Now the rest becomes elementary. }
47. g4 Rc8 48. Qb3+ Kh7 49. Kg3 Rec5 50. Kh4 Rc3 51. Qe6 Rd8 52. Qf7 Re3 53.
Qb7 Rdd3 54. Qg2 Ra3 55. Qh1 Rf3 56. Qg2 Rad3 57. Qh1 g5+ 58. fxg6+ Kxg6 59.
