1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Qa4+ Nbd7 6. Qxc4 c5 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8.
Nc3 a6 9. Qb3 Ra7 10. Na4 Qa5+
{ Our course ended here with the following comment: 'As  11.Bd2  runs into  11...Bxf2  , White was forced to compromise the position and Black was better and eventually won the game in 0-1 Fedoseev, V @@StartBracket@@2724@@EndBracket@@-Duda, J @@StartBracket@@2738@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2019.' }
11. Kf1 { 11.Bd2??  Bxf2+-+ } 11... b6
{ 11...O-O !?  12.Nxc5  Nxc5  13.Qc2  Qd8  White is unable to take on c5 due to the mate on d1. Black is ready to play b6 when the queen won't come under attack on a5. 13...b6 transposes to the game.  14.Nf3  b6⩱  White still has issues with his king safety. }
12. Nxc5
{ 12.Nf3  O-O  13.Bd2  This way at least White could trade the queens when the king on f1 won't feel that uncomfortable.  13...Qb5  14.Nc3!  Qxb3  15.axb3  b5⇆  White's king is not that weak anymore without the queens, but still he got double pawns and must play precisely to maintain the balance. }
12... Nxc5 13. Qc2 O-O
{ Now Black keeps the queen, making White's king uncomfortable. } 14. Nf3
{ 14.Bd2  Qb5∓ } 14... Bb7 15. Bd2 Qb5 16. Nd4
{ White tries to exchange a few more pieces. It is a bad sign when in a Catalan, White is trying to save himself by trading the light-squared bishop. }
16... Qd7
{ If we take a fresh look at the position we see White did not get anything from the opening. In fact, Black is ahead of development and practically it is easier to play from the Black side. }
17. Bxb7 Rxb7
{ 17...Nxb7!  Getting to the c-file faster with Rc8.  18.Nf3  Rc8  19.Qd3  Qxd3  20.exd3  Nd5⩱  Black keeps the strategic advantage due to White's weak pawn on d3. }
18. Nf3 Nce4 19. Rc1 { Stopping Rc7/Rc8 is more important than playing Kg2 }
19... Qd5
{ 19...Rbb8!?  Trying to get the c-file.  20.Qd3!  A counter intuitive and a tough move to make. White is ready to compromise the pawn structure to make his king safe.   20.Kg2?!  Rbc8  21.Qd3  Qxd3  22.exd3  Nxd2  23.Nxd2  Rfd8⩱  Now the king on g2 is far from the weak pawn on d3.  20...Qxd3  21.exd3  Nxd2+  22.Nxd2  Rfd8  23.Ke2⇆  White has a weak pawn, but his centralized king and rook on the open file compensates enough to hold the balance. }
20. Bb4 Re8 21. Kg2
{ 21.a3  would be too slow  21...Qf5  22.Kg2  g5  23.h3  h5→  This could be very unpleasant for White. }
21... Qb5
{ 21...Qxa2  22.Rhd1  22...e5  23.Nxe5  23...Qe6  24.Nd3⇆  White managed to salvage the opening disaster and now it should be close to equality. }
22. Ba3
{ 22.Qc4!  Qxc4  23.Rxc4⩲  and here white keeps some advantage due to the better pieces }
22... h5 23. Rhf1
{ White goes passive here with overprotecting the f2 pawn. The active Rhd1 was still better }
23... Rd7 24. e3
{ This is a serious mistake weakening all the light squares. From 0.00 with one strategic mistake, White got himself to -2.   24.Rfd1!  There is nothing wrong with admitting one's own mistakes. In fact, it is one of the biggest qualities one can have. It was not too late to trade pieces and get a decent position.  24...Red8  25.Rxd7  Rxd7  26.h3=  Stopping Ng4 and planning to play Rd1 next. Engines call it 0.00 which seems fair. }
24... h4
{ Doesn't spoil the advantage, but there was a stronger move available.   24...Red8!  Was the easiest way to win  25.Rfd1   @@StartBracket@@  25.h3  Nd2!  26.Nxd2  Rxd2  27.Qc6  Nd5!  28.Kg1  Qd3-+  White will get mated soon.@@EndBracket@@  25...Rxd1  26.Rxd1  Rxd1  27.Qxd1  Ng4-+ }
25. Nxh4
{ The position is already difficult for White but taking the pawn and allowing Rd2 is disaster.   25.Qc6  Qh5  26.Nxh4  still loses, but better than the game continuation.  26...g5  27.Nf3  g4  28.Nh4  Rd2∓  White remains under tremendous pressure. }
25... Rd2 26. Qc4
{ White trades queens, but it is too late already.   26.Qc6  Qxc6  27.Rxc6  Ng4-+ }
26... Qxc4 27. Rxc4 b5 { Black nees his knight on g4 to seal White's fate. }
28. Rd4 { 28.Rb4  a5!  29.Rxb5  Ng4-+ } 28... Rc2 29. Bb4 e5 30. Rd3 Rxb2 31.
a3 Ng4 { Now it's all over and the rest doesn't require any comments. } 32. Be1
Rc8 33. Nf5 Rcc2 34. Rd8+ Kh7 35. Kh3 Ngxf2+ 36. Kh4
{ Leads to mate.   36.Kh4  g5+  37.Kh5  Nf6+  38.Kxg5  N2e4+  39.Kh4  Rxh2 } *

