[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Nf3 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qd3 c4 10. Qc2 Rc8 11. e4 Be7 12. Qe2 O-O 13. Rd1 Na5 14. d5 exd5 15. e5
Ne8 16. Rxd5 Nc7 17. Rd1 Qe8 18. Nbd2
{ This move wasn't mentioned in the course. 18.Nc3 is by far the most natural way, and I didn't see much point in keeping the knight on d2. Black's play remains simple and logical.   In the course the following move was given as the main move  18.Nc3  White stops Bf5-Bd3 ideas by quickly bringing his knight to e4.  18...Nc6!   @@StartBracket@@It is time for Black to do prophylaxis. Now  19.Ne4  will be answered with  19...Bg4  attacking the pawn on e5. If White goes  20.Bf4  then after  20...Ne6  the bishop comes under attack, along with Nd4 threats that pose some issues in White's position.@@EndBracket@@  19.Bf4  Ready to meet Bg4 with h3 and not give Black any time to jump with his knights.  19...Nb4  The knight finds his dream spot on d3.  20.Ne1  White is reluctant to allow Black to get his knight to d3 so, he makes this passive move.  20...Bc6!  Now Black changes White's pride, the Catalan bishop.  21.a3  21...Bxg2  22.Kxg2  Nc6⇆  With the Catalan bishop gone, White is left with a bad bishop on f4, which will soon be attacked with Ne6 after Black plays a calm a6 move to protect the pawn on b5. White's play on the center has come to a standstill and Black has a comfortable position. In the 2020 correspondence game, Black had no problems and the game eventually ended in a draw. }
18... Nc6 19. b3
{ White tries to open up the queenside and solve his queenside development issues.   19.Ne4  Bg4  White gets into a very nasty pin.  20.Bf4  Ne6⩱  Black will soon take on f4, and damage White's pawn structure. }
19... c3
{ Black is not interested in helping White free his queenside pieces. } 20. Ne4
b4
{ This protected passed pawn will become a nightmare for White in any endgame. }
21. Be3
{ This was the only move to maintain the balance. White wants to play Nd6 and take on d6 with the pawn. The bishop on e3 unpins the queen on e2!   21.Bf4  Bf5  22.Nd6  Bxd6  23.Rxd6  Ne7∓  The pawns on c3-b4 will soon decide the game in Black's favour. }
21... a6 { Black wants to get Nb5 next, controlling the d6 square. } 22. Nd6
{ White picks up the bishop while it is still possible to take. } 22... Bxd6
23. exd6 { Now White also gets a passed pawn. } 23... Nb5 24. Rac1 h6
{ It is not easy to suggest some direct plans for both sides. Making slow improvements seems wiser.   24...Qe6  25.Ng5! }
25. Ne1 Ncd4
{ Definitely Black is favorable here from a practical point of view, but in correspondence chess, this is not enough :@@EndBracket@@ }
26. Qh5 Nf5 27. Nc2 Nbxd6 28. Re1 { 28.g4  Nxe3  29.Nxe3  Nb5-+ } 28... Qd8 29.
Nxb4 Re8 30. Nc2 { 30.Bf4  Nb5  31.Bd5  Qf6⇆ } 30... Qa5
{ 30...Nxe3  31.Nxe3  c2  32.Qd5  Bf5  33.Qd2   @@StartBracket@@  33.Nxf5  Rxe1+  34.Rxe1  Nxf5-+  @@EndBracket@@  33...Qe7  34.Bf1  Bg6  35.Bd3  Ne4  36.Bxe4  Bxe4⇆  in an over the board game I would be very optimistic about Black's position but the engines believe its just equal. }
31. g4 g6 32. Qh3 Nxe3 33. Nxe3 c2
{ 33...h5  34.Qg3!  34...Ne4  35.Qf4  g5  36.Qf3∞  With utmost precision White escapes here with an equal but dynamic position. }
34. Qxh6 Qd2 35. Bd5 Be6
{ The game ended in a draw here, and after the following sequence of moves position becomes equal  35...Be6  36.Nf5!  Qxh6   @@StartBracket@@  36...Qxe1+!?  37.Rxe1  Nxf5  38.gxf5  Bxd5  39.Rc1  Rc6=∞  @@EndBracket@@  37.Nxh6+  Kg7  38.Bxe6  fxe6  39.g5  Nb5  40.Ng4  Nd4  41.Kf1= }
