1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qd3 c4 10. Qd1 Rc8 11. Bg5 Be7 12. Nc3 b4 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Ne4 O-O
{ Our course ended here with the following comment: ' White tries to enter with his queen to the kingside. In the online olympiad 2021 Bu had a game with Black when White opted for  15.d5  and after  15...exd5  16.Qxd5  Be6  17.Qh5  Qd5  , White was dead lost with no attack on the kingside, and Black's double bishop and strong pawns on the queenside sealed White's fate.' }
15. d5
{ Probably the wrong assessment of the ensuing position.   15.Qd2  f5  16.Nc5  Be8⩱  Black keeps the upper hand thanks to the bishop pair and the uncoordinated White pieces. However, compared to what happened in the game this is a dream for White. }
15... exd5 16. Qxd5 Be6 17. Qh5 Qd5
{ Any endgame would favor Black here because of the bishop pair and the pawns on b4-c4. Black rightly decides to exchange the queens. }
18. Qh4
{ Obviously, White's hopes are pinned on an attack against the black king. }
18... Qf5
{ 18...Nd4!  Was more direct and convincing  19.Nxf6+   @@StartBracket@@  19.Nxd4  Qxd4  20.e3  Qxb2  The powerful queen destroys White's queenside while protecting his own kingside.  21.Rab1  Qe5  22.Rxb4!  22...Rc7-+  Stopping White's idea of Rb7, and once again the c-pawn will decide the outcome of the game.@@EndBracket@@  19...Bxf6  20.Qxf6  Nxe2+  21.Kh1  Qf5!  22.Qh6  c3-+  Thanks to the queen on f5, Black's king is very safe, and the pawn on c3 decides the outcome of the game. }
19. Rad1
{ Rac1 would still give some fighting chances.   19.Rac1!  19...Rfd8  20.Ned2!!  A very easy move to miss for any human. Instead of attacking the king, White targets the pawn on c4 now.  20...Na5  21.e3!  It turns out Black's task is not so easy here. He has lost a large part of his advantage.  21...Qg4  22.Qxg4+  Bxg4  23.Nd4⩱  White is still slightly worse but the worst is over. }
19... Rfd8
{ With one rook gone, the queenside pawns will become more dangerous. } 20. e3
Kg7
{ 20...Rxd1!  21.Rxd1  Qg6  22.Qf4  Ne5  Trading pieces is the simplest way to win here.  23.Nxe5  fxe5  24.Qxe5  c3-+  the c pawn is too fast. }
21. h3 Qg6
{ 21...h6-+  with the idea of Qh7 is strongest according to engines. Reminds me of the famous Johner vs Nimzowitsch, 1926. }
22. Qf4 { 22.Rxd8  Rxd8  23.Qf4  Qf5∓ } 22... Qh6
{ 22...Rxd1  23.Rxd1  c3!  wins the game as White is not able to take the pawn.  24.bxc3  bxc3  25.Nxc3  Qc2-+ }
23. g4
{ Probably both players were under severe time pressure and hence White missed the last opportunity to save the game.   23.Rxd8!  Qxf4  24.gxf4  Rxd8  25.Rc1  with some practical chances to hold on. }
23... Qxf4 24. exf4 f5
{ The knight on e4 must move, and the queenside pawns becomes even stronger. }
25. Neg5 Bd7 26. Nh2 Bf6 27. Bd5 Bxg5 28. fxg5 Ne7 29. Bb7 Rb8 30. Bf3 Be6
{ White's position is hopeless here. } *

