Bd2 f5 15. Na5 b6 16. Nc6 Bf6 17. Rac1 Bb7 18. Rc2 Rfc8 19. Rdc1 Kf7 20. e3 Ke8
{ Our course ended here with the following comment 'With Kd7 coming next, White has nothing to maintain the knight on c6, and Black gets a fine position. 21.Bf1 with the idea of Bb5 can be answered with 21...a6 . Black had no issues in the game 1/2-1/2 Sasikiran, K @@StartBracket@@2676@@EndBracket@@-Wojtaszek,R @@StartBracket@@2734@@EndBracket@@ New Delhi 2012.' }
21. e4
{ 21.g4!?  g6   @@StartBracket@@  21...fxg4  22.e4  Bxc6  23.Rxc6  Ne7  24.e5  Bh4∞  Remains sharp and unclear with 0.00 evaluation :@@EndBracket@@  (@@EndBracket@@)  22.e4  fxe4  23.Bxe4  After the inclusion of g4-g6 Black cannot play in the similar manner like in the game, since after taking twice on c6 Kd7 is not possible anymore, as after Bxd5-ed5 the bishop on f6 hangs.  23...Ne7   @@StartBracket@@  23...Kd7  24.Ne5+  Kd6  25.f4  Rxc2  26.Rxc2  Rc8=  @@EndBracket@@  24.Be3  Nd5⇆   According to the engines the best move for White would be to repeat the position with  25.Bd2  . }
21... fxe4 22. Bxe4 Bxc6 23. Rxc6 Rxc6 24. Rxc6 Kd7
{ And now Black is faster in creating the passed pawn. } 25. Rc2 g6
{ 25...h6⩱  It would have been better to keep the pawn structure more stabilised on the kingside. }
26. Be3 Rc8 27. Rxc8 Kxc8 28. Bd3
