1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 Nf6 5. O-O e6 6. c4 dxc4 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8.
Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 c3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Bb2 Bd7 12. c4 Be7 13. Nb3 Rfc8 14. Bxf6
Bxf6 15. Rxd7 Bxa1 16. Nxa1 Rd8 17. Rd2 Ne5 18. Nb3 Nxc4
{ Our course ended here with the following comment 'Black's rook will invade the first rank if White doesn't trade, as in the game Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@-Praggnanandhaa,R @@StartBracket@@2608@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021' }
19. Rc2
{ An inaccuracy. White should have kept the d-file under control with Rd3 and tried to reduce the damage.   19.Rd3!  Rxd3  20.exd3  Nd6⇆  Black still keeps some pressure due to White's horrible pawn structure. With Rc8 coming next, it is not easy to stop the black rook from invading. However, the engines seem to hold the draw with some precise moves here. }
19... Rd1+ { Taking control of the 1st rank. } 20. Bf1 Rc8
{ Black now intends to exchange one pair of rooks. } 21. Nbd2 b5
{ 21...Nb6  22.Rb2  Rdc1∓  followed by R8c2 and white will be in big trouble. }
22. a4 { The best try. } 22... Nb6
{ 22...a6  23.axb5  axb5  24.e3⇆  Without the weak a-pawn White should hold this easily. }
23. Rxc8+ Nxc8 24. axb5 Nd6 { Black is playing for only two results here. } 25.
e3
{ It was necessary to play b6. The outside passed b-pawn is less dangerous than the a-pawn.   25.b6  axb6  26.e3  b5  27.Kg2  b4  28.Nb3=  We see here White is able to block the b-pawn rather easily. }
25... Nxb5 { Now it would be almost impossible to stop the a-pawn. } 26. Kg2
Nc3 { 26...Nd6∓ } 27. Nc4 Ra1 28. Nd4 Ra2 { Black goes for the f2 pawn now. }
29. Bd3 a5
{ 29...g5!  Black could try to expand in the kingside first, and later exchange the Knights creating excellent winning chances  30.h3  Kg7  31.Bc2  h5∓ }
30. Nc2 a4
{ The rook gets trapped now  30...Na4!!  and still it is very difficult for White  31.N4a3  Nc5  32.Bc4  Rb2  The pawn on a5 with the active rook would restrict White for a long time. }
31. Kf1 e5 32. f3 Nd5 { Pragg finds the only way to keep the balance. } 33. Ke1
a3 34. Kd1 { 34.N4xa3  Nxe3= } 34... Rxc2
{ This little trick saves the game for Black. } 35. Bxh7+
{ 35.Kxc2  Nb4+  36.Kc3  a2  37.Kb2  Nxd3+  38.Kxa2= } 35... Kxh7 36. Kxc2
{ Now the game fizzles out to a draw. } 36... e4 37. fxe4 a2 38. Kb2 Nc3 39.
Nd2
{ White remains a pawn up on paper, but there is no way to make any kind of progress with such a bad pawn structure. }
39... Kg6 40. Nf3 Kf6 41. Ka1 g5 42. g4 Nxe4 43. Kxa2 Nf2
{ The rest of the game doesn't need any commentary. } 44. Kb3 Nxg4 45. h4 gxh4
46. Nxh4 Nxe3 47. Kc3 Kg5 48. Nf3+ Kf4 49. Nd4 Ke4 50. Nb5 Nf5 51. Kd2 Kf3 52.
