[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Giri, Anish vs. Wojtaszek, Radoslaw, Shenzhen Du Te Cup 2nd, 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c5 4. O-O Nc6 5. d4 e6 6. c4 dxc4 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8.
Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 c3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Nb3 Be7 12. c4 Bd7 13. Bb2 Rfd8
{ This move is not a part of our course. Although the most popular move in the position by the number of games.  The starting position of this line in our course goes with: 'This move is very rare. More than 200 games reached this position, and this move was played only about 10 times so far.   However, it is gaining rapid popularity, and in the World Rapid and Blitz, every time this position was reached, Black opted for this move. Now that White committed to Bb2 and stopped the e5 plan, Black gets the forces to the queenside and goes for Be8 plans.   This is not a blunder. Black invites White to take on f6 and take on d7.   After  13...Rac8  White plays  14.c5  and gets a better version of a4 lines when they didn't have to play a4-a5 to stop Black from playing b6.   The traditional mainline is to play  13...Rfd8  when the line goes with  14.Nfd4  Rac8  15.Nb5  and White gets a double bishop advantage by playing Nd6. Those positions are also playable, but I like this rare concrete approach, and I feel soon this will become the mainline instead of the traditional Rfd8.' }
14. Nfd4 Rab8
{ This move was played only twice at a GM level. First, I played this against Ipatov in March 2018. Then Radek tried this against Anish in November 2018, which is our current game. It is not rocket science to understand that this move was one of Team Anand's ideas. It was more of a surprise element. After my game, the surprise element was gone, and Anish was well prepared. }
15. Nxc6
{ 15.Nb5  Be8  is one of the point of 14...Rab8 as after  16.c5   @@StartBracket@@  16.Bxc6  bxc6  17.Nxa7  @@EndBracket@@  16...Nb4!  17.Nd6  Bc6⇆  This move becomes possible as the rook is not hanging anymore on c8. }
15... Bxc6 16. Rxd8+
{ A novelty by Anish which was later played in some correspondence games.   16.Bxc6  bxc6  17.Be5  was my game against Ipatov when after  17...Rxd1+  18.Rxd1  Rb6⇆  Black got ample counterplay with his active rook, and I had no problem throughout the game. 1/2-1/2 Ipatov,A @@StartBracket@@2665@@EndBracket@@-Ganguly,S @@StartBracket@@2657@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2018 }
16... Rxd8 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Bxf6
{ A very surprising and psychologically brilliant decision. White gives up the bishop when there are pawns on both wings, and it is not at all obvious why the black bishop could become useless in certain situations. This was the real novelty. This move was never played in any human games or correspondence games. }
18... Bxf6
{ Recapturing with a tempo. How bad can this be? It turns out Black loses some serious tempo here, and the bishop on f6 is not ideal in these positions.   18...gxf6!  Not at all an easy move to make. Only if Black knew what was White's deep idea after 18...Bxf6 he could make this prophylactic move aimed against White's main idea.  19.c5  Surprisingly even here this so-called anti-positional move @@StartBracket@@keeping the pawn on the same square of opponent's bishop@@EndBracket@@ is the strongest.  19...Rd5  20.Rc1  f5⇆  Black has enough counterplay against White's c5 pawn and will not have any issues maintaining the balance. }
19. Rc1 g5
{ Black is already in trouble and this move doesn't stop White's idea.   19...Rb8  20.c5!  White wants to activate his rook via c4  20...Kf8   @@StartBracket@@  20...Rb5  21.Rc4  @@EndBracket@@  21.Rc4  21...Bd8  22.Ra4  a5⩲  Computer holds in its own bizzare way, but for human playing like this is not trivial. }
20. c5
{ First Bxf6 and now c5. White's play might look highly anti-positional, but it is very deep and strategic in reality. The pawn on c6 and a7 are weak, while the pawn on c5 is stable. After all, the black bishop is on f6 and not on e7 @@StartBracket@@Remember Bxf6?@@EndBracket@@. White wants Rc4-Ra4, and Black cannot stop this idea. }
20... Kf8 21. Rc4 Ke8 22. Kg2
{ Typical human move. Anish is in no rush. Never hurrying in the endgame is a good strategy. Although according to machines it was stronger to play the direct Ra4.   22.Ra4  Rd7  23.g4±  This time fixing the pawn nicely. White keep huge pressure, and Black will suffer for a long time. }
22... h5 23. h3 { Once again showing patience and not rushing. } 23... Be5 24.
Ra4 Rd7 25. Na5 Rc7
{ After this move Black's position worsens drastically.   25...Bd4  26.Nxc6  Bxc5  27.Ra5+-  Black loses either the g5 or the a7 pawn.   25...Rd4!  26.Ra3  Rd5!  27.Nb3   @@StartBracket@@  27.Nxc6  Rxc5  28.Nxa7   @@StartBracket@@  28.Nxe5  Rxe5=  @@EndBracket@@  28...Bb8=∞  @@EndBracket@@  The knight on a7 gets stuck, and Black gets enough compensation.  27...Bb8  For machines it is easy to play like this, but naturally from a human perspective it looks scary to put the bishop on b8.  28.g4⩲  White still keeps huge pressure, although computer manages to hold with precise play. }
26. Nc4 Bg7 { 26...Bd4  27.Nd6++- } 27. Rb4
{ Stops Black's idea of attacking the pawn with Bf8.   27.Nd6+  Ke7  28.f4  gxf4  29.gxf4+-  Black's bishop is lacking any good square on the board. }
27... Ke7 { 27...Bf8  28.Rb8+!  Ke7  29.Nd6+- } 28. e3
{ Simple and effective. White keeps stopping Black's ideas. No more Bd4. }
28... g4 29. hxg4 hxg4 30. a4
{ Now that Black is not moving anywhere, White marches his pawn all the way to a6. }
30... a5
{ 30...f5  was a more stubborn defense.  31.a5  Kd7  32.a6  Bf8  33.Ne5+  Kc8□  34.Rc4±  White dominates totally, but still winning the game is far away. }
31. Rb3
{ Only move to win but not a difficult one. White stops Bc3 and threatens Nxa5 now. }
31... Ra7 32. Rb6 Kd7 33. Rb8
{ White's rook finally enters, and Black's position collapses. } 33... Ke7 34.
Rc8 Bc3 35. Rxc6 Bb4 36. Rc8
{ A great game by Anish. I hope this game gives a good lesson on how not to play such endgames. }
*

